<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Oak Ridge Reservation:  A Valuable National
Natural Resource</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> The Oak Ridge
Reservation:  A Valuable National Natural Resource</H1>

<I>Patricia D. Parr and Linda K. Mann</I><P>

During the last 50 years, the U.S. Department of Energy's Oak Ridge
Reservation has evolved into a nationally valuable natural resource.
Occupying ~35,000 acres of mostly contiguous native forest, the
reservation contains relatively undisturbed ecosystems that are
important habitats for many species now uncommon or unknown in
surrounding areas.  Since government acquisition, the reservation has
experienced natural processes with minimal impact from traditional human
land use in the region providing an invaluable reference point for
determining effects of human development on natural resources.
Increasingly uncommon communities such as cedar barrens, river bluff
communities, forests, and wetlands exist.  Protected blocks of forests
representing more common communities exist, providing opportunities for
research not available elsewhere.  More than 1000 species of vascular
plants can be found.  Checklists include 60 reptilian and amphibian
species; 63 fish species; more than 120 species of terrestrial birds; 32
species of water fowl, wading birds, and shore birds; and ~40 mammalian
species.  Twenty-three wildlife species are state or federally listed,
and the habitat exists for at least 20 more species whose presence has
not yet been confirmed.  As urban and agricultural development in the
Ridge and Valley province continues, the Oak Ridge Reservation will play
an increasingly important role in understanding and protecting of
regional ecosystems.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="parr.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to Parr's talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="parr1.gif"><br>
Pat discussed the evolution of the Reservation since its time<br>
as a farming community to the present.</H5>

<H5><IMG SRC="parr2.gif"><br>
Pat Parr describes the many uncommon species found on the<br>
Reservation today.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>PATRICIA (Pat) D. PARR is an Oak Ridge native, who graduated from Oak
Ridge High School.  She is the ORNL area manager for the Oak Ridge
Reservation and one of the research staff members at ESD.  She managed
the Oak Ridge National Environmental Research Park from 1984 through
1994.  Pat received an M.S. degree in Ecology from The University of
Tennessee in 1981.  She has served on many boards and with many
organizations including the Oak Ridge Reservation Resource Management
Organization (reservation land use planning), the Public Affairs
Committee of the Southern Appalachian Man and the Biosphere Program, the
Ecological and Physical Sciences Study Center (program for precollege
education), the National Sciences Advisory Board of the Tennessee
Wesleyan College, and the Association of Southeastern Biologists.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

