<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Oak Ridge Reservation Geology - Controls of and
Reservation-Wide Integration with Hydrology</TITLE></HEAD></TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> Oak Ridge
Reservation Geology - Controls of and Reservation-Wide Integration with
Hydrology</H1>

<I>Robert D. Hatcher</I><P>

Knowledge of the geology of ORR is extensive but not exhaustive; yet, we
do know the ORR is by far the most complex DOE site.  The geology
consists of a laterally variable sequence of early Paleozoic marine
limestone, dolostone, shale, chert, and siltstone that was deposited on
a crystalline basement of continental crust.  During the late Paleozoic
era, the sedimentary sequence was pushed northwest independent of the
``basement'' along thrust faults that propagated along bedding in weak
parts of the sequence.  Westward transport along these faults produced a
shingle-like stack of thin sheets of rock that today remains gently
inclined southeast.  The Copper Creek and Whiteoak Mountain are two of
these large faults that are traceable from Virginia to Georgia through
the ORR.<P>

To date, most hydrogeologic investigations have focused on small areas,
principally in areas of waste disposal.  Future efforts should
concentrate more on reservation-wide integration of geologic with
hydrologic data, employing the unique ``tracers'' (organic, dissolved
metal, and radionuclide contaminants) present here.  With this approach,
it should be possible to produce both applied and basic scientific
results that would be applicable to better understanding of groundwater
systems in an area underlain by fractured sedimentary rocks.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="hatcher.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to Hatcher's talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="hatcher1.gif"><br>
Hatcher describes the complex geology of the Oak Ridge<br>
Reservation.</H5>

<H5><IMG SRC="hatcher2.gif"><br>
Hatcher discusses the underlying fractured sedimentary rock<br>
system of the Reservation.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>ROBERT D. HATCHER has been a Distinguished Scientist and Professor of
Geology at The University of Tennessee and ORNL since 1986.  He received
a B.A. and an M.S. from Vanderbilt University in 1961 and 1962,
respectively, and a Ph.D. in Structural Geology from The University of
Tennessee in 1965.  His primary research is in the relationships between
crustal structure and the evolution of mountain chains.  He is also
involved in studies of the relationships between fractures, along with
regional studies of fractures and intraplate seismicity.  Bob is active
in many national and international groups, including the Geological
Society of America, for which he was president, and the American
Geological Institute, for which he is currently president-elect.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

