<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Innovative Use of Groundwater Tracers for
Hydrogeologic Investigations on the Oak Ridge
Reservation</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> Innovative Use
of Groundwater Tracers for Hydrogeologic Investigations on the Oak
Ridge Reservation</H1>

<I>Gerilynn R. Moline</I><P>

Tracers are being used as surrogate contaminants in groundwater
investigations on the Oak Ridge Reservation because they mimic the
transport behavior of interest while providing a safe and economic means
for studying key transport processes.  The use of multiple tracers is
allowing researchers to separate out the effects of various transport
mechanisms, to quantify key parameters required for realistic
groundwater models, to identify transport pathways from contaminant
sources to points of release, to assess the impact of sampling
methodologies on the representativeness of groundwater samples, and to
assess the probable effectiveness of remedial alternatives.  From
current investigations researchers are developing new types of tracers,
innovative methods for sampling these tracers, and immediate
applications to environmental restoration problems.  This presentation
provided an overview of the tracers in use by researchers in the
Division and the important information that is being obtained as a
result of these investigations.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="moline.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to Moline's talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="moline3.gif"><br>
Moline describes some of the many research projects which use<br>
tracers on the Oak Ridge Reservation.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>GERILYNN (Geri) R. MOLINE has been a member of the research staff at
ORNL since October 1992.  She also holds an adjunct appointment at The
University of Tennessee.  She received a B.A. in Geology from the
University of Southern Maine in 1986 and an M.S. in Geophysics and a
Ph.D. in Geology from the University of Wisconsin-Madison in 1989 and
1992, respectively.  Geri's specialty is groundwater geology and her
current research interests are geostatistical methods for estimating
hydrologic parameters in heterogeneous systems, estimating regional
groundwater dynamics through statistical analysis of well hydrographs,
flow and transport mechanisms in fractured rocks, groundwater modeling,
and environmental restoration.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="index.html">ESD Annual Information Meeting, 1995</A>
/ <A HREF="/~forrest">webmaster@www.esd.ornl.gov</A>
