<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Environmental Restoration Technology: Where Science,
Engineering, and Politics Meet</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> Environmental
Restoration Technology: Where Science, Engineering, and Politics
Meet</H1>

<I>Brian Spalding, Libby West, Robert Siegrist, Mike Morris, Diana
Hicks, Al Hardesty</I><P>

Three large-scale environmental remedial actions have been undertaken
recently based on extensive ESD research, engineering, and programmatic
involvement.  In 1994, at the Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant in
Piketon, Ohio, two plots, used for radioactively contaminated oil
biodegradation, were remediated by in situ soil mixing with thermally
enhanced vapor extraction, supplemented with soil vapor extraction.
Researchers provided the bench-scale demonstrations and actual-scale
on-site demonstration and evaluation of several in situ soil mixing
techniques to remove residuals of trichloromethene and trichloromethane
from fine textured soils.  The final in situ-mixing site remediation
removed ~80% of these volatile organic compounds.<P>

At ORNL Waste Area Grouping 5, two seeps, which have made significant
contributions to the <SUP>90</SUP>Sr discharge of White Oak Creek, were
identified for remediation.  Treatment facilities were constructed;
seep treatment effectiveness is being evaluated; and sampling in the
stream immediately above and below the seep areas provides a measure of
<SUP>90</SUP>Sr still discharging to the stream.  Recent monitoring has
shown that the treatment systems are effectively reducing the overall
release to the stream by at least 75%.  <A HREF="/ern/isv/isv.html">In
situ vitrification</A> will be applied to a seepage pit formerly used
for radioactive liquid waste treatment at ORNL during the summer of
1995.  During in situ vitrification, electrical power is delivered into
the contaminated soil where the soils' natural resistance is used to
generate heat sufficient to melt it in place.  This will be the first
large-scale application of in situ vitrification in Oak Ridge.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="spalding.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to Spalding's talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="spalding2.gif"><br>
Spalding describes the in situ soil mixing project in which<br>
volatile organic carbon material is collected during remediation.</H5>

<H5><IMG SRC="spalding1.gif"><br>
Spalding discusses other research projects for remediation<br>
including in situ vitrification.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>BRIAN P. SPALDING received a B.S. in biochemistry in 1969 from
Pennsylvania State University and an M.S. and a Ph.D. in soil science
from Cornell University in 1974 and 1976, respectively.  From 1976 to
1977 he was a National Research Council postdoctoral associate at the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency Corvallis Environmental Research
Laboratory, where he investigated the effects of heavy metal pollution
on forest litter decomposition.  Brian joined ORNL in 1977 to study the
effects of dissolved organic matter on radionuclide migration in soils.
He has been involved in a variety of laboratory and field studies of
radionuclide movement and contamination in ORNL waste disposal sites.
In collaboration with staff in ESD he has carried out field
demonstrations of in situ chemical treatment of <SUP>90</SUP>Sr in
buried waste and groundwater; dynamic compaction; in situ grouting with
polyacrylamide, sodium silicate, and cement-based formulations; and in
situ vitrification.  Brian is currently a senior development staff
member in the Environmental Chemistry Section.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="index.html">ESD Annual Information Meeting, 1995</A>
/ <A HREF="/~forrest">webmaster@www.esd.ornl.gov</A>
</ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
