<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Large Scale, Long Term Studies on the ORR as Part of
the Biological Monitoring and Abatement Program (BMAP)</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> Large Scale,
Long Term Studies on the ORR as Part of the Biological Monitoring and
Abatement Program (BMAP)</H1>

<I>George R. Southworth</I><P>

Each National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System (NPDES) permit
issued to DOE facilities on ORR contains a requirement for a Biological
Monitoring and Abatement Program (BMAP) to augment routine chemical
monitoring of effluents.  These programs monitor toxicity in effluents
and receiving waters, the health of individual fish, the abundance and
community structure of aquatic life in receiving streams, and the
accumulation of contaminants in aquatic life and terrestrial
consumers.  Data collected as part of the BMAP monitoring program
assist regulators in assessing whether classified uses of receiving
streams are met.  The data also (1) allows permitted facilities the
opportunity to demonstrate that interim discharge limits are protective
of classified uses and (2) provides the ability to detect the presence
of substances that should be regulated but are not listed in the NPDES
permit.  Monitoring conducted by BMAP on ORR also provides the
opportunity to conduct large-scale, long-term studies on the effects
and transport of environmental contaminants.  Because of the continuity
afforded by a stable core program that has been in place for a period
of years, BMAP has been able to study the long-term responses of
impacted aquatic communities to reductions in pollutant exposures.
Information obtained from these studies on the rates and degree of
recovery of impacted systems following pollution abatement provides a
scientific basis for planning future remedial actions and evaluating
their success.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="southworth.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to Southworth's talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="southworth1.gif"><br>
Southworth describes the BMAP findings from research<br>
conducted to date by ESD scientists.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>GEORGE R. SOUTHWORTH has worked as a researcher in environmental
chemistry and toxicology at ORNL ESD since 1974.  He received a B.S. in
chemistry from Rochester Institute of Technology in 1970 and an M.S. in
aquatic ecology from the University of Michigan in 1974.  Before joining
the Biological Monitoring Program in 1985, he participated in research
on the environmental transport and transformation of chemicals in
surface waters and groundwater and in studies of the toxicological and
ecological effects of chemicals on aquatic organisms and communities.
From 1985 to 1994, he was principal investigator for the
bioaccumulation monitoring tasks of the Biological Monitoring and
Abatement Programs at the DOE facilities in Oak Ridge.  In 1995, he
became Group Leader of the Ecological Monitoring Group in ESD's
Environmental Biotechnology Section.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>
