<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Decision Analysis and Environmental Remediation:  How
It Can Help</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG
SRC="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/images/esdlogo-small.gif"> Decision
Analysis and Environmental Remediation:  How It Can Help</H1>

<I>Bruce R. James, Dale D. Huff, John R. Trabalka, Richard Ketelle, and
Craig T. Rightmire</I><P>

Across the nation, the efficient allocation of remediation resources is
critical because of the large number of contaminated sites and resource
contraints.  One important allocation decision addresses whether it is
cost-effective to proceed with interim containment activities now or
wait for improved technology and methods.  Decision analysis based on
risk-cost-benefit analysis is being used to guide decision makers in
finding cost-effective solutions to this and other similar problems.<P>

Preliminary results were presented from a field case at ORNL, where
trenches of buried transuranic elements, such as plutonium, are located.
The transuranics will eventually be remediated by a method such as in
situ vitrification.  However, until that time, the transuranics could
spread, resulting in increased cleanup costs.  The field case results
indicate that carrying out an interim containment action is not likely
to be cost-effective.<P>

It was also shown that a risk-cost-benefit anlaysis provides an
important means of communicating the reasoning behind such decisions to
the stakeholders.<P>

<HR>
<A HREF="james.au"><IMG ALT="[Audio]" SRC="/images/sound.xbm"> Listen to James' talk</A>
<HR>

<H5><IMG SRC="james1.gif"><br>
James discussed the enormous costs associated with<br>
remediation and public reaction to such expenditures.</H5>

<H5><IMG SRC="james3.gif"><br>
James describes methods used for deciding on remediation<br>
alternatives.</H5>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>BRUCE R. JAMES was born in Canada.  He received a B.A.Sc. degree in
Geological Engineering from the University of Waterloo and a Ph.D. in
Geological Engineering from the University of British Columbia.  He also
received the Certificate Practique de Langue Fancaise, ler Degree, from
l'Universite de Grenoble III.  Before joing ESD in 1994, Bruce worked at
Standford University for 1 year as a postdoctoral fellow.  His major
area of research is in the application of decision analysis, or
risk-cost-benefit analysis, to environmental contamination problems.</I>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="index.html">ESD Annual Information Meeting, 1995</A>
/ <A HREF="/~forrest">webmaster@www.esd.ornl.gov</A>
</ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
