<HR>
<H2>April 1997</H2>
<H3>Clean Fuels Symposium</H3>
<P>April 13-17, San Francisco, California</P>
<P>With the passage of the Clan Air Act Amendments of 1990, cleaner burning
transportation fuels are required to meet the stricter emission requirments.
This symposium, held at the
<A HREF="http://www.acs.org/meetings/sanfran/welcome.htm">American Chemical
Society Meeting</A>,  will focus on all aspects related to clean fuels.</P>
<P>Symposium Co-Chairmen<BR>Edwin L. Kugler, Chemical Engieering Dept., West
Virginia University, P.O. Box 6102, Morgantown, WV 26506-6102, 304-293-2111 x414
(voice), 304-293-4139 (fax), <A HREF="mailto:kugler@cemr.wvu.edu">kugler@cemr.wvu.edu</A><BR>and<BR>Gary
Stiegel, U.S. Department of Energy, Pittsburg Energy Technology Center, P.O. Box
10940, Pittsburgh, PA 15236, 412-892-4499 (voice), 412-892-4604 (fax),
<A HREF="mailto:stiefel@petc.doe.gov">stiefel@petc.doe.gov</A></P>
<HR>
<H2>May 1997</H2>
<H3>Nineteenth Symposium on Biotechnology for Fuels and Chemicals</H3>
<P>May 4-8, 1997, Colorado Springs, CO</P>
<P>
Advances in biotechnology improve the economics for production of fuels and
chemicals. The 19th Symposium for Fuels and Chemicals continues the symposium
series in which participants gather in an informal, congenial atmosphere to
present research results and exchange ideas in this area. Topics for the year
include: feedstock supply and processing; applied biological research;
bioprocessing research; industrial needs; commercialization and process
economics; specialty chemicals, with emphasis on environmentally benign products
and process; and applications of biotechnology in the paper and pulp industry.
Form technical sessions, a poster session, information discussion groups and
tours are arranged to provide a format for productive interactions among
attendees from industrial, academic, and government sectors. 
</P>
<P>For additional information, contact Mark Finkelstein, National Renewable
Energy Laboratory, 1617 Cole Boulevard, Golden, CO 80401-3393, 303-275-3884
(voice), 303-275-3799 (fax), <A HREF="mailto:finkelsm@tcplink.nrel.gov">finkelsm@tcplink.nrel.gov</A></P>
<H3>8th Global Warming International Conference &amp; Expo (GW8)</H3>
<P>May 25-28, 1997, New York, New York</P>
<P>The conference will include discussions of global warming and climate
change, alternative fuels, sustainable agriculture, sustainable forestry, energy
and chemcials from biomass, global surveillance, remote sensing, extreme events
and economic impacts. Symposia will also be held on global warming and public
health, energy and natural resource management, water resources as well as
concurrent sessions on alternative technologies, education, international law
and policy making and state and local governments. It will also feature the
Greenhouse Gas Executive Workshop.</P>
<P>GW8 is being sponsored by the Global Warming International Center (GWIC) and
the Columbia University. For additional information, contact GW International
Progam Committee, c/o GWIC, 22W381 75th Street, Naperville, IL 60565-9245,
708-910-1551, 708-950-1561 (fax) [please note that the 708 area code will change
to 630 on August 3, 1996]</P>
<P>Abstracts are due by October 17, 1996. Attendance will be limited to 400
participants.</P>
<HR>
