<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>ESD GPS Capabilities</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="IMAGES/YWEAVE.GIF">
<BASEFONT SIZE="4">
<CENTER><H1><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="IMAGES/ESDLOGO.GIF">ESD GPS
Capabilities</H1></CENTER><br clear="all">
<HR>

<H2><A NAME="intro">Introduction</A></H2>

In July 1992, $120k worth of Global Positioning System (GPS) equipment
was purchased by the <A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental
Sciences (ESD)</A> and Environmental Restoration and Waste Management
(ER) Divisions.  The equipment has been maintained by <A
HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~oki">Dan Levine</A>, with the <A
HREF="/programs/CRERP/INDEX.HTM">Clinch River Environmental Restoration
Program (CR-ERP)</A>.  Dan, <A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~hnw">Bill
Hargrove</A>, and Clint Rash ensure the equipment is operating properly
and provide training on equipment and software use, advice on most
appropriate software and hardware, and troubleshooting when problems
arise.  Dan and Bill have established a GPS base station which operates
from the roof of building 1505 at ORNL.  They have also established a
base station at the radio tower facility on McKinney Ridge at K-25.
This allows real-time broadcasting of GPS corrections from a local base
station to ORNL or K-25 and surrounding areas.  The GPS equipment has
been used successfully for 2.5 years on a number of ER and ESD projects
within and outside the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR) almost exclusively
to locate sampling locations.  Since July 1992, Dan, Bill, and Clint
have become adept at determining the most efficient use of the
equipment and software to maximize field time and minimize problems.
They have become familiar with numerous problems with GPS data
collection and processing and have developed troubleshooting skills
that allow recovering of data in nearly all situations.  Programs exist
to extract X-Y-Z values and data quality information from the GPS
post-processing software output files for direct input into the <A
HREF="/programs/CRERP/INDEX.HTM">Clinch River Environmental Restoration
Program (CR-ERP)</A> data base, which is largely based on the OREIS
data model.  These programs can be expanded to better meet the
requirements of the new geographic ETA-Data standards.<P>

<H2><A NAME="equipment">Equipment and Capabilities</A></H2>

<UL>
<LI> 3 ASHTECH Me-XII receivers (12-channel Dual Frequency
Carrier-phase/Code-phase receivers) capable of sub-centimeter
accuracy.  Two are equipped with UHF radio links which provide
real-time accuracy to 0.5 meter.

<LI> 1 ASHTECH Ranger receiver (12-channel Code-phase receiver) capable
of sub-meter accuracy using post-processing.

<LI> 2 Magellan NAVPRO 5000's (5-channel Code-phase receivers) more
useful for gross measurements (within meters)

<LI> All associated software for mission planning and post-processing.

<LI> A 486 computer with 32 MB of RAM and 600 MB hard disk for mission
planning and post-processing GPS data.

<LI> 3 Copies of Geolink software.  This software links GPS to GIS in
the field to allow mapping in real-time while building geographic
attribute data bases. It also allows any environmental measuring device
capable of produce a serial data stream to be linked to the spatial
position as data is collected.

<LI> Assorted field equipment including: tripods, optical plummets,
backpacks, carrying cases, range poles, etc.
</UL>

<H2><A NAME="tasks">Typical Tasks</A></H2>

Several thousand point locations have been determined since the
acquisition of the GPS equipment.   We have used the equipment to
locate all sampling locations for the <A
HREF="/programs/CRERP/INDEX.HTM">Clinch River Environmental Restoration
Program</A>, many locations for WAG2 ERP, the equipment has been used
to map groundwater seeps in the X10 area, and we have successfully
mapped a number of sampling grids in Yellowstone National Park used by
ESD researchers.<P>

