<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>ESD GPS Equipment Checkout and General Use
Information</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="IMAGES/YWEAVE.GIF">
<BASEFONT SIZE="4">
<CENTER><H1><IMG ALIGN="LEFT" SRC="IMAGES/ESDLOGO.GIF">ESD GPS
Equipment Checkout and General Use Information</H1></CENTER><BR
CLEAR="ALL">

<HR>

<P>GPS equipment can only be used by people who have been trained in
its use.  For training contact Dan Levine (4-6398).</P>

<P>The ESD/ER GPS equipment is basically available on a first come
first serve basis. Specific receivers may be switched with other users
if conflicts arise depending on receiver capabilities and user
needs.</P>

<P>There is a sign up book for each receiver, including the base
station. You should first determine when you want to go into the field;
which day(s) and time. Then check the sign up books in Room 359 for the
availability of receivers and sign up for those days using your name
and phone number.  If you are planning on using the base station for
differential post-processing, sign up for it too.  If you don't you run
the risk of the base station being turned off by someone else who can't
tell you need it.</P>

<P>You are responsible for charging batteries.  The afternoon before
you go out you should set the batteries you are going to need on charge
so they are ready to go in the morning. Please don't take someone elses
charged batteries. When you get back from the field set the batteries
you used to charge as well.</P>

<P>After you get a successful post-processing session and you are
satisfied with your results, delete the files from the field receiver
and the base station receiver (if no one else is using it).  This is
done by going to screen 8, pressing the ``e'' key and using the arrow
keys to highlight the file you want to delete.  Once that file is
highlighted press ``456'' and ``e'' and the file will be deleted.
Repeat this process to remove all your files from the receiver.</P>

<HR>

<H2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs)</H2>

<DL>
<P>
<DT>Can I download the base station while it is logging to the file I
want.

<DD>Yes, the receiver will keep logging while you download the active
file.</P>

<P>
<DT>I think I lost some data, I only see one file with just the last
site ID in it.

<DD>You probably have all your data in the one file. This is how the
receiver data logger is designed.  If you have logged data at multiple
sites without turning off the receiver untill you were finished, all
the data is in the one file. The file name will be whatever was in the
SITE field on screen 9 when you turned off the receiver.  The receiver
automatically closes files when power is lost. This way if you have
power problems in the field you don't lose data.</P>

<P>
<DT>How accurate are the coordinates I get from the GPS?

<DD>It depends!  Using the standard 5 to 10 minute occupation at a
single location, a reasonable PDOP (less than 6), and the Ranger
post-processing software, the accuracy of the coordinates usually are
within a meter or two.  This is typically good enough if you are
plotting locations on top of the S16A base map or even the new base
map.  If you require higher accuracy talk to Dan Levine.</P>

<P>
<DT>How can I tell if my data are good?

<DD>There are a number of things to look for. First, check the RMS
value for each site in the vectors.out file. The RMS should be less
than about 5. If it is larger than this it could mean that you were
moving while the receiver thought it was standing still. There are
other reasons for this as well. We have also seen strange jumps in the
ellipsoid height that indicate bad data. The typical value for the
Clinch River/Poplar Creek ellipsiod height is around 200 meters (+/-
3). If you are on the reservation or Melton Hill Reservoir you should
have ellipsoid heights greater than 200 and typically not more than
400.</P>

<P>
<DT>When I plot my GPS points on the S16A digital map they don't fall
exactly where they should?

<DD>This is usually because the S16A map is not as accurate as your GPS
points. For instance, the accuracy of a road feature on the S16A map is
+/- 20 feet. This could also be the result of improper coordinate
projections from geographic coordinates and the WGS84 spheriod that the
GPS uses to whatever the S16A projection you are using is in.  This is
a tricky business.  I recommend getting access to the new base map. It
is more accurate and based on a more comparable spheroid.</P>
</DL>

<P>
For answers to other questions email <A
HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~oki">Dan Levine</A> (<I><A
HREF="mailto:oki@ornl.gov">oki@ornl.gov</A></I>)</P>

<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="INDEX.HTM">ESD Global Positioning System (GPS)</A> /
<A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~forrest">webmaster@www.esd.ornl.gov</A>
</ADDRESS></BASEFONT></BODY></HTML>
