<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>GPS and the Yellowstone Fires</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BACKGROUND="../IMAGES/YWEAVE.GIF">
<BASEFONT SIZE="4">
<CENTER><H1>GPS and the Yellowstone Fires</H1>
<img src="GPS06.JPG">
<H2>We weren't where we thought we were!</H2></CENTER><br clear="all">
<hr>

<P>The <A HREF="../CAPABIL.HTM#equipment">ORNL GPS equipment</A>
was used to obtain positions for locations in Yellowstone National Park
where plant regrowth measurements had been made following <A
HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/ern/embyr/embyr.html">the 1988
Yellowstone fires</A>.  Square 1 km grids and orthogonal transect lines
had been laid out as carefully as possible on the ground using sighting
compasses and hip chain strings.  Investigators needed to correlate
information on severity of the fire, available from <A
HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/ern/embyr/spot.gif">satellite images</A>,
with vegetation regrowth.</P>

<P>Several study sites were located off the South Arm of Yellowstone
Lake, in the remote Yellowstone backcountry.  The GPS team was <A
HREF="BOAT.JPG">dropped off by boat</A>, then ferried equipment by
canoes.  A position benchmark was located, from which the team
leapfrogged to establish a <A HREF="STATION.JPG">new base station</A>.
A <A HREF="RECEIVER.JPG">roving receiver</A> was used against this base
station to carry out post-processed differential positioning of the
study locations.  Electrical power to the base station and a laptop
computer were provided by a <A HREF="BATTERY.JPG">deep-cycle marine
battery</A> during the 9-day trip.</P>

<P><img align="right" src="GPS05.JPG"> Prior to the survey, the
investigators made a <A HREF="HRTGRID.GIF">``best guess'' attempt</A>
to locate their study sites relative to the satellite maps.  The
colored grid maps reflect degree of burn severity, from red (hottest
fire) to green (unburned).  Each grid square is 30 meters on a side.
These ``best guess'' locations are shown as gray lines on the maps.
Then the ORNL GPS equipment was used to fix the positions to within 1
meter accuracy.  True sample positions are shown as crossed black
squares, and the irregular blue lines represent the <A
HREF="HRTPATH.GIF">walking track of the scientists</A> as they
carried the GPS receivers!</P>

<P>It is obvious that, in almost every case, the researchers were not
where they thought they were.  Burn severities from the ``estimated''
positions are quite different from the actual positions, and would have
precluded sensible correlations with measured plant regrowth.</P>

<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~hnw">William W. Hargrove</A> (<A
HREF=mailto:hnw@mtqgrass.esd.ornl.gov>hnw@mtqgrass.esd.ornl.gov</A>)
<DT><A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~oki">Daniel A. Levine</A> (<A
HREF=mailto:levineda@ornl.gov>levineda@ornl.gov</A>
<DT>Robert H. Gardner (<A HREF="mailto:gar@ael.umd.edu">gar@ael.umd.edu</A>)
</DL>

<HR>
<ADDRESS><A HREF="../INDEX.HTM">ESD Global Positioning System (GPS)</A>
/ <A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~hnw">William W. Hargrove</A>
</ADDRESS></BASEFONT></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
