<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><IMG SRC="photos/trench.gif"></H1>

<H1>Introduction </H1>

<P>
Aerial photography can play an in important role in characterization
of hazardous waste sites. Frequently disposal records are inaccurate
or inadequate.  For example, the above picture is a 1957 photograph
showing workers placing canisters of low-levels radioactive waste
into a trench within Solid Waste Storage Area 4 (SWSA 4) on the
Oak Ridge Reservation.   A few years later, a fire in the records
trailer destroyed most of the disposal records for SWSA4.  In
such cases the comparison of current aerial photographs with historical
photographs can provide clues about burial ground construction,
cut and fill activities, and other waste management practices.
Subtle patterns in vegetation associated with contaminant migration
and small topographic depressions created by the settling of the
uncompacted soil used to cover the waste trenches can be difficult
to detect from the ground, but are frequently visible on aerial
photographs. 
<P>
Once the hazardous waste sites have been characterized, aerial
photography can be useful during the clean up of hazardous waste
sites. Photographs taken before, during, and after remediation
provide excellent step-by-step documentation of the work performed.
 Aerial photographs allow for clear presentation of results to
regulators and the public.
<P>
Aerial photographs are especially useful once they have been ortho-rectified.
An ortho-rectified photograph has been translated, rotated, and
scaled, to conform to a given coordinate system and can then be
displayed, along with other spatial information, using a Geographic
Information System Display (GIS).  GIS systems have proven extremely
useful for managing and displaying the data collected as part
of hazardous waste site investigations. Site characterization
data is best organized in a spatial database where spatial patterns
can be recognized and interpreted, and GIS systems are ideally
suited to this task. GIS software can be used to organize spatial
data such as roads, steams, utilities, buildings, land-use classifications,
and proposed construction activities, into layers that can be
superimposed in any order. For example, the results of groundwater
analyses, sediment analyses can superimposed on the known waste
trench locations, or hydraulic conductivity measurements can be
superimposed on local topographic maps, geologic maps - or a rectified
aerial photograph. Once an image has been rectified, GIS software
can be used to plot the location of sediment samples, soil gas
measurements, the results of geophysical surveys, and other waste
site characterization activities in their correct locations directly
on top of the aerial photograph.  Rectified aerial photographs
are often used as the base layer GIS software.
<P>
However, image rectification involves more than rotating, translating
and scaling the image. After these preliminary steps the roads,
streams, buildings, still won't overlay in their proper locations
on the image. This is because of image distortion from three principle
sources: (1) the camera was not pointed absolutely straight down
when picture was taken, (2) the camera lens optics are imperfect,
and (3) a photograph is a two dimensional representation of a
three dimensional surface, so unless the area photographed is
perfectly flat there will be distortion created by topography.
Removing these distortions requires the digital warping of photographic
images, analogous to the stretching of a rubber sheet, to force
objects visible in the photograph with known coordinates (ground
control points) to appear in the correct locations.
<P>
The proceeding discussion assumes that up to date aerial photographs
are available. But aerial photographs are expensive to acquire,
 consequently at most hazardous waste sites they are collected
infrequently or not at all.  However, by using a radio-controlled
aircraft in place of a conventional aircraft, we have found it
possible to significantly reduce the cost and effort of acquiring
aerial photographs. 
<P>
Hobbyists have designed and tested radio-controlled airplanes
and helicopters for over 50 years, devoting their efforts largely
to designing aircraft are simple to fabricate and repair, easy
to fly, and above all -- inexpensive. There are hundreds of models
available from hobby stores and catalogs. The typical hobbyist's
plane or helicopter weighs less than 25 lb., can remain aloft
for about 20 minutes, and generally costs less than a thousand
dollars, including the radio transmitter. Most hobbyist planes
are designed either for acrobatics, to mimic full-scale aircraft,
or for simple flying pleasure, but a few are also suitable for
carrying an ordinary 35 mm camera or a small video camera and
video transmitter.
<P>
Hobbyists are not the only ones working in this interesting field;
the various branches of the military have worked with radio-controlled
aircraft for over fifty years. Military efforts are now coordinated
under the Joint Program Office (JPO), which had a budget of over
2 billion dollars in 1994. The military has uses unmanned aircraft
for surveillance, as communication relays, as targets, and as
weapons. Many of these aircraft are equipped with sophisticated
onboard systems: video cameras, night vision cameras, video transmitters,
synthetic aperture radar, autopilot navigation systems, and onboard
microprocessors.  In contrast with the hobbyist's model airplane,
the military systems are typically heavier than 25 lb., often
as large or larger than conventional fighter aircraft, are capable
of long range missions (by military standards anything less that
30 miles is very short range), and cost anywhere from twenty thousand
dollars to millions of dollars.
<P>
The system described in this paper is designed to occupy a niche
between the hobbyist and the military systems. Our objective was
to augment an inexpensive hobbyist airplane with enough hardware
and software to produce high-quality aerial photographs suitable
for use as a base layer in a Geographic Information System (GIS)
at minimal additional cost. We have had excellent results, obtaining
high-quality aerial photographs with a system that is easy to
operate and<B> </B>maintain. 
<P>
In the rest of this report we describe our system, and applications
at hazardous waste sites.
<P>
<A NAME="OLE_LINK6"><IMG SRC="greenball.gif"> </A><A HREF="tmaster.htm" >The Airplane: A Senior Telemaster</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm" >Table of Contents</A>
