</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><IMG SRC="photos/jntm.gif"></H1>

<H1>The Airplane: A Senior Telemaster </H1>

<P>
Using a radio-controlled airplane for aerial photography requires
a plane that is simple to build and fly, easy to maintain, inexpensive,
and can carry a 5-10 lb. payload. Most of our work has been with
the Senior Telemaster, a kit available from Tennessee Model Hobbies.
The Telemaster kit comes pre-cut, and can be built in about 40
hours. It is designed to be a &quot;trainer,&quot; not a stunt
plane, and it's high-wing design makes it stable and easy to fly.
Constructed out of lightweight materials such as balsa wood, plywood,
and plastic film, the Telemaster weighs only about 15 lbs. including
the motor, servos and battery pack, despite an 8 ft. wingspan.
<P>
The standard Senior Telemaster kit yields a serviceable airplane,
but our current design incorporates a number of customizations.
First, we widened the fuselage to create a large payload compartment
beneath the wing (the center of gravity) with an opening in the
bottom for the camera lens.  Second, we added flaps and spoilers
to improve lift during take-off and to kill lift during landings.
The spoilers are especially nice for landing in tight quarters,
because the Telemaster has a light wing loading when carrying
only the 35mm camera and normally requires a long landing approach
to loose altitude. 
<P>
Detailed construction information can be found in the Telemaster
kit and in Walker (1992), but we offer the following additional
advice.  Allow extra time to construct the first airplane or enlist
the aid of an experienced hobbyist. To facilitate the construction
of multiple airframes, cut out duplicate parts at each step. Take
care to balance the payload under the center of lift, but keep
in mind that it is better to be a little nose-heavy than tail-heavy.
On initial test flights we use a dummy payload consisting of modeling
clay wrapped in foam with the same total weight as the camera.
There is no point is risking the camera on the maiden flight!
Finally, a little extra horse-power can pull you out of trouble.
We currently use a 60-size, 4-stroke model engine, which has plenty
of power and is considerably quieter than the comparable 2-stroke
engine.
<P>
Click here for the <A HREF="details.htm">details</A> of our design
modifications.<BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="camera.htm">Photographic Equipment</A>
