<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><IMG SRC="photos/innards.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM">Photographic
Equipment </H1>

<P>
Almost any 35mm camera will work. The only requirement is an autowind,
and the ability to trigger the camera remotely using a plug-in
cable. We use a Ricoh model KR-10m, which is capable of shutter speeds
up to 1/2000th of a second, and has the ability to automatically
bracket the exposures (the advantages of this feature will be
discussed later). At present, digital cameras are either too expensive,
or produce images of inferior quality.
<P>
There is also a wide choice of film available. Walker (1992) discusses
his results with different types of films and ASA ratings. In
general, we have had good results with Kodachrome Gold 200. We
see no point in using film with less than 36 exposures per roll.
The cost of film is minimal compared with the time and trouble
of preparing for a flight, and the extra shots increase the chances
of a perfect picture.
<P>
The circuit we use to trigger the shutter using the radio controller
was published in xxx. It is easy to assemble, and the components
are readily available at Radio Shack or other electronic suppliers.
Of course, the radio used to control the plane must have a free
channel available to trigger the camera. If the funds are available,
a small video camera and video transmitter greatly improve chances
of taking the desired photograph. This is discussing in more detail
under the section on target acquisition.<BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="target.htm">Target Acquisition</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT13-B35-148</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA001-000009-B003-182</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.esd.ornl.gov:80/ern/uav/target.htm 128.219.24.7 19970101052538 text/html 3872
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 05:25:41 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.2
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>Target Acquisition </H2>

<P>
Of primary importance is nature of the target. To acquire a simple,
unrectified image of a small site is generally the easiest.  The
plane must simply be over the target high enough to capture the
target in a single frame, and the camera setting must be correct.
But this easier said than done. Air currents rock the plane during
flight, and a small deviation from vertical is sufficient to point
the camera in completely the wrong direction and miss the target
entirely. Furthermore, from the ground it difficult to determine
when to trip the shutter unless you are standing on the target
and the plane is directly overhead.
<P>
The low-cost solution to the problem of target acquisition is
to shoot a whole 36-exposure roll of film and hope that at least
one of the photographs is framed correctly. It helps to have someone
assisting the pilot. We generally station someone at the target
site with a two-way radio to tell the pilot when the plane is
over the target.  Fly the plane as high as you can track it over
the site to maximize the camera's field of view.  Our experience
has shown that the image quality remains excellent.
<P>
A more expensive, but more reliable method is to equip the plane
with a small video camera and wireless transmitter. We have a
color video camera that is optically coupled to the viewfinder
of the 35mm camera so that the video camera shows what a you would
see if you were looking through the camera's viewfinder. Video
is transmitted to a base station receiver hooked up to a VCR and
monitor, with all three powered by a portable gas-powered generator.
An assistant watching the live video can tell the pilot precisely
when to trigger the shutter, or a second radio can be used to
allow the assistant to trigger camera directly.
<P>
The cost of a adding video viewfinder depends on the choice of
camera and video transmitter. A simple black and white video camera
can be purchased for less than $500 and a small video transmitter
designed to transmit in the ham-radio band can be purchased for
less than $1,000. Unfortunately, a ham license is required to
operate a video transmitter in the ham band. Furthermore, it is
forbidden to use ham frequencies for government or commercial
purposes.  We use a small, rugged, 1 watt video transmitter that
operates on a government frequency, and is designed to meet tough
military specifications.  But the transmitter and receiver together
cost nearly $5,000.  Furthermore, a video transmitter consumes
a lot of power, so the plane must carry an additional battery
pack.
<P>
Despite the increased cost and weight, a video viewfinder unquestionably
improves the chances of success and is essential when the goal
is to acquire a sequence of shots to construct a photo-mosaic
covering a large area.  But please, before flying the plane with
a new video transmitter, <I>check and recheck that the video transmitter
does not interfere with the airplane's receiver</I>. Placing a
video transmitter near the receiver can shut down the receiver
even when both radios are FM and operate on widely separated frequencies.
Worse yet, the problem may not occur until the radio controlling
the airplane is too far away to override the interference create
by the video transmitter. The result is that once the plane flies
beyond a certain distance it stops responding to the controller.
 We learned this lesson at the cost of an airplane!

<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="exposure.htm" >Selecting the correct exposure</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
