<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>Selecting the Correct Photographic Exposure </H2>

<P>
While target acquisition is the fundamental problem, getting the
exposure correct isn't simple either.  The amount of light reaching
the film depends on the length of the exposure (shutter speed)
and the size of the opening (aperture).  Most 35 mm cameras have
internal light meters to adjust the exposure automatically by
selecting the appropriate shutter speed for a given aperture.
But to minimize the image blur, which is created by the motion
of the plane while the shutter is open, it is best to use the
fastest shutter speed the camera allows, usually 1/1000 or 1/2000
th of a second.  Thus the exposure must be controlled by choice
aperture (F-stop).  Normally the selection aperture depends on
the desired depth of field, but for aerial photography all objects
are effectively at infinity, so it is reasonable to use aperture
to control exposure.
<P>
Because cameras to not automatically vary aperture, the F-stop
must be set on the ground before loading the camera in the plane.
 Setting the aperture on the ground is tricky because the light
conditions on the ground are not necessarily the same as in flight.
Furthermore, light conditions can change during the flight, for
example, when a cloud passes before the sun. We have found that
in general the best way to meter the camera on the ground is to
aim at the horizon to obtain a light level intermediate between
the sky and the ground. 
<P>
With some cameras it is possible set the camera to &quot;autobracket&quot;
the exposure. With each shot the camera actually make three exposures:
one at the preset aperture, one a half stop higher, and one a
half stop lower. The disadvantage of this approach is that you
can take only one third as many pictures per flight and two-thirds
of the shots will be under- or over-exposed, but the chances of
all of the photographs being at the wrong exposure setting is
reduced.  In the beginning we relied on autobracketing to ensure
some good images, but with practice we learned to estimate the
exposures correctly from the ground. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/orlite.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> Over Exposed Photograph
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/orrite.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> Correctly Exposed
Photograph
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/ordark.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> Under Exposed Photograph
<BR>

