<BODY>

<H2><IMG SRC="photos/russ.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"> </H2>

<H2>Site Conditions </H2>

<P>
Our low-cost system requires that the pilot maintain visual contact
with the plane at all times during the flight. This can be difficult
if there is no suitable location for takeoff and landing the plane
near the target area. Although it is possible to hand-launch the
plane, and with careful planning the plane can even be deliberately
landed in a tree (Walker, 1992), in general a cleared runway at
least a hundred meters long is required. We have successfully
experimented with the use of <A HREF="details.htm">spoilers</A>
to cause the plane to drop down quickly for landings in small
clearings.  But inevitably, there are sites where there is no
suitable landing site within visual range of the target area.

<P>
For such sites, the low cost solution is two employ two pilots,
two radios and transfer control of the plane mid-flight. This
is not difficult to do provided that there is a midpoint where
both pilots can see the plane. Pilot A is in charge of takeoffs
and landings, while pilot B is in charge of photographing the
target. It is important to use PCM fail-safe radios to accomplish
this maneuver. The alternative is for the pilot to fly the plane
while being driven to the target area from the landing strip --
this requires a skilled pilot!
<P>
It is also possible to design a system where the plane can be
flown using a forward-looking video camera mounted in the nose
of the plane, giving the pilot a cockpit-view. While this approach
can be effective, there are risks associated with loss of video
contact or with the pilot becoming disorientated. A number of
UAV vendors have supplemented the forward-looking camera with
autopilot systems based on Global Satellite Positioning (GPS)
navigation (e.g. BAI Aerosystems, Bosch Aerospace, AeroEnvironment).
The autopilot can be used to fly the plane to preset way-points
and to automatically return to base if the plane loses radio contact.
Naturally the addition of video and GPS considerably increases
the cost of the system.
<P>
Apart from a suitable runway, the most important site consideration
is micro-meteorology (Walker, 1992). Small, lightweight, radio-controlled
aircraft are vulnerable to near-surface turbulence and thermals.
 For example, on the downwind side of a hill the plane may suddenly
lose lift and stall. Landings and takeoffs from a tree lined road
can be disrupted by the turbulence created when wind funnels through
the break in the trees.  On more than one occasion we have had
to struggle to maintain control of the plane just as it clears
the tree line and is suddenly subjected to the unobstructed wind.
Walker reports cases where dust-devils have spun a plane completely
around released it in a new direction.  Prudence dictates a careful
examination of each site to anticipate the possible influences
of nearby trees, hills and buildings. An engine with a little
extra horsepower doesn't hurt either. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="gcpts.htm" >Ground Control Points</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
