<BODY>

<H2><IMG SRC="photos/gcpts.gif" ALT="Photograph with ground control points indentified">Ground
Control Points </H2>

<P>
If final objective is to scan the photographs and use them in
conjunction with a GIS system, then ground control points are
so that the digital images can be rectified as described in the
next section. If the target area contains numerous roads, buildings,
telephone poles, or other man-made structures, then these can
act as control points and their coordinates determined from engineering
records or by a surveyor. For clearings or wooded areas it is
best to lay out a grid of markers before flying the area. We have
had good results using 1-ft wide colored tape available from forestry
suppliers, making a series of Xs on the ground, then using a ground-based
differential GPS survey system to determine the marker's coordinates.
<P>
But for our work on the Oak Ridge Reservation older orthophotographs
are generally available covering the area of interest.   We selected
ground control points by matching objects visible in both the
older orthophotograph and the new unrectified photograph. The
importance of ground control points is discussed further in the
section on image rectification. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="scan.htm" >Scanning the Photograph</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
