<BODY>

<H2><IMG SRC="photos/resol.gif" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></H2>

<H2>Scanning the Photograph </H2>

<P>
Image rectification requires a digital image. In the future digital
cameras that record the photographic image directly into computer
memory may be the best choice, but at present commercially available
digital cameras produce low resolution images, or are prohibitively
expensive (Too expensive to risk in a radio-controlled aircraft!).
Consequently, image rectification generally starts with scanner.
<P>
There are scanners that can scan slides or negatives, but these
are generally very expensive. Commercial services are available
where the customer's photographs are returned as images on a CD-ROM
rather than as prints or slides. Although the resulting images
are generally of superb quality, processing requires several weeks
--- a delay that might prove unfortunate if was a problem with
the film (over-exposure, under-exposure, missed target) and it
is necessary to fly the area again. Simple flat-bed scanners costing
only a few thousand dollars are widely available, capable of scanning
color photographs in with 24-bit color and at resolutions or 600
dpi or greater --- more than adequate for low-elevation aerial
photographs. All of the images discussed in this report were scanned
using either an HP scanner or a NeXt flatbed scanner.
<P>
Digital images require considerable computer memory to manipulate
and hard disk space to store. The size of the image depends on
the scanner resolution used and whether the image is 8-bit (256
colors) or 24-bit (millions of colors, but three times the file
size). We recommend scanning the image in 24-bit color, even when
ultimately planning to produce an 8-bit image. The problem with
scanning the photograph directly as an 8-bit image is that there
are almost invariably more that 256 colors in the photograph (the
limit for 8-bit storage) and the scanner has to select the optimum
256-color subset as it scans the image. Better results can be
achieved by scanning the photograph as a 24-bit image and then
experimenting with 24 to 8 bit conversion options within a image
processing software package such as PhotoShop, or simply working
with computer capable of handling 24-bit images.
<P>
The choice of scanner resolution, on the other hand, depends on
the desired pixel size in the final image. Our approach is to
estimate the required resolution by measuring the size of an object
on the photograph (building, road wide, car or truck) and calculating
the number of pixels required to yield the desired final resolution.
For example, if a 16 ft-long pickup truck measures 0.25 inches
on the photograph, this implies a scale of roughly 1:768; so scanning
at 300 dpi will create an image with an approximate pixel size
of 2.6 inches. If for the final image 1-ft pixels are adequate
then a lower resolution scan will suffice. However, this method
yields only a rough estimate, because the rectification process
will stretch the image in some places and compress it in others.
There is no way to tell in advance whether the part of the photograph
containing the pick-up truck will be stretched or compressed.
We solve this problem by scanning the image at slightly higher
resolution than required by our calculations.
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="icpts.htm">Identifying the Ground Control Points</A>

<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
<BR>

</BODY>

</HTML>
</DOC>
