<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/l07ul.gif">
<P>

<H2>Identifying the Control Points </H2>

<P>
The next step in image rectification after scanning the image
is to identify the control points. For each control point the
pixel coordinate must be matched with the coordinate of the control
point in the desired coordinate system. If surveyed markers were
placed on the ground prior to the photo mission, then the row
and column number corresponding to the center of each marker in
the image and the corresponding surveyed coordinates are tabulated
in a file. If instead of ground markers, a map or existing registered
aerial photograph is being used for ground control, then objects
such as building corners, road intersections, and telephone poles,
must be matched with image pixel coordinates.
<P>
Consider the following example. The image above shows part of
an ortho-photograph, the upper left corner of 
tile L07 from the base-mapping project for the Oak Ridge Reservation.
The photograph was taken in 1992 by the TVA land mapping division.
The image covers part of the Y-12 Sanitary Landfill with a pixel
resolution of 0.5 meters (Note: all the images here have been
reduced in size to facilitate network transfer and therefore have
reduced resolution; the original images are about six times larger).
 Below is an unrectified image taken in 1994 using the Telemaster
that covers a smaller area, but at a potentially higher resolution.
To establish the control points we first loaded the photo tile
into in to GIS software MapInfo as an existing table, then we
loaded the photograph taken from the telemaster as an unregistered
image which automatically starts MapInfo's image registration
routine. MapInfo's registration routine is inadequate for image
rectification because is handles only image rotation, translation
and scaling. It assumes that the image has already been corrected
for distortion created by terrain and off-nadir camera angle.
<P>
However, the Mapinfo registrations routine is useful for creating
the registration file used by RSOrtho. After the photo tile and
unregistered images have been loading into map info we simple
place the cursor on a control point on the photo tile (panning
and zooming as required) to determine it's coordinate. Then we
click on the same point in the unregistered image and enter this
control point's coordinate. This process is repeat, going back
and forth between the two images, until all of the ground control
points have been entered. The MapInfo TAB file containing the
registration information needed by RSOrtho is saving automatically
when the registration routine is exited.
<P>
The figure below shows a photograph taken with our system and several
of the ground control points.
These are entered into the MapInfo TAB file containing the ground
control information.  MapInfo is not needed to produce this file,
any text editor will suffice; the pixel coordinates and matching
ground control points can be determined using an alternate GIS
package such as ArcView or using image processing software such
as Photoshop.<BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/bcunrec.gif">
<p>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="rectify.htm" >Rectification</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
