<BODY>

<H2>Image Rectification </H2>

<P>
The rectification software we used, RSOrtho, works directly with
the TAB files produced by the GIS software MapInfo. For input
RS Ortho expects a image file in Microsoft Windows BMP format
(8-bit or 24-bit), a MapInfo TAB file, and a parameter file that
specifies the target pixel size of the final rectified image and
a spacing for an optional coordinate grid overlay.
<P>
Unlike some of the more sophisticated (and expensive) image rectification
software packages, RS Ortho does not provide any error estimates
for the rectification of the final image, or any indication that
a particular ground control point is erroneous. Large errors will
be obvious in the rectified images. The figure below shows a trial
rectification of the image from the last section 
with several erroneous control point
coordinates (due to bad GPS fixes). While it is possible that
smaller errors might go undetected, in general a bad control point
creates obvious distortion in the final image.
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/joda.gif" ALT="Image distorted by using bad control points in the rectification">

<P>
The correctly rectified image is shown below.
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/bcvr.gif" ALT="Correctly rectified image">
<P>
<HR>

<H2>Image Filtering and Color Balancing </H2>

<P>
Final image quality can be greatly enhanced using image processing
software such as PhotoShop. This is too large a topic to treated
in detail here.
<HR>

<H2>Superposition </H2>
<P>
If the final rectified image updates part of an older existing
aerial photograph, then the final step of image processing is
to superimpose the newer image in the correct location on the
older image. In most commercial GIS packages this superposition
is handled automatically within the software. For example,  the
figure above shows a rectified color IR photograph of the Bear
Creek Sanitary Landfill taken using the Telemaster superimposed
on a natural color photograph taken using a conventional aerial
photography system.  The GIS software Arcview 2.1 was used to
superimposed the images.
<p>
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/bcvtile.gif">
<P>
<P>
Image superposition can also be accomplished manually using Photoshop.
In this case it is necessary to first convert both images to the
same pixel size. Then the newer image is carefully dragged into
the correct location on top of the older image. This is easier
to do if the newer image is first made semi-transparent; once
in position it can be made opaque again. Merging the images in
Photoshop keeps the total file size to a minimum because it is
no longer necessary to keep the underlying pixels in memory. This
can be especially important when piecing together a mosaic involving
a large number of images. Current plans call for a future release
of  RSOrtho to automatically rectify and piece together a sequence
of images to form a photomosaic.<BR>
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="update.htm" >Updating large-scale
aerial photograhic coverage</A>
