<BODY>

<H3><IMG SRC="photos/both.gif"></H3>

<H3>Updating Aerial Photographs </H3>

<P>
The useful lifetime of existing large-scale aerial photographs
can be extended by simply photographing the changed areas and
patching the new image on top of the older photograph. Acquiring
orthophotographs over a site as large as the Oak Ridge Reservations
(35,000 acres) is too ambitious for our system and requires a
sophisticated land mapping system and manned aircraft. This is
expensive and takes years to complete, so it is not likely to
be repeated soon.  Within less than a year sites change, new buildings
are constructed, land is cleared, and portions of the aerial coverage
no longer reflect current conditions at the site.  In the changed
areas the aerial coverage is outdated and largely of historical
value. 
<P>
By using a radio-controlled airplane to take aerial photographs
when an area changes, a new image can be spliced into the older
coverage, just as a patch is placed over a worn spot on a quilt,
to update the original large-scale coverage that was so expensive
to acquire. The patch will not be perfect (invariably differences
lighting and vegetation will make it impossible to exactly match
the colors), but the new image will reflect current conditions
at the site. Patching can continue until the original coverage
is so &quot;worn&quot; that a completely new base map is required.
  Successive patches also serve to document the evolution of the
site; the condition at any time since the acquisition of the base
coverage can be displayed by selectively overlay the patches acquired
up to the desired date. We feel that updating existing aerial
photographs is potentially one of the most useful applications
of our system.
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="subtle.htm">Detecting Subtle Changes in Vegetation and Topography</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
