</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H3>Waste Trenches: An Example of Detecting Subtle Changes in
Topography and Vegetation </H3>

<P>
The photograph below shows canisters of low-level radioactive
waste being lowered into a trench and Solid Waste Storage Area
4 on the Oak Ridge Reservation. This was a typical disposal method
in the 1950s and 1960s. Today the precise location and orientation
of many of these waste trenches is unknown.
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/trench.gif"><BR>

<P>
Aerial photographs often reveal subtle patterns in vegetation
and topography that are difficult to detect from the ground. The
next picture shows a photograph taken with the Telemaster of the
southern end of Solid Waste Storage Area 5.  Notice the linear
depressions in the ground (distinct from the mowing pattern),
areas where the ground has subsided slightly because the fill
material placed over the waste trenches has settled.
<P>
<IMG SRC="photos/swsa5.gif" ALT="Photograph of SWSA 5 showing lineations associated with trenches">

