</DOCHDR>
<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>Significance </H2>

<P>
Using radio-controlled aircraft for aerial photography is significant
because it provides an inexpensive way to acquire quality aerial
photographs. The ease of use and cost savings open up new applications
for supporting environmental restoration: weekly fly-overs of
a site for environmental monitoring, for example, or routine updating
of existing aerial photographs. Site characterization activities
such as drilling, sediment sampling or geophysical surveying can
be documented with an aerial photographs. Pre- and post-closure
conditions at a site can be documented, supplementing standard
ground photography.
<P>
The examples in the proceeding section show, radio-controlled
aircraft can be used to acquire high-quality, inexpensive aerial
photographs. There are several reasons why this is significant.
First, for many smaller environmental sites the cost of obtaining
aerial photographic coverage cannot be justified in the overall
budget. By cutting costs, an RPV based system encourages greater
used of aerial photographs in environmental site characterizations
and subsequent clean-up and facility management. Thus, the tools
of remote sensing are brought to bear on sites formerly considered
too small to justify the expense.
<P>
Second, it becomes economical to schedule frequent over-flights.
Continually updated aerial coverage provides a whole new way to
monitor a site, to provide a chronological sequence of aerial
photographs documenting changes at a site, such as constructing
of a new treatment plant, installation of waste caps, changes
in vegetation patterns, sediment scouring by storms, and ground
subsidence created by soil settling over burial areas. Sophisticated
change detection algorithms are available in GIS software to facilitate
the analysis of sequential images, but is seldom used at waste
sites because the coverage is not available.
<P>
Third, the useful lifetime of existing large-scale aerial photographs
can be extended. Acquiring orthophotographs over a site as large
as the Oak Ridge Reservations (35,000 acres) is too ambitious
our system and requires a sophisticated land mapping system and
manned aircraft. This process is expensive and takes years to
complete, so it is not likely to be repeated. With time the sites
change, new buildings are constructed, land cleared, and portions
of the aerial coverage no longer reflect current conditions at
the site. The aerial coverage becomes outdated and largely of
historical value. But by using a radio-controlled airplane to
take aerial photographs when an area changes a new image can be
spliced into the older coverage, much as a patch is placed on
a worn spot on a quilt, and update the large-scale coverage current
so expensive to acquire. The patch will not be perfect (invariably
differences lighting and vegetation will make is difficult to
exactly match the colors), but the new image will be current.
Patching can continue until the coverage is so &quot;worn&quot;
that a completely new base map is required. An additional benefit
is that the original base map and successive patches document
the evolution of the site. The condition at any time since the
acquisition of the base coverage can be displayed by selectively
overlay the patches acquired up to the desired date.<BR>

<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="limit.htm">Limitations</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm">Table of Contents</A>
</BODY>

