<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>Limitations </H2>

<P>
Our simple, inexpensive system has limitations. First, it is difficult
to acquire coverage over large areas. Because the pilot must maintain
visual contact with the aircraft to track it's position and attitude,
our current system has an operational ceiling of about 1000 ft.
With an ordinary 50mm lens this limits the area covered in a single
to photograph to about xxx x xxx. Larger coverages must be pieced
together from individual photographs. This is feasible, but time
consuming. It does not seem reasonable to attempt to cover areas
of many square miles in this fashion. 
<P>
Second, image rectification requires numerous ground control points.
Roads, buildings, fences, may serve in developed areas, but over
forests or lakes it is very difficult to establish ground control
points. 
<P>
Third, some areas are difficult to fly because of poor access
or over-head obstructions. A road or clearing several hundred
feet in length is required for landing and take-off. In some cases
we have circumvented this problem by using two pilots and two
separate radios to control the airplane. The first pilot handles
take-off and landing.
<P>
These limitations are surmountable, but the solutions add to the
cost of the system.  For example, we discussed previously that
adding an onboard video camera, video transmitter, and GPS autopilot
can overcome the lack of suitable runway near the target, but
these additions cost thousands of dollars.  The right approach
is to begin with a simple, inexpensive system supplemented with
the minimum additions to get the job done.
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="acknwldg.htm">Sponsors and people </A>
<P>
