<TITLE>Earth and Atmospheric Sciences</TITLE>

<H1>Earth and Atmospheric Sciences</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

Staff in the Earth and Atmospheric Sciences Section of the
Environmental Sciences Division (ESD) at Oak Ridge National Laboratory
(ORNL) conduct basic and applied research on interdisciplinary problems
related to the broad field of earth sciences.  Most of the section's
research focuses on managing energy-related waste materials, with
field, laboratory, and computer-based investigations supporting these
efforts.  Research is directed toward understanding and controlling the
physical and chemical factors that affect the movement of material
through the lithosphere, the hydrosphere, and the atmosphere.<P>

The common theme of most section activities is the study of waste
materials and by-products from energy production.  Activities span
major portions of the energy cycle.  For instance, a significant part
of the research involves the characterization of past and future
disposal sites, whereas another major part focuses on an understanding
of the physical and chemical factors that lead to the migration of
materials away from disposal sites in groundwater, surface water, and
the atmosphere.  Closely coupled with this effort are projects that
deal with the development of quantitative capabilities for predicting
the behavior of natural systems.  Another part of the energy cyclealso
related to wasteinvolves in situ treatment of disposed materials in the
ground to mitigate their movement into the environment.  Global studies
in the section analyze the relationship between fossil fuel emissions
and increases in atmospheric CO2 concentration as it is controlled by
the global carbon cycle.<P>

The Earth and Atmospheric Sciences Section is fortunate to have a wide
variety of sponsors.  The single greatest area of support reflects the
need for on-site characterization of geologic and hydrologic conditions
on Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR) and at other U.S. Department of Energy
(DOE) facilities (such as the Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant in
Kentucky).  Much of this support is through the Environmental
Restoration and the DOE Office of Technology Development programs, as
well as through direct funding from some of the facilities; activities
funded through DOE's Hazardous Waste Remedial Action Program are
included.<P>

The DOE Office of Health and Environmental Research (OHER) provides
some of the support for the section's basic research on subsurface
transport phenomena and for an advanced global carbon cycle research
program.  OHER also supports the Atmospheric Radiation Measurement
Program.  Funding for geophysical and geochemical research comes from
the DOE Office of Basic Energy Sciences.  The section also performs
research for a number of non-DOE sponsors, including the Electric Power
Research Institute, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA),
National Aeronautics and Space Administration, and the U.S. Geological
Survey.<P>

Throughout its efforts, the section is substantially involved in
science education at all levels, from precollege to graduate to
postgraduate.  The section consists of seven groups, each designated by
a title that reflects the training and activities of the staff.<P>

<H2>Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes</H2>

The Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes Group performs basic research
designed to quantify and understand the processes that influence the
transport, transformation, deposition, and fate of materials released
into the environment.  This research encompasses the fields of
atmospheric, marine, freshwater, and soil sciences.  Primary areas
include the atmospheric chemistry and deposition of trace metals,
air/surface exchange and its role in biogeochemical cycling, and
processes controlling transformation and mobility of radionuclides and
other contaminants in aquatic and soil systems.<P>

During FY 1992 staff in the group used a throughfall network to
quantify the importance of forest edges and gaps in increasing
atmospheric deposition in complex terrains.  The group also developed a
mass flow control system to produce highly precise and accurate
air-flow measurements that are critical to the application of
micrometeorological methods to deposition of mercury.<P>

<H2>Earth Systems Modeling</H2>

The Earth Systems Modeling Group develops, applies, and evaluates
mathematical models used in addressing local, regional, and global
environmental issues.  Current research emphasizes the development of
new models and the examination and integration of disparately scaled
existing models to comprehensively address global carbon dynamics.
This work is designed to increase understanding of the global carbon
cycle and to forecast the effects of changes in atmospheric carbon
emissions on global climate and ecological resources during the next
century.  Group interests also include quantification of the
implications of model uncertainties on model performance.  Sensitivity
and uncertainty analyses are used to evaluate performance and to place
model forecasts in the context of global risks.  Earth systems modelers
use an innovative synthesis of techniques to address problems in
mesoscale, regional, and global modeling.<P>

A new model of global terrestrial carbon cycling was developed during
FY 1992 and used to analyze the effects of past land use on atmospheric
CO2.  In addition, a major review paper on soil carbon dynamics in the
global carbon cycle was published.<P>

<H2>Energy Systems and Environmental Restoration Programs</H2>

During the year, two major new activities grew:  The Oak Ridge
Hydrology Support Program and the Energy Systems Groundwater Program
Office.  Both entities support a consistent technical approach to
groundwater studies, in parallel with compliance directives, at all
five Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc., facilities.  A significant
part of the Oak Ridge Hydrology Support Program is the highly
challenging study of the hydrology of ORR, the most complex hydrology
at any DOE site.<P>

The Oak Ridge Hydrology Support Program provides the five Energy
Systems plants with technical expertise in the broad areas of hydrology
and geology.  Two principal groups make up this program.  The first
consists of hydrologists who advise the groundwater programs on
groundwater and surface water issues related to environmental
restoration and regulatory compliance.  The second group is directed
toward understanding fundamental hydrogeologic principles related to
groundwater flow and remediation in fractured rock systems such as
those that dominate ORR.<P>

The Oak Ridge Hydrology Support Program published a conceptual model of
ORR's hydrology during FY 1992 and encouraged the development of
similar documents at the other Energy Systems sites.  Staff members
also participated in the development of a groundwater operable unit
strategy for the three ORR sites and the implementation of
comprehensive programs.<P>

The Energy Systems Groundwater Program Office is responsible for
providing coordination for all groundwater activities at the five DOE
facilities managed by Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.  The primary
objective of the program is to develop a consistent approach to ensure
that applicable state or federal environmental laws and relevant DOE
orders are satisfied and that the environment and the health of the
public are protected.  The Groundwater Program Office provides
management support to achieve these goals by working through
Groundwater Coordinators at each of the sites.<P>

During FY 1992 the Energy Systems Groundwater Program Office developed
a program management plan that established the organization of the
groundwater program and defined roles and responsibilities of key
participants.  In  addition, the office provided technical guidance for
sites dealing with dense, nonaqueous liquid contamination.<P>

The Technical Oversight Review Committee provides the Environmental
Restoration Program with technical expertise from a variety of ORNL
divisions.  Principal activities of this group include reviewing
documents and program plans, providing advice that will shape future
restoration efforts throughout Energy Systems, and overseeing quality
assurance for many projects.<P>

<H2>Geology and Geophysics</H2>

The Geology and Geophysics Group deals with field-based geologic and
geophysical aspects of waste management.  Principal emphasis is on (1)
elucidation of geologic principles that are important in quantifying
groundwater flow, (2) characterization and evaluation of waste disposal
sites, and (3) geologic mapping.  Specific topics currently addressed
include analysis of structural and lithologic controls on groundwater
flow paths, development and application of nonintrusive surface and
borehole geophysical techniques to geologic problems in waste
management areas, and geologic characterization of ORR and other DOE
sites.<P>

The Ultrasonic Ranging and Data System project, a 3-year endeavor for
EPA that automates data location and collection, was successfully
completed during FY 1992.   Staff also began collecting geophysical
data (microgravity, ground-penetrating radar, and high-resolution
seismic reflection data) so that researchers can use geophysical
methods to characterize karst features at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant.<P>

<H2>Groundwater Hydrology</H2>

The Groundwater Hydrology Group addresses a wide range of technical
problems related to preservation and restoration of groundwater
quality.  Staff activities include application of complex numerical
models to simulate multiphase flow of fluids in porous and fractured
systems, design and operation of groundwater monitoring systems,
characterization of large-area hydrologic properties, use of artificial
tracers and natural groundwater chemistry to study transport processes,
and interactions with surface water and groundwater.  Field work is
directed at understanding flow mechanisms in complex subsurface
systems.<P>

Current research topics include the effects of fracture flow systems on
the dynamic storage and release of pollutants and direct measurement of
rates of recharge by groundwater dating with H3 and 3He.  Modelers
within the group are adapting the extensive ensemble of ORNL
groundwater models to massively parallel computers and exploring new
modeling techniques on these computers.<P>

During FY 1992 the group's ability to characterize and evaluate
contaminant transport in the intermediate and deep flow systems was
greatly increased with the installation of six multiport well systems,
from 400 to 1300 ft, at ORNL and the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant.  A
three-dimensional, multiregion flow and transport model was developed,
verified, and calibrated and will be used to assess contaminant
transport issues on DOE sites.  Fundamental research using a down hole
colloidal borescope resulted in new guidance for purging and sampling
groundwater monitoring wells.<P>

Researchers in the group also initiated a fundamental field study on
the role of diffusion as a limiting mass transfer mechanism for
subsurface cleanup, using a suite of dissolved noble gas tracers.  In
addition, the group analyzed groundwater transport in an ORNL waste
area through the use of a large-scale three-dimensional groundwater
flow model configured to run on a parallel processing supercomputer.
ORR Hydrologic and Geologic Study modelers calibrated a
three-dimensional groundwater flow program on an Intel supercomputer
system for studies of an ORNL waste site remediation.<P>

<H2>Soils and Environmental Engineering</H2>

The Soils and Environmental Engineering Group performs basic and
applied research within a variety of environmental restoration and
waste management projects funded principally by DOE and EPA.  Soils
research is centered on understanding the interactions of radionuclides
and chemicals with soil.  Major research areas include stabilizing
former waste disposal trenches and ponds, assessing the chemistry and
mineralogy of area soils, and developing and evaluating methods to
decontaminate uranium from soils.<P>

The environmental engineering research involves the development and
testing of new techniques for controlling contaminant transport in the
environment, technical and management oversight for technology
demonstrations, and participation in national and international
projects whose major goal is to develop and evaluate remedial action
approaches in site restoration and waste management activities.  One
primary activity involves cleanup of soils and sludges containing
unacceptable levels of hazardous organic solvents.  The environmental
engineering projects entail interactions with multiple disciplines
throughout ORNL and in some cases with personnel from universities and
other national laboratories in the United States and Europe.<P>

During FY 1992 the X-231B Technology Demonstration at the Portsmouth
Gaseous Diffusion Plant in Ohio was successfully completed.
Chlorinated solvents were effectively treated in clay soils
contaminated by organic solvents and trace levels of radioactive
substances.  A novel approach was demonstrated, coupling selected
physicochemical processes in continuously mixed subsurface soil
reactors.  The processes are being used for closure and remediation of
the X-231B and similar solid waste management units at estimated
savings of several million dollars.<P>

Bench-scale leaching studies conducted during FY 1992 indicated that
soil washing/leaching technologies can be used to decontaminate
uranium-contaminated soils at the DOE uranium processing facility in
Fernald, Ohio.  Sodium carbonate and citric acid extractions removed
&gt;95% of the uranium from those soils tested.  In addition, citric acid
was determined to have the highest efficiency of seven extraction
solutions for removing uranium from contaminated soils at the Fernald
site.<P>

<H2>Subsurface and Surficial Geochemistry</H2>

Basic and applied research in geochemistry emphasizes the understanding
of processes that control the transport, fate, and transformation of
elements in subsurface and surficial geological environments.  This
understanding is then used to develop and apply interpretive models of
element behavior to the solution of energy-related problems.
Complementary field, laboratory, and computational research efforts are
being used to evaluate strategies for (1) effective use of energy
resources, (2) disposal options for future wastes, and (3) remedial
actions for existing contaminated sites.  This research incorporates
principles from the disciplines of aqueous geochemistry,
biogeochemistry, computer science, geology, hydrology, isotope
geochemistry, limnology, radiogeochemistry, and soil chemistry.<P>

Current research efforts include biotic and abiotic transformations of
contaminants in natural waters, soils, and sediments; characterization
of contaminants in active and inactive waste disposal areas; colloid
mobility; contaminant transport in unsaturated, heterogeneous soils;
element cycling and rock-water interactions in hydrothermal systems;
hydrogeochemical investigations of the local groundwater system; in
situ vitrification for the stabilization of contaminated soils;
sorption of trace metals onto natural materials; and trace element
transport and cycling in river, lake, and coastal zone environments.<P>

During FY 1992 researchers in the group completed a report describing
the solidification of a simulated ORNL waste trench through the use of
in situ vitrification technology.  No volatilization of 90Sr, 241Am,
239Pu, or 240Pu was detected, and almost complete retention of these
isotopes in the melt was estimated.  Researchers also found that the
thermal and petrologic behavior of the 1991 in situ vitrification melt
is an excellent analogue to natural magmatic systems and that it
provides insight into the dynamic processes of volatile release and
crystallization.<P>

Staff used field mesocosms to determine the bioavailability of
sediment-bound mercury in the environment.  During FY 1992, research
provided an improved understanding of geochemical processes and
increased the ability to predict the behavior of metals in sediments
and heterogeneous soils.<P>

<H2>Surface Water Hydrology</H2>

The Surface Water Hydrology Group was created in 1992 in order to
provide more attention to problems of flow and water quality in natural
and impacted surface water systems.  The main effort is directed at
characterizing and quantifying contaminant transport in contaminated
drainages on ORR by investigating mechanisms of flow, sediment
production, sediment transport, and contaminant movement.  Group
members study groundwatersurface water interactions by analyzing the
occurrence and chemical signature of seeps and springs and their roles
in surface water production.  Investigations include developing and
implementing models of water budgets and watershed hydrology, with an
emphasis on flow in fractured-rock terrain.<P>

During FY 1992 members of the group managed the Comprehensive
Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act of 1980
Remedial Investigation of the White Oak Creek floodplain.  A multiyear
storm sediment sampling initiative and a new mechanistic modeling
program are aimed at understanding the effects of extreme floods on
contaminant mobilization.  In addition, an ORNL-wide task to sample and
characterize seeps and tributaries further defines the role of shallow
subsurface flow in contaminant movement for regions typified by humid
climate and by bedrock that is both porous and fractured.<P>

Researchers defined the tight linkage between groundwater and surface
water described in the Conceptual Hydrologic Model for ORR in
identifying a new approach to monitoring the effectiveness of remedial
actions at historical waste sites that emphasizes changes in surface
water quality rather than changes in groundwater quality.  A
comprehensive sampling and computer modeling effort to quantify the
movement of contaminated sediments in the watershed that drains ORNL
and the historical waste burial areas was initiated.<P>

