<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="1"><H1>1</H1></A>

<H2>Analysis of White Oak Creek Surface Water Hydrology Data Supports
Popular Hypothesis on Losing Reach near Headwaters</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. M. Borders, S. M. Gregory, R. B. Clapp, B. J. Frederick (1), and
J. A. Watts
</DL>

Hydrologic monitoring supports long-term assessment of the
effectiveness of remedial actions in limiting the transport of
contaminants across waste area grouping (WAG) boundaries and ultimately
off-site.  The identification of spatial and temporal trends in
hydrologic parameters and mechanisms that affect the movement of
contaminants in the White Oak Creek (WOC) watershed supports the
development of interim corrective measures and remedial restoration
alternatives.<P>

For several years surface water hydrology data have been collected and
processed at a number of stations within and near the WOC watershed.
Data collected at 16 monitoring stations [eight ESD stations and eight
U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) stations] from October 1990 to December
1991 have been added to the surface water hydrology data base.
Analysis of the data indicates that significant progress has been made
in the reliability of the data through upgrades in monitoring stations
and improved instrumentation.  Of particular note, the reach between
the White Oak Creek headwaters station at the base of Chestnut Ridge
north of Bethel Valley Road and the USGS station south of Bethel Valley
Road is a losing reach.  A popular hypothesis is that the water lost in
this reach reappears as surface flow at the pond northeast of Building
4500.<P>

An examination of the water budget for the pond reveals that &lt;10% of
flow entering the pond can be attributed to losses in the losing reach
of WOC.  The remainder of the inflow is probably derived from
groundwater flows in the Knox Formation underlying Chestnut Ridge.  The
Knox Formation consists of dolomite and has solution cavities.
Analysis of gains and losses within reaches of WOC provides important
information on the relationships between geology and flow of the
system.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="2"><H1>2</H1></A>

<H2>Hydrologic Data for the White Oak Creek Watershed Are Summarized</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. M. Borders (1), J. A. Watts, and R. B. Clapp
</DL>

The White Oak Creek Watershed, consisting of White Oak Creek (WOC) and
its tributaries, White Oak Lake, and the White Oak Creek Embayment on
the Clinch River, is the primary surface drainage for ORNL.  Streamflow
has been monitored in the watershed for more than 40 years.  The stream
network consists of small perennial and intermittent first- to
third-order streams.  In addition to natural runoff and groundwater
discharge, WOC and its tributaries receive waste effluents, which
represent a significant portion of the annual streamflow, from ORNL
facilities.  Sediments within the WOC flow system have sorbed chemical
and radioactive contaminants from nearby waste areas.  Consequently,
the WOC floodplain sediments and the White Oak Lake sediments and water
contain measurable quantities of dissolved 3H, 90Sr, 137Cs, and 60Co.<P>

Surface water data measured within the WOC flow system include
discharge and runoff, water quality, radiological and chemical
contaminants in sediments and water, and descriptions of outfalls to
the system.  Twenty-seven surface water monitoring stations, operated
by ESD, the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS), and the Environmental
Surveillance Section of the Office of Environmental Compliance and
Documentation, are located within, or in the immediate vicinity of, the
WOC watershed.  In Water Year 1990 (October 1989-September 1990), 17
monitoring stations were operating.  Hydrographs compared flows at
selected gaging stations and isolated contributions from various areas
of the watershed.  Differences shown in flows measured in WOC above the
confluence with Melton Branch, WOC's primary tributary, and at the USGS
station near Haw Ridge (upstream of the confluence) were negative ~50%
of the time during a period of drought (May 1987-88).  For a wet period
(October 1989-September 1990), the differences were positive ~90% of
the time.  These comparisons highlight the major contribution of
precipitation to the water budget of the watershed.  Analyses of
radionuclides in water samples show an inverse relationship between
concentration and discharge for 3H and 90Sr at both the WOC and Melton
Branch monitoring stations; however, mass flux of contaminants
increases with increasing discharge.  The concentration-vs-discharge
relationship for 137Cs and 60Co is a function of suspended sediment
transport and does not parallel the 3H and 90Sr results.<P>

Characterization of the hydrology of the WOC watershed provides a
better understanding of the processes that drive contaminant transport
in the watershed.  Analyses of streamflow monitoring data show spatial
and temporal patterns that are useful in predicting and identifying
hydrologic trends in parameters and mechanisms affecting contaminant
movement.  This information is necessary to develop interim corrective
measures and remedial restoration activities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="3"><H1>3</H1></A>

<H2>Hydrologic Isolation of Buried Wastes Beneath Temporary Caps at
SWSA 6 Was Monitored</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. B. Clapp and D. S. Marshall
</DL>

In 1988 interim corrective measures (ICMs) were implemented at Solid
Waste Storage Area 6 (SWSA 6) at ORNL.  The SWSA 6 site is regulated
under the Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA).  The ICMs
consist of eight large high-density polyethylene sheets placed as
temporary caps over trenches known to contain RCRA-regulated
materials.  Environmental monitoring for FY 1991 consisted of measuring
water levels at 13 groundwater wells outside the capped areas and 44
wells at or near the capped areas in order to identify any significant
loss of hydrologic isolation of the wastes.  Past annual reports had
shown that the caps are only partially effective in keeping the waste
trenches dry and that many trenches consistently or intermittently have
water in them.<P>

Monitoring during the past year showed that the patterns, both in time
and in space, of trenches with saturated conditions were similar to
patterns previously observed.  None of the caps showed any sign of
failure with respect to hydrologic isolation as compared with their
performance in previous years.  According to well hydrographs, the ICM
caps have improved the hydrologic isolation of the buried wastes at all
cap sites because direct infiltration has been eliminated; however,
impermeable caps cannot ensure total hydrologic isolation.  Even if
stormflow is diverted or eliminated, groundwater can saturate wastes in
low-lying places during the wet season.  At one cap near White Oak
Lake, water levels in trenches are related to the elevation of the lake
itself, and this factor must be considered in plans for future
remediation.  In cases in which inundation can result from rising water
tables, hydrologic isolation of waste in trenches may require wide-area
suppression of recharge, artificial lowering of the water table by
inducing drainage, and/or building a barrier to groundwater movement.<P>

<A NAME="4"><H1>4</H1></A>

<H2>Annual Report of the Environmental Restoration Monitoring and
Assessment Program Is Published</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. B. Clapp, D. E. Miller, and H. L. Boston
</DL>

The <I>Annual Report of the Environmental Monitoring and Assessment
Program at Oak Ridge National Laboratory for FY 1992</I> (ORNL/ER-124)
summarizes the investigation and monitoring activities conducted in
support of the Environmental Restoration (ER) Program.  This summary
primarily reflects the comprehensive efforts of the Waste Area Grouping
(WAG) 2 and Site Investigations (SI) Program.<P>

WAG 2, which includes the lower portion of White Oak Creek (WOC), the
floodplain, and White Oak Lake, is the drainage area that receives most
of the contaminants released from the waste disposal sites and the
discharges from the main plant at ORNL. Surface water from WAG 2
discharges to the Clinch River.  As a part of the remedial
investigation for WAG 2, a long-term multimedia environmental
monitoring effort takes advantage of the role of WAG 2 as an integrator
and conduit for contaminants.  These monitoring efforts rely heavily on
the expertise and diversity of staff from ESD and other ORNL
divisions.<P>

Research activities are divided into four major tasks--Surface Water,
Groundwater, Biota, and Soil and Sediment--and include support
activities such as risk assessment and remedial assessment.
Radionuclides (especially 137Cs, 60Co, and 90Sr) constitute the major
risks from the ORNL WAGs; the most significant risk is from gamma
exposure to 137Cs in the soils and sediments.  Interrelated contaminant
transport pathways (e.g., groundwater to surface water, surface water
to sediment and soils, and surface water and sediment to biota) have
led to an integrated and comprehensive approach to providing
information in support of ER efforts at ORNL.  The results of this
integrated effort are used to develop a conceptual understanding of the
key contaminants and the sources, fluxes, and processes affecting their
distribution and movement within the WOC watershed.  The WAG 2/SI
Program exemplifies the incorporation of applied and basic research to
form a basis for prioritizing sites and for selecting, implementing,
and evaluating remedial actions within the WOC watershed.  The program
also can serve as a model for future remedial investigations.<P>

<A NAME="5"><H1>5</H1></A>

<H2>High-Resolution Seismic Reflection Data Are Acquired at Bear Creek
Burial Grounds</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. E. Doll
</DL>

The migration of dense nonaqueous-phase liquids (DNAPLs) through low
permeability materials is determined largely by the structural features
in the rocks--primarily faults and fractures.   Recent analysis of well
monitoring  data indicates that DNAPLs have migrated to a depth of at
least 270 ft in two wells adjacent to the Bear Creek Burial Grounds at
the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant.  Proposed migration pathways for these
substances include bedding plane fractures (which dip at ~45 degrees to
the south) and faults that are oriented oblique to the strike of the
bedding planes.  Such faults have been inferred by well logs and by
surface drainage patterns.  The possible pathways must be better
defined to provide a basis for future monitoring and remediation
efforts.<P>

To image structural features that might control DNAPL migration, 8000
ft of seismic reflection data were acquired during the week of July 13,
1992, along four profile lines south of the Bear Creek Burial Grounds.
Data were acquired through the use of an auger gun (which detonates
blank shotgun shells at depths of 2-3 ft) at 10-ft intervals along the
four profile lines.  Additionally, most of the shots were recorded by a
string of 48 hydrophones, which were deployed in existing wells at
depths as great as 500 ft.  These hydrophone data will be used to
determine velocities for processing the seismic reflection data.  They
may also provide additional information on steeply dipping faults or
reflectors and may detect tube waves from active fractures.<P>

Preliminary inspection of part of the reflection data indicates good
reflections at a depth of ~1000 ft.  Offsets of this layer could be
indicative of faulting of the lithologic strata.  It is anticipated
that shallower reflectors will be enhanced by further processing.<P>

<A NAME="6"><H1>6</H1></A>

<H2>Wells of Hydraulic Head Measuring Stations Are Constructed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. B. Dreier, J. Switek, and B. A. Couzens (1)
</DL>

The Hydraulic Head Measuring Stations (HHMS) are well clusters and
single wells that provide data required for evaluating the transition
between shallow and deep groundwater systems and the nature of these
systems.  Specifically, this project provides a means for defining the
bounds of the uppermost aquifer; identifying potential pathways of
off-site contamination for shallow, intermediate, and deep groundwater
flow; and evaluating the capacity for contaminant transport in
intermediate and deep groundwater flow systems.<P>

As part of FY 1992 HHMS activities, three wells have been constructed
along the south perimeter of Haw Ridge in Oak Ridge.  The wells are
located roughly along geologic strike; two of the wells straddle White
Oak Creek, and the third is sited west of the creek.  The wells will be
instrumented with multiport measuring systems so that a vertical
distribution of water samples and pressure measurements can be
obtained.  Initial examination of core and borehole geophysical logs
shows that all three boreholes are collared in the Pumpkin Valley Shale
and intersect the Rome Formation at varying depths, reflecting local
relief in the Pumpkin Valley ShaleRome Formation contact and possibly
in the underlying Copper Creek Thrust Fault.  All three wells are
flowing artesian, and the elevated heads are attributed to recharge
from neighboring Haw Ridge.<P>

Estimated flow rates vary among the wells from ~0.1 gal/min to 25
gal/min.  The largest flow rate is observed in the well that is
apparently finished within or immediately above the Copper Creek Thrust
Fault.  This well will be deepened so that the well is finished in
Chickamauga Group rocks within the footwall of the thrust fault.  Water
chemistry and hydraulic head measurements obtained from the finished
wells will allow us to evaluate hydrogeologic relationships between
proposed stratified flow systems and a thrust faulted geologic system
of carbonate and clastic lithologies.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="7"><H1>7</H1></A>

<H2>New Methods Are Being Developed for Installing Shallow Monitoring
Wells at Contaminated Sites</H2>

<DL>
<DT>N. D. Farrow
</DL>

For shallow groundwater characterization, driven wells offer advantages
over augered wells.  Those advantages are as follows: (1) driven wells
minimize solid waste, (2) equipment is portable, (3) equipment can be
remotely operated, and (4) installation is rapid and relatively
inexpensive.  Because driven wells generate no soil trimmings,
solid-waste or contaminant-transfer issues are of minimal concern.  If
driven wells must be retrieved, they can be retrieved into a sleeve
that can be sealed for transporting to the decontamination facility.
Retrieval is simple and can be accomplished immediately after the need
to retrieve a well is determined.  The portability of the equipment
makes it possible to install wells in areas where it is difficult or
impossible to use a conventional drill rig.  The capacity to remotely
operate equipment provides a margin of operator safety not common to
conventional drill rigs.  Disadvantages of driven wells are that they
are limited to unconsolidated soils, and installation is relatively
shallow.<P>

The Geosciences Section has developed unique capabilities derived from
the driven well concept.  We have placed standard pipe-size drive
points as small as 1/2 in. to as large as 2 in. in a variety of
hazardous waste environments.  We are using and continuing to develop
well designs for special purposes.<P>

One design permits the sampling of discrete zones, which enables water
quality to be profiled.  The device is driven to the desired depth; the
protected screen is exposed; multiple samples or water level
measurements can be taken; and the process can be repeated until the
desired depth or refusal is reached.  When the well is of no further
use, it can be withdrawn.  Two options are available: (1) when an
expendable point and screen are used, the casing can be used to grout
and seal the hole; (2) a retrievable point permits recovery of the
complete system.<P>

Multiport systems, which permit multilevel sampling within a single
casing, are being used with conventional auger installations.  We are
developing a flush-coupled multiport system that can be driven or
pushed into unconsolidated material to accomplish the same goal but in
a single step installation.  This device can be used in soils having an
adequate clay content to seal against the casing material or in areas
where groundwater is stratified.<P>

These techniques have been successfully used in characterization
studies of low-level radioactive waste sites.  In Solid Waste Storage
Area (SWSA) 4 the capacity to remotely operate equipment was developed
to eliminate the concern over puncturing pressurized cylinders that
might be encountered.  Below SWSA 5, water quality profiling showed the
presence of a discrete flow path for 3H and 90Sr migration with
concurrent diffusion into the soil matrix.  The multiport system is
being developed in conjunction with this work and has future use at
sites both on and off the Oak Ridge Reservation.<P>

Bioremediation of a diesel fuel spill on Kwajalein Atoll in the
Republic of the Marshall Islands is in progress using wells, soil
corers, and gas probes installed with portable-driven equipment.  The
size of the test cells and their spacial arrangement make it impossible
to use a conventional drill rig.<P>

Augered wells provide more precise installation and more flexibility in
design but are more labor intensive and expensive in terms of waste
disposal.  For remedial investigations a combination of driven and
augered wells may be most effective.  When a plume is being delineated,
for example, several drive points can be placed, samples taken, results
analyzed, and augered wells located at strategic points for subsequent
monitoring.<P>

<A NAME="8"><H1>8</H1></A>

<H2>Transport of Contaminated Sediment in the White Oak Creek Catchment
During Floods Is Evaluated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>T. A. Fontaine and H. L. Boston
</DL>

Over the past 49 years, operations and waste disposal activities at
ORNL have resulted in the contamination of parts of the White Oak Creek
(WOC) catchment.  The contaminants presenting the highest risk to human
health and the environment are particle reactive and are associated
with the soils and sediments in the WOC drainage system.  When erosion
occurs during floods, contaminants are transported both within the
catchment and off-site into the Clinch River.<P>

A data collection program and a modeling investigation are being used
to estimate the magnitude of contaminated sediment transport during
floods and to develop strategies for controlling the off-site transport
of contaminants.  A nested series of models will predict the movement
of sediment from subcatchments to the main channels and floodplain and
will link with models for transport in the Clinch River.<P>

Results from several storms sampled during the winter of 1991-92
indicate that nonlinear relationships exist between precipitation
intensity, streamflow, suspended sediment concentration, particle size
of suspended sediment, and contaminant concentration.  Therefore,
predictions of the off-site transport of particle-reactive contaminants
during extreme floods and future land-use changes cannot be based on
the extrapolation of field measurements made during moderate floods.
Instead, these nonlinear relationships will be simulated for extreme
flood conditions using computer models, which are being developed.
Although driven by the need to predict the transport of contaminated
sediments under future conditions, the modeling effort requires a new
application of basic principles of streamflow generation and sediment
dynamics, and the results of model development and testing have
implications for both basic and applied applications.<P>

<A NAME="9"><H1>9</H1></A>

<H2>Soil Washing/Leaching May Be a Feasible Restoration Technology for
Uranium-Contaminated Soils at Fernald</H2>

<DL>
<DT>C. W. Francis
</DL>

Large volumes of uranium-contaminated soils (some in excess of 1,000
pCi/g) are present at the former DOE-operated Feed Materials Production
Center near Fernald, Ohio.  Restoration as well as decontamination and
decommission activities are being planned for this facility.  To
eliminate the potential need for the long-term disposal of these
high-volume soils, soil decontamination technologies are needed.<P>

Research is under way on the selective leaching of uranium from these
soils.  The objective is to leach the soils with a nonhazardous
extracting solution that selectively removes uranium from soil without
significantly altering the soil's physicochemical characteristics or
agronomic production capacity.  Initial extraction tests using citric
acid and sodium carbonate on soil samples containing ~280 pCi/g were
lowered to activities &lt;10 pCi/g, a level well below the proposed 35
pCi/g cleanup level.  These initial tests are encouraging and imply
that a soil washing/leaching technology might be used to decontaminate
soils at the Fernald site.<P>

<A NAME="10"><H1>10</H1></A>

<H2>Coal Resources and Recent Faulting Are Related to the Development
of the Cretaceous Sevier Foreland Basin of the Southwest United States</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. M. Goldstrand (1)
</DL>

Stratigraphic studies and computer backstrip-modeling in conjunction
with more concise age-dating techniques provide new insights into the
development of the Late Cretaceous Sevier foreland basin of the
Southwest United States.  Between ~94 million and 89 million years ago,
the foreland developed into an asymmetric basin (deepening to the west)
bounded by thrust-faulted uplands to the west and the Cretaceous seaway
to the east.  From ~89 million to 80 million years ago, although the
foreland generally represented an underfilled asymmetric basin,
high-angle brittle faulting occurred within the foreland, disrupting
sedimentary facies and dispersal patterns.<P>

The presence of these Cretaceous high-angle fault blocks within the
foreland basin strongly affects the distribution of coal-bearing units
in southern Utah.  Several thick and laterally continuous coal beds
thin rapidly or pinch out across these Cretaceous structures.  Between
80 million and 65 million years ago, the basin overfilled, and rivers
began draining to the northeast.  High-angle faults active within the
foreland from 89 million to 80 million years ago were reactivated
during the early Tertiary (65 million to 50 million years ago) and are
active today as the eastern boundary of what geologists call the Basin
and Range structural province (e.g., Hurricane, Sevier, and Paunsaugunt
faults).<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="11"><H1>11</H1></A>

<H2>Can 137Cs Be a Tracer for Material Transport from Arctic Tundra
in Lakes?</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. M. Grebmeier (1), L. W. Cooper, I. L. Larsen, C. Solis (2), and
C. R. Olsen (3)
</DL>

Recent 14C studies in the Arctic indicate that organic matter is being
lost from tundra and may be accumulating in lakes.  Since 1989 we have
been studying 137Cs (30.2-year half-life) inventories in upland tundra
and in lake sediments at Toolik Lake, Alaska (68 deg 38' N; 149 deg 38'
W).  The watershed covers 65 km^2, and Toolik Lake covers 1.5 km^2; the
lake has a mean and maximum depth of 7 and 25 m, respectively.
Deposition of radiocesium from nuclear testing (decay-corrected to
1991) is ~122 mBq/cm^2 for this latitude.  Cesium-137 inventories in
tundra were consistent with flux input estimates, ranging from 102.1 to
222.1 mBq/cm^2, and were concentrated in the top 10 cm of soil,
associated with mosses, lichens, peat, and other organic material.  In
addition to the tundra, we also observed rapid translocation of 137Cs
from soil into annual Arctic berries used for food by native peoples
and wildlife, although the modest levels (20-171 mBq/g dry wt) do not
constitute a health hazard (&gt;1500 mBq/g dry wt).<P>

To test whether 137Cs is a suitable marker for following the transfer
of organic material to lakes, ten sediment cores were collected in 1991
along a transect in Toolik Lake from near the main inflow to the lake
outlet.  Cesium-137 sediment inventories ranged from 140.8 to 202.7
mBq/cm^2 at the inlet side of the lake, dropping to inventories ranging
from 17.7 to 44.9 mBq/cm^2 nearer to the outlet, in spite of similar
depths (5-10 m).  Toolik Lake is an oligotrophic lake, and 210Pb
measurements corroborate a previous study that indicated a very low
sediment accumulation rate (~0.02 cm/year).  The high 137Cs lake
sediment inventories observed near the inlet, similar to tundra core
inventories, indicate an accumulation of 137Cs-tagged particulate
matter that has eroded from land into the lake.  The low 137Cs lake
sediment inventories observed near the outlet suggest that scouring and
removal processes dominate.  A basic inventory of the total 137Cs input
in the region, including both the watershed and lake surface area,
indicates a net 0.026% of the tundra within the watershed is eroded
annually and accumulates in Toolik Lake, which contributes to the low
sediment accumulation regime in the lake.  Although the accumulation of
particulate organic carbon is low in the lake, a large fraction of
organic carbon may be lost from the tundra and enter the lake as
dissolved organic carbon that is not associated with 137Cs, which is a
particle-reactive radionuclide.  The cycling and transport of this
dissolved organic carbon phase, both within the watershed and lake,
require further investigation.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Graduate Program in Ecology, The University of Tennessee,
Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Instituto de F&iacute;sica, Universidad Nacional
Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico, M&eacute;xico.</I>
<DT>(3) <I>Office of Health and Environmental Research, DOE, Washington,
D.C.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="12"><H1>12</H1></A>

<H2>Subsurface Zones of High and Low Groundwater Flow Are Related to
Contaminant Transport from SWSA 5</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. S. Hicks
</DL>

Of all the contaminants transported through the White Oak Creek
watershed, a large portion come from Solid Waste Storage Area (SWSA)
5.  An understanding of subsurface transport processes is essential in
order to produce realistic predictions of future contaminant discharge
and evaluations of proposed remedial actions.<P>

A preliminary investigation was initiated in 1991 to characterize the
subsurface movement of contaminants (primarily 3H) from an area on the
southeast edge of SWSA 5.  The vertical profile of 3H (0.02 to 279
micro-Ci/L) observed over the sampled interval (0 to 10 ft deep) may be
a result of upward diffusion from a hydraulically dominant fracture (or
fractured zone) below the sampled interval.  The study continued this
year with the main objective of defining where the most permeable zones
exist in the subsurface.  This was accomplished through the use of two
methods.<P>

The first was a survey of vertical flows at selected depths within a
26-ft-deep borehole using the electromagnetic borehole flowmeter
developed by the Engineering Laboratory of the Tennessee Valley
Authority.  The second method, using borehole dilution (point-dilution)
tests, was also performed in the 26-ft borehole by isolating intervals
with packers and introducing distilled water to the interval.  The
interval was slowly mixed, and the specific conductance of the interval
was measured over time as groundwater flow through the section
gradually removed the distilled water.  Estimates of groundwater flows
for the different intervals were computed from the specific conductance
vs time relationships.  The results from the two methods correspond
quite well.<P>

The electromagnetic borehole flowmeter results suggest that the zone
from 15 to 18 ft is relatively the most permeable in the borehole,
whereas the dilution test results indicate that the highest
water-bearing zone is within the interval of 13 to 16.25 ft.  Next year
3H activities will be determined in the different subsurface zones.  A
comparison of the 3H activity in the most hydraulically active regions
with the activity in the surrounding matrix can be used to help
determine whether primary sources are still active and whether
contaminant release from SWSA 5 to the stream will continue to increase
or decrease.<P>

<A NAME="13"><H1>13</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Vitrification Melt Is Successfully Monitored Through the
Use of Acoustic Methods and Thermal Sensors While Being Demonstrated on
a Tracer-Level Radioactive Test Trench</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. Jacobs, N. Dunbar (1), D. Farmer, M. Naney (2), M. Peterson (3),
T. Powell (3), B. Spalding, M. Speece (1), R. Williams (1), and A.
Witten (4)
</DL>

ORNL, Pacific Northwest Laboratory, and The University of Tennessee
staff successfully completed a joint test of in situ vitrification
(ISV) technology on a scale-model trench.  Objectives of the test
included (1) minimized accumulation of 137Cs in the off-gas processing
trailer, (2) evaluation of seismic imaging and advanced thermometric
methods for monitoring the progression of melting and its application
to natural magmatic systems, (3) elucidation of melting and volatile
release processes, (4) assessment of the radiological and operational
performance factors associated with applying ISV to a radioactive site,
and (5) confirmation of the durability of an ISV waste form containing
radioactive components.<P>

Approximately 10 mCi of 137Cs in a sludge sample (~500 g) from inactive
seepage pit 2 was placed into a half-scale model of trench 7. Power
(~200-250 kW) was applied to the electrodes for 127 h to reach a final
depth of ~2.7 m (9 ft). Subsidence to the top of the ISV block as a
result of the volume decrease during melting was ~1.5 m (5 ft). The
size of the ISV block created was ~3 m (10 ft) in diameter with an
estimated mass of 12 Mg.  Approximately 2.7% of the 137Cs was
volatilized from the melt.<P>

In a previous field demonstration using stable cesium carbonate rather
than radioisotopes, only 0.12% of the cesium volatilized. To determine
if this difference was related to differences in materials properties,
a study was completed on the volatilization of 134Cs from laboratory
crucibles containing various mixtures of soil and limestone or dolomite
that had been used in both the present and previous field
demonstrations. No significant differences in cesium volatilization
were observed related to different sources of soil or carbonate gravel
used in the two demonstrations. All of the radioactive material was
trapped within the prefilter assembly of the high-efficiency
particulate air filters, thus successfully meeting objective No. 1.<P>

Sequential samples from particle filters indicate that most of the
137Cs was released over a 24-h period, when the melt first contacted
the zone containing the waste. Core drilling confirmed that the ISV
block crystallized to a gray, rocklike substance, and textures were
observed in drill core samples, including void spaces containing
partial fillings of long acicular crystals and holocrystalline masses
of coalesced spherulites.  Thermal profiles were successful in
monitoring both the progression of melting and temperatures within the
melt.  Seismic imaging successfully illustrated major differences
between acoustic properties of the soil and melt regions recorded at
different times during heating and cooling.<P>

For example, changes in the traces on the transmitted, or
forward-scattered, side of the melt are greater than on the reflected,
or back-scattered, side. Furthermore, differences in the travel times
for the first arrivals are less obvious than travel time and amplitude
changes in the later arrivals. Future work during FY 1992 will
emphasize detailed testing to assess the durability of the ISV
material, evaluation of the ISV process engineering data, and analysis
of the chemical, seismic, and thermal data. <P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Process Engineering Department, Pacific Northwest
Laboratory, Richland, Washington.</I>
<DT>(3) <I>Office of Operational Readiness and Facility Safety,
ORNL.</I>
<DT>(4) <I>Energy Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="14"><H1>14</H1></A>

<H2>Observations from the Colloidal Borescope Suggest Modifications to
Groundwater Sampling Procedures</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. M. Kearl and N. E. Korte
</DL>

The literature presents many arguments regarding the principles
involved in obtaining a representative water sample from a monitoring
well.  Controversial aspects of well sampling include purging,
filtration, and pumping rate.  These issues were reexamined by means of
direct observation in the borehole using a newly developed device--the
colloidal borescope.  Observation of colloidal movement with the
borescope suggests that modifications to sampling procedures are
necessary.<P>

Insertion of a sampling device results in the mobilization of colloids
sorbed to the surrounding formation.  Because of these colloids, 24 h
should pass before sampling is initiated.  In addition, horizontal
laminar flow was observed in the well screen, which indicates that
stagnant water in the well casing does not mix with the water in the
well screen.  Therefore, dedicated sampling devices should be placed in
wells to eliminate disturbances and subsequent increases in colloidal
densities resulting from the insertion of the sampler.  If dedicated
sampling devices are pumped at 100 mL/min or less, no significant
increase in the colloidal density occurs.<P>

Because natural colloids could be a transport mechanism for otherwise
immobile contaminant species, collected samples should not be filtered
when the total mobile contaminant load is assessed.  Finally, this
approach can save a considerable amount of money.  When well purging is
eliminated prior to sampling, the savings of both the time involved
with purging and the cost associated with purge-water disposal can be
substantial.<P>

<A NAME="15"><H1>15</H1></A>

<H2>Deconvolution of Atmospheric CO2 Record Provides Global Estimate of
CO2 Exchange with Ecosystems Not Disturbed by Land-Use Change</H2>

<DL>
<DT>A. W. King
</DL>

The history of atmospheric CO2 exchange with the terrestrial biosphere
can be inferred by the deconvolution of data recording the history of
changes in atmospheric CO2.  The equation for changes in the mass of
atmospheric CO2,

<PRE>
	dc_a
        ---- = F_i + F_r - F_as,                         (1)
         dt
</PRE>

is solved for the unknown or residual flux F_r, where c_a is the
observed mass of atmospheric CO2, F_i is the known flux of CO2 to the
atmosphere from industrial sources, and F_as is the net CO2 flux from
the atmosphere to the ocean, as calculated by a carbon cycle model.
The residual flux, F_r, can be interpreted as net flux between the
atmosphere and the terrestrial biosphere by making the following
assumptions:  (1) Eq. 1 completely describes the atmosphere's CO2
balance; (2) all anthropogenic CO2 emissions are distributed among
atmosphere, ocean, and terrestrial biosphere reservoirs; and (3) F_as
completely describes net oceanic uptake.<P>

By assuming no net atmospheric CO2 exchange with terrestrial ecosystems
that have remained undisturbed by land-use change, the residual flux
can be interpreted as an estimate of the net terrestrial biospheric CO2
exchange that accompanies changes in land use.  If an estimate of CO2
release from land-use change is also included (replacing F_i in Eq. 1
with F_a = F_i + F_l, where F_a is total anthropogenic input and F_l is
the flux from land use), the residual flux can be interpreted as the
net exchange between the atmosphere and those portions of the
terrestrial biosphere not disturbed by land-use change.<P>

Deconvolutions using three variants of a box-diffusion model of oceanic
carbon turnover without inputs from land-use change suggest that
terrestrial ecosystems have historically (1900-80) been a small and
declining net source (&lt;0.5 gigaton of carbon per year) and recently
(ca. 1980) been a small net sink (&lt;0.5 gigaton of carbon per year).
When published estimates of land-use emissions from a
historical-ecological model of land-use change are included, the
deconvolutions yield estimates of a recent (ca. 1980) moderate-to-large
(0 to 3 gigatons of carbon per year) sink in natural or unaltered
ecosystems.  These results suggest that either net releases from past
changes in land use have been appreciably lower than those estimated by
the model of land-use change or a significant amount of carbon uptake
and sequestering by terrestrial ecosystems not experiencing land-use
change has occurred.<P>

Continuing investigations focus on developing global models of
terrestrial ecosystems for reevaluating estimates of past emissions
from land-use change and testing hypotheses about the responses of
natural or disturbed ecosystems to changing environmental conditions.
For example, can natural ecosystems sequester the amounts of carbon
implied by the deconvolution results?  And if so, what mechanisms
(e.g., CO2 fertilization) might be consistent with both the magnitude
and timing of the implied sink?<P>

<A NAME="16"><H1>16</H1></A>

<H2>Groundwater Remediation Strategy Is Developed for the Kansas City
Plant</H2>

<DL>
<DT>N. E. Korte and D. E. Brown (1)
</DL>

Groundwater at the Kansas City Plant (KCP) is contaminated with
chlorinated solvents, and treatment is being performed by
pump-and-treat.  Treatment goals, as developed through a consent order
with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), are maximum
concentration levels or their equivalent.  The difficulty with the
approach is that pump-and-treat technology will not restore the aquifer
to the established goals.  ORNL scientists working at KCP recognized
this problem at an early stage and have assisted KCP in developing a
groundwater strategy that places an increased emphasis on environmental
risk and cost effectiveness.<P>

Preliminary risk considerations reveal the following:  (1) The alluvial
aquifer at KCP has a low yield and no projected uses.  The low recharge
and the low flow rate in the silty-clay matrix have led to the
establishment of reducing conditions.  Such conditions have mobilized
naturally occurring Fe, Mn, and As, which exceed either secondary (Fe
and Mn) or primary (As) drinking water standards in some locations.
(2) The bedrock aquifers at KCP are not threatened by the contaminated
alluvium.  (3) Calculations demonstrate that the quantity of
contamination that could be discharged to the surrounding streams is so
low that contaminants would not be detectable.<P>

The long-term strategy, therefore, is that ORNL scientists are
assisting KCP in the preparation of an Alternate Concentration Limit
petition so that the groundwater treatment program has goals that are
both cost-effective and achievable.  Preparation of the petition will
involve extensive computer modeling and hydraulic testing.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Environmental Restoration Program, Kansas City Plant.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="17"><H1>17</H1></A>

<H2>Exploratory Sampling Program Is Conducted in Los Alamos, New
Mexico, Subdivision</H2>

<DL>
<DT>N. E. Korte and S. E. Wagner (1)
</DL>

A sampling and analysis program was conducted in a residential location
in Los Alamos, New Mexico, known as the Western Area.  The project was
conducted in response to a concern that brain cancer incidence was
higher than expected.  This concern extended to a consideration that
activities from Los Alamos National Laboratory (LANL) might have
contaminated the area.<P>

ORNL personnel from Grand Junction, Colorado, performed the data
evaluation and interpretation.  The sampling and analysis program was
exploratory and was designed to determine whether the Western Area
should be included as an official investigation site for the LANL
Environmental Restoration (ER) program.  The sampling design emphasized
areas of suspected high incidence of primary brain cancer and locations
likely to accumulate contaminants.  This design served to determine
whether a full-scale program was necessary to assess the extent of
contamination.<P>

Probability plots were used to partition the sample data into its
constituent populations.  Two populations are typically present in
contaminated locations, one representing background and the other
contamination.  The probability plots and an extensive literature
review demonstrated that the analytical results did not show an impact
from LANL activities.  Organic analytes that were detected included
fluoranthene (one sample) and chlorinated pesticides.  Industrial and
laboratory solvents were not detected.  Inorganics, except for nickel
(one sample) and traces of cyanide (three samples in concentrations
below the detection limits for most of the other samples), were
reported at concentrations typical of native soils.  Radiochemical
analyses showed that the concentrations present were typical of
background whether due to natural occurrence or fallout.  The
conclusions drawn from the data were that LANL operations had not
affected the area and further investigation was unnecessary.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Environmental Restoration Program, Los Alamos National
Laboratory, Los Alamos, New Mexico.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="18"><H1>18</H1></A>

<H2>A 137Cs Hot Particle Is Discovered and Isolated from a Municipal
Wastewater Treatment Sludge Sample</H2>

<DL>
<DT>I. L. Larsen, E. A. Stetar (1), S. Y. Lee, and H. L. Boston
</DL>

Several industries in the area served by the Oak Ridge, Tennessee,
sanitary sewage plant dispose of treated radioactive wastewater, under
state regulation, directly into the system.  The sewage system also
receives radionuclides used in medical applications from body wastes of
patients inoculated for treatment.  In addition, naturally occurring
and fallout radionuclides also enter the sanitary system through storm
runoff.  These radionuclides usually enter the system in liquid
(soluble) form but may become associated with particulate matter or
become insoluble and nonexchangeable during treatment.<P>

As part of a tracer study to investigate the fate of certain
radionuclides entering the Oak Ridge wastewater treatment plant, 1-L
samples of primary-treatment sludge were collected during a preliminary
investigation to evaluate radionuclide input concentrations.  These
samples were collected intermittently over time and counted directly
for gamma-ray radioactivity.<P>

During the analysis of these samples, one sample became suspect when
the 137Cs activity exceeded the other sample values by more than two
orders of magnitude.  Reanalysis of the sample after vigorous shaking
produced an additional anomalously high value but of differing
concentration, which indicated nonhomogeneity.  The presence of a "hot
particle" was suspected because such results could be obtained by the
presence of a particle in variable locations in the beaker with respect
to the detector.  Since the beakers had been thoroughly washed and
rinsed before use, the occurrence of prior contamination was
eliminated.<P>

The particle was isolated by repeatedly dividing the sample and
analyzing each portion.  A final 1-mL sample containing the hot
particle was dried and the hot particle quantified, indicating a 137Cs
activity of 1.82 kBq.2  The particle was then prepared for
energy-dispersive X-ray spectrometry (EDX) and scanning electron
microscope analysis to determine composition and size.<P>

The radioactive particle appeared cylindrical in shape, had a diameter
of ~50 micro-m and a length of ~20 micro-m, and was not an aggregate.
The lack of any dominant EDX spectrum, other than that attributed to
the gold spectra from preparation for analysis, suggested a dominant
carbon composition rather than metallic.<P>

Subsequent analyses on some 200 samples of primary and secondary
treatment wastewater samples and some 150 anaerobic digested sludge
samples from this treatment plant have not indicated the presence of
additional hot particles.  Since state-licensed facilities must
prefilter releases through 0.45-micro-m pore size filters, the particle
may have originated through a malfunction of a filtering system.
Although the particle itself is probably anthropogenic in origin based
on its shape, size, and activity level, its explicit source remains an
enigma.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Performance Technology Group, Inc., Nashville, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>I. L. Larsen, E. A. Stetar, S. Y. Lee, and H. L. Boston,
``Discovery of a Cesium-137 Hot Particle in Municipal Wastewater
Treatment Sludge,'' </I>Health Phys.<I> <B>62</B>(3), 235-38 (1992).</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="19"><H1>19</H1></A>

<H2>Studies Reveal Uranium Particulate to Be the Dominant Form of
Uranium in DOE Fernald Project Site</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. Y. Lee and J. D. Marsh, Jr.
</DL>

The DOE Office of Technology Development has established the Integrated
Demonstration (ID) for remediation of uranium-contaminated soils.  The
Fernald site was selected as the DOE facility for the field
demonstration.  The principal objective of this ID is to evaluate and
compare the versatility, efficiency, and economics of various
technologies that may be combined into systems for the removal of
uranium from contaminated soils.<P>

The ID characterization task group designed a study to obtain basic
information relating to soil properties and the nature of uranium
contamination of the soil at the site.  Such information is essential
for the selection of (1) contaminated soils for use in treatability
studies, (2) a field demonstration area at the site, and (3) integrated
technologies.  The task group selected five areas and collected two
core samples from each area.<P>

Researchers investigated the nature of soil contamination by examining
(1) uranium distribution with soil depth, (2) soil particle size
distributions and their uranium contribution, (3) soil chemical and
physical properties, (4) particle density of soil and contaminant, (5)
mineralogical and microscopic properties of soil and contaminant, (6)
chemical leaching characteristics, and (7) background soil uranium
content and soil properties.<P>

The results indicated (1) except in an area contaminated by acidic
solution spills, the contamination depth of most areas was shallow
(usually &lt;10 cm containing from 10 to 2800 pCi/g); (2) background
uranium concentration of off-site soils was &lt;4 pCi/g; (3) the sand-
and silt-size fraction of soils contained from 48 to 79% of the uranium
in soils; (4) the dominant form of uranium was sand- and silt-sized
particulate often associated with Ca, P, Fe, and Si; (5) most of the
uranium particulates had a density &gt;2.9 g/mL, however; and (6)
considerable amounts of soil uranium, 10 to 49% and 20 to 75%, could be
extracted using 2% solutions of ammonium carbonate and citric acid,
respectively.<P>

On the basis of the soil characterization results, two areas, Plant 1
Drum Storage area and the Incinerator area, were selected for use in
treatability studies and in situ characterization demonstration areas.
The Plant 1 Drum Storage area was contaminated by uranium product
spills, and the Incinerator area was contaminated by airborne uranium
materials during the incineration of contaminated materials.
Particulate uranium was the dominant form associated with the sand and
silt fractions of both soils.  Some uranium in the soils was not
readily extractable.  Therefore, simple chemical extraction or size
separation alone would not effectively reduce waste volume in soil
remediation.  The development of more advanced selective extraction
technology and density-based physical separation technology is needed
to meet the ID cleanup goal.<P>

<A NAME="20"><H1>20</H1></A>

<H2>Major Book Synthesizes the Results of the Integrated Forest Study</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. E. Lindberg and D. W. Johnson (1)
</DL>

In 1985 ESD initiated the Integrated Forest Study, a major 6-year study
of the role of atmospheric deposition in forest nutrient cycles.  This
was the most comprehensive study ever to use state-of-the-art methods
and common protocols to measure atmospheric deposition in a wide
variety of forests over an extended period.  The study was truly
interdisciplinary, involving for the first time in such an extensive
project researchers from the atmospheric, ecological, and soil
sciences.  ESD scientists designed the project, obtained the funding,
and managed the work, which involved more than 25 scientists
representing more than 20 different institutions and universities in
North America and Europe.<P>

The study established forest research sites at 17 locations in the
eastern and western United States and in Canada and Norway.
Atmospheric deposition and forest nutrient cycles were studied at each
site during the period 1986-89.  To assure data comparability, common
protocols were established by the Integrated Forest Study research
group prior to the initiation of data collection and were followed
throughout the study.  In addition to the field tasks, the study
included several laboratory studies to further elucidate selected
deposition or biogeochemical processes such as foliar leaching, canopy
uptake, and cation exchange and nitrogen saturation in soils.  The
complete results of the Integrated Forest Study have been published in
a single volume authored by all the participants.<P>

The primary objective of the study was to assess the effects of
deposition on nutrient cycles in forests.  The highlights include the
following:

<UL>
<LI>Atmospheric deposition of acidity and oxides of sulfur and nitrogen
was greatest at the high elevation sites, where cloud water impaction
was important.  Deposition was also higher in the southeastern United
States than in the Northeast, an unexpected result that could not have
been predicted from existing deposition networks or from bulk
deposition measurements often used in forests.

<LI>Acidic deposition and ozone exposure pose little potential for
depleting foliar nutrient pools, with the possible exception of the
mountain sites.

<LI>Deposition of sulfate and nitrate has clearly increased the rate of
base cation leaching from most of the forest soils in the Integrated
Forest Study by 20-60%, and in the most acidic soils, deposition has
increased potentially toxic aluminum levels as well.

<LI>Deposition may have contributed to the decline of red spruce stands
in the Smoky Mountains by increasing the leaching of both nitrate and
aluminum.
</UL>

The Integrated Forest Study has for the first time accurately
quantified atmospheric inputs into biogeochemical cycles in forests.
Without exception, these new estimates are substantially larger than
measurements obtained by traditional methods using bulk collectors.
These new data create significant changes in how nutrient cycles are
interpreted.  Forecasts of nutrient depletion resulting from deposition
or harvesting, for example, may require important revisions.  The study
has considerably expanded the data base on forest biogeochemical cycles
based on measurements using common protocols.  This facilitates
improved site comparisons and the application of new models.  In
addition to the comprehensive analysis of these data in the book, the
information will prove useful for further applications.  According to
one book reviewer, ``This synthesis of results from many sites has
provided convincing evidence of a number of issues in atmospheric
deposition, and it will be regarded as an important text for years to
come.''<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Desert Research Institute, Reno, Nevada.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>D. W. Johnson and S. E. Lindberg, eds.  </I>Atmospheric
Deposition and Forest Nutrient Cycling<I>, Ecological Studies Series
No. 91, Springer-Verlag, 1992.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="21"><H1>21</H1></A>

<H2>What Is Our National Responsibility for Greenhouse Gas Emissions?</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. Marland
</DL>

As of October 1990, 13 countries had announced or were seriously
considering national targets for greenhouse gas emissions.  At the
first meeting of the International Negotiating Committee for a
greenhouse convention in early 1991, the United States announced,
``Implementation of the President's Comprehensive Climate Change
Strategy will result in U.S. greenhouse gas emissions in the year 2000
being equal to or below 1987 levels.''<P>

If the international community is ready to contemplate limiting
greenhouse gas emissions, limits need to be based on some equitable
accounting.  Proposals to limit emissions on a per capita basis, on a
per-unit-of-gross-national-product basis, and even on a
per-unit-of-area basis have surfaced.  Proposed allocations take into
account current emissions and are formulated in light of a lifetime
allocation.<P>

Our data base of CO2 emissions is the foundation for much of the
discussion.  The concept of greenhouse warming potential, most fully
elaborated in the report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate
Change Working Group I, has provided a beginning for aggregating the
greenhouse effect of a variety of gases that have different atmospheric
lifetimes and infrared absorption properties.<P>

Our tabulations of national CO2 emissions provide estimates of CO2
physically discharged within national boundaries.  These numbers are
useful for geochemical modeling and offer insight for understanding
historical trends, but they do not get to the issue of national
responsibility or accountability.  The problem is well illustrated by a
comparison of an estimate of emissions from California, prepared with
our assistance, with one prepared by the California Energy Commission
(CEC).  The difference is largely in how the two accounts chose to
treat emissions from, for example, a coal-fired power plant when the
plant resides elsewhere but the electricity is used in California.<P>

CEC was willing to accept responsibility for the CO2 even as the group
accepted the electricity; similarly it took responsibility for fuel
used in refineries elsewhere if the refined products were to be used in
California.  On the other hand, some economic benefit must accrue in
the area where the power plant resides, and it is there that decisions
are made regarding fuel choice, plant design, and operating
efficiency.  The difference in emissions is not trivial; California
emissions of CO2 from fossil fuels increased by 17% when CEC accepted
responsibility for imported electricity and refined products.  However,
CEC did not broach the general idea of embodied energy (i.e., the
energy and CO2 emissions embodied in energy-intensive products like
aluminum and petrochemicals).  One way for a nation to meet CO2
emissions goals would be to export, intentionally or unintentionally,
energy- intensive industries and to import the final products.  This is
true unless, of course, the national accounts of CO2 emissions include
emissions embodied in traded materials and products.<P>

<A NAME="22"><H1>22</H1></A>

<H2>Leachates from Two Shallow Waste Burial Sites Prove to Be Heavy in
Deuterium</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. D. Marsh, Jr., and L. W. Cooper
</DL>

Most low-level radioactive wastes on the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR)
are in shallow trenches that come into contact with rainfall and
subsurface flow.  Although this shallow groundwater takes on new
chemical characteristics rather quickly when it interacts with the
wastes in the trenches, it should reflect the stable isotope
composition of local rainfall.<P>

Leachates from two shallow (&lt;20 ft) waste sites, one at the Solid
Waste Storage Area 4 Bathtubbing Trench at ORNL and the other at Bear
Creek Burial Ground at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant, have been analyzed for
the stable isotopes deuterium (2H) and 18O.  The relationship between
these isotopes of the two sites was compared with the global meteoric
water line, which describes the fractionation processes of the isotopes
during the global water cycle and which is expressed by the equation
delta-2H = 8 delta-18O + 10.<P>

Analysis revealed that the data from the sites better fit a line
expressed by the equation delta-2H = 8 delta-18O + 2O.  These results
indicate that the leachates are relatively enriched in 2H.  Analysis of
unevaporated rainfall also indicates that the levels of 2H in local
precipitation are higher than the levels that would be expected from
the global meteoric water line.  Therefore, the water in these shallow
wells may reflect a local meteoric water line, although more extensive
sampling of rainfall is needed to adequately develop such a line for
ORR.  The development of a local meteoric water line would aid
significantly in the study and interpretation of shallow groundwater
flow.<P>

<A NAME="23"><H1>23</H1></A>

<H2>New System Is Developed for Mapping Soil Contaminated with Heavy
Metals</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. E. Nyquist and M. S. Emery (1)
</DL>

Superfund sites typically include areas where the soil is contaminated
with heavy metals such as Pb, As, Hg, and Cd.  A good screening method
can greatly reduce the cost of site characterization by decreasing the
number of soil samples sent to the laboratory.  The U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency (EPA) has had considerable success mapping metals
contamination using commercially available portable X-ray fluorescence
(XRF) analyzers.  To further increase the efficiency of XRF screening,
EPA sponsored a 3-year work-for-others contract to interface an XRF
analyzer with the Ultrasonic Ranging and Data System (USRADS) developed
at ORNL by researchers in ORNL's Health and Safety Research Division
and Instrumentation and Controls Division.<P>

USRADS automatically tracks the position of a surveyor by using an
array of microphones distributed over the survey area to determine the
location of an ultrasonic transmitter carried in the surveyor's
backpack.  The backpack also contains a radio transmitter that
broadcasts the XRF results.  The surveyor's position is calculated and
displayed on a portable computer operated from a van or trailer serving
as a mobile base station.  Each time the portable XRF analyzer
completes a measurement, the location of the surveyor is determined and
stored on a hard disk along with the XRF data received by radio.
Because metal concentrations and measurement locations are available in
the field, a soil sampling strategy can be developed on-site.  The
completed USRADS/XRF system was demonstrated to the EPA in February
1992, and the final project report is in progress.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Instrumentation and Controls Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="24"><H1>24</H1></A>

<H2>Interaction Between Vegetation and Soil Under Conditions Associated
with Global Change Is Studied</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. M. Post, J. Pastor (1), A. W. King, and W. R. Emanuel
</DL>

The terrestrial biosphere is an important component in determining the
concentration of CO2 in the earth's atmosphere.  Changes in atmospheric
CO2 levels since 1860 may have changed the balance between global net
primary production and decomposition.  In order to evaluate this
possibility, it needs to be determined whether the experimental
observations on plant growth affect carbon storage in ecosystems.<P>

Experimental results for forest ecosystems are not currently
available.  We used a forest gap model to evaluate several potential
effects of elevated atmospheric CO2 on the storage of organic matter in
the ecosystem.  These analyses focus on some aspects of ecosystem
carbon dynamics.  However, they ignore many processes and interactions
that are needed to give accurate estimates of changes in forest
ecosystem carbon storage resulting from global changes of climate and
atmospheric CO2 concentration.<P>

Contrary to previous CO2 fertilization experiments using forest gap
models, we show that considerable potential exists for increasing
carbon storage in forest ecosystems as a result of plant responses to
elevated CO2 levels.  All potential plant responses examined (increased
annual basal area increment, decreased water use, increased allocation
of carbon and nitrogen to roots) could increase organic matter in
forest ecosystems.  The amount of increased organic matter storage
depends on species composition, soil water-holding capacity, and
resultant nitrogen dynamics.  Most changes in storage occurred in
aboveground biomass.  The litter and soil organic matter pools changed
very little between model experiments.  The enhancement of net
ecosystem production is relatively short-lived.  The difference in
ecosystem carbon storage between nominal plant response and potential
CO2-enhanced responses does not increase after 100 years or so.<P>

Carbon storage over long periods of time on soils with good
water-holding capacity can be increased on average by 25% if the basal
area of trees grows 50% faster.  Increases in carbon storage can be
even relatively greater in water-limited forest ecosystems.  The
indirect effect of reduced transpiration can have even greater effects
than the direct CO2 growth effects on carbon storage in water-limited
forest ecosystems.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Natural Resources Research Institute, Duluth, Minnesota.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="25"><H1>25</H1></A>

<H2>Simple, Closed-Form Solutions for Hillslope Drainage Were Developed
and Tested</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. E. Sanford
</DL>

Equations for the prediction of the cumulative outflow volume, the flow
rate, and the approximate water table shape during drainage from a
sloping aquifer have been developed.  The equations are based on the
Boussinesq approximation for subsurface flow of water above a sloping
impermeable layer and have been derived for two boundary conditions.<P>

The first boundary condition is where there is a constant depth of
water at the toe of the slope.  The second boundary condition is where
there is a sudden drawdown of the water table at the outflow end.  The
equations developed for the second boundary condition are valid for
both sloping and horizontal aquifers.  The advantage of the theory used
to derive the equations is that, unlike other solutions, the assumption
of a long, thin aquifer is not necessary.  The equations use only
parameters with physical meaning that can easily be measured:  slope,
drainable porosity, saturated hydraulic conductivity, and layer
thickness.<P>

Cornell University validated the equations through a series of
laboratory and field experiments, and ESD refined the theory.  The
model can be used to predict the contribution of subsurface storm flow
to the hydrographs for streams on the Oak Ridge Reservation and to
measure the changes in saturated hydraulic conductivity of
subsurface-flow constructed wetlands used for wastewater treatment.
Work will continue on the development of the theory for application to
converging and diverging hillslopes and to leaky aquifers.<P>

<A NAME="26"><H1>26</H1></A>

<H2>Magmatic Volatiles Condense into the Hot Spring Waters of Loowit
Canyon, Mount St. Helens, Washington</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. Shevenell (1) and F. Goff (2)
</DL>

Geochemical studies on cold meteoric waters, post-1980 hot spring
waters, fumarole emissions from the dacite dome, and volcanic rocks
were conducted at Mount St. Helens from 1985 to 1989 to investigate
possible interactions between the new hot spring system and magmatic
volatiles.  Cold meteoric waters range from -83 to -98 per mil delta-D
and from -11.5 to -3.5 per mil delta-18O.  Hot spring waters are
enriched in delta-18O by as much as 1.5 per mil and also display
enrichments in delta-D relative to cold waters.  However, chemical
geothermometry and chloride-enthalpy relations suggest that the thermal
aquifer supplying the springs has equilibrated at temperatures of 130
deg C; thus, the isotopic enrichments are not easily explained by
high-temperature, rock-water isotopic exchange.<P>

A well-defined isotopic trend is displayed by &gt;400 deg C fumarole
condensate collected from the central crater in 1980 (-33 per mil
delta-D, +6 per mil delta-18O; Evans et al. 1981), condensate samples
collected on the dome, and the cold meteoric and hot spring waters.
The trend indicates that mixing occurs between meteoric water
precipitated in the crater and magmatic water degassing from the dome.
As much as 10% magmatic water occurs in the hot springs and 25-60%
magmatic water occurs in the dome fumaroles.  Tritium analyses of hot
springs (6-10 T.U.) indicate the age of the meteoric component is
&lt;10 years.<P>

Other components in the hot spring waters are also partially derived
from magmatic volatiles.  For example, hot spring Cl (&lt;1050 mg/kg)
must originate by the addition of some fumarole condensate (Cl &lt;=
6900 mg/kg) into the hydrothermal fluid, not solely from the leaching
of volcanic rocks (Cl &lt;= 410 mg/kg).  The B/Cl of the hot spring
waters is similar to the B/Cl of the condensates.  The delta-13C-HCO3
in spring waters (-9.5 to -13.5 per mil) brackets the values obtained
on delta-13C-CO2 of fumaroles (-10.4 to -10.8 per mil), and the 3He:4He
(R:RA) values of hot spring water are 5.7.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, New Mexico.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="27"><H1>27</H1></A>

<H2>Uncertainty Analyses Are Used to Rank the ORNL Waste Area Groupings
on the Basis of Human Health Risks</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. Shevenell (1) and F. O. Hoffman
</DL>

Because finances are limited, it has become necessary to evaluate
contaminated sites to determine which areas pose the greatest potential
threat to the environment.  Potential impacts to human health and the
environment can be evaluated through risk assessment calculations, and
results have been obtained for the ORNL Waste Area Groupings (WAGs)
through the application of deterministic calculations and calculations
that use uncertainty analyses.  Four radionuclides (60Co, 137Cs, 90Sr,
and 3H) were selected for ranking the WAGs because these contaminants
are believed to be among the most important at all ORNL WAGs.  The
assessment endpoint was the maximum exposed individual at two receptor
locations: on-site at WAG 2 and off-site at Clinch River mile 9.5.<P>

It is believed that the majority of the contaminants discharge from
runoff and groundwater to on-site surface waters.  Hence, measured
concentrations and flow rates of on-site surface waters were used to
estimate current and future health risks from surface waters associated
with each WAG. The formulation and parameters recommended by the
National Council on Radiation Protection and the International Atomic
Energy Agency for generic screening calculations were adopted in this
work and adjusted to reflect site-specific climate and behavior
patterns when necessary.  Human health risks associated with
contaminants released from the WAGs were calculated and summed over the
following pathways:  vegetable, fish, beef, water, and milk
consumption; shoreline exposure; and ground exposure from
irrigation.<P>

The uncertainty of risk assessment parameters results in large
differences in calculated risks and ranking of WAGs when deterministic
calculations are used.  Therefore, the overall effects of parameter
uncertainty were considered. Uncertainty analyses are needed to
reliably rank waste sites according to potential health risks
associated with exposure to site contaminants. The results of the study
indicate that the WAGs should be considered for further investigation,
or remediation, in the following order:  (1) WAG 1; (2) WAGs 2, 6, and
7 (as one combined WAG) and WAG 4; (3) WAGs 3, 5, and 9 (WAGs 3, 5, and
9 are indistinguishable); and (4) WAG 8. The uncertainty analyses
indicated that 137Cs is the dominant contaminant contributing to
potential health risks over all pathways, and the greatest 137Cs
contribution to risk was through fish ingestion.<P>

Several parameters contributing to the uncertainty in the total
calculated health risk at each WAG are common among all WAGs.  Most
notable is the factor used to convert radiation dose to health risk.
Holding these parameters constant to account for only the uncertainty
in parameters unique to a particular WAG reduces the ambiguity in the
rankings.  Additional calculations using only the uncertainty in
contaminant concentrations indicated that the WAGs should be ranked in
the following order:  (1) WAG 1; (2) WAGs 2, 6, and 7 (combined) and
WAG 4; (3) WAG 5; (4) WAG 9; (5) WAG 3; and (6) WAG 8.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="28"><H1>28</H1></A>

<H2>Karst Features Are Identified in the Maynardville Limestone,
Bear Creek Valley</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. Shevenell (1), R. B. Dreier, and W. K. Jago
</DL>

The Maynardville Limestone (ML) is believed to act as a hydrologic
drain for groundwaters in Bear Creek Valley (BCV).  Monitor well
clusters were, hence, installed along traverses (pickets) oriented
perpendicular to the strike of the ML in order to evaluate potential
contaminant transport through karst features in this limestone.<P>

The ML has been subdivided into six different informal lithologic
zones.  Two of the six zones are relatively prolific water-bearing
zones, and wells drilled through other zones generally intersected
fewer water-bearing intervals.  Cavities (solutionally enlarged
features) were intersected in numerous wells in all pickets.  The
greatest likelihood of intersecting a cavity in the ML occurs within
the uppermost zone, whereas no cavities were encountered in zone 3.
Most of the cavities in all zones were at depths of ~100 ft, suggesting
the active karst system may be relatively shallow.  The number of
cavities encountered per well generally increases as elevation
increases, whereas the number of fractures encountered generally
decreases at elevations &gt;600 ft, which suggests that fractures are
more likely to be solutionally enlarged at higher elevations (shallower
depths).<P>

Water flow and contaminant transport occur along strike in conduits
located at elevations generally &gt;720 ft, but hydraulic communication
between the conduits and fractures at elevations &lt;700 ft apparently
allows contaminants to be transported downdip.  The groundwater system
as a whole is active to elevations as low as 686 ft because
trichloroethene contamination has been detected at this elevation in a
fracture intersected by one of the picket wells.  The base level for
the active portion of the karst system in BCV appears to be located at
the intersection of BCV and the Clinch River (Watts Bar Lake).  The
extent to which contaminants may migrate along strike in the ML toward
the west is currently being investigated.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="29"><H1>29</H1></A>

<H2>Groundwater Contaminant Levels Are Decreasing near the S-3 Ponds
Site at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. A. Shevenell (1), G. K. Moore (1), and R. B. Dreier
</DL>

Liquid wastes, including metals dissolved in nitric acid, were
discharged into the S-3 Ponds at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant for 32 years
(1951-83).  The density of the liquid, which contained about 50,000
mg/L of nitrate as nitrogen, may have caused some downdip flows, and
peak concentrations of &gt;5000 mg/L occur in groundwater at depths of
both 23 m and &gt;200 m.  The deep groundwater is probably nearly
stagnant, but some shallow flows are discharged into Bear Creek.<P>

Neutralization of the S-3 Ponds in June 1983 caused a dramatic decrease
in the concentrations of contaminants in Bear Creek about 3 months
later.  For the past 8 years, the concentrations of constituents in
Bear Creek have decreased at a first-order, exponential rate.  This
rate and a convergence of other evidence show that (1) the contaminant
reservoir is the unfractured rock matrix; (2) contaminants are slowly
being flushed by natural recharge and discharge processes; (3) the
concentrations of all constituents in the headwaters of Bear Creek will
meet drinking water standards by 2012; and (4) the rate of flushing is
limited by the rate of molecular diffusion, regardless of whether
groundwater is pumped for treatment.<P>

Only three monitoring wells show an exponential decrease in the
concentrations of nitrogen with time.  Pumping during sampling may pull
water from tight fractures, where the water is nearly stagnant between
sampling events.  If so, in situ monitoring or sampling without purging
would show decreasing nitrogen concentrations in nearly all of the
monitoring wells.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="30"><H1>30</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Treatment of Contaminated Soil Is Achieved Through the Use
of Physicochemical Processes in a Continuously Mixed Subsurface Soil
Reactor</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Siegrist, M. I. Morris (1), O. M. West, D. D. Gates, D. A.
Pickering (2), R. A. Jenkins (3), T. J. Mitchell (4), D. W. Greene (2),
C. A. Muhr (2), S. E. Herbes, T. M. Gilliam (1), H. L. Jennings (1), A.
J. Lucero (1), J. Zutman (2), T. McKnight (5), J. S. Gierke (6), K. G.
Robinson (7), J. S. Watson (1), and D. T. Davenport (8)
</DL>

Fine-textured soils contaminated by trichloroethylene (TCE) and other
chlorinated solvents present a serious environmental restoration
challenge at DOE sites.  The X-231B Solid Waste Management Unit at the
Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant presented such a challenge.  Because
X-231B was used in the past as a land disposal site for waste oils and
solvents, the soil and groundwater beneath it were contaminated by
volatile organic compounds (VOCs) and radioactive substances.
Conventional treatment approaches were judged either technically
infeasible or too costly.<P>

DOE and Energy Systems initiated the X-231B Technology Demonstration
project at ORNL in July 1991, and during the past year numerical
analysis and modeling, laboratory experimentation, and full-scale field
testing have been completed.  Directed by ESD, the project has
integrated contributions of research and technical staff from six
divisions at ORNL and principal collaborators from The University of
Tennessee and Michigan Technological University, along with support
from several private industries.  As a result of this effort, an in
situ treatment approach has been demonstrated that couples selected
physicochemical processes in continuously mixed subsurface soil
reactors to either vaporize, oxidize, or immobilize contaminants in
their original location.<P>

Treatment processes can be used individually or in combination.
Treatment of soil VOCs can be effectively and rapidly accomplished
(e.g., &gt;85% efficiency at &gt;20 tons/h) while limiting worker
exposure and controlling the fate of VOCs and radioactive substances.
Moreover, in situ treatment costs appear substantially lower than
available ex situ technologies.  Portsmouth is using the demonstrated
processes for effective closure and remediation of its solid waste
management units at an estimated savings of several million dollars.
This project clearly demonstrates the benefits gained from fast-track,
focused research and demonstration activities in which technical
resources at a DOE national laboratory are coupled with those of
academia and private industry to solve pressing environmental problems
at a DOE site.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Chemical Technology Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Health and Safety Research Division, ORNL, Grand Junction,
Colorado.</I>
<DT>(3) <I>Analytical Chemistry Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(4) <I>Engineering Physics and Mathematics Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(5) <I>Instrumentation and Controls Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(6) <I>Michigan Technological University, Houghton, Michigan.</I>
<DT>(7) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(8) <I>Environmental Restoration Division, Martin Marietta Energy
Systems, Inc., Piketon, Ohio.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="31"><H1>31</H1></A>

<H2>Evolution of Na-HCO3-Type Groundwater Has Implications for Depth of
Shallow Flow System</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. E. Toran, J. A. Saunders (1), and T. O. Early
</DL>

Groundwater geochemistry is often used as an indicator of evolution of
flow paths and thus suggests how dissolved contaminants may travel.
The most important places to monitor groundwater are likely to be
shallow, active systems, but these cannot always be easily
distinguished.  Evolution of groundwater from Ca-HCO3 type in recharge
areas to Na-HCO3 type further along flow paths is attributed to
exchange of Na for Ca on exchange sites of clays.  Recent geochemical
modeling indicates that Na-HCO3 waters can also be produced by
alumnosilicate alteration.  For example, metastable illite can weather
to a more stable alumnosilicate such as smectite, releasing Na and Si
and increasing pH.<P>

The cation exchange mechanism and the clay alteration mechanism imply
different things about the evolution and length of the groundwater flow
system.  In the case of cation exchange, three stages occur: first,
Ca-HCO3 water is present; second, sufficient exchange occurs that Na is
the dominant cation; and third, exchange sites fill up so that Ca-type
water will flush out Na-type water.  Thus, the Na-HCO3 boundary
eventually gets pushed down and out.  Groundwater compositions alone
cannot indicate which state is operating, so the presence of
Na-HCO3-type water from cation exchange is only an ambiguous indicator
of ``evolved'' water.<P>

For feldspar dissolution/clay alteration, the rate at which the system
reaches chemical equilibrium and the quantity of metastable clays are
the only factors in evolution of Na-HCO3 waters.  Although these are
difficult to determine precisely, the presence of Na-HCO3-type waters
from alumnosilicate alteration indicates water in its final equilibrium
stage and, thus, marks the transition between active circulation (flow
paths too short to weather silicate) and slow groundwater flow.<P>

To test the feasibility of Na-HCO3 production from clay alteration on
the Oak Ridge Reservation, groundwater samples from multiport samplers
at depths of 200-1000 ft were modeled with a reaction path geochemical
model.  The suite of samples was collected under the Oak Ridge Y-12
Plant Groundwater Protection Program and provided an opportunity to
study geochemical changes as a function of depth.  Observed groundwater
compositions were reproduced with the clay alteration model.  It is
likely that a mixture of the two geochemical processes occurs, and
because of the implication to interpretation of the groundwater flow
system, it would be useful to try to quantify the relative importance
of these processes.  This could be done as follows:  First, the
mineralogy and geochemistry of the core must be further examined to
look for the degree of cation exchange and clay alteration.  Second, a
coupled flow and geochemical model must be used to examine possible
rates of the processes.<P>

A final piece of information about depth of flow systems obtained from
core mineralogy as part of this geochemical modeling effort is that
celestite (SrSO4) observed at the 1226 depth of one corehole is likely
to be at or close to the saline zone in Bear Creek Valley, which has
not been previously determined.  The zone of saline water is likely to
be a bottom boundary on flow systems because of the sluggish flow rates
and isolation needed to produce such waters.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Auburn University, Auburn, Alabama.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="32"><H1>32</H1></A>

<H2>Mesocosms Show Low Bioavailability of Sediment-Bound Mercury</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. R. Turner, G. R. Southworth, M. A. Bogle, and N. A. Bloom (1)
</DL>

Large-scale field enclosures (mesocosms) are being used to examine the
bioavailability of sediment-bound mercury downstream of a DOE
facility.  Results will help guide appropriate remediation of the creek
and expand the understanding of the importance of waterborne vs
sediment-bound mercury in limiting mercury methylation and
bioaccumulation.<P>

In these experiments, fish are maintained in enclosures representing
the following treatments: (1) mercury-contaminated water flowing over
mercury-contaminated sediment, (2) clean water flowing over
mercury-contaminated sediment, (3) mercury-contaminated water only, and
(4) clean water only.  In each enclosure the mercury uptake of the fish
is tracked, and the fluxes and speciation of mercury are monitored.<P>

Preliminary results for a cool period (October through December 1991)
show significant bioaccumulation of mercury only in those treatments
including waterborne mercury and thus support the hypothesis that
sorption to sediment greatly limits bioavailability of mercury.  These
results suggest that initial remediation efforts should be directed at
reducing waterborne mercury concentrations.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Frontier Geosciences, Seattle.</I>
</DL>

