<TITLE>Ecosystem Studies</TITLE>

<H1>Ecosystem Studies</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

Research in the Ecosystem Studies Section of the Environmental Sciences
Division (ESD) at Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) is directed
toward quantitatively characterizing the structure and functional
relationships of regional landscapes and terrestrial and aquatic
ecosystems, communities, and populations.  This information is then
used to predict the responses of these regions and ecosystems to both
natural and human-induced disturbances.  The section focuses on
complementary areas of research, including theoretical ecology,
biogeochemical cycling of materials, hydrosystems, resource analysis,
and physiological ecology of terrestrial plants.<P>

Major sponsors of the section's research are the U.S. Department of
Energy (DOE) Environmental Sciences Division of the Office of Health
and Environmental Research (OHER), the DOE Biofuels Feedstock
Development Program, the U.S. Forest Service (USFS) managed by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, the U.S.  Environmental Protection Agency
(EPA), the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI), the National
Science Foundation (NSF), and the Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.,
Environmental Restoration (ER) Program.<P>

The section has important collaboration and interaction with the
Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA), the Great Smoky Mountains National
Park, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's Atmospheric
Turbulence and Diffusion Division, and such universities as the
University of Georgia, University of Wisconsin, The University of
Tennessee, Fort Lewis College, University of Wyoming, University of
Maryland, and University of Rhode Island.  Section staff are affiliated
with the Southern Appalachian Biosphere Reserve of the U.S. Man and the
Biosphere Program.<P>

<H2>Biogeochemical Cycling</H2>

Staff in the Biogeochemical Cycling Group are engaged in research
concerning element cycling within environmental systems; the spatial
patterns and temporal trends of storage and fluxes of nutrients and
pollutants; the role of biogeochemical cycling of chemicals in
regulating productivity, species composition, and stability of
ecosystems; and the development of innovative methods of measurement,
analysis, modeling, and interpretation of biogeochemical cycles at
site-specific, regional, and global scales.<P>

The group is involved in several areas of research:  (1) the DOE
OHERfunded Walker Branch Watershed Project, which focuses on the
relative importance of hydrogeochemical transport and biogeochemical
cycling in regulating biological structure and primary productivity in
forests and streams at different temporal and spatial scales; (2) the
USFS-funded project on atmospheric deposition, red spruce nutrition,
and aluminum toxicity in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park, a
project that builds on results of the multiyear and multisite
EPRI-funded Integrated Forest Study; (3) the use of stable isotopes and
radioisotopes to study cycling processes in aquatic and terrestrial
systems; (4) the EPA-funded Critical Loads Project, which evaluates
critical loads of sulfur and nitrogen on forested areas in the eastern
United States; (5) research on nitrogen and carbon dynamics and
storage/export in high- and low-elevation watersheds in the region; and
(6) an NSF study on nutrient cycling and stability in stream
ecosystems.<P>

Important accomplishments during FY 1992 included the initiation of a
major climate change manipulation experiment on the water balance of
Walker Branch Watershed and the initiation of new research on nitrogen
dynamics of high-elevation forests in the southern Appalachians.<P>

<H2>Hydrosystems</H2>

The Hydrosystems Group conducts applied and basic research required for
the management and analysis of water resources and related natural
systems (e.g., fish populations affected by water allocation or
land-use practices as they interact with water quality), focusing
specifically on hydroelectric energy production and its environmental
effects.  The group specializes in the development and application of
quantitative assessment techniques to solve environmental problems over
a range of spatial scales up to large river basins or national
levels.<P>

In addition to hydropower projects, other water resource issues
addressed by the group include instream flow needs, fish population
modeling, multiple-use trade-off analyses, cumulative impact
assessment, contaminant transport, surface water and groundwater
monitoring, acidic deposition, and climate change.  The group
integrates simulation and optimization modeling, sensitivity and
uncertainty analysis, geostatistical applications, geographic
information systems, and scientific data base management as tools for
large-scale water resource assessment.  The three major sponsors of the
Hydrosystems Group are DOE, Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, and
EPRI.<P>

Research activities during FY 1992 included significant research
contributions in the following areas:  (1) understanding the economic
costs and environmental benefits of mitigation practices at
hydroelectric projects; (2) developing new fish population models for
application to assessment of instream flow needs; (3) assessing the
cumulative impacts of hydroelectric projects clustered in the Cascade
Mountains of Washington; and (4) resolving water allocation conflicts
in California between anadromous fisheries resources and municipal and
irrigation water users.<P>

<H2>Physiological Ecology</H2>

The Physiological Ecology Group evaluates the effects of environmental
stress on plant growth and vigor and examines the role of physiological
processes in biogeochemical cycling of pollutants within terrestrial
ecosystems.  Specific atmospheric pollutants such as ozone, acid
deposition, and nitrogen oxides are examined, as well as the effects of
other changes in the chemical and physical atmospheric environment.
Increases in atmospheric CO2 and high-energy ultraviolet radiation are
studied in relation to global environmental pollution.  The use of
physiological indicators in intensive biomass production from
silviculture is being investigated as part of the search for nonfossil
energy sources, and the role of interactive stresses on physiological
indicators of whole-plant resource use has also received research
attention.  Primary sponsors of the group's work are DOE, EPRI, USFS,
and EPA.<P>

During FY 1992, staff determined that short-term responses of
yellow-poplar seedlings to elevated CO2 can be sustained over several
growing seasons under field conditions, but limitations of water and
nutrients and internal plant feedbacks will combine to moderate the
growth response of forests to rising CO2 concentrations.  New
developmental studies were established to develop exposure capabilities
for the study of CO2 and temperature interactions on forest tree growth
and to establish techniques for insertion of genes into hybrid poplar
to enhance the cellulose content of wood.<P>

<H2>Resource Analysis</H2>

Staff of the Resource Analysis Group characterize environmental
resources and evaluate their development and sustainability, especially
at large spatial scales, and develop and improve methodologies for
making such evaluations.  Efforts of the group can be divided into
those activities focused on the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR) and other
DOE facilities and those activities not related to specific DOE
facilities.  The Resource Analysis Group is involved in characterizing
and reporting on environmental measurements taken at DOE facilities,
developing environmental data bases for the DOE Environmental
Restoration Program, managing the National Environmental Research Park
at Oak Ridge, and providing geographic information systems support to
both on-site and off-site environmental programs.  Members of the group
are also involved in broader resource issues, including the
sustainability of protected areas, the environmental implications of
large-scale development of biomass energy, and the analysis and
reporting of national environmental trends.  DOE is the primary sponsor
of this group.<P>

New initiatives for FY 1992 included the preparation of well-received
environmental reports for all Energy Systems facilities, a wildlife
management plan for ORR, development of a broad government and
nongovernment organization constituency for addressing the
environmental implications of biofuels, and a ground-breaking
cost-supply analysis of energy crops, which included environmental,
economic, and spatial constraints.<P>

<H2>Theoretical Ecology</H2>

The Theoretical Ecology Group develops simulation and mathematical
methods to describe and predict the behavior of ecological systems.
The tools developed within the group are applied to a spectrum of
problems including environmental assessments, theoretical questions in
population and ecosystem dynamics, and analyses of phenomena that span
scales from the landscape to the globe.  Research focuses on landscape
ecology (funded by DOE's Environmental Sciences Division), development
of individual-based models of fish population (funded by EPRI), and
development of biological indicators and landscape models for the
Environmental Monitoring and Assessment Program of EPA.  Important
collaborations were developed with Fort Lewis College and the
University of Wyoming to support research on the fires in Yellowstone
National Park.<P>

During FY 1992 the group developed a model for use in considering the
social and environmental effects of land-use management.  Researchers
also applied a landscape simulation model to study the winter foraging
of elk and bison in Yellowstone National Park, and they have used an
individual-based smallmouth bass population model to evaluate
alternative scenarios for fisheries management issues, such as
determining the opening date of fishing season that is most appropriate
to ensure the best survival during the nest-guarding period.<P>

<H2>TVA Ecology Program</H2>

As a consequence of a common interest in the environmental impacts of
energy development and use, TVA and DOE Oak Ridge Operations have
developed an agreement to pursue joint research activities,
specifically involving ESD staff and members of the Division of Water
Resources at TVA.  Under this arrangement, TVA personnel are assigned
to ORNL to develop programs investigating the impacts of air and water
emissions on terrestrial and aquatic resources.  This relationship
combines the experience gained from TVA's power-producing activities
with the unique research-support facilities of ESD to produce timely
and relevant research findings.<P>

A number of major projects were implemented during FY 1992.  Whereas
initial research projects centered on water quality and
nutrient-cycling issues in the context of acid rain, current activities
focus on ozone and other chemical and physical changes in the
environment that are associated with the general topic of global
climate change.<P>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="33"><H1>33</H1></A>

<H2>Mitigation Measures for Fish Passage at Hydroelectric Power Plants
Are Reviewed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. F. Cada and J. E. Francfort (1)
</DL>

Hydroelectric power plants can block fish movements in both upstream
and downstream directions.  Fish passage requirements are becoming an
increasingly common factor in hydropower licensing.  Recognizing that
both developers and regulatory agencies need an improved basis for
designing cost-effective fish passage mitigation, the DOE Hydropower
Program sponsored a review of current technologies.  The analysis is
part of a larger, continuing effort that is also considering the
effectiveness and costs of mitigating problems with dissolved oxygen
and instream flow at hydropower facilities.<P>

Data bases of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, which regulates
nonfederal hydropower projects, were searched to identify projects with
fish passage requirements.  Developers of these projects were contacted
to determine what mitigation methods were used, the basis for the
requirement, and the nature of postinstallation performance
monitoring.  Federal and state resource agencies that consult on fish
passage issues were also contacted to obtain technical information and
policies regarding mitigation.  Literature surveys were conducted to
assess the general knowledge base in regard to the effectiveness of
fish passage measures.<P>

Research revealed that fish ladders are the most common means of
passing fish upstream of dams; fish elevators are less common, but
their use appears to be increasing.  Numerous methods are applied to
prevent downstream-moving fish from being drawn into the turbine
intakes; such measures range from the simple spilling of water over the
crest of the dam to the use of various physical screens and light- or
sound-based guidance.  The average capital costs per facility were
$7,600,000 for fish ladders and $322,000 for angled bar racks, a
commonly required measure for preventing turbine passage.  Although
fish passage measures were required more frequently in the past decade,
performance monitoring remains relatively rare.  For example,
performance monitoring is not required for 82% of the projects with
downstream fish passage measures.  Despite considerable efforts to
install fish passage devices at significant cost to the hydropower
industry, little information is available about the biological benefits
of the devices.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Idaho National Engineering Laboratory, Idaho Falls.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="34"><H1>34</H1></A>

<H2>Oxygen-18 Abundances in Natural Waters Provide Insight into Arctic
Hydrological Processes</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. W. Cooper, C. Solis (1), D. L. Kane (2), and L. D. Hinzman (2)
</DL>

Because of its natural abundance, 18O has been used for approximately
20 years to follow water flow during storms and snowmelt on the
assumption that 18O is a conservative tracer.  In one of the first
applications to a watershed underlain by permafrost, we observed
differing conditions in which this assumption is both true as well as
apparently false.  Under dry antecedent conditions in late summer at
Imnavait Creek, Alaska (68 degrees 37' N, 149 degrees 17' W), rainfall
behaved conservatively as a ``piston,'' forcing isotopically distinct
``old'' water already within the soil into the stream before the "new"
water contributed by rain changed the isotopic composition of the
increasing streamflow.  However, during snowmelt, we observed that the
18O compositions of streams are influenced apparently by isotopic
fractionation during phase change from solid to liquid.<P>

Measurements of snow redistribution, ablation, snow and soil moisture
content, and snowmelt runoff at Imnavait Creek indicate little mixing
of meltwater with underlying ice-rich soils.  The  delta-18O values of
Imnavait Creek changed dramatically during the first 8 d of streamflow
in 1990, increasing from -30.3%o on May 14 to -22.5%o on May 22.
Because the soil remains frozen and impermeable throughout snowmelt,
these observations are more consistent with isotopic fractionation
during melt than with mixing with underlying soil moisture.  The
apparent fractionation includes the preferential release of relatively
18O-depleted meltwater initially, the preferential overnight refreezing
of relatively 18O-enriched meltwater, and its release the following
morning on the rising limb of the stream hydrograph.<P>

The isotope data indicate that it is inappropriate to use 18O as a
conservative tracer to determine the sources of runoff during snowmelt
in this watershed; however, the total runoff, the water content of the
snow prior to ablation, and the observed isotopic shift were used
independently to estimate evaporation during ablation.  At a time of
increased concern about the potential effects of global change on
arctic hydrological processes, our results demonstrate that care must
be taken if a widely used isotopic technique for tracing water flow is
to be applied to high-latitude watersheds.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Instituto de F&iacute;sica, Universidad Nacional
Aut&oacute;noma de M&eacute;xico.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Water Research Center, Institute of Northern Engineering,
University of Alaska, Fairbanks.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="35"><H1>35</H1></A>

<H2>Laser Ablation Mass Spectrometry of Strontium in Striped Bass
Scales Differentiates Populations</H2>

<DL>
<DT>C. C. Coutant and C. H. Chen (1)
</DL>

Recognition of fish populations is important for evaluating effects of
energy technologies on aquatic environments.  Researchers in ESD and
ORNL's Health and Safety Research Division examined the variability of
strontium concentrations in the scales of striped bass, using a laser
ablation microprobe and mass spectrometry.<P>

Striped bass exhibited marked differences in the average amounts of
strontium in their scales: striped bass from freshwater reservoirs in
Tennessee had low levels, and striped bass from the Roanoke
River/Albemarle Sound estuary system in North Carolina had high
levels.  Scales from reservoir fish had little strontium variability
with age (distinguished by annular rings), whereas scales from
estuarine fish had high interannual variability, which may reflect
migrations between fresh and saline water.  A strontium peak was found
at the center of the fish scale in striped bass from the freshwater
Roanoke River, but not in that of fish from reservoirs; the peak may
indicate saltwater parentage.<P>

Because locations on a fish scale are related to age, chemical analysis
of the discrete locations by laser ablation microprobe can be valuable
for studying life history patterns.  The technique is promising for
applications to environmental problems of interest to DOE.  It can help
researchers (1) detect introduced chemical markers (e.g., in
hatcheries) that identify fish produced for hydropower mitigation; (2)
detect naturally occurring or pollution-derived chemical markers that
identify wild fish stocks affected by hydropower or other energy
operations; and (3) identify the time periods when migrating fishes are
exposed to chemical pollutants derived from DOE facilities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Health and Safety Research Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="36"><H1>36</H1></A>

<H2>Computer Model Simulates the Social and Environmental Effects of
Land-Use Management</H2>

<DL>
<DT>V. H. Dale, R. V. O'Neill, and F. Southworth (1)
</DL>

The socioeconomic and ecological aspects of land-use change are
interrelated, especially in the Brazilian Amazon, where immigrants are
rapidly cutting the forest to establish farms but are unable to support
themselves by agriculture.  A computer simulation has been developed to
project land-use changes, carbon release, and the length of time that
residents can remain on a lot.  The model can simulate the social
extremes of land-use practices and typical land-use conditions for
central Rond&ocirc;nia, Brazil.  Scenarios are chosen on strictly
social criteria to simulate conditions under which farmers remain on
the lots for different periods.<P>

The best case results in both social and environmental improvement in
comparison with the other scenarios:  the people can maintain
themselves on the land, less carbon is released, and the land maintains
a mix of habitat types.  The model results illustrate that both social
and environmental effects of land management practices need to be
considered, particularly for areas adjacent to ecological reserves.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Energy Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="37"><H1>37</H1></A>

<H2>Book on Nutrient Cycling in Food Webs Is Published</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. L. DeAngelis
</DL>

As part of a project funded by the National Science Foundation on
nutrient recycling in streams and in more general ecological systems, I
wrote the book <I>Dynamics of Nutrient Cycling and Food Webs</I>,
published by Chapman and Hall.  The book reviews and synthesizes what
is known about the interactions between the cycling of nutrients in
ecosystems and the dynamics of food webs.  Understanding how one or
more nutrients limit biological production has implications for
predicting both the ability of food webs to recover from disturbances
and their rate of recovery.  Many important aspects of food web
dynamics are affected by nutrient limitation and cycling.  The level of
nutrient input, for example, may affect the stability of plantherbivore
interactions.<P>

Many of the current problems of ecological systems involve human
disturbances of food webs and the nutrients that cycle through them.
The addition of nutrients to aquatic systems, for example, may upset
the competitive balance of the species present.  Dynamic phenomena such
as these can be understood through the use of mathematical and computer
models.  These models, therefore, are used throughout the book to form
a framework for discussion of the various phenomena.<P>

The book starts with very simple models of nutrient turnover in
one-compartment systems, such as a simple homogeneous lake or
reservoir.  Autotrophs and then herbivores and higher trophic levels
are successively added to the system, and the effects of nutrient
limitation are studied.  The effects of decomposition are then
included.  The interactions of nutrient limitation and competitive
systems are investigated.  Models with both spatial extent and temporal
variation of nutrient inputs are analyzed.  The book concludes with a
discussion of the global implications of nutrient interactions with
food webs.<P>

<A NAME="38"><H1>38</H1></A>

<H2>State-of-the-Art Ultraviolet-B Field-Exposure Techniques Do Not
Qualitatively Simulate Expected Global Increases in Ultraviolet-B
Irradiance</H2>

<DL>
<DT>N. T. Edwards
</DL>

A substantial decrease in the earth's protective stratospheric ozone
(O3) layer is occurring.  This decrease is primarily the result of the
conversion of O3 to O2, for which chlorine from anthropogenically
produced chlorofluorocarbons acts as a catalyst.  Depletion of the O3
layer is expected to continue for many years.<P>

A projected stratospheric ozone decrease of 16% over the next 30 years
would theoretically result in a 32% increase in the 305-nm wave band of
ultraviolet-B (UV-B) reaching the earth's surface, and even greater
increases would occur at shorter wavelengths.  Although irradiance
levels at these shorter wavelengths are extremely low in relation to
those at longer wavelengths, they are more biologically damaging.  It
is therefore important that facilities designed to evaluate biological
responses to UV-B deliver UV-B of the same quality (not just the same
quantity) as that resulting from stratospheric O3 depletion.<P>

The current study evaluated a state-of-the-art UV-B field-exposure
system developed at ORNL to study vegetation responses to enhanced
UV-B.  In the system, computer-controlled lamps produce a broad
spectrum (270-380 nm) of irradiance, and cellulose acetate filters
remove the germicidal wave bands below 280 nm (UV-C).  The system was
evaluated by using a diode array spectrograph that measures irradiance
at every 0.1 nm within the UV-B wave band.  Integrated measurements
were taken beneath the UV-B lamps to account for shading by the lamps
themselves and for variation in the UV-B delivered by the system.<P>

Results revealed a discrepancy between the expected quality of the UV-B
increase as a result of O3 depletion and the quality of the UV-B
actually delivered by the system.  At wavelengths &gt;300 nm,
irradiance under the lamps was representative of expected UV-B
increases.  However, the opposite was observed at &lt;300 nm (the most
biologically active UV-B); the irradiance in the 280- to 295-nm wave
band was actually greater in natural sunlight than in sunlight
supplemented with UV-B. These results raise doubts concerning our
ability to simulate expected global increases in UV-B irradiance and
call into question the relevance of previous field research on
biological responses to enhanced UV-B.<P>

<A NAME="39"><H1>39</H1></A>

<H2>Studies Indicate Limits to the Dispersal of Radioactivity by
Wildlife from Contaminated Sites on the Oak Ridge Reservation</H2>

<DL>
<DT>C. T. Garten, Jr.
</DL>

Environmental studies indicate that animals may disperse radioactivity
from waste disposal sites at ORNL to sites beyond the Laboratory's
boundaries.  An assessment of radionuclide uptake and dispersal of
radioactivity by insects, birds, and mammals was undertaken to evaluate
the limits to and potential for dispersal of radioactivity by
wildlife.  Dispersal of radioactivity may occur as a result of either
the transport of contaminated materials to nest sites or
bioaccumulation and  animal emigration.  Published data indicate that
contaminated animals or animal nests at ORNL contain levels of 90Sr or
137Cs on the order of picocuries or microcuries per gram and trace
amounts of other radionuclides.<P>

The highest concentrations of 137Cs have been measured in emergent
aquatic insects, small birds, and Canada geese.  The highest levels of
90Sr have been measured in bones from turtles and small mammals.
Mud-dauber wasps and barn swallows may transport radioactive mud over
short distances (from 0.2 to 1 km) for nest building.  Frogs, turtles,
and small mammals that emigrate from waste sites may also disperse
radioactivity over short distances (&lt;5 km).  Larger animals, like
white-tailed deer, are more likely vectors of radioactivity because of
their greater body size, longer life expectancy, and larger home
range.  However, among animals studied at ORNL, the larger ones usually
have lower concentrations of 137Cs.<P>

This assessment shows that animals that fly and have behavior patterns
or developmental life stages involving contact with sediments of
radioactive ponds (e.g., emergent aquatic insects and waterfowl)
present the greatest potential for the dispersal of radioactivity.
Consistent with studies at other DOE facilities, the present study
indicates that the amount of radioactivity that could be removed by
dispersal of wildlife from contaminated sites at ORNL is on the order
of 0.001 to 10 mCi/year.<P>

<A NAME="40"><H1>40</H1></A>

<H2>Two Storage Methods Are Evaluated for Their Effects on the Wood
Quality of American Sycamore Destined for Biomass-to-Ethanol Conversion
and Thermochemical Fuels</H2>

<DL>
<DT>C. A. Gunderson and A. Wiselogel (1)
</DL>

Implementation of large-scale biomass energy conversion technologies
requires the availability of biofuels feedstocks throughout the year
for efficient energy production.  Woody crops (e.g., American
sycamore), however, may be harvested only during a limited portion of
the year to ensure regrowth from the rootstock.  Minimizing feedstock
quality losses while facilitating storage and handling of the wood thus
becomes an issue in long-range planning for biofuels development.<P>

As part of a National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) study,
researchers at ORNL compared two methods of wood storage:  (1)
formation of large piles of wood chips (efficient in terms of handling)
and (2) stacking of whole trees (wood protected by bark; less surface
area).  Analyses performed at NREL and Colorado State University
included analysis of components (cellulose, hemicellulose, lignin, and
ash), pretreatment response, and ethanol production by simultaneous
saccharification and fermentation.  In addition, some samples will
undergo pilot-scale pyrolysis conversion.<P>

Moisture content in the interior of the chip pile decreased over time
with increasing pile temperature (43C maximum), whereas exterior layers
remained wet (65% moisture) throughout the storage period. Wood stored
as whole trees dried more slowly than chips in the pile interior (40%
vs 27% moisture at 13 weeks), but both piles dried to 20% moisture by
26 weeks.  Despite differences in moisture content, densities of
interior and exterior chips differed insignificantly even after 26
weeks.  Densities of wood stored as whole trees, however, were 10 to
30% higher than those of wood stored as chips after 13 weeks.  These
preliminary data suggest that whole-tree storage is better for
maintaining wood quality during storage periods longer than 13 weeks.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>National Renewable Energy Laboratory, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="41"><H1>41</H1></A>

<H2>Mechanistic Model of HNO3 Vapor Deposition on Hardwood and Conifer
Foliage Is Proposed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. J. Hanson and C. T. Garten, Jr.
</DL>

The transfer of anthropogenically produced nitrogen compounds from the
atmosphere to vegetation (nitrogen loading) has been identified as a
possible causal factor leading to changes in natural ecosystems.
Although precipitation-derived nitrogen deposition can be measured
directly, the deposition of important trace nitrogen gases must be
inferred from theoretical models based on ambient concentration
measurements.<P>

Nitric acid vapor (HNO3) is the primary sink for the removal of trace
nitrogen species from the atmosphere, but surface-specific measurements
of its deposition are known to be problematic.  Stable isotope (15N)
labeling allowed a direct measure of H15NO3 deposition on leaves of
white oak, red maple, and loblolly pine.  This labeling approach
minimized common concerns about losses of HNO3 to chamber surfaces and
facilitated the specific quantification of surface-sorbed vs internally
bound fractions of HNO3-derived nitrate after deposition.  Total
deposition of H15NO3 vapor on foliar surfaces ranged from &lt;5 to 27
nmol * m^2 * s^-1; the variability was largely accounted for by
differences in air concentrations and stomatal conductance.<P>

Of the total amount of H15NO3 vapor deposited on leaves, an average of
39 to 48% was immediately ``bound'' into hardwood foliage, whereas only
3% was bound to loblolly pine needles; this disparity implies that rain
events might extract greater amounts of HNO3-derived nitrate in
throughfall from conifer canopies, other conditions being equal.  The
rates of postexposure H15NO3 uptake across the leaf cuticle increased
as surface nitrate concentrations increased, but the rates were 1 to 2
orders of magnitude lower (0.06 to 0.24 nmol * m^2 * s^-1) than the
rates of total HNO3 deposition during exposure.<P>

These data allowed us to parameterize a generalized leaf-level model
capable of simulating HNO3 deposition pathways to sorption sites on the
leaf surface and to the metabolically active leaf interior via
transcuticular or stomatal pathways.  This model also explains other
published data on HNO3 vapor deposition and will be useful for planning
future work on HNO3 deposition.<P>

<A NAME="42"><H1>42</H1></A>

<H2>Non-CH4, Non-CO2 Carbon Emissions Are Measured from Landscape
Surfaces</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. A. Hoffman, Jr. (1), and P. J. Hanson
</DL>

Respiration and decay are known sources of atmospheric carbon in the
form of CO2 and CH4 in the landscape.  Other gas phase compounds often
present include ethene (C2H4), isoprene (C5H8), and a number of
terpenes (C10H16)n.  We have developed a trap-purge-cryofocus gas
chromatograph to quantify the total efflux of non-CO2, non-CH4 carbon
from landscape surfaces.  Coupled with mass spectrometry, this analytic
approach also allows us to identify specific eluant compounds.  The
trap-purge-gas chromatograph has also been used to routinely monitor
trichloroethylene in samples generated from bioremediation studies
concerning Savannah River Laboratory sites.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Denison University, Granville, Ohio.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="43"><H1>43</H1></A>

<H2>Spatial Distribution of Smallmouth Bass Is Simulated for the North
Anna River</H2>

<DL>
<DT>H. I. Jager, D. L. DeAngelis, M. J. Sabo (1), M. J. Sale, D. D.
Schmoyer (2), J. A. Tyler (3), and W. Van Winkle
</DL>

The hydropower industry and its regulators are currently hampered by
the inability to predict the relationship between alternative flow
regimes and fish population response.  As part of the Compensatory
Mechanisms in Fish Populations Program, we have developed a spatially
explicit, individual-based model of stream populations of smallmouth
bass in streams.<P>

In the model, the profitability of alternative stream locations varies
in response to habitat depth and velocity because changes in prey
density, foraging behavior, and metabolic cost.  Fish in the model make
daily movement decisions based on whether their recent experience in
the local area is better or worse than their longer- term experience
over the larger area.  The average distance moved by individual fish is
modeled as an increasing function of fish size.<P>

A visualization software called PV/WAVE enables researchers to view
model simulations.  This tool enabled a collaborator from Virginia
Polytechnic Institute and State University to observe simulated fry
during dispersal from the nest and to provide us with feedback on model
performance.  The locations and types of habitats occupied by model
fish compared favorably with those the collaborator observed for
smallmouth bass fry in the North Anna River in Virginia.  However, the
collaborator suggested that the rate of dispersal in the model needed
to be adjusted.  Such feedback from researchers familiar with the
stream system is critical to model validation.  If the model is
validated, it will provide a tool to evaluate the population-level
consequences of alternative flow regimes adopted by hydropower
facilities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University,
Blacksburg, Virginia.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Computing and Telecommunications Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(3) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="44"><H1>44</H1></A>

<H2>Northern Red Oak Trees and Seedlings Exhibit Differential
Sensitivity to Ozone Stress</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. M. Kelly (1), G. S. Edwards, and S. D. Wullschleger
</DL>

Quantitative predictions of the responses of individual trees, stands,
and forest ecosystems to pollutants and climatic variables require the
extrapolation of existing data sets that are derived largely from
seedling studies.  During the 1990 and 1991 growing seasons, mature
trees and seedlings were exposed to subambient, ambient, and
twice-ambient ozone concentrations.  Two striking differences observed
between seedlings and mature trees were the number of foliar growth
flushes and their timing.  Seedlings flushed at least twice during each
growing season; mature trees flushed only once.  This observation
suggests different carbon allocation strategies and possible
differences in ozone sensitivity.<P>

Seedlings showed no gas exchange response to ozone during the growing
season.  However, the twice-ambient ozone treatment resulted in reduced
photosynthetic rates for the mature trees.  Although gas exchange rates
of seedlings were not affected by ozone treatments, the total biomass
of seedlings exposed to twice-ambient ozone levels was significantly
less at the end of the 1991 growing season.  Disproportionate
reductions in root biomass also resulted in reduced root:shoot ratios
at elevated concentrations of ozone.<P>

The responses observed in this study raise several issues and
questions.  Instantaneous gas exchange measurements on individual
leaves are not adequate for predicting subtle responses to ozone:  (1)
Seedling biomass decreased with increasing ozone, although gas exchange
rates were not significantly affected.  (2) What can be inferred about
the biomass of mature trees if photosynthesis rates were significantly
less for the tree exposed to elevated ozone?  (3) If the biomass of
mature trees is reduced when ozone is increased, does a
disproportionate decrease in root biomass occur, as seen with
seedlings, and what are the long-term implications in regard to water
and nutrient uptake?<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Tennessee Valley Authority, Knoxville, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="45"><H1>45</H1></A>

<H2>Regulatory and Procedural Requirements for the White Oak Creek
Embayment Time-Critical Removal Action Are Investigated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>B. L. Kimmel and M. Leslie (1)
</DL>

The DOE Environmental Restoration and Waste Management Program
encourages interim remedial actions to achieve risk reduction and to
prevent off-site contamination.  Interim response actions, conducted
under the provisions of the Comprehensive Environmental Response,
Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA) and the National Contingency
Plan, Title 40, <I>Code of Federal Regulations</I>, Part 300, provide a
mechanism for achieving these objectives.  A time- critical CERCLA
removal action in progress at the White Oak Creek Embayment (WOCE) on
the Oak Ridge Reservation provides an initial example of the
application of this mechanism.<P>

Risk-screening analyses conducted during the scoping phase of the
Clinch River Remedial Investigation identified WOCE as a high- priority
site for further characterization and potential remediation.  Analysis
of a sediment core collected from the lower portion of WOCE revealed
higher than expected levels of 137Cs contamination at the sediment
surface.  This result produced immediate concern because WOCE surface
sediments were susceptible to erosion and transport off-site into the
Clinch River.<P>

A time-critical CERCLA removal action was proposed to achieve control
of the contaminated WOCE sediments.  However, numerous uncertainties
existed concerning both regulatory and procedural requirements for
on-site, time-critical response actions at federal facilities.  To
resolve these uncertainties, immediate actions were undertaken to (1)
involve and achieve consensus among all appropriate state and federal
agencies; (2) review relevant federal and state regulations to identify
required actions, notification and permit requirements, applicable or
relevant and appropriate requirements (ARARs), and their associated
schedules; and (3) verify the applicability of the identified ARARs,
procedural requirements, and reporting requirements to DOE on-site
response actions.<P>

Investigation of the regulatory and procedural issues associated with
the WOCE time-critical removal action provides a useful model for
conducting similar interim response actions at federal facilities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>CDM Federal Programs Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="46"><H1>46</H1></A>

<H2>Pore-Scale Analysis of Solute Transport Offers New Insights
for Waste Remediation</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. J. Luxmoore, P. M. Jardine, and L. A. Ferrand (1)
</DL>

At three contrasting areal scales (4 m^2, 4700 m^2, and 380,000 m^2),
elevated chemical concentration has been found to occur along with high
flow rates during rain-fed transport.  A dilution effect, as might be
expected, did not occur for solutes in soil water prior to rainfall.
We evaluated several pore-scale mechanisms to explain these
observations: (1) movement of antecedent water in soil micropores into
larger drainable pores, (2) diffusion of solutes through a large
surface area of interaction from nondraining pores (containing
antecedent water) to larger draining pores containing new water, and
(3) disconnection/reconnection of water in flow paths during drying and
wetting cycles.<P>

Three-dimensional percolation modeling was employed to evaluate these
mechanisms, revealing that the latter two hypotheses seem to have some
merit.  The surface area of the second interaction mechanism is
inadequate by itself to account for the phenomenon because the surface
area of interaction between draining and nondraining pore classes is
inadequate.  Percolation modeling has shown the feasibility of the
disconnection/reconnection mechanism in which a cluster of percolating
pores disconnects upon drying, causing some drainable pores to ``hang
up'' in the percolation network.  The stranded water in these pores is
expected to equilibrate with water in the matrix as a result of
diffusion during the period between drainage events.  The equilibrated
water becomes readily mobilized in the next drainage event.  As
rainfall increases, the network of stranded (drainable) antecedent
water is hypothesized to expand in the landscape, increasing the
proportion of antecedent water in the outflow and, hence, the solute
concentration with flow rate.<P>

Percolation models offer a means for quantifying pore-scale mechanisms
contributing to solute dynamics.  They also provide an approach for
calculating continuum-scale transport coefficients (conductivity,
dispersion, and mass-transfer coefficients) and for identifying fractal
scaling rules that will aid in applying the model to large field-scale
problems.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Department of Civil Engineering, City University of New York.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="47"><H1>47</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Measurements of Whole-Stream Metabolism Using a Direct
Measure of the Reaeration Coefficient Allow Comparisons with Other
Stream-Scale Studies</H2>

<DL>
<DT>E. R. Marzolf, P. J. Mulholland, A. D. Steinman (1), A. V. Palumbo,
and D. L. DeAngelis
</DL>

Metabolism measurements in low-order streams have been hindered by
methods of estimating the reaeration coefficient that rely on imprecise
predictive equations or artificial substrate/chamber studies.  By
combining releases of a conservative tracer (NaCl) and a volatile
tracer (propane) in Walker Branch, ESD researchers demonstrated that
reaeration coefficients can be directly measured.  The coefficient
changes throughout the year because of changes in flow and in the
fraction of stream surface covered with leaves.  Using the measured
reaeration coefficient and applying the traditional upstream/downstream
dissolved oxygen method, we were able to make accurate in situ
estimates of whole-stream metabolism in this first-order stream.<P>

Measurements of whole-stream metabolism are useful in understanding
such ecosystem processes as nutrient cycling, use of light, and
secondary production.  Studies currently under way in Walker Branch
using this new application focus on the following: the hydraulic
conditions, which affect the importance of phosphorus cycling by the
periphyton community; comparison of the physiological and the
ecological responses of periphyton to light; and the relationships
between the rates of secondary productivity, community respiration, and
gross primary production as an indication of the relative importance of
autochthonous vs allochthonous production in the stream food web.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Knoxville College, Knoxville, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="48"><H1>48</H1></A>

<H2>Hydrologic Storage Zones in Streams Are Important Sites of Nutrient
Cycling and Retention</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. J. Mulholland, D. L. DeAngelis, E. R. Marzolf, A. V. Palumbo,
A. D. Steinman, and R. V. Wilkerson (1)
</DL>

Zones of water that exchange very slowly with free-flowing water
(hydrologic storage zones) may be important sites of nutrient cycling
and retention in streams, thus retarding the downstream loss of
nutrients and enhancing primary and microbial productivity.  We have
conducted modeling and empirical studies to evaluate the importance of
hydrologic storage zones in streams.  We have developed models of
nutrient cycling in streams that explicitly incorporate hydrologic
storage zones, and these models generally predict tighter nutrient
cycles and greater amounts of living biomass than models that do not
include these zones.  We have also conducted experimental studies
involving whole-stream injections of conservative and nutrient
radiotracers and measurements of metabolism to compute the size of
hydrologic storage zones and their importance in phosphorus cycling and
retention in streams.<P>

Studies in laboratory streams show that storage zones created by thick
algal mats attached to the stream bottom increase the rate of
phosphorus cycling and retention compared with streams with thin algal
mats.  Experiments performed in Walker Branch, a small stream on the
Oak Ridge Reservation, indicate that channel backwater areas formed by
debris accumulations or rock obstructions function as hydrologic
storage zones and enhance the cycling and retention of phosphorus.<P>

Our findings suggest that the hydrodynamic characteristics of streams,
particularly those that influence the temporary storage of water, are
of great importance to the cycling and retention of nutrients and hence
the biological productivity of stream ecosystems.  Our findings also
suggest that the effects of biologically toxic materials may be greater
in streams with large hydrologic storage zones as a result of increased
retention of these materials.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Jaycor, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="49"><H1>49</H1></A>

<H2>Forest Responses to Increasing Concentrations of Atmospheric CO2
Will Be Modified by Other Environmental Resources</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. J. Norby, C. A. Gunderson, S. D. Wullschleger (1), E. G.
O'Neill, and M. K. McCracken (2)
</DL>

Increased forest growth in response to globally rising CO2
concentrations could provide an additional sink for the excess carbon
added to the atmosphere from fossil fuels.  The magnitude of the
response of trees to elevated concentrations of CO2, however, can be
expected to be modified by the interactions of other environmental
resources and stresses, higher-order ecological interactions, and
internal feedbacks inherent in the growth of large, perennial
organisms.<P>

To test whether short-term stimulation of tree growth by increased CO2
can be sustained without additional inputs of other environmental
resources, yellow-poplar (<I>Liriodendron tulipifera L.</I>) saplings
were grown for most of three growing seasons with continuous exposure
to ambient or elevated concentrations of atmospheric CO2.  Despite a
sustained increase in leaf-level photosynthesis and lower rates of
foliar respiration in CO2-enriched trees, whole-plant carbon storage
did not increase.  The absence of a significant growth response is
explained by changes in carbon allocation patterns in response to a
limited nitrogen supply: leaf production decreased, whereas fine root
production increased.<P>

This shift in carbon allocation represents a trade-off between
potential carbon acquisition and water and nutrient acquisition.
Hence, these compensatory responses favor the efficient use of
resources over the longer term, although they offset the potential
increase in carbon storage that elevated levels of CO2 would effect.
The results show that the short-term responses of yellow-poplar
seedlings to elevated CO2 can be sustained over several growing seasons
under field conditions, but resource interactions and feedbacks will
modify the response of forests to rising CO2 concentrations.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="50"><H1>50</H1></A>

<H2>Decomposition Rates of Yellow-Poplar Leaf Litter Are Not Reduced as
a Result of CO2 Enrichment</H2>

<DL>
<DT>E. G. O'Neill and R. J. Norby
</DL>

Litter quality has been predicted to decline in leaves of forest trees
growing in elevated concentrations of CO2 because of decreases in
concentrations of nitrogen in relation to concentrations of
recalcitrant carbon compounds (e.g., lignin).  Changes in nutrient
ratios could reduce decomposition rates and potentially affect nutrient
cycling within forested ecosystems.  These predictions are largely
based on observed nutrient concentrations in green leaves of potted
seedlings following CO2 enrichment; researchers have never measured
actual decomposition rates of naturally abscised leaves produced in
elevated-CO2 atmospheres under field conditions.<P>

Seedlings of yellow-poplar (<I>Liriodendron tulipifera L.</I>) were
soil-grown in open-top field chambers at the Global Change Field
Research Site and exposed to ambient air enriched with O2 at the level
0, 150, or 300 mol/mol for one growing season.  In late fall of 1989,
2-mm mesh bags were filled with abscised leaves from the seedlings,
placed beneath indigenous litter on Walker Branch Watershed, and
periodically retrieved for nutrient analysis and dry mass measurements
over the next 2 years.<P>

Initial lignin and nitrogen concentrations were slightly lower in
leaves produced under CO2 enrichment.  Litter mass losses for the first
18 months were 54.7% of the original mass for ambient-grown leaves,
57.9% for leaves grown in ambient + CO2 at 150 micro-mol/mol, and 53.6%
for leaves grown in ambient + CO2 at 300 micro-mol/mol.  Rates of loss
were not different among CO2 treatments.  Neither the rates of loss in
litter mass nor the changes in lignin and nitrogen concentrations over
time support the hypothesis that decomposition rates will be reduced in
leaves grown in an elevated-CO2 environment.  Although these results
cannot be generalized across all forest tree species, the potential for
changes in nutrient cycling rates resulting from retarded decomposition
may be less than originally anticipated.<P>

<A NAME="51"><H1>51</H1></A>

<H2>Plan for Wildlife Management on the Oak Ridge Reservation
Is Updated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. D. Parr and J. W. Evans (1)
</DL>

A wildlife management plan has been developed and published to update
the 1984 plan prepared before the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR) was
designated as a Wildlife Management Area.  Since 1984, Tennessee
Wildlife Resources Agency (TWRA) has managed wildlife resources on ORR
through a cooperative agreement with DOE, and ESD currently administers
the program.  Management issues are species richness, featured species,
game species, threatened or endangered species, and pests.  The newly
published plan defines wildlife management on ORR and establishes
long-term goals through FY 1995.<P>

Management of wildlife on the large ORR is necessary to ensure public
safety (i.e., by reducing the number of deer/vehicle collisions) and to
maximize the health and diversity of wildlife.  Maintenance of critical
habitats is essential in the preservation of listed rare species.  The
characterization of habitats and the understanding of wildlife
requirements are necessary in making decisions about a species or a
community and evaluating potential impacts.  Information on the types
of habitats present, on wildlife diversity, and on protected habitat
locations is necessary in land- use planning and decision making.
Additionally, TWRA will use information collected through the wildlife
program in its regional forest and wildlife management activities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="52"><H1>52</H1></A>

<H2>Fire Scale, Fire Pattern, and Winter Severity Influence Simulated
Ungulate Survival in Northern Yellowstone National Park</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. G. Turner, Y. Wu, W. H. Romme (1), and L. L. Wallace (2)
</DL>

A spatially explicit individual-based simulation model was
developed to explore the effects that the scale and pattern of fire
have on winter foraging dynamics and the survival of free-ranging
elk (<I>Cervus elaphus</I>) and bison (<I>Bison bison</I>) in northern
Yellowstone National Park. The 77,020-ha landscape is represented
as a gridded, irregular polygon with a spatial resolution of 1 ha. 
Forage intake is a function of an animal's initial body weight, the
absolute amount of forage available on a site, and the depth and
density of snow.  When the energy expenditures of an animal exceed
the energy gained during a day, the animal's endogenous reserves
are reduced to offset the deficits.<P>

Simulated elk survival for three winters (1987-88; 1988-89; 1990-91)
agreed with observed data.  A factorial simulation experiment to
explore the effects of fire size, fire pattern, and winter severity on
ungulate survival demonstrated that winter severity played a dominant
role in ungulate survival.  When winter conditions were extremely mild,
even fires that affected 60% of the landscape had no effect on ungulate
survival during the initial postfire winter.  The effects of fire on
ungulate survival became important when winter conditions were normal
to severe.<P>

The spatial patterning of fire affected ungulate survival if fires
covered small to moderate proportions of the landscape (e.g., 15 or
30%) and if winter snow conditions were moderate to severe.  Ungulate
survival was higher with a clumped rather than a fragmented fire
pattern, suggesting that a single, large fire is not equivalent to a
group of smaller, disconnected fires.  The interaction between fire
scale and spatial pattern suggests that knowledge of fire size alone is
not always sufficient to predict ungulate survival.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Biology Department, Fort Lewis College, Durango, Colorado.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Department of Botany and Microbiology, University of Oklahoma,
Norman.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="53"><H1>53</H1></A>

<H2>Ultraviolet-B Damage to Forest Tree Pollen Is Assessed and
Quantified</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. A. Tuskan, T. J. Tschaplinski, and N. T. Edwards
</DL>

Continued reductions in stratospheric ozone levels are predicted to
have serious consequences for plant and animal species because of
concomitant increases in ultraviolet radiation at the earth's surface.
Biologically active ultraviolet-B radiation (UV-B, wavelengths between
280 and 320 nm) is projected to increase by 2% for every 1% decrease in
stratospheric ozone.  Forest reproduction and, therefore, forest
regeneration and adaptation to stress are likely to be affected by
elevated levels of UV-B radiation.  In fact, reproduction may be the
most susceptible stage in a forest tree species' life cycle.  To ensure
reproductive success, forest tree species have evolved several
species-specific modes of reproduction, including wind pollination with
delayed fertilization, wind pollination with prompt fertilization, and
insect pollination with prompt fertilization.  The modes of
reproduction may predipose the species to differing degrees of damage
associated with elevated levels of UV-B radiation.  A study was
undertaken to describe the morphological and physiological effects that
elevated levels of UV-B radiation have on pollen function in northern
forest tree species.<P>

Pollen was collected from loblolly pine (<I>Pinus taeda</I> L.), red
spruce (<I>Picea rubens</I> Sarg.), and yellow-poplar (<I>Liriodendron
tulipifera</I> L.).  Three irradiance levels (0%, 30%, and 100% above
ambient) and two exposure times (4 h and 8 h) were used to test the
sensitivity of pollen to elevated levels of UV-B radiation.  Five
milligrams of pollen was placed on a nylon membrane overlaid on a 0.6%
agar-solidified nutrient medium.  Twelve petri plates were used per
treatment.  Treatments were applied within a growth chamber fitted with
UVB-313 fluorescent lights covered with cellulose acetate filters.
This light bank transmits UV-A (wavelengths between 320 and 400 nm) and
UV-B radiation.  Mylar filters (0.13 mm) were used to attenuate UV-B
radiation within the control treatments.  Data collection and analyses
included evaluation of the percentage of germination, the length of
germ tubes, the percentage of abnormal pollen tube formation, and
secondary plant metabolites that attenuate UV-B.  Germination
measurements were made on four subsamples per petri plate 72 h after
treatment; 25 pollen cells were counted to determine percent
germination per subsample, and ten pollen tubes were measured for germ
tube length per subsample.  Phenolic compounds that absorb UV- B were
screened by reversed-phase, high-pressure liquid chromatography (HPLC)
with the use of a methanol/water:  tetrahydrofuran gradient and
detection with a diode array detector at 301 nm.<P>

Pollen from the three tested species varied in their response to
elevated UV-B radiation.  Under 8-h exposures, all pollen failed to
germinate.  Under 4-h exposures, the insect-pollinated species,
yellow-poplar, was more sensitive to UV-B radiation than were the
wind-pollinated species.  In all species, significant increases
occurred in the frequency of abnormal tube formation in the exposed
pollen.  HPLC analysis revealed large differences among species in the
concentration and form of compounds that absorb UV-B.  Efforts are now
under way to characterize those specific compounds and to relate the
differences between species to the species' ability to tolerate
elevated levels of UV-B.<P>

<A NAME="54"><H1>54</H1></A>

<H2>Exploratory Study Evaluates the Use of Nitrogen Isotope Ratios in
Plants as an Indicator of Soil Nitrogen Status</H2>

<DL>
<DT>H. Van Miegroet and C. T. Garten
</DL>

Researchers are interested in assessing the ability of forests to
retain nitrogen deposition because of the potentially detrimental
effects of excessive nitrate leaching on soil and stream-water
quality.  A study in the Great Smoky Mountains tests to what extent the
isotopic nitrogen composition of plants can be used as an indicator of
soil nitrogen status and retention capacity.<P>

Belowground nitrogen dynamics are largely controlled by microbial
uptake and release processes that are often difficult to quantify.
They occur at different relative rates depending on the availability of
nitrogen in the soil and also differ in the relative use of 14N versus
15N.  According to theoretical models, these differences should cause a
change in isotopic compositions of the available nitrogen pool between
nitrogen-poor and nitrogen-rich soils and, consequently, in the
isotopic nitrogen composition of plants using that soil nitrogen.<P>

To validate these concepts eight field sites that were assumed to range
in soil nitrogen status from nitrogen-deficient to nitrogen-saturated
were selected in the Great Smoky Mountains.  At each site, foliage
samples from conifer, hardwood, and understory species are analyzed for
their isotopic nitrogen composition and will be compared with forest
floor and upper mineral soil samples in regard to their nitrogen
mineralization and nitrification potential.  If a correlation can be
successfully established between the soil nitrogen status and the
foliar isotopic nitrogen composition, then the latter could become a
useful tool in broad geographical assessments to indicate forested
sites that (1) have low nitrogen retention capacity and (2) will be
sensitive to the effects of atmospheric nitrogen deposition.<P>

<A NAME="55"><H1>55</H1></A>

<H2>Individual-Based Fish Population Model Is Applied to Management
Issue</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. Van Winkle, D. L. DeAngelis, M. S. Ridgway (1), B. J. Shuter (1), and
K. O. Winemiller (2)
</DL>

An individual-based population model has been developed for smallmouth
bass as part of the Program on Compensatory Mechanisms in Fish
Populations, which is funded by the Electric Power Research Institute.
This model is now being tested using empirical data from different
lakes and is being applied to specific management questions concerning
this species.<P>

The smallmouth bass model, previously tested on Lake Opeongo, Ontario,
Canada, has been tested on approximately 12 additional lakes in
Ontario, spanning an appreciable latitudinal range.  Spawning starts
nearly 1 month later, and the length of the growing season for the
young-of-year bass is more than 1 month shorter at the most northern
latitude than at the most southern latitude.  Input data for each lake
included daily temperature values, date and temperature of spawning,
and size of each nesting male.  Given these input data, the model
predicted the size-frequency distribution of young-of-year through the
summer and until the end of the first growing season.  These predicted
distributions were compared with the observed size-frequency
distributions.  The data for each lake provided an independent test of
the model.  This corroboration process established bounds on the
accuracy and robustness of the smallmouth bass model.<P>

We found that the model provides acceptably accurate simulations of
size-frequency distributions of young-of-year in different lakes based
on our process-oriented representation of growth and survival of the
early life stages.  We are now evaluating alternative scenarios for the
opening date of the fishing season.  By varying the opening date, it is
possible to explore the results of increasing and decreasing the degree
of overlap between the spawning and nest-guarding period and the
exploitation of guarding male smallmouth bass by fishing enthusiasts.
The degree of overlap, in turn, will influence the survival and
subsequent growth of both the guarding males and the young-of-year,
possibly in a density-dependent or compensatory manner.  This
application will provide valuable guidance for the Ontario Ministry of
Natural Resources in its deliberations on the opening date for
smallmouth bass.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources, Maple, Ontario, Canada.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="56"><H1>56</H1></A>

<H2>NOYELP Landscape Model Simulates Winter Foraging by Elk and Bison
in the Northern Range of Yellowstone National Park</H2>

<DL>
<DT>Y. Wu (1) and M. G. Turner
</DL>

Northern Yellowstone National Park includes 78,000 ha of winter range,
which is important to ungulates.  The 1988 fires in the park created a
heterogeneous landscape in terms of both resource patterns and
availabilities, but the response of ungulates to such broad-scale
landscape change is not well known.  NOYELP is a landscape simulation
model of winter foraging by large ungulates in the northern range of
Yellowstone National Park developed to study the effects of burning
patterns and winter severity on the survival of ungulates.<P>

An initial model for a 100 X 100 grid-cell landscape was used to
explore implications of alternative model formations to provide a
better basis for developing NOYELP.  The results from the initial model
suggest that the fragmentation of large resource patches in a landscape
may strongly influence winter foraging and ungulate survival.  As
resources become limited, their spatial distribution becomes
important.  It is also found that winter severity affects ungulate
survival by both redistribution and reduction of available forage and
limitation of ungulate mobility.<P>

NOYELP is a spatially explicit model of the 78,000-ha winter range and
simulates individual elk (<I>Cervus elaphus</I>) and bison (<I>Bison
bison</I>) foraging in heterogeneous landscapes.  A basic feature of
the model is a linkage of the core simulation program written in
FORTRAN to a visualization environment, PV-WAVE, through the use of a
procedure written in the computer language C.  The visualization
includes (1) landscape maps displaying the location of elk and bison
and the distributions of available biomass and snow and (2) graphs
showing the time-series dynamics of ungulate survival, landscape
patchiness, biomass availability, and energetic balance.  The
methodology of spatially simulating and displaying landscape dynamics
is a challenge for landscape ecologists and is of interest to land
management agencies.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Fort Lewis College, Durango, Colorado.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="57"><H1>57</H1></A>

<H2>Long-Term Growth at Elevated Concentrations of Atmospheric CO2
Reduces Leaf Respiration in Saplings of Yellow-Poplar</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. D. Wullschleger and R. J. Norby
</DL>

An assessment of the influence of increasing CO2 concentrations on
forest vegetation requires information on both the gain of carbon
through photosynthesis and the loss of carbon through respiration.
Photosynthesis frequently increases during CO2 enrichment, and such
increases can be sustained over a relatively long time scale.  However,
the response of leaf respiration to elevated CO2 is less well
documented.  Given that respiratory carbon losses from mature
ecosystems can account for &gt;50% of gross primary productivity,
respiration must be recognized as an important process in plant-
response studies to global change.<P>

We established a 4-year field study of tree responses to elevated
concentrations of CO2 in which we could examine whether leaf
respiration is affected by CO2 enrichment.  Yellow-poplar
(<I>Liriodendron tulipifera</I> L.) seedlings were planted in the
ground within six open-top chambers in May 1989.  Chamber atmospheres
were enriched with CO2 to one of three concentrations:  +0
micro-mol/mol (ambient), +150 micro-mol/mol, and +300 micro-mol/mol.
Two replicate chambers were provided per treatment.  During 1991, rates
of leaf respiration and the kinetics of leaf growth were measured.<P>

Despite no effect of CO2 on leaf area expansion or relative growth
rate, enrichment of the ambient atmosphere with CO2 in the amount of
150 or 300 micro-mol/mol decreased the respiration rate by 28 to 45% in
comparison with that of ambient-grown plants.  When the respiration
rate was mathematically partitioned to its growth and maintenance
components, the growth coefficient was reduced 19% by CO2 enrichment,
and the maintenance coefficient was decreased by 34% in comparison with
the coefficients of leaves from ambient-grown controls.<P>

Simulation studies indicated that leaf respiration integrated over a
50-d life span was reduced 21-26% for a leaf exposed to CO2
concentrations of ambient +150 or ambient +300 micro-mol/mol in
comparison with one grown at ambient CO2 conditions.  These reductions
were strongly driven by decreasing maintenance respiration, whereas the
contribution of decreasing growth respiration was largely offset by
greater leaf dry weight.<P>

Although reductions in the respiratory cost of growth and maintenance
are often interpreted as being beneficial, leaf respiration is unlikely
to decrease without a concomitant decrease in other metabolic
processes.  Although reduced respiration did not affect developmental
events such as leaf expansion and relative growth rate, decreased
maintenance respiration could possibly influence a plant's capacity to
withstand other co-occurring stresses.  As we continue to examine the
mechanisms by which plants respond to CO2 enrichment, consideration
should be given to the consequences of decreasing respiration and its
implications for forest health.<P>

