<TITLE>Environmental Analyses</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Analyses</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Analyses Section of the Environmental Sciences
Division (ESD) at Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) develops theory
and methods, analytical tools, and numeric data bases to evaluate
environmental problems and issues, and it prepares interdisciplinary
assessments of environmental issues at spatial scales ranging from the
individual site to the regional landscape to the globe.  The section
also provides technical assistance for the development of policy
concerning compliance with environmental regulations.  These objectives
are accomplished by the four groups into which the section is
divided.<P>

<H2>Environmental Assessment</H2>

The Environmental Assessment Group prepares impact analyses for use by
sponsors within the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE), the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission (FERC), the Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC),
and the U.S. Department of Defense (DOD) as part of their compliance
with the National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA).  These analyses
assess impacts on terrestrial and aquatic ecological resources, land
and water use, and water quality for environmental impact statements
and related documents.<P>

Staff members also conduct technical reviews and analyses of NEPA
documents and related issues for the DOE Office of NEPA Oversight and
the Environmental Compliance Division of the DOE Office of
Environmental Restoration and Waste Management, and they provide the
Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Office of Federal Activities with
technical support.  The goal of the Environmental Assessment Group is
to apply state-of-the-art assessment tools to complex issues at
individual plants, at geographically large sites, and in areas that are
programmatic in scope.<P>

In FY 1992, staff provided NEPA training for DOE managers and, as
members of Tiger Teams, played an important role in assessing NEPA
compliance at DOE facilities.  The group is also analyzing the
environmental implications of the development of a geothermal project
and multiple hydroelectric power plants, the relicensing of nuclear
power plants, the disposal of the U.S. stockpile of chemical agents and
munitions, and continuation of the U.S.  Antarctic Program.  In
addition, staff cochaired an international task force on the
application of environmental impact assessment (EIA) to government
policy, plans, and programs for EPA.  New initiatives for EPA include
the development of an EIA sourcebook or manual.<P>

<H2>Environmental Compliance</H2>

The Environmental Compliance Group conducts a variety of regulatory
analysis and environmental compliance activities in support of a number
of sponsors, such as the DOE Office of Environmental Guidance and the
U.S. Air Force.  Intense pressure to clean up and protect the
environment at federal sites is currently being exerted by Congress,
the regulatory authorities, and the public.  The regulatory programs
that implement the major federal environmental statutesincluding the
Resource Conservation and Recovery Act and the Comprehensive
Environmental Response, Compensation and Liability Act--are complex mazes
of rules, procedures, and technical requirements that change frequently
as the regulatory authorities respond to changes in law.<P>

The Environmental Compliance Group provides the necessary information
resources and uses scientific, engineering, legal, and regulatory
expertise to analyze regulatory issues and to develop environmental
compliance methodologies and strategies to assist DOE and other
sponsors in complying with environmental requirements.  DOE and other
sponsors are provided with technical assistance through the tracking of
new laws and regulations, comment and analysis of new regulatory
initiatives, development of guidance, issuance of periodic reports and
bulletins, and training on various environmental regulatory issues.<P>

In FY 1992 the Environmental Compliance Group issued 8 reports, several
information briefs, and 2 regulatory bulletins, and staff conducted 14
training workshops on environmental laws and regulations for DOE and
contractor staff.<P>

<H2>Environmental Risk</H2>

The Environmental Risk Group develops methods for quantitative
assessment of environmental risks; applies these methods to local,
regional, and national environmental problems; and provides regulatory
agencies with guidance on the uses of environmental risk assessment.
Specific areas of interest include defining and measuring the health of
ecological resources, extrapolating test data from laboratory to field
and from individuals to populations and ecosystems, quantifying
ecological risks at the watershed and landscape levels, and predicting
the movement of contaminants through food chains.<P>

Research is conducted jointly with other ESD groups and with other ORNL
divisions and supports the ORNL Center for Risk Management.  The
current principal focus of the group is assessment of ecological risks
of toxic contaminants at DOE facilities.  Other significant program
areas include the characterization of ecological resources at regional
scales and the economic valuation of environmental impacts of energy
technologies.  Current sponsors include DOE, EPA, the Bonneville Power
Administration, and the Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.,
Environmental Restoration Program.<P>

Activities initiated through the Center for Risk Management in FY 1992
included research for EPA on the feasibility of establishing uniform
soil quality criteria for the protection of groundwater.  Staff also
assessed the cumulative health and ecological impacts of DOE's
environmental restoration and waste management programs.<P>

<H2>Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems</H2>

The purpose of the Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems
Group is to provide the information, data, and analytical capabilities
essential to performing comprehensive, resource-intensive regional and
global evaluations of increases in radiatively active trace gases in
the atmosphere (``greenhouse'' gases) and the potential effects of such
changes on environmental and societal resources.  The group employs
state-of-the-art information, data management, and analytical
techniques to ensure the proper exchange of information and data
between researchers and a diverse user community of scientists,
policymakers, educators, students, and corporate officials.  To achieve
the careful balance of information and data support needed to meet
project requirements, the group relies on information theory, computer
science, geographic information systems, library science,
telecommunications, scientific visualization, statistical science, and
data management.<P>

The products of the Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems
Group include journal articles, newsletters, brochures, ORNL and DOE
reports, and fully documented numeric data packages and computer model
packages.  The single largest function of the group is to operate the
Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center (in support of the DOE
Global Change Research Program) and the World Data Center-A for
Atmospheric Trace Gases (part of the World Data Center System, which is
coordinated by the International Council of Scientific Unions).  The
Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems Group has also been
active in the analysis of the potential effects that changes in climate
and sea level would have on environmental and societal resources.<P>

In FY 1992 the Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center prepared and
distributed a wide variety of data and information products and
responded to thousands of information requests.  The group completed a
project to compile a Coastal Hazards Data Base for North America, which
includes data useful for estimating the relative vulnerability of
coastal regions to the inundation and erosion associated with rising
sea level.  To evaluate the land uses potentially at risk from changing
climate and rising sea level at six study sites along the southeastern
U.S. coast, the group also completed a report in which data from the
Coastal Hazards Data Base are combined with information on storms and
sediment transport.<P>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="58"><H1>58</H1></A>

<H2>Uranium Enrichment Program Is Provided with Technical Support on
Management of Environmental Issues</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. K. Eddlemon, J. R. Barker (1), P. M. O'Connell (2), T. L.
Ashwood, M. S. Salk, G. F. Cada, and J. W. Webb
</DL>

During the past year, staff of the Environmental Analyses Section of
ESD have provided the environmental program of DOE's Office of Uranium
Enrichment with technical support on the management of environmental
issues.  Among other things, a draft document was developed outlining
program-specific planning and guidance in regard to compliance with the
National Environmental Policy Act (NEPA).  Staff members also drew up a
draft of a guidance and resource document on the major requirements of
more than 15 environmental laws and their implementing regulations,
federal facility compliance agreements, DOE orders, and applicability
to the Portsmouth and Paducah Gaseous Diffusion plants.<P>

Specific NEPA procedures for placing Portsmouth production operations
for highly enriched uranium in cold standby were also developed, and
draft guidance documents produced by the Office of Uranium Enrichment
were reviewed.  ESD has also contracted with Systematic Management
Services, Inc., to develop a computerized environmental program network
that will include all major environmental program actions over the
planning period.  This effort has resulted in a draft updatable network
of program milestones for Paducah for use as a basis for scheduling and
integrating program activities, preparing annual budget requests, and
assessing the status of program implementation.<P>

<DL>
