<DT>(1) <I>Systematic Management Services, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, College of Law.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="59"><H1>59</H1></A>

<H2>Bird Mortality Due to Collisions with Nuclear Power Plant
Facilities Is Assessed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Kroodsma
</DL>

The 40-year operating licenses of nuclear power plants in the United
States begin to expire at the end of this century.  ORNL is assisting
the U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC) in preparing a generic
environmental impact statement (GEIS) addressing the impacts of
relicensing these nuclear plants.  At the time of each plant's
relicensing, NRC will prepare a plant-specific environmental assessment
or impact statement.  One impact under consideration is the possible
reduction of bird populations as a result of bird collisions with
nuclear plant cooling towers and power lines.  A review of literature
and nuclear plant monitoring data was performed to assess this
potential impact.<P>

The review found that millions of birds in the United States die from
natural causes each year, and millions more are killed after colliding
with windows of houses and other buildings, power lines from all types
of generating facilities, radio and television towers, vehicles,
telephone and local electric lines, smokestacks, cooling towers, and
many other man-made objects.  However, the literature did not recognize
cooling towers, including the tall natural-draft cooling towers at some
nuclear plants, as a significant concern.  Monitoring data were
available for 6 of 21 nuclear plants with natural-draft towers.  The
data indicated that migrant birds frequently collided with towers
before plant operation began, but collisions were much less frequent
during operation.  Cooling tower noise and power plant lights
illuminating the towers during operation may have minimized collisions,
according to monitoring personnel.  The data also showed that local
bird populations were unaffected, because birds residing in the area
seldom collided with the towers.<P>

Bird collision mortality has been surveyed along many power lines and
at many other structures.  However, whether long-term avian population
densities are reduced as a result of collision with power lines or
other structures is unknown.  Some authors believed that collisions
with all types of man-made objects did not reduce overall bird
populations.  However, a few authors believed that collision frequency
along the thousands of miles of power and communication lines was not
feasible to document by field studies and that such collisions could be
affecting overall populations of some migratory species.  More concern
was expressed for rare species.  For example, the principal known cause
of death for the endangered whooping crane is collision with power
lines.  Many sandhill cranes also collide with power lines, but their
population has increased significantly during the past few decades.
Aviation marker balls and other types of markers have been used
successfully in some areas to make power lines more visible to birds,
thus reducing collision frequency.<P>

Bird collision mortality was monitored along the power lines of
apparently only one nuclear plant, where the lines crossed a wetland
area.  Mortality was monitored for several years and was too small to
have affected any bird population.  No power lines of nuclear plants
have been identified as causing significant bird mortality.<P>

This review of literature and nuclear plant monitoring data led to a
GEIS conclusion that cooling towers were not significantly affecting
bird populations and that nuclear plant power lines were not affecting
birds any more than power lines in general.  Collision with power lines
in general has apparently not reduced long-term bird population levels,
but no conclusive determination could be made.<P>

<A NAME="60"><H1>60</H1></A>

<H2>Environmental Criteria for Assessing Cumulative Impacts on Wildlife
Are Identified for Proposed Hydropower Projects in Washington</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Kroodsma
</DL>

Several private firms propose to construct and operate a total of 11
small hydropower projects in the Skagit River Basin in the northern
Cascade Mountains of northwestern Washington.  The Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission, the hydropower licensing agency, contracted ORNL
to prepare an environmental assessment to identify (1) those projects
that would contribute significantly to cumulative impacts and should be
considered in a basinwide environmental impact statement (EIS) and (2)
those projects that would have negligible contributions to cumulative
impact and would not require consideration in an EIS.<P>

To assess potential cumulative impacts on important wildlife species, I
developed from the literature a comprehensive list of 15 environmental
criteria that, if affected by a project, would suggest the occurrence
of cumulative impacts on wildlife.  Examples of the criteria include
nest or den sites, food resources, habitat block size, and dispersal
mechanisms.  Analysis of the project proposals indicated that the
projects would have negligible effects on wildlife in terms of seven of
these criteria.  The other eight criteria were useful in quantitatively
rating the potential impact of each project and in determining which
projects could cause cumulative impacts and should be included in the
basinwide EIS.<P>

Four of the 11 proposed projects were judged to have negligible
potential for impact on wildlife.  These included two projects whose
proposed sites had been extensively clearcut and had roads and no
important wildlife habitat and two other project sites that were very
small and were adjacent to already disturbed areas.  Two of these
projects will nevertheless be included in the basinwide EIS, which ORNL
is currently preparing, because of potential impacts on other
resources.  The EIS will require detailed analysis of potential impacts
on each important wildlife species with respect to the criteria
selected.<P>

<A NAME="61"><H1>61</H1></A>

<H2>PC-Based Software for Risk Assessment Is Developed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>A. E. Rosen, G. W. Suter II, and L. W. Barnthouse
</DL>

In previous work we demonstrated methods for linking laboratory-derived
toxicity test data to fish population models.  The purpose was to
estimate the effects of toxic chemicals, as revealed by conventional
laboratory test data, on fish populations in the field.  To accomplish
this, we developed three computer programs that ran on an IBM mainframe
computer.<P>

The next step was to develop a PC-based, user-friendly program that
combined the above activities.  The program is menu-driven, allowing
nonprogrammers to enter data, execute either the reproductive potential
model or the life-cycle model, and view the results in graphical or
tabular form.<P>

This program is used in the off-site Environmental Restoration Program
to estimate risks of various contaminants to largemouth bass
populations.<P>

<A NAME="62"><H1>62</H1></A>

<H2>Revision of the <I>Federal Manual for Identifying and Delineating
Jurisdictional Wetlands</I> Was Reviewed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. S. Salk, C. C. Trettin (1), C. L. Hardy (1), and V. R. Tolbert
</DL>

On August 14, 1991, EPA, the Army Corps of Engineers, the Soil
Conservation Service of the Department of Agriculture, and the Fish and
Wildlife Service of the Department of the Interior published a joint
notice in the <I>Federal Register</I> (2) proposing a revision of the
1989 <I>Federal Manual for Identifying and Delineating Jurisdictional
Wetlands</I> and asking for public review and technical comments on
it.  The manual was initially adopted in 1989 to provide a consistent
interagency approach to the identification of jurisdictional
wetlands.<P>

After using the manual for 2 years, the agencies proposed the revision
with the intention of improving the scientific validity of the
delineation methods and minimizing erroneous wetlands determinations.
At the request of DOE's Office of Environmental Guidance (EH-23), ORNL
staff prepared a series of documents that included a written summary of
the proposed revision, an assessment of its impact on DOE operations,
substantive technical comments regarding the issues that are important
to DOE, a review of the comments received from other DOE facilities,
and a draft consolidation of comments for transmittal to EPA.  The
above information formed the basis of what EH-23 submitted to EPA.<P>

Many of the changes proposed in the manual appear to be the result of
political rather than scientific considerations and are, therefore,
very controversial.  The intention of ORNL's technical comments was to
improve the scientific basis of the revised manual and make it a more
objective document; the aim was to preserve as many of the nation's
remaining wetlands as possible.<P>

These technical comments included the following: (1) The period of
saturation or inundation should be limited to 2 weeks.  (2) The best
alternative for delineating wetlands combines field indicators and
staff judgment.  (3) The occurrence of water stains on tree trunks is a
useful secondary indicator of duration of flooding.  (4) It is
reasonable to recognize that some wetlands meet only two of the three
wetland criteria.  (5) Facultative species can be important components
of wetland ecosystems.  (6) The proposed specifications for determining
when the wetland hydrology criterion is met are excessive and should be
limited to 3 years of records.  (7) Establishing criteria for
delineating obvious wetlands to eliminate the need for site-specific
assessments seems unwarranted.  (8) The growing season should be
defined by the use of physiological benchmarks for indicator species.
(9) Provisions for the assessment of disturbed wetlands need to include
the consideration of natural disturbances on wetland indicators.  (10)
The distinction between soil taxonomic units and soil map units should
be recognized.  (11) The list of special wetlands that fail the
hydrophytic vegetation criterion should be expanded to include lowland
hardwood swamps, jack pine swamps and bogs, and coniferous swamps,
among others.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Jaycor, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) Federal Register, <I><B>56</B>, 20446.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="63"><H1>63</H1></A>

<H2>EAG's NEPA Activities Grow in Calendar Year 1991</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. L. Sigal, G. F. Cada, G. K. Eddlemon, C. G. Heckman, M. S. Salk,
W. E. Schramm, E. D. Smith, V. R. Tolbert, C. C. Trettin, and J. W.
Webb
</DL>

The Environmental Assessment Group (EAG) has provided the DOE Office of
NEPA Oversight (EH-25) and its predecessors with technical support
since 1980.  In general, this support includes assessment of DOE
compliance with the National Environmental Policy Act of 1969 (NEPA),
preparation of background information and analyses of NEPA issues,
review of NEPA documents, and assistance at DOE Headquarters.<P>

Compliance activities during CY 1991 included participation in nine
Tiger Team visits to DOE facilities to assess their compliance with
NEPA.  In addition, the DOE NEPA Compliance Assessment Protocol
(written by EAG in 1989) was revised to reflect the new DOE NEPA order
and the DOE NEPA regulations.  In 1990 EH-25 asked EAG to assist it in
developing a NEPA training program for senior and middle DOE management
personnel as a response, in part, to deficiencies uncovered by the
Tiger Teams.  The training program was revised in CY 1991 to
accommodate changes in the DOE NEPA requirements.  EAG staff
participated in NEPA training at seven DOE facilities.  NEPA training
was also provided for Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.  Also in CY
1991, EAG assisted EH-25 in the development of the new DOE NEPA order,
proposed DOE NEPA regulations, and started revision of the <I>DOE NEPA
Compliance Guide</I> to reflect the new requirements.  (In 1988 EAG
participated in a major revision of the guide.)<P>

Document review for EH-25 averaged seven requests per month during CY
1991.  In response to requests from ORNL's Energy Division, EAG
reviewed NEPA documents and provided the division with technical
support in preparing the ecological sections of NEPA documents.  During
the first half of CY 1991, EAG contributed technical assistance to
EH-25 in Washington, D.C., on a weekly basis.  At EH-25's request, EAG
staff also acted as facilitators and participants in the following
workshops sponsored by the President's Council on Environmental
Quality, EPA, and DOE, respectively:

<UL>
<LI>NEPA Integration:  Effective, Efficient Environmental Compliance in
the 1990s;

<LI>Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability
Act (CERCLA)/NEPA at Federal Facilities; and

<LI>Fulfilling the Commitment:  Implementing the Letter and Spirit of
NEPA.
</UL>

EAG's extensive NEPA experience has also recently gained recognition
from EPA.  During CYs 1990 and 1991, EPA asked EAG to cochair an
international task force and write a report for the group on
environmental impact assessment (EIA).  For CYs 1991 and 1992, EPA
asked EAG to develop an EIA sourcebook that EPA can use in document
review, training, and distribution to other federal agencies and
foreign countries.<P>

These activities have enhanced EAG's NEPA expertise and, thus, the
group's ability to assist DOE in responding to the fourth initiative of
the Secretary of Energy's ten-point plan:  ``Improving the way in which
DOE complies with the National Environmental Policy Act.''<P>

<A NAME="64"><H1>64</H1></A>

<H2>Effluents from the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant Adversely Affect Water
Quality in East Fork Poplar Creek</H2>

<DL>
<DT>V. R. Tolbert, H. J. Eckman (1), and J. G. Smith
</DL>

Past wastewater discharges from the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant have
significantly affected the benthic macroinvertebrate community in the
upper reaches of East Fork Poplar Creek (EFPC).  The responses of
<I>Hydropsyche depravata</I>, a net-spinning caddis fly, were studied
to determine if the thermal regime or water quality may contribute to
reductions in benthic populations at EFPC km (EFK) 23.4 immediately
downstream of the Y-12 Plant.<P>

A laboratory experiment was conducted to determine the effects of
temperature on larval growth, time of emergence, number of emerging
adults, larval mortality, number of eggs per female, and adenosine
triphosphate (ATP) analysis as a measure of food availability.  Larval
third and fourth instars of <I>H. depravata</I> were collected at site
EFK 13.8, divided into three groups, and placed in plastic troughs.
The first group was exposed to daily temperature fluctuations typical
of EFPC at EFK 23.4 (24-31 degrees C), the second to an EFK 13.8 regime
(24-28 degrees C), and the third to a control temperature (24 degrees
C).  The same parameters were measured in another experiment to
determine the effects of ambient water quality on individuals held in
water collected from each site and a control (dechlorinated tap
water).  In this study the larvae were maintained at a constant
temperature in small recirculating tanks in the laboratory; the water
was exchanged with fresh water collected from the appropriate site
every other day.  In both experiments the tanks and troughs were
checked daily for emerged adults, and larvae were weighed every 2 weeks
to determine growth.<P>

Larvae exhibited no significant difference in growth among the three
thermal regimes.  Although the time spans between the beginning of the
experiment and adult emergence were similar among treatments, the
number of emerging adults, rate of emergence, and number of eggs
produced per female were significantly greater with the EFK 13.8
thermal regime than the EFK 23.4 regime (<I>p</I> &lt; 0.05).  Greater
larval mortality occurred at the higher thermal regime (EFK 23.4);
however, the differences were not significant. In the water quality
study, significantly more adults emerged from water taken from EFK
13.8, whereas the number of eggs produced was significantly greater in
females emerged from EFK 23.4 regime (<I>p</I> &lt; 0.05).<P>

ATP analysis of water samples from EFK 23.4 indicated that the
availability of organic matter was adequate to support <I>H.
depravata</I> and other filter-feeding species.  However, the above
studies demonstrated that temperature and water quality in upper EFPC
adversely affect survival, emergence, and egg production of
filter-feeding macroinvertebrates and may also affect other species
that are as sensitive as or more sensitive than <I>H. depravata</I>.
Although water quality did not appear to adversely affect the number of
eggs produced by <I>H. depravata</I> at EFK 23.4, the low number of
adults may limit reproduction, thus reducing the population available
to colonize upper EFPC.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>University of Georgia, Athens.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="65"><H1>65</H1></A>

<H2>Roadmapping Process Was Applied to Waste Management at ORNL in 1991</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. R. Trabalka
</DL>

The DOE Office of Environmental Restoration and Waste Management uses
roadmapping, an issue-oriented planning process, to identify activities
needed for achieving final waste disposal, completing site remediation,
and bringing waste management (WM) operations into compliance.  DOE
installations develop roadmaps by following a systematic process
focused on issue identification, root-cause analysis, and issue
resolution.  Successful application of this process at ORNL required
the involvement of a dedicated, multidisciplinary team knowledgeable
about WM program planning, operations, information resources, and
regulatory compliance.  The ORNL roadmapping team identified issues for
DOE, Energy Systems, and ORNL.  However, most of the issues identified
will require DOE Headquarters support to resolve.  The most important
of these are associated with deficiencies in the planning process.<P>

A total-systems perspective is often absent from the planning process.
Consequently, short-term solutions to problems often create long-term
problems.  Specific examples include commitments [e.g., Federal
Facilities Agreement (FFA) for the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR)] made
without sufficient analysis of their consequences, and mismatches
between such commitments and the resources needed for compliance.  For
example, the inability of ORNL to meet FFA requirements affecting the
liquid-low-level-waste (LLLW) system because of technical, resource,
and logistical constraints could result in shutdowns of some WM and
research-and-development activities.  A total-systems planning effort,
one that includes a formal process for substantive ORNL participation,
reconsideration of existing commitments and resource allocations, and
effective contingency planning to minimize impacts of budget
fluctuations, is needed to address such issues.<P>

The fragmented approach to planning has failed to identify the (1)
limited capacity of ORR for disposal, (2) inadequacy of current
treatment and storage capabilities, and (3) critical need for off-site
treatment and disposal facilities for both low-level-radioactive and
mixed wastes from ORNL.  This situation has resulted in (1) dependence
on long-term storage and accumulation of a significant waste legacy,
(2) regulatory noncompliances (e.g., mixed wastes that carry
land-disposal restrictions) requiring development of multiple
compliance agreements, and (3) depletion of available storage
capacity.  Continued deferral of the Waste Handling and Packaging Plant
at ORNL will severely restrict LLLW and solid transuranic WM and
prolong regulatory noncompliances.<P>

Some of the actions needed from DOE to resolve these issues include
development and implementation of a national WM strategy (e.g.,
national/regional treatment and disposal facilities) and alleviation of
delays in funding and approvals for major ORR facilities.  In addition,
DOE needs to assert its technical leadership and work with the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission and EPA to accelerate the development of (1)
federal below-regulatory concern (BRC) limits and interim off-site
release limits for radionuclides, (2) a coherent approach to
radioactive mixed WM (including BRC limits for hazardous chemicals),
and (3) improved performance assessment methods for waste disposal
facilities.<P>

<A NAME="66"><H1>66</H1></A>

<H2>Analysis of Proposed Hydropower Projects in Washington Reveals
Possible Cumulative Impacts on Wildlife</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. W. Webb
</DL>

National Environmental Policy Act regulations require that analyses of
environmental impacts include assessments of cumulative impacts.
Cumulative impacts are the incremental effects of an action on specific
resources added to past, present, and reasonably foreseeable impacts of
other actions (40 CFR 1708.7).  The forests and associated wildlife of
the western Cascade Mountains in the Pacific Northwest, for instance,
are under great stress from such activities as logging and recreation.
Additional potential stress on the resource is created by multiple
applications for hydropower development of mountain streams, a process
governed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC).
Scientists at ORNL assisted FERC in conducting a preliminary screening
of such applications for the Nooksack River basin, Washington, to
assist in determining whether to prepare a full environmental impact
statement (EIS) on the projects.<P>

A team of specialists in terrestrial and aquatic ecology, land use and
recreation, cultural resources, and geology visited the basin and
toured each proposed hydropower site.  From the visit and from
information in the application as well as in the open literature, team
members judged whether each project might contribute to potential
cumulative impacts on the various resources.<P>

Many of the project areas were considered subject to landslides and
other geologic instability, either from the project itself or from
other activities.  Slope failure could lead to project-related damage,
such as pipeline rupture, which in turn could damage other resources.
Terrestrial resources at risk included the bald eagle (on the federal
list of threatened and endangered species), the spotted owl (recently
added to the federal list), mountain goats, deer, and old-growth
forests.  Because these and other terrestrial resources are already
rare and under continuing pressure from human activities, even a small
potential impact was considered important.  As a result, all seven of
the projects proposed for hydropower development in the Nooksack River
basin were considered to have potential for cumulative impacts on at
least one of the terrestrial resources.  Because of this conclusion and
similar conclusions for other resources, FERC will prepare an EIS for
projects in the basin to evaluate cumulative and other impacts more
fully.<P>

