<TITLE>Environmental Biotechnology</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Biotechnology</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Biotechnology Section is involved in basic and
applied research on the mechanisms through which contaminants affect
biological systems, the ways in which receiving systems affect the
availability and distribution of materials to which they are exposed,
and the modification of biological and environmental systems to enhance
degradation or immobilization.  Research is conducted from the
subcellular and biochemical level to the ecosystem level with
experimental, observational, and simulation studies.  Researchers
investigate both the role that molecular, biochemical, and
physiological processes have in regulating the biological accumulation
of contaminants and the adverse effects that the contaminants have on
the environment.<P>

Section activities center on the response of Oak Ridge Reservation
(ORR) streams to waste management and cleanup activities and on the
development of capabilities for predicting direct and indirect effects
of contaminants released to the environment.  Further areas of research
are environmental transport, fate of contaminants in aquatic
environments, and biogeochemistry of contaminants.  Major emphasis is
on the off-site environments surrounding ORR.  The section provides
data management responsibilities for the environmental restoration
projects at Energy Systems facilities.<P>

Research in the section also addresses the sources of chronic and acute
toxicity in wastewaters and streams on ORR and the development of in
situ and laboratory tests to detect and quantify toxicity.  In
addition, section staff are participating in a major effort in
incorporating molecular biology with traditional microbiological tools
to understand and control degradation of soil and groundwater
contaminants.<P>

<H2>Biological Markers</H2>

The Biological Markers Group assists in the assessment of the health of
the environment by identifying and evaluating biological responses
induced in biota exposed to contamination.  Biological responses are
studied at the molecular, biochemical, and physiological levels, both
to understand the basic toxicological mechanisms elicited by exposure
to environmental contaminants and to relate these changes to effects
observed at higher levels of biological organization.<P>

Studies of freshwater fish demonstrate that biochemical and
physiological measures of contaminant-related stress can serve as early
warning signals of impending damage at higher levels of biological
organization.  Two studies, one dealing with the effect of PCBs on fish
health in a reservoir and the other with the risks to the blue heron
nesting sites downstream from the Oak Ridge Reservation, focus on large
field investigations.  Several investigations are being conducted to
develop and refine molecular markers.  These investigations include the
comparison of chromatin structure in blood cell nuclei of three fish
species and the use of restriction fragment lenght polymorphism for
environmental population genetics studies.<P>

<H2>Biomonitoring</H2>

Activities of the Biomonitoring Group include studies to assess the
responses of aquatic populations and communities to radiological and
nonradiological contaminants in existing point-source (effluent)
discharges and nonpoint-source discharges associated with past waste
disposal operations at DOE facilities in Oak Ridge, Tennessee; Paducah,
Kentucky; and Portsmouth, Ohio.  These studies focus on identification
of appropriate parameters for evaluating the impacts on and recovery of
stream ecosystems.  Projects in the group incorporate a variety of
techniques ranging from laboratory toxicity tests and manipulative
field experiments to comprehensive ecological surveys. Established
protocols combined with innovative, state-of-the-art techniques are
used to document regulatory compliance and to ensure environmental
protection and restoration.<P>

Researchers have conducted biological monitoring on the Oak Ridge
Reservation since 1985.  Fish abundance has increased in three streams
following restoration activities on new wastewater treatment facilities
coming on-line.  Polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) remain contaminants
of concern and, therefore, are investigated through several monitoring
projects.  A study with clams indicates that chlorine in the stream
discharge causes clams to modify their filtering and feeding
behaviors.   Consequently, the clams exhibit a lower PCB
bioaccumulation than what occurs in indigenous aquatic life.<P>

<H2>Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program</H2>

The Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program, which is conducted
for the Energy Systems Environmental Restoration Program, addresses the
transport, fate, and effects of contaminants in surface waters beyond
the boundaries of the DOE Oak Ridge Reservation.  Ongoing
investigations focus on (1) determining the nature and extent of
off-site surface water contamination, (2) assessing potential
contaminant transport and exposure pathways and the associated risks to
human health and the environment, and (3) evaluating and implementing
appropriate remedial actions.<P>

<H2>Ecotoxicology</H2>

The Ecotoxicology Group uses laboratory bioassays of fish, daphnids,
snails, and algae to quantify toxicity, identify toxic constituents in
wastewaters, and verify the efficacy of changes in treatment
operations.  The group also conducts diverse laboratory and in situ
toxicity tests and uses field manipulative experiments to identify and
quantify toxic conditions in contaminated streams.  Experimental
studies of community structures and food webs in contaminated and
noncontaminated streams, ponds, and wetlands show how contaminants
modify aquatic communities or indirectly alter populations,
communities, or ecological processes.<P>

Fathead minnow and <I>Ceriodaphnia</I> toxicity tests identified three
artifacts that require consideration when ambient toxicity studies are
conducted.  These artifacts relate to pathogenic bacteria or fungi
(fathead minnow), brood size, and the ability of chlorine to be
modified by food added to the <I>Ceriodaphnia</I> test.  Studies of
lipids in periphyton show them to be useful as integrative indicators
of the physiological status of this community.<P>

<H2>Environmental Chemistry</H2>

The Environmental Chemistry Group investigates the transport,
transformation, and accumulation of materials in surface water
environments, including sediments and biota.  Additionally, the
dispersal of contaminants through the subsurface environment is being
examined, especially with respect to the role of organic and inorganic
colloidal particles in enhancing the mobility of hazardous chemicals in
groundwater.  Investigations conducted by the Environmental Chemistry
Group form an important link between information on basic principles
and processes and their applications to current applied research, such
as environmental restoration and remedial actions.<P>

Research within this group was directed toward contaminant transport
within the Clinch River and the role of colloids in affecting
subsurface transport.  The finding of elevated levels of 137Cs on
surface sediments within WOCE led to accelerated site characterization
and, ultimately, construction of a detention dam.  Colloid studies
emphasized field investigations of natural organic matter and iron
oxides in a sandy aquifer.  The transport of colloids was significantly
delayed relative to the transport of nonreactive colloid tracers in the
field study.  Data for improving predictions of contaminant transport
resulted from the identification of field-scale processes that affect
the mobility of natural organic matter and colloids.<P>

<H2>Microbial Interactions</H2>

The Microbial Interactions Group uses powerful new techniques of
molecular biology to complement traditional microbiological methods in
attempting to understand the processes by which microorganisms
transform hazardous chemical contaminants in soils, surface water, and
groundwater.  The goals of these investigations are to optimize
microbial degradation of hazardous chemical contaminants and to
demonstrate application of innovative microbial techniques and
bioremediation approaches to the solution of contamination problems at
DOE sites.<P>

Studies in this group in 1992 had two general fociresearch on
degradation of organic contaminants and development of biosensors that
enable researchers to measure microbial activity in the subsurface.
Laboratory studies have been conducted to determine what level of
formate addition is necessary to produce high levels of soluble methane
monooxgenase in the methanotroph OB3b for rapid trichloroethylene
degradation.  A bioluminescent reporter strain of <I>Pseudomonas
putida</I> (RB1401) was created as an indicator of bioavailability of
toluene and xylene and as a reporter of <I>xyl</I> activity.<P>

<H2>Reservation Data Systems</H2>

The role of the Reservation Data Systems Group is to provide data
management support for environmental restoration projects conducted at
all Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc. (Energy Systems) facilities.
The group has assumed data management responsibilities for the ORNL
remedial action activities and for the Clinch River Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act Facility Investigation.  Emphasis is
placed on developing for Energy Systems a consolidated environmental
data base in which environmental restoration and compliance monitoring
data will be easily accessible to various users.<P>

On-site and off-site Environmental Restoration projects were the
research focus again this year.  The on-site efforts center on the
consolidation of environmental data that will allow the technical
enhancement of cost-effective restoration activities.  Off-site (Clinch
River) efforts continue to develop the systems and documentation
necessary to comply with Comprehensive Environmental Response,
Compensation, and Liability Act requirements.<P>

Two principal activities occupied most of this year's effortsfurther
development of site characterization and the White Oak Creek Embayment
(WOCE) remedial action.  The site characterization efforts on the
Clinch River have determined that the highest concentration of 137Cs in
the Clinch River and Watts Bar Reservoir is primarily located in the
river-channel sediments, where exposure to humans is unlikely.
Risk-screening analyses identified WOCE as a high-priority site for
further characterization.<P>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="67"><H1>67</H1></A>

<H2>Biochemical and Physiological Stress Responses in Aquatic Organisms
Provide Early Warning Indicators of Population-Level Effects</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. M. Adams
</DL>

Biochemical and physiological measures of contaminant-related stress
can serve as early warning signals of impending damage at higher levels
of biological organization. To establish correlative relationships
among toxicant exposure, physiological effects, and population-level
responses, biological indicator studies were conducted on redbreast
sunfish from a stream receiving chronic inputs of mixed
contaminants.<P>

Elevated levels of detoxification enzymes, which provided evidence of
direct toxicant exposure, were associated with low lipid levels,
histopathological damage, and reduced growth for fish at the upper
sections of the stream nearest the contaminant source.  Decreased
fecundity, exhibited by fish exposed to the highest levels of
contaminants, may have been due to the reduced capacity of the liver to
manufacture yolk proteins.  Reduction in lipid pools due to metabolic
drains appeared to have decreased the amount of physiological useful
energy needed for growth, resulting in smaller age-specific sizes of
fish at the upper three sites.  This approach to the investigation of
the relationships among contaminant exposure, physiological effects,
and population level responses such as growth and reproductive
competence could serve as a model for designing biomonitoring studies.
It could also stimulate further research to improve the ability to
evaluate the ecological significance of chronic contaminant stressors
on aquatic ecosystems.<P>

<A NAME="68"><H1>68</H1></A>

<H2>Bioluminescent Reporter Strains of Bacteria Demonstrate Growth
Conditions for Optimum Expression of Catabolic Genes</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. S. Burlage and D. Kuo (1)
</DL>

Degradation of organic contaminants by microorganisms, both in
aboveground reactors and in situ, holds great promise for remediation
of contaminated soil and groundwater. The conditions for effective
microbial degradation of organic contaminants are usually arrived at by
scientific ``best guess'' and labor-intensive experimentation.
Moreover, these conditions may change as the bacterial monoculture is
incorporated into a microbial consortium.<P>

In order to accelerate the pace at which optimized reactor or in situ
conditions can be established and to learn more about the expression of
the catabolic genes, we are developing bioreporter strains for specific
functions. A bioluminescent reporter strain of <I>Pseudomonas
putida</I>, RB1401, was created as an indicator of bioavailability of
toluene and xylene and as a reporter of <I>xyl</I> gene activity. This
strain has been tested in various media, in batch and in continuous
cultures, and under various conditions of nutrient stress and
abundance.<P>

Results indicate the appropriate nutrient levels for growth of the
strain and for expression of the catabolic genes.  Results have also
demonstrated differential use of carbon sources that are catabolized by
the <I>xyl</I> pathway, suggesting either a difference in uptake of
substrates or a new regulatory function for different substrates. These
results are a necessary starting point for the more difficult work of
evaluating catabolism in microbial consortia and provide basic
information on the mechanism of gene expression, which is essential
toward the long-term goal of controlling bioremediation processes.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="69"><H1>69</H1></A>

<H2>The Transport and Fate of Contaminants in the Clinch River and
Watts Bar Reservoir System Are Assessed Through the Use of 137Cs</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. B. Cook, B. L. Kimmel, K. A. Rose, A. L. Brenkert, C. C. Brandt, 
I. L. Larsen, C. J. Ford, D. A. Levine (1), and C. R. Olsen (2)
</DL>

The Clinch River and Watts Bar Reservoir are being investigated as part
of the Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program to assess the
potential risk to human health and the environment associated with
off-site contamination downstream from the DOE Oak Ridge Reservation.
For the site characterization, techniques at a variety of spatial
scales were used to examine the transport and fate of one of the
primary contaminants (137Cs) in the river and reservoir system.<P>

Individual sediment cores taken throughout the reservoir reveal that
137Cs levels corresponding to peak release in the 1950s are buried deep
within the sediments.  A sediment accumulation/mixing model showed that
sediment accumulation was the primary process affecting the vertical
distribution of 137Cs and that sediment mixing did not significantly
redistribute the 137Cs.  Data from 60 sediment cores and nearly 1000
surface sediment samples were used to estimate the spatial distribution
of 137Cs in the reservoir.<P>

This analysis indicates that a significant percentage of the 137Cs
originally released from the reservation is still present in the
reservoir, and the accumulation patterns are spatially heterogeneous.
In the upper portion of the reservoir, 137Cs accumulated in deeper
embayments and in the adjacent main channel.  In the lower portion of
the reservoir, more 137Cs accumulated in the main channel than in
embayments.  The 137Cs concentration in surface sediment samples are
consistently low downstream of the confluence of the Tennessee River
and the Clinch River.<P>

Surface sediment 137Cs concentrations in the Clinch River were highest
near White Oak Creek, the source of 137Cs in the reservoir.  The
highest concentrations of 137Cs in the Clinch River and Watts Bar
Reservoir are primarily located in river-channel sediments, where
exposure to humans is unlikely.  The estimated contaminant distribution
in the reservoir will be used to guide future sampling efforts.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Office of Health and Environmental Research, DOE,
Washington, D.C.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="70"><H1>70</H1></A>

<H2>Chromatin Structure in Blood Cell Nuclei of Medaka, Bluegill
Sunfish, and Mosquito Fish Is Analyzed</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. J. D'Surney (1), C. J. Theodarakis (2), P. H. Russell (3), D.
Arroyo-Colon (4), and L. R. Shugart
</DL>

The Japanese medaka (<I>Oryzias latipes</I>) is resistant to alkaline
denaturation of DNA and is induced to a greater degree following
exposure to genotoxic compounds.  Protein, tightly complexed with
extracted DNA, is associated with this effect.<P>

Japanese medaka were exposed to BaP (4 micro-g/L) for 52 d.  BaP tetrol
I-1 adducts were detected at a 42-h exposure but were absent by 10 d of
exposure.  DNA strand breaks, absent at a 42-h exposure, were observed
at a low but significant level after 10 d of chronic BaP exposure.
These observations suggest an efficient DNA repair system in medaka.<P>

High-strength dissociation of proteins from blood cell chromatin showed
that unexposed medaka have a greater variety of nonhistone proteins
relative to those of bluegill sunfish.  These proteins become depleted
after medaka have been exposed to BaP for 52 d.  Exposed medaka also
have a higher histone H5:H1 ratio, indicating a possible shift in red
cell maturational state.  Low-strength dissociation of chromatin
proteins showed that bluegill core histones were more easily extracted
than core histones for medaka, and easy extraction is indicative of a
stronger nucleosomal-DNA association.  Treatment of fish red cell
nuclei with micrococcal nuclease showed that medaka chromatin is more
resistant to endonuclease digestion than bluegill and mosquito fish
chromatin.<P>

This observation supports a model proposing that the chromatin
structure of medaka red blood cells is organized into a tighter
DNA-protein complex.  The biological/toxicological significance has yet
to be determined.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education  (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities),  Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(3) <I>Self-employed.</I>
<DT>(4) <I>Department of Science and Technology, Turabo University,
Turabo, Puerto Rico.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="71"><H1>71</H1></A>

<H2>Suspected Elevated Levels of 137Cs on Surface Sediments in the White
Oak Creek Embayment Lead to Accelerated Site Characterization and
Interim Corrective Measures</H2>

<DL>
<DT>C. J. Ford, D. E. Miller (1), M. L. Frank, B. G. Blaylock, B. L.
Kimmel, and S. L. Niemela (1)
</DL>

Discharges of radiological, organic, and inorganic contaminants from
ORNL into the White Oak Creek Embayment (WOCE) have occurred since
1943, and peak releases of particle-associated radionuclides occurred
during the 1950s.  WOCE has its confluence with the Clinch River ~5 km
downstream from Melton Hill Dam.  The principal radiological
contaminant is cesium-137 (137Cs, t_1/2 = 30 years), a waste product of
reactor research at ORNL.  WOCE sediments were sampled for Phase 1 of
the Clinch River Remedial Investigation, conducted by the Clinch River
Environmental Restoration Program.  On the basis of historic
information, maximum 137Cs contamination levels in WOCE were expected
to be buried under less contaminated surface sediments.  However,
results from a Phase 1 sampling, collected near the WOCE mouth, yielded
a peak concentration of 137Cs at the sediment surface (45,000 pCi/g).
Grab samples of surface sediments were then collected near the WOCE
mouth in order to assess the areal extent of surface sediment
contamination.<P>

Although results from this series of surface sediment grab samples were
not as high as the initial result, these surface sediment analyses
confirmed that high levels of 137Cs radioactivity existed on the
surface sediments throughout the lower portion of WOCE.  High 137Cs
levels were of concern because highly radioactive surface sediments
were susceptible to erosion and transport downstream, access to the
area was minimally controlled, and other contaminants co-occur with
137Cs in the sediments.  Each of these concerns emphasized the need to
stabilize and isolate the surface sediments.  In order to address these
concerns, a structure was built at the mouth of WOCE during 1991-92.
The structure was built by driving interlocking sheet piles through the
sediments to bedrock, shoring up the inside bottom of the sheet-pile
cells with columns of cement grout, capping the structure with
concrete, placing rock gabions on top of the structure to slow water
flows, and armoring the shoreline in the vicinity of the structure.
This structure contains the sediments in lower portions of the
embayment, minimizes the surging of water into and out of lower WOCE,
achieves year-round inundation of WOCE sediments, and minimizes the
movement of fish into and out of WOCE.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="72"><H1>72</H1></A>

<H2>PCBs Adversely Affect Fish Health in a Contaminated Reservoir</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. S. Greeley, Jr., S. M. Adams, W. D. Crumby, and S. L. Niemela
</DL>

The dangers to human and ecological health associated with the
accumulation of polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) in the environment
continue to be a topic of considerable debate.  An ongoing project by
researchers from ESD, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, the Tennessee
Valley Authority, and various state agencies from South Carolina and
Georgia is attempting to document the effects of PCBs on the health of
the biota in Hartwell Lake, South Carolina.  This man-made reservoir is
heavily contaminated along one arm by PCBs from an industrial facility
located on a tributary stream.<P>

In a preliminary study, largemouth bass (<I>Micropterus salmoides</I>)
were collected from various sites in the reservoir having widely
varying degrees of PCB contamination.  Average concentrations of PCBs
in fish muscle tissue were found to range from &gt;20 ppm at the study
site nearest the facility (site 1) to &lt;0.4 ppm in the uncontaminated
arm of the reservoir (site 2).  A preliminary health screening
procedure based primarily on whole body and organ appearance indicated
that largemouth bass from site 1 were in much poorer physical condition
than those from site 2.  The activity of detoxification enzymes was
also elevated in fish from site 1, and there was both direct and
indirect evidence of gill, renal, liver, and reproductive dysfunction.
Population characteristics differed significantly between the study
sites as well; the mean age of fish was lower, the instantaneous
mortality of older fish was higher, and the mean survival was lower at
site 1.<P>

Taken together, these population characteristics suggest a
disproportionate mortality at the most contaminated site of older fish,
which carry the highest body burden of PCBs.  The findings of this
study strongly suggest that PCBs have pronounced adverse effects on
fish health at the moderately high environmental concentrations found
in Hartwell Lake.  Continuing studies in both the reservoir and the
tributary on which the source of the contamination lies should greatly
enhance our ability to identify and document the ecological effects of
PCBs in contaminated aquatic habitats.<P>

<A NAME="73"><H1>73</H1></A>

<H2>Great Blue Herons Nesting on the Oak Ridge Reservation Are at Risk
from Exposure to Environmental Contaminants</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. S. Halbrook (1), S. J. D'Surney (1), and L. R. Shugart
</DL>

The screening level risk assessment for off-site ecological effects in
surface water downstream from the Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR) indicates
that piscivorous wildlife along the Clinch River are at risk from
exposure to environmental contaminants.  Great blue herons feeding at
White Oak Creek and Poplar Creek within ORR would be expected to
accumulate and concentrate radionuclides, mercury, and polychlorinated
biphenyls (PCBs).  These contaminants potentially pose adverse effects
on the population and could be transported off ORR.<P>

ESD staff are conducting a field study to determine the concentration
of radionuclides, PCBs, and mercury in selected great blue herons
nesting on ORR and the potential for transport of these contaminants
off-site.  Biochemical assays, including biomarkers of DNA integrity,
microsomal enzyme induction, and tissue histology, in addition to
physical condition and reproductive success, will be used to evaluate
the general health of the ORR great blue heron population.  Preliminary
results indicate that mercury and PCB concentrations are higher in
great blue herons nesting on ORR than in those nesting off the
reservation.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="74"><H1>74</H1></A>

<H2>Key Grazers Are Food Limited in Oak Ridge Reservation Streams</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. R. Hill (1)
</DL>

Food limitation and exploitative competition were implicated as
important ecological constraints on invertebrate grazers in headwater
streams in eastern Tennessee.  In a laboratory feeding experiment,
grazing snails (<I>Elimia clavaeformis</I>) and caddis fly larvae
(<I>Neophylax etnieri</I>) from upper White Oak Creek (WOC) grew seven
times faster and two times faster, respectively, on a diet of
high-biomass periphyton than they did on a diet of WOC periphyton.<P>

Both grazer species also accumulated disproportionately more neutral
lipid on the high-biomass periphyton, and snails increased their mean
condition index (ash-free dry mass per unit wet mass) by 50% while
feeding on high-biomass periphyton.  The growth and condition of
grazers that ate WOC periphyton in the laboratory were very similar to
the growth and condition of the grazers in situ, indicating that
laboratory conditions closely approximated conditions in the stream.
Analysis of gut contents demonstrated that the dietary overlap of the
two taxa was great both on high- and low-biomass periphyton diets.
Thus, periphyton quantity, not periphyton quality, limited the growth
and condition of the grazers in WOC.<P>

In a natural experiment, periphyton and <I>Neophylax</I> from six
streams containing <I>Elimia</I> were compared with the periphyton and
<I>Neophylax</I> from six streams lacking <I>Elimia</I>.  Periphyton
biomass, the mass of <I>Neophylax</I> at diapause, and the lipid
content of <I>Neophylax</I> were each substantially greater in streams
lacking <I>Elimia</I> than they were in streams containing
<I>Elimia</I>.<P>

This finding implies that the snails created or exacerbated
food-limiting conditions for <I>Neophylax</I>.  The strong responses of
the grazers to increased periphyton biomass will complicate analyses of
environmental conditions in streams on the Oak Ridge Reservation.  In
streams where snails and contaminants co-occur, for example, grazing
could importantly influence the uptake, ecological effects, and
downstream transport characteristics of persistent contaminants.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="75"><H1>75</H1></A>

<H2>Data Quality Is Ensured for the Clinch River Environmental
Restoration Program</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. A. Hook, M. J. Gentry (1), and G. J. Haynes
</DL>

Environmental restoration projects carried out under the Comprehensive
Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA) are
required to rigorously maintain data and documents to ensure their
legal defensibility.  Documentation of the data acquisition process
during remedial investigations ensures that the resulting data are of
known quality and useful for site characterization, risk assessment,
and remediation tasks.  Traceability of environmental data, beginning
with sample collection and running through laboratory analyses, data
validation, data analysis, and reporting, is essential for meeting
environmental restoration project objectives.  Comprehensive
documentation of all processes related to data acquisition ensures a
complete and verifiable record of project activities.  The ability to
cross-reference various data types allows the integration of electronic
numeric data with supporting hard-copy documentation.<P>

The Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program (CR-ERP) has
integrated the following data types: sample collection, sample
tracking, laboratory analysis results, validation results, records
management, staff training records, procedures development, data forms
control, and quality control data.  This approach can yield reports to
ensure that all procedures and staff training have been completed
before sampling begins or to confirm that only trained staff collected,
processed, and analyzed samples.<P>

Field and laboratory data forms and notebooks are controlled through
the records management system and cross-referenced with the electronic
numeric data.  Retrievability of documents and data is ensured by
detailed indexing, which includes such categories as sample locations,
dates, identifiers, and document numbers.  This data integration
activity meets CR-ERP requirements for documentation of data quality,
traceability, and legal defensibility and will be used as a model for
other environmental restoration projects.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="76"><H1>76</H1></A>

<H2>Regulatory and Procedural Requirements for the White Oak Creek
Embayment Time-Critical Removal Action Are Investigated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>B. L. Kimmel and M. Leslie (1)
</DL>

The DOE Environmental Restoration and Waste Management Program is
encouraging interim remedial actions to achieve risk reduction and to
prevent off-site contamination.  Interim response actions, conducted
under the provisions of the Comprehensive Environmental Response,
Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA) and the National Contingency
Plan, Title 40, <I>Code of Federal Regulations</I>, Part 300, provide a
mechanism for achieving these objectives.  A time-critical CERCLA
removal action conducted at the White Oak Creek Embayment (WOCE) on the
DOE Oak Ridge Reservation provides an initial example of the
application of this mechanism.<P>

Risk-screening analyses conducted during the scoping phase of the
Clinch River Remedial Investigation identified WOCE as a high-priority
site for further characterization and potential remediation.  Analysis
of a sediment core collected from the lower portion of WOCE revealed
higher than expected levels of 137Cs contamination at the sediment
surface.  This result produced immediate concern because the WOCE
surface sediments were susceptible to erosion and transport off-site
into the Clinch River.<P>

A time-critical CERCLA removal action was proposed to achieve control
of the contaminated WOCE sediments.  However, numerous uncertainties
existed concerning both regulatory and procedural requirements for
on-site, time-critical response actions at federal facilities.  To
resolve these uncertainties, immediate actions were undertaken to (1)
involve and achieve consensus among all appropriate state and federal
agencies; (2) review relevant federal and state regulations to identify
required actions, notification and permit requirements, applicable or
relevant and appropriate regulatory requirements (ARARs), and their
associated schedules; and (3) verify the applicability of the
identified ARARs, procedural requirements, and reporting requirements
to DOE on-site response actions.<P>

Investigation of the regulatory and procedural issues associated with
the WOCE time-critical removal action provides a useful model for
conducting similar interim response actions at federal facilities.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>CDM Federal Programs Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="77"><H1>77</H1></A>

<H2>Toxicity of Ambient Waters Can Be Attributed to Artifacts</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. A. Kszos and A. J. Stewart
</DL>

Short-term toxicity tests with fathead minnow (<I>Pimephales
promelas</I>) larvae and <I>Ceriodaphnia dubia</I> are used to estimate
the acute and chronic toxicity of effluents and ambient waters on the
Oak Ridge Reservation.  Three artifacts were encountered when these
tests were used in ambient applications.  One artifact was specific to
the minnow test; it manifested as a large among- replicate variance in
survival.  Survival among replicates in effluents and ambient waters
was compared.  When mean survival of minnows was between 40% and 70%,
among-replicate variation for ambient tests was significantly greater
than it was for the effluent tests.<P>

A large variation in survival makes it more difficult to use the minnow
test to distinguish among ambient sites.  The unusual minnow mortality
in tests with ambient water appears to be caused by the presence of
pathogenic bacteria or fungi; when water was exposed to ultraviolet
light before testing, mortality was nearly eliminated.  Low mean
survival in such cases would falsely indicate toxicity.<P>

Two other artifacts affected the <I>C. dubia</I> tests.  Analyses of
<I>C.  dubia</I> tests showed that reproduction in algal-rich ambient
waters often was higher than in control water.  The disparity in <I>C.
dubia</I> reproduction between controls and ambient water samples was
2.1  1.2 (mean +- SE) offspring per female when controls produced >20
offspring per female.  The disparity increased to 6.0 +- 1.8 offspring
per female when controls produced 15 to 20 offspring per female.  This
finding suggests that the EPA criterion for <I>C. dubia</I>
reproduction (15 offspring per female) may be too low to prevent the
masking of toxicant effects when the <I>C. dubia</I> test is used to
evaluate ambient waters.  Finally, food that is added to the water
during the <I>C. dubia</I> test rapidly destroys chlorine and, as a
result, could lower the water's toxicity.<P>

The existence of these artifacts does not mean that the two tests
cannot be used effectively to assess the toxicity of ambient waters;
instead, it indicates that factors other than toxicity may need to be
considered in the interpretation of the results of these tests when
they are used for ambient studies.<P>

<A NAME="78"><H1>78</H1></A>

<H2>Molecular Cloning of Brown Trout Mitochondrial DNA Is Initiated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>Kai-Lin Lee
</DL>

Southern analysis has been widely used for visualizing restriction
fragment length polymorphism (RFLP) in mitochondrial deoxyribonucleic
acid (mtDNA), owing to its simplicity and high sensitivity.  We intend
to use this method for our environmental population genetic studies.
Toward this goal we have initiated molecular cloning of mtDNA of brown
trout.<P>

Mitochondrial DNA was isolated from the liver and ovarian tissues of a
brown trout obtained from a local fishery by established alkaline/SDS
lysis method and was further purified by banding on a CsCl density
gradient.  The highly purified mtDNA was digested with the restriction
enzyme, <I>Hind III</I>, and the resulting DNA fragments were analyzed
by agarose gel electrophoresis.  Staining the gel with ethidium bromide
revealed four fragments that were 8.5, 3.5, 2.3, and 1.75 kb in size.
Restriction mapping analysis indicated that they represent the entire
mitochondrial genome of brown trout.  These four DNA fragments were
then ligated to the Puc9 vector at the unique <I>Hind III</I> site with
T4 ligase.<P>

The ligated DNA products were used to transform competent E. coli RR1
cells.  The transformed cells were plated on nutrient plates (agar 1%,
Blue-gel 40 micro-g/mL, IDPG 160 micro-g/mL, and ampicillin 50
micro-g/mL).  Independent recombinants (165) were collected, and the
plasmid DNA from each of the recombinants was prepared.  Restriction
enzyme analysis of all recombinant plasmids identified the clones
carrying plasmid with 3.5, 2.3, or 1.75 kb of trout mtDNA.  However, no
plasmid was found to carry the 8.5-kb trout DNA.  The failure to clone
an 8.5-kb fragment of trout DNA may be due to its large size.<P>

A unique <I>Sal I</I> site does exist in trout mtDNA.  <I>Hind
III</I>-digested trout mtDNA was further digested with <I>Sal I</I>,
which cuts the 8.5-kb DNA into 2.0- and 6.5-kb fragments, then cloned
into <I>Hind III/Sal I</I> sites of Puc9 vector.  Screening the
resulting library readily identified the recombinant clones carrying
the plasmid with the 2.0-kb trout mtDNA; but no recombinant clones
carrying the plasmid with 6.5-kb trout mtDNA were identified.  But the
plasmid isolated from two recombinant clones yielded two inserts, sizes
1.7 and 6.5 kb, upon digesting the plasmid with <I>Hind III</I> and
<I>Sal I</I>.  These plasmids most likely result from ligation of three
fragments (one vector plus 1.7- and 6.5-kb mtDNA fragments).
Hybridization analysis, currently being conducted, should confirm the
nature of the inserted DNA.<P>

Successful cloning of brown trout mtDNA will provide us with an
unlimited supply of DNA probes that can be used for RFLP analysis of
fish mtDNA.  I have used the cloned trout mtDNA as a probe to detect
mtDNA of mosquito fish based on Southern analysis.<P>

<A NAME="79"><H1>79</H1></A>

<H2>Transport of Natural Organic Matter and Iron Oxide Colloids Is
Demonstrated in a Sandy Aquifer</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. F. McCarthy, L. Liang (1), and B. Gu (2)
</DL>

A two-well forced-gradient field manipulation was conducted to examine
the mobility of natural organic matter (NOM) and NOM-coated iron oxide
colloids to improve understanding of NOM's role in the transport of
contaminants that sorb to NOM or inorganic colloids.  Water from a
wetlands pond, diluted with groundwater to ~30 mg of carbon per liter,
was injected into a shallow sandy coastal aquifer in Georgetown, South
Carolina, for approximately 600 h.  Groundwater with low NOM
concentrations was injected for the next 300 h, enabling us to monitor
any desorption of NOM from the aquifer.  Finally, a suspension of iron
oxide (hematite) colloids coated with NOM at 4 mg of carbon per liter
was injected.  Through the sequence of injections, groundwater was
withdrawn from a pumping well 5 m from the injection well.<P>

Before injecting NOM and colloids, we characterized the injection site
by conducting 312 slug tests in 32 wells to estimate the spatial
distribution of hydraulic conductivity.  We verified a three-
dimensional flow model by monitoring chloride transport at 132 spatial
locations.  On the basis of these results, sampling locations for NOM
were selected at two horizons at 1, 2, 3, and 4 m from the injection
well and at the pumping well.<P>

The NOM was mobile in the aquifer.  Approximately 25% of the NOM
arrived at the first well without retardation, presumably because of
slow adsorption processes.  Adsorption retarded the arrival of NOM at
all other wells.  Breakthrough peaks at progressively more distant
wells were delayed and broader.  Differences were observed in the
mobility of NOM subcomponents.  NOM with a low molecular weight was
transported more rapidly and with much less attenuation than was
macromolecular NOM.<P>

The iron oxide colloids were also mobile in the sandy aquifer.  Even
though the hematite was positively charged at the near-neutral pH of
the groundwater, NOM that had adsorbed to the colloids promoted the
colloidal stability of the hematite particles and permitted them to be
transported.  The concentration of hematite arriving at the monitoring
wells was in agreement with that predicted from laboratory column
studies.  However, in the field study, the arrival of the colloids was
significantly delayed in relation to the nonreactive chloride
tracer.<P>

The transport of both the NOM and the inorganic colloids is being
incorporated into the three-dimensional flow model.  By identifying
field-scale processes that affect the mobility of NOM and colloids,
these studies will help improve predictions about the transport of
contaminants.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="80"><H1>80</H1></A>

<H2>Periphyton Lipids Provide Framework for In Situ Toxicity Test</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. E. Napolitano (1), W. R. Hill (1), A. J. Stewart, and D. C. White (1)
</DL>

Periphyton is a ubiquitous biofilm of microscopic algae, bacteria,
fungi, and protozoans; it forms on submerged surfaces in lakes and
streams.  Measurements of periphyton community biomass can be used to
monitor environmental quality, but these measurements provide little
resolution of community status.  Alternatively, the analysis of lipids
of the autotrophic and heterotrophic components of periphyton can be
used as integrative indicators of the periphyton physiological
condition.<P>

Lipid classes, fatty acid compositions, and uptake of 14C-bicarbonate
and 3H-amino acids were measured in periphyton from reference and
impacted sites in White Oak Creek (at ORNL), Mitchell Branch (at the
Oak Ridge K-25 Site), and upper East Fork Poplar Creek (near the Oak
Ridge Y-12 Plant).  Fatty acids were analyzed by capillary gas
chromatography/mass spectrometry, and lipid class profiles were
obtained by an Iatroscan analyzer, through the use of thin-layer
chromatographyflame ionization detection (TLC-FID).  Periphyton
transferred from a reference site to contaminated stream sites rapidly
changed in species composition and fatty acids profiles. Diatoms (e.g.,
<I>Gomphonema, Cymbella,</I> and <I>Nitzschia</I>) were typically the
dominant algal group in reference sites, whereas green algae (mostly
<I>Stigeoclonium</I>) dominated where chlorine was present.<P>

Analysis of principal components differentiated reference and impacted
sites on the basis of the periphyton fatty acid composition alone.
Lipid class composition of periphyton revealed differences in
organismal physiological status.  Incorporation of 14C-bicarbonate into
lipids and measurement of major periphyton lipid classes by TLC-FID
provided short- and long-term evaluations of periphyton physiological
status.  These two independent measurements indicated that
membrane-to-storage lipid ratios were higher in periphyton from
impacted sites than they were in periphyton from reference sites.<P>

Increased membrane-to-storage lipid ratios (i.e.,
phospholipids:triglycerides) may be related to physiological stress.
Changes in the membrane-to-storage lipid ratio may occur as the
periphyton metabolism switches from producing storage materials to
mechanisms of repair for cellular structures damaged by exposure to
toxicants.  Because changes in fatty acid composition and
membrane-to-storage lipid ratios in periphyton appear predictable, they
have the potential for serving as the basis for quantitative tests for
toxicity assessment.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="81"><H1>81</H1></A>

<H2>Copper and Formate Additions Are Used in Producing High Levels of
sMMO in the Methanotroph OB3b for Rapid TCE Degradation</H2>

<DL>
<DT>A. V. Palumbo, J. M. Strong-Gunderson (1), S. Bergman (2), and S.
E. Herbes
</DL>

High levels of soluble methane monooxygenase (sMMO) activity are
necessary for efficient trichloroethylene (TCE) degradation by the
methanotroph <I>Methylosinus trichosporium</I>, strain OB3b.  In
collaboration with Envirogen (a biotech company) we have taken two
approaches to increasing the biomass and sMMO of OB3b grown in mixed
batch culture, and in association with The University of Tennessee we
are testing these approaches in a laboratory bioreactor.<P>

One approach is based on growing the bacteria in the presence of low
levels of copper.   Although copper limitation is essential for sMMO
production, it results in slower growth and possibly lower biomass
levels.  Experimental results indicate that high levels of sMMO
production can be achieved by growth in the presence of copper at 5
micro-g/L if biomass in the cultures is high.  Apparently, sMMO is
produced in large amounts after the copper becomes limiting because of
the dilution of the copper in high levels of biomass.  Production of
high levels of biomass is a problem: although CH4 is necessary for
promotion of MMO activity, it is difficult to supply enough CH4 for
rapid growth without exceeding the explosive limit.<P>

The second approach includes the addition of formate to the bacteria
grown with low levels of copper.  Addition of formate (816 mM) to the
growth media in the presence of CH4 appears to boost both biomass and
sMMO production, even though formate alone does not promote sMMO
production.  The relationship between sMMO activity and TCE degradation
is currently being verified, and the recovery of the sMMO activity
after exposure to TCE is being examined.  Our next step is to optimize
sMMO recovery, thereby maximizing the efficiency of TCE degradation.
This work is designed to result in more efficient TCE degradation using
methanotrophs.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Roane State Community College, Harriman, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="82"><H1>82</H1></A>

<H2>Effect of Chlorinated Discharges on PCB Accumulation in Clams
Is Investigated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. J. Peterson, G. R. Southworth, and K. D. Ham (1)
</DL>

To help identify and quantify sources of polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB)
contamination in area streams, uncontaminated Asiatic clams
(<I>Corbicula sp.</I>) were placed in cages and transplanted into
streams receiving industrial discharges on the Oak Ridge Reservation
from 1987 to 1990.  Results to date suggest that clams were effective
monitors of PCBs under most conditions.  However, PCB accumulation in
clams placed in chlorinated stream reaches immediately downstream of
ORNL and the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant was consistently lower than expected,
based on the amount of PCBs found in fish and sediment at those
sites.<P>

A field experiment was conducted in March 1991 to investigate the
effect of a chlorinated discharge on the PCB monitoring capability of
caged Asiatic clams. Clams were placed in two flow-through tanks
located alongside the chlorinated reach of East Fork Poplar Creek
(EFPC).  One tank received untreated water from EFPC (total residual
chlorine ranged from 0.02 to 0.07 mg/L daily), and the other tank
received EFPC water treated with thiosulfate to chemically reduce all
the chlorine in the water.  Clam valve movement, growth, and PCB
accumulation were measured after a 4-week exposure to the two
treatments.

The shells of clams exposed to untreated EFPC water were closed for
~75% of the monitoring period compared with ~25% in clams exposed to
dechlorinated EFPC water.  Clams exposed to the untreated EFPC water
apparently did not increase filtering rate to compensate for the
decreased time the shell was open, because clams grew very little (mean
length and weight increase were 0.12 mm and 0.01 g, respectively) in
comparison with clams exposed to dechlorinated EFPC water (mean length
and weight increase of 0.54 mm and 0.15 g, respectively).  Clams placed
in untreated EFPC water had a mean PCB concentration of 0.11 micro-g/g,
which was significantly lower (t-test, <I>p</I> &lt; 0.05) than that
observed in clams placed in dechlorinated EFPC water (mean = 0.63
micro-g/g).  These results suggest that clams used as bioaccumulation
monitors for PCB contamination in waters with low chlorine
concentrations close their shells to avoid chlorine exposure, thus
reducing filtering/feeding time and, consequently, PCB uptake.<P>

This study showed that transplanted Asiatic clams exposed to low levels
of chlorine may not reflect the extent of PCB contamination at a site.
This finding is a significant consideration for clam monitoring
programs because PCBs and chlorine co-occur in many receiving waters.<P>

Caged clams should be placed outside the chlorine gradient if
possible.  If measurable chlorine levels exist at a monitoring site,
factors such as water quality, clam condition, and the amount of PCB
contamination in other components of the stream ecosystem must be
evaluated in the interpretation of the results of biological monitoring
programs that use caged clams to assess contaminant bioavailability.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="83"><H1>83</H1></A>

<H2>Fish Abundance Indicates Ecological Recovery in Three Receiving
Streams near DOE Oak Ridge Facilities</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. G. Ryon, J. M. Loar, and E. M. Schilling
</DL>

Since 1985 the Biological Monitoring and Abatement Programs for the DOE
Oak Ridge facilities have included assessments of plant operations on
fish communities of receiving streams.  Within these programs, fish
abundance (density per unit area) is measured to reflect the ecological
suitability of a site for fish and to identify impacts on the community
and any recovery resulting from remedial actions.<P>

One East Fork Poplar Creek site is located below a lined basin (Lake
Reality) at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant.  Initial abundance averaged 0.1
fish per 1 square meter but increased to 4.6 fish per 1 square meter in
fall 1986 following the construction of wastewater treatment
facilities.  Another increase to 11.0 fish per 1 square meter occurred
after Lake Reality replaced the old basin.  One Bear Creek (BC) site is
below an area that was known as the S-3 ponds.  The ponds received
wastes until 1984, were neutralized in 198384, and capped in 1989.
Recovery of the fish community in upper BC was slow; abundance
increased from 0 in spring 1984 to 1.7 fish per 1 square meter in fall
1989 to 3.4 fish per 1 square meter in spring 1992.  At one White Oak
Creek site within ORNL, density never exceeded 0.3 fish per 1 square
meter.  However, in spring 1990 a new wastewater treatment facility
became operational, and density increased to 10.4 fish per 1 square
meter in fall 1991.<P>

A similar pattern of recovery was observed at all three sites, each of
which is just downstream of plant operations and had received
significant adverse impacts in the past.  Improvements in waste
disposal operations reduced the instream toxicity, resulting in
ecologically significant increases in fish community abundance.  This
first stage in the recovery of a stressed community indicates that
conditions are favorable for successful reproduction and survival of
the more pollution-tolerant fish species.<P>

<A NAME="84"><H1>84</H1></A>

<H2>Scale-Aging Technique for Fish in Stream Impacted by Contaminants
and/or Altered Temperature Regimes Is Validated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>E. M. Schilling and M. G. Ryon
</DL>

Determination of population age structure and growth rates of fish is
an important component of biological monitoring programs designed to
evaluate the effectiveness of remedial actions on the streams of the
Oak Ridge Reservation (ORR).  Fish are aged and growth is determined by
interpretation of annuli on scales and otoliths and by recapture of
tagged individuals.  Although a combination of these techniques may be
used to validate the primary method of aging fish, little is known
about the validity of fish aging by scales in streams impacted by
contaminants and/or altered temperature regimes.<P>

Validation of the primary aging technique (scale analysis) was
conducted on ORR streams through the use of sunfish species.  Growth of
sunfish aged by scale analysis during a mark-recapture study of fish
from East Fork Poplar Creek (EFPC) and an off-site reference stream,
Brushy Fork, corresponded well (77 and 100%, respectively) with actual
growth.  The differences between the two streams may be related to
differences in temperature regimes or contaminant levels.  A second
validation of the accuracy of the scale method was obtained by
concurrent aging using otoliths from the same individuals.  Otoliths
are considered more reliable than scales for the aging of fish but
require sacrifice of the specimens.<P>

Comparisons between otoliths and scales yielded 90 and 91% agreement
for White Oak Creek and Brushy Fork, respectively, for the age of fish
and the back-calculated lengths at each age.  The results from
validation of scale analysis suggest that sunfish can be aged
accurately from streams receiving contaminants and/or thermal
discharges and without an excessive investment of time or sacrifice of
fish.<P>

<A NAME="85"><H1>85</H1></A>

<H2>Modulation of Chromosomal Proteins May Correlate with DNA Damage</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. R. Shugart, R. Russell (1), and S. D'Surney (2)
</DL>

We are investigating the damaging effects of the test contaminant
benzo[<I>a</I>]pyrene (BaP) on fish deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA).
Damages studied include adducts formed by the diol-epoxide metabolite
of BaP and single strand breaks.  In exposure studies conducted on the
Japanese medaka, adducts were detected after 42 h, but none were
detected after 10 d.  Strand breaks were detected after 10 d, but not
earlier at 42 h.  In the strand break studies medaka DNA resisted
denaturation from alkalinity and heat, and that observation has led to
studies investigating this phenomenon.<P>

Medaka were exposed to BaP in water, at a concentration of 4 micro-g/L,
for 51 d.   Nuclear chromatin was isolated from blood samples of
control and exposed medaka, along with control bluegill, and
chromosomal/nuclear proteins were studied by SDS polyacrylamide gel
electrophoresis.  Major differences were observed in the histone
fractions between medaka and bluegill extracted with NaCl, and between
exposed and control medaka, that may account for resistance of medaka
DNA to chemical denaturation.  A noticeable decrease was observed in
nonhistone protein in medaka exposed to BaP for 51 d; this suggests
that the phenomenon is a consequence of chronic exposure to BaP and may
affect the expression or integrity of genetic information.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Earlham College, Richmond, Indiana.</I>
<DT>(2) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="86"><H1>86</H1></A>

<H2>Effects of Sampling Frequency on Detecting Impacts to Stream
Invertebrate Communities Are Evaluated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. G. Smith
</DL>

Since 1984 long-term biological monitoring and abatement programs have
been implemented on several streams affected by operations at the three
DOE facilities in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.  The number of benthic
invertebrate samples collected each year from these streams has greatly
exceeded the number that can be processed; therefore, a sample backlog
exists, and a lag in information results.  Several options are being
considered to resolve this problem, including a reduction in sampling
frequency.<P>

Benthic invertebrate data were obtained from samples collected monthly
from 15 sites in 5 streams, and subsets of the data and the entire data
set were analyzed to determine if reducing the sampling frequency from
either monthly to quarterly or semiannually would affect the ability to
identify impacts.  For each stream, between-site comparisons of
density, total taxonomic richness, and taxonomic richness of the orders
Ephemeroptera, Plecoptera, and Trichoptera (EPT), which contain many
pollution-intolerant taxa, were made for each sampling frequency with
an analysis of variance (ANOVA).<P>

Changing the sampling frequency generally changed mean values for
density threefold or more and mean values for taxonomic and EPT
richness twofold or less.  Also, each reduction in sampling frequency
generally doubled the standard error of the mean for all parameters and
diminished the ability to detect statistically significant differences
between reference and impacted sites where impacts were more subtle.
EPT richness was the most sensitive parameter for identifying impacts
at all sampling frequencies, and the results of the ANOVAs on this
parameter were usually influenced least by sampling frequency.<P>

These results not only emphasize a need for caution when researchers
interpret statistical results as sampling frequency decreases but also
show that fairly reliable conclusions can be made when sensitive
parameters are used.<P>

<A NAME="87"><H1>87</H1></A>

<H2>Decreased PCB Contamination in Fish Is Limited to Only One Drainage
on the Oak Ridge Reservation</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. R. Southworth and M. J. Peterson (1)
</DL>

Polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB) levels in fish are monitored at ORNL,
the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant, and the Oak Ridge K-25 Site as part of the
National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System Biological Monitoring
and Abatement Programs.  A key objective of these monitoring programs
is to assess changes in the levels of contamination in biota as new
treatment systems and various remedial actions are implemented.<P>

PCBs are found in fish from virtually all streams draining the three
major DOE facilities, including White Oak Creek, East Fork Poplar Creek
(EFPC), Mitchell Branch, and Bear Creek (BC).  Catfish from the Clinch
River arm of Watts Bar Reservoir also contain elevated concentrations
of PCBs that are attributable in part to DOE facilities.  Remedial
actions capable of influencing PCB releases to BC and EFPC from DOE
facilities or waste disposal sites have been implemented at the Oak
Ridge Y-12 Plant.  In November 1988 EFPC was diverted around a
PCB-contaminated pond (New Hope Pond) and through a newly constructed
settling basin.  Despite the elimination of New Hope Pond as a
potential PCB source, PCB concentrations in sunfish in EFPC have
remained at levels similar to those observed prior to the closure of
the pond.  Seepage of PCB-contaminated oils to tributaries of BC at
waste burial sites was eliminated by major remedial actions completed
in spring 1990.  PCB concentrations in fish in BC downstream from the
burial grounds appeared to increase in 1989 during site excavation and
construction of the closure system, but have subsequently declined to
the lowest levels observed before remediation.<P>

Because PCB concentrations in fish exhibit substantial year-to-year
variability, even in the absence of efforts to eliminate or reduce
sources, several more sampling periods are needed before any decreasing
trend can be statistically discerned.  PCB concentrations in fish from
other sites where remedial measures have not been implemented continue
to exhibit no increasing or decreasing trend.<P>

Biological monitoring programs in place at all Oak Ridge DOE facilities
can detect decreases in PCB contamination in fish that result as a
consequence of eliminating major sources, but there is likely to be a
lag between completion of remedial actions and observation of a
response.  The combination of continued remedial efforts and ongoing
monitoring will eventually result in a better understanding of these
lag times and will also provide an opportunity to assess the importance
of secondary sources of contamination, such as sediments and floodplain
soils.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="88"><H1>88</H1></A>

<H2>Subsurface Bacteria Are Screened for Their Ability to Use Volatile
Organic Contaminants as Carbon Sources</H2>

<DL>
<DT>J. M. Strong-Gunderson (1) and A. V. Palumbo
</DL>

Identification of bacterial strains that can use or degrade contaminant
compounds relies predominantly on traditional microbiological
techniques that are labor intensive and not cost-effective for
screening large numbers of bacteria.  We have developed a more
efficient system for screening isolates that can degrade semivolatile
and volatile organic compounds and be used in bioremediation programs.<P>

Suspensions of bacteria are inoculated into 96-well plates containing a
tetrazolium dye and are exposed to carbon tetrachloride, toluene, or
xylene vapors in a sealed container.  The development of a purple
color, which is quantified at intervals with the use of an automated
spectrophotometric system (Biolog, Inc.), indicates microbial oxidative
activity and thus possible degradation of the contaminant compound.<P>

To date these studies have identified 25 out of 100 isolates from Idaho
National Engineering Laboratory, Pacific Northwest Laboratory, and
Savannah River Laboratory that could potentially use at least one of
the three carbon sources.  These isolates have been further tested in
batch studies, and approximately half have shown microbial growth on a
mixture of these contaminant compounds.  In addition to the individual
isolates above, investigations of mixed consortia from soil enrichments
from Yakima Barricade in Hanford, Washington, indicate that some
consortia can use one or more of the carbon sources.<P>

This research enables isolates to be rapidly screened for their ability
to use a broad range of contaminant compounds.  This methodology
circumvents the need to use laborious and expensive manual screening
techniques by initially identifying potential microbial strains that
can be evaluated in more detail for possible application in the
bioremediation of DOE sites.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

