<TITLE>Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</TITLE>

<H1>Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Biofuels Feedstock Development Program (BFDP) is a national program
of research and development on biomass energy crops that is managed by
the Environmental Sciences Division (ESD) at Oak Ridge National
Laboratory (ORNL) for the U.S.  Department of Energy (DOE) Office of
Transportation Technologies.  The program's goal is to develop the
technologies needed to produce economically competitive and
environmentally acceptable crops and cropping systems for growing
biomass for energy.  BFDP concentrates on cellulosic crops, primarily
trees and grasses, that can be used to produce liquid transportation
fuels.<P>

Major research areas in BFDP include the genetics and physiology of
selected woody and herbaceous species, environmental research and
analysis, and economic analysis and assessment.  Research is performed
at ORNL and at 25 cooperating institutions across the United States.
Activities in BFDP are closely coordinated with DOE-sponsored programs
at the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) that are developing
technologies for converting cellulosic crops to ethanol, methanol, and
reformulated gasoline components.<P>

In FY 1992, BFDP supported research and analysis at ORNL, universities,
and U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) research stations.  Major
efforts included genetic improvement research for woody and herbaceous
species; related studies on physiology, nutrient cycling, silviculture,
and agronomics; environmental research and analysis; and economic
analysis.  The genetic-improvement, silvicultural, agronomic, and
physiologic studies were performed primarily at cooperating
institutions, supported by subcontracts and interagency agreements.
Environmental and economic analysis, nutrient cycling research, and
stress physiology were performed in ESD and ORNL.<P>

In FY 1992, BFDP had four major research components:  Model Wood Energy
Species, Model Herbaceous Energy Species, Environmental Research and
Analysis, and Economic Analysis and Integration.  Other program efforts
included Data and Information Handling and International Energy Agency
(IEA) activities.  The current status of each of these areas is
described briefly in the following sections.<P>

<H2>Model Wood Energy Species</H2>

The goal of the Model Wood Energy Species component is to develop wood
energy crops for U.S. regions where land availability and climate are
favorable for the establishment of biomass-based energy systems.  Model
species have been selected on the basis of their potential to be highly
productive on a broad range of sites under environmentally sound
management practices.<P>

BFDP has supported research on the production of short- rotation woody
crops for energy since 1978.  In FY 1992, woody crop research was
performed at 12 institutions, including universities, USDA Forest
Service research stations, private industries, and ORNL.  The research
focuses on four model species, with emphasis on the genus
<I>Populus</I>.  Subcontracted research primarily examines crop
development, including breeding and the creation of a restriction
fragment length polymorphism map of <I>Populus</I>.  Efforts to obtain
resistance to disease and insects in the model species have increased
in the last few years.  Related research conducted by ESD includes
exploration of tree physiology and nutrient use in sycamore plantations
and stress physiology of water stresstolerant <I>Populus</I> clones.<P>

<H2>Model Herbaceous Energy Species</H2>

BFDP has supported research on the production of herbaceous energy
crops since 1984.  In FY 1992, seven universities, a USDA Agricultural
Research Service facility, and ORNL conducted herbaceous crop
research.  Species under investigation include annual and perennial
grasses and legumes.  Major components of this research involve the
evaluation of species and cropping systems, chemical analysis of
lignocellulosic crop species, and assessment of handling and storage
procedures.  New research on switchgrass (<I>Panicum virgatum</I> L.)
included the creation of new, improved varieties for biofuels
production, development of physiological indicators to be used in
breeding and evaluation strategies, development of tissue culture
techniques, and documentation of cultural and genetically based
improvements for existing and newly created varieties.  The regional
focus of this new research is the southeastern and south central United
States, where potential switchgrass yield appears quite high.<P>

<H2>Environmental Research and Analysis</H2>

The environmental effort incorporates the interests and capabilities of
a complex network of research groups including USDA, the USDA Forest
Service, other national laboratories, conservation groups, utilities,
and academic institutions.  Effort in this task is directed at
systematically documenting environmental effects of energy crop
development at the field, landscape, and regional levels.  Field
studies, evaluations of land-use change, and investigations of economic
variables are under way to determine what sites will be affected and
how cropping systems may affect biodiversity, sustainability, and net
changes in various nonpoint-source emissions.  This information will be
used to develop more environmentally friendly energy crops.  The
information also helps improve analyses of the total fuel cycle of
biomass energy systems.<P>

BFDP expanded its efforts in environmental research and analysis in FY
1992.  These efforts have three major emphases.  The first involves
integrating economics and land-use analyses to determine the existing
uses of land most likely to be affected by energy crop deployment.
These assessments can produce the data needed to evaluate the degree to
which policy influences land use, environment, agriculture, energy,
forestry, and energy crops.  Evaluations of this kind are being
completed for locations in the Southeast and Midwest.<P>

The second major emphasis involves the quantification of environmental
effects from energy crops on the basis of various agricultural
analogies and existing information on such topics as chemical transport
and fate, habitat qualities and biodiversity, and carbon cycling.
These efforts are enabling researchers to set clearer priorities for
environmental research.<P>

The third emphasis is on the collection of new data from energy crops,
their analogues, and control environments.  Studies have already
examined a number of related aspects, including small mammals, carbon,
soil bacteria, and nitrogen cycling.  In FY 1992, evaluations focused
on avian populations in short-rotation woody crops.<P>

<H2>Economic Analysis and Integration</H2>

BFDP's economic analysis activities provide a common economic framework
for evaluating the results of the program's crop- specific research.
They also provide an analytical interface for addressing issues that
cut across the production and conversion aspects of biomass fuel
cycles.  The goal of these activities is to ensure that all factors
(economic as well as noneconomic) affecting the overall viability of
biomass-based fuel cycles are considered in program research and
planning.  Economic Analysis and Integration staff also provide the DOE
Office of Transportation Technology and NREL with considerable support
in the area of national biomass energy planning and analysis.  This
work is primarily conducted by ESD and Energy Division staff at ORNL
and cooperators at The University of Tennessee.<P>

<H2>Data and Information Handling</H2>

The need for information concerning the potential of dedicated energy
crops has escalated in the past few years.  To meet this need, in FY
1992, BFDP began publishing and distributing a newsletter, <I>Energy
Crops Forum</I>, three times a year.  The program also expanded a
computerized inventory containing lists of contacts at more than 2200
federal, state, and municipal government offices; research scientists
from around the world; and representatives from private industry, trade
associations, and the media.  Other efforts included the continued
maintenance and expansion of data bases on publications related to
woody species and technical information about herbaceous species.
Staff also organized an extensive document and photograph collection,
which, in combination with the data bases, enables the staff to respond
expeditiously to information requests.<P>

<H2>IEA Activities</H2>

IEA biofuels activities are designed primarily for information exchange
among participating countries.  BFDP gives technical support to DOE for
activities in the IEA task on efficient and environmentally sound
biomass production systems.  Such activities include new cultural
treatments and yield optimization; growth processes; genetic
improvement; pest and disease control; exchange, evaluation, and joint
testing of genetic stock; and other (nonwoody) biomass crops.
Activities directly involve ESD staff and BFDP subcontractors in
cooperative evaluations and joint efforts to summarize and synthesize
research results.<P>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="89"><H1>89</H1></A>

<H2>Cost and Environmental Impacts of the Use of Energy Crops to Supply
a Power Plant Intertwine</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Graham
</DL>

The cost and environmental impacts of using energy crops to supply
fuel to power facilities intertwine.  Energy crops will be planted
when farmers can earn a greater return on their land by growing
energy crops rather than conventional crops.  What crops are
displaced by energy crops and where that displacement occurs will
determine the environmental impact of growing energy crops.<P>

A linear programming model was developed to determine the cost and
environmental impacts of furnishing sufficient woody biomass (grown
in energy plantations) to supply an East Tennessee power plant. 
This model optimized the regional net return on agricultural land
and was sensitive to crop production costs and prices, soil
quality, and distance from the power plant.  Conventional
agricultural crop rotations were included in addition to four
different energy crops.<P>

The modeling analysis showed that given current production
technology, a delivered biomass price of more than $3/MBtu would be
required to create a sufficient supply of woody biomass to fuel the
East Tennessee power plant.  The production of energy crops would
reduce corn production within the 42-county region by 27.8%,
decrease erosion by 7.2%, and reduce the use of nitrogen fertilizer
by 7.5%.  Reduction in erosion and fertilizer use was greater in
counties closer to the power plant.  High-quality land was the
first land to be converted to energy crops.  Government
agricultural commodity programs raised the cost of supplying wood
to the power facility by 20%.<P>

This analysis provided a methodology for integrating economic and
environmental constraints with biomass energy development at the
scale of a single facility. The methodology is appropriate for
projecting the environmental impacts and cost of growing and
supplying biomass to any energy facility (power or ethanol
production) regardless of its location.<P>

<A NAME="90"><H1>90</H1></A>

<H2>Model Herbaceous Species for Increasing Biofuels Production
Capacity Combines High Potential for Ecological and Economic Gain</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. B. McLaughlin
</DL>

The Biofuels Feedstock Development Program (BFDP) has selected
switchgrass (<I>Panicum virgatum</I>), a perennial crop, as a model
species for further development as a biofuels feedstock.  As a widely
adapted endemic species of the tall grass prairies, switchgrass has
demonstrated a capacity for high yields on relatively poor quality
sites for which water and nutrient availability would prevent
successful production of conventional crops.  Maximum yields on test
plots in Auburn, Alabama, have been 15 dry tons per acre, well above
the production level considered prerequisite for a successful biofuels
industry.  A large and deep root system is the key to high production
and soil improvement on poor quality sites.<P>

Research at Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University
shows that soil organic carbon increased by 30% during a 4-year
cycle, indicating that switchgrass has a significant capacity to
improve soil quality by sequestering carbon below ground.  Improved
erosion control, reduced fertilizer and pesticide requirements, and
a capacity for providing wildlife cover are additional positive
environmental attributes.  An important perceptual quality of
switchgrass is its strong potential appeal to landowners, for whom
cultivation of a perennial crop that can be grown, harvested, and
stored like hay with conventional equipment represents an easy
interface with current agricultural practices.  The high and stable
yields, relatively low production costs, and positive environmental
attributes of switchgrass also make this species of tremendous
potential benefit to small-farm economies in the depressed
agricultural industry.<P>

In summary, the dual benefits of production of cleaner-burning
fuels from renewable resources as well as ancillary economic
benefits to the agricultural industry make switchgrass a very
desirable addition to the nation's energy strategy.  With a new
series of research projects initiated in the spring of 1992 to
improve switchgrass production through breeding, production
research, physiology, and genetic selection techniques, BFDP is
providing DOE an opportunity to significantly enhance the technical
feasibility of the biofuels industry.<P>

<A NAME="91"><H1>91</H1></A>

<H2>Report Estimates Environmental Emissions Levels That Are Likely to
Result from Supplying Biofuel Facilities with Energy Crops</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. D. Perlack (1), J. W. Ranney, and L. L. Wright
</DL>

DOE is interested in evaluating the environmental risks and
benefits of renewable energy technologies.  An analysis was
conducted to identify all sources and approximate levels of
environmental emissions that may result in the year 2010 from
supplying biofuel conversion facilities with energy crops.  The
establishment, maintenance, harvesting, handling, and transport of
energy crops involve operations that create soil erosion, chemical
runoff or leachate, particulate releases, air emissions from fuel
use and chemical applications, and biogenic emissions.<P>

The analysis considered five different energy facility locations
(each in a different major crop-growing region) and three classes
of energy cropswoody crops, perennial herbaceous grasses, and an
annual herbaceous crop (sorghum).  Soil losses resulting from wind
and water erosion were the largest ``emissions'' for all crop types
at all locations.  Fossil-fuel CO2 was the next most significant
emission (carbon uptake by the growing plants was not subtracted in
this phase of analysis).  Fossil fuel CO2 emissions from production
operations were lowest (per unit of biomass energy produced) for
the crops and locations with the highest yield per acre.  Handling
and transportation emissions were lowest at the location where the
average transportation distance was shortest.  Biogenic emissions
of volatile organic compounds were identified as a possibly
significant emission of woody crops, and the importance of these
emissions for perennial grasses remains unknown.<P>

This report provides the first comprehensive summary of the types
and possible levels of emissions that may be associated with the
feedstock production component of biofuel production based on
detailed assumptions about land, crops, and production techniques. 
When the emissions from biomass production are combined with the
emissions from biomass conversion processes, DOE will be able to
compare total energy cycle emissions from biofuels with those from
other energy sources.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Energy Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>


<A NAME="92"><H1>92</H1></A>

<H2>The Male <I>P. deltoides</I> Parent Confers Osmotic Adjustment to Water
Stress in a Hybrid Poplar Pedigree</H2>

<DL>
<DT>T. J. Tschaplinski, G. A. Tuskan, and C. A. Gunderson
</DL>

Water stress tolerance may be a determinant of productivity in hybrid
poplars, particularly if grown on sites that experience periodic
drought.  Plant species tolerate water stress by maintaining low
osmotic potential and/or by accumulating solutes to increase their
osmotic potential.  The objectives of this study were to characterize
the degree of genetic variability for water stress tolerance in a
poplar pedigree, consisting of parental clones for black cottonwood
(<I>P. trichocarpa</I>) and eastern cottonwood (<I>P. deltoides</I>)
and four hybrid progeny.<P>

Trees were grown outdoors in pots; well-watered trees were kept moist,
and stressed trees were subjected to repeated cyclical stresses of 1-
to 2-d duration over the 14-week study.  The greater osmotic adjustment
(0.25 MPa) in leaves of the male parent and 242  hybrid may have
facilitated the almost complete recovery of stomatal conductance after
severe stress, in contrast to female clones, which had only partially
recovered or their stomata remained closed.  The water stress tolerance
traits (i.e., maintenance of dry matter production of the main stem and
osmotic adjustment under water stress) of three of the four hybrids
were likely conferred by the male parent, whereas the stress-induced
allocation of carbon to branches and roots was likely conferred by the
female parent.<P>

Screening poplar clones for drought tolerance should take into account
the tendency of some genotypes to allocate carbon to lateral meristems
under stress.  Clones that lose apical dominance should be eliminated
from breeding programs.  Biochemical analyses to characterize the
metabolites that constitute water stress tolerance in leaves and fine
roots are nearing completion.  The studies will provide useful
biochemical indicators of water stress tolerance that can be used as
selection criteria in breeding programs.<P>

<A NAME="93"><H1>93</H1></A>

<H2>Nitrogen Fertilization Regime Affects Soil Water Quality in
Short-Rotation Sycamore Plantations</H2>

<DL>
<DT>H. Van Miegroet, R. J. Norby, and S. E. Lindahl (1)
</DL>

Interest is increasing in the use of herbaceous and woody crops as an
alternative source of energy.  Growing trees for biomass in
short-rotation plantations (5 to 10 years) may eventually reduce the
fertility of sites because of the large amounts of nutrients removed
per unit of biomass harvested.  Consequently, fertilization is often
necessary to sustain productivity.  Indiscriminate fertilization in
excess of tree nutrient requirements not only wastes money and
resources but also is possibly harmful to water quality.  Our study
focused on the effect of nitrogen (N) fertilization because this
nutrient commonly limits tree productivity and because elevated levels
of nitrate may threaten groundwater quality.<P>

To assess the effect that the dosage and frequency of nitrogen
fertilization have on soil water chemistry, a field study was initiated
in 1989 in a 1-year-old plantation of American sycamore (<I>Platanus
occidentalis</I>).  During a 3-year period, a total of 450 kg of
nitrogen per hectare was added in the form of urea at the following
rates: (1) a single dose of 450 kg/ha in 1989; (2) three equal annual
applications of 150 kg/ha; (3) three annual applications that increased
with time:  50 kg/ha in 1989, 150 kg/ha in 1990, and 250 kg/ha in 1991;
and (4) three applications of 50 kg/ha every year during the 1989,
1990, and 1991 growing seasons.  Three replicate plots were used per
treatment, and plots receiving no fertilizer served as controls.  Soil
solutions were collected continuously with tension lysimeters placed at
a 40-cm soil depth and were analyzed every month for ammonium and
nitrate levels.<P>

Solution nitrate was consistently low in the unfertilized plots.
Fertilization increased nitrate levels in the soil water, but the
extent and duration of these changes depended on the fertilization
regime, tree uptake rate, soil temperature, and soil moisture.  After a
single heavy dose, nitratenitrogen solution levels remained above 10
mg/L (EPA's drinking water standard) for 1 year and gradually declined
to control-plot values thereafter.  Equal annual doses caused summer
peaks above 10 mg/L that extended into the winter of 1991.  Periodic
additions of small amounts of fertilizer or annual fertilization that
increased as tree growth increased had the lowest impact on solution
nitrate levels.  The latter treatment also had the greatest stimulatory
effect on biomass production.  These findings are important to the
management of short-rotation woody crops because they indicate that
potentially adverse impacts of fertilization on water resources can be
minimized by adjusting fertilizer frequency and dose in relationship to
tree growth patterns.<P>


<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education (formerly Oak
Ridge Associated Universities), Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

