<TITLE>Environmental Information Analysis Program</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Information Analysis Program</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Sciences Division (ESD) at Oak Ridge National
Laboratory (ORNL) has a long history in the management and analysis of
environmental data.  The division has designed and implemented the
Eastern Deciduous Biome Data Center; the data base system GEOECOLOGY;
the U.S.  Environmental Protection Agency's (EPA's) National Lake,
Stream, and Soil Survey data centers; and the U.S. Department of
Energy's (DOE) Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center (CDIAC),
among others.  The common thread of these activities is the necessity
of intermeshing data management and scientific analysis to the
enhancement of both.<P>

ESD has formalized these types of activities under a single program,
the Environmental Information Analysis Program, which consists of
CDIAC, the Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS), and the
Atmospheric Radiation Measurement Program (ARM) Archive.  The program
is closely integrated with the ORNL Center for Global Environmental
Studies and is coordinating the ARM activities with the new ORNL High
Performance Computing initiative.  The new Intel Paragon supercomputer
and the massive ARM data archive will be linked to allow complete,
close interaction of both systems.<P>

Future activities include continued interlaboratory and interagency
collaboration with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration,
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, EPA, and other
organizations on research data analysis projects.<P>

<H2>Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</H2>

Operational since 1982, CDIAC is a fully integrated information
analysis center, whose primary mission is to support DOE's Global
Change Research Program by acquiring or compiling, quality-assuring,
documenting, archiving, and distributing data and other information
related to CO2, other greenhouse gases, and climate.  CDIAC helps
fulfill the extensive data and information needs of the international
research, policy-making, education, and corporate communities,
assisting them in the evaluation of complex environmental issues
associated with elevated concentrations of atmospheric CO2 and other
greenhouse gases.<P>

CDIAC staff identify users' needs by attending workshops, reviewing
literature, and maintaining personal contacts.  The center obtains and
evaluates data, articles, and reports for potential worldwide
distribution; produces digital numeric data and computer model
packages; distributes DOE reports; and produces the newsletter <I>CDIAC
Communications</I> (which has a worldwide distribution of more than
7500) and the <I>DOE Research Summary</I> series.<P>

CDIAC has published such varied information products as <I>Trends '91:
A Compendium of Data on Climate Change</I> (the second issue in the
<I>Trends</I> series) and <I>Glossary:  Carbon Dioxide and
Climate</I>.  In addition, CDIAC operates the World Data Center-A for
Atmospheric Trace Gases, a component of the World Data Center System,
which is coordinated by the International Council of Scientific
Unions.<P>

<H2>Atmospheric Radiation Measurements Program Data Archive</H2>

ESD is the long-term data archive for ARM, a DOE field project that
will obtain precise measurements of phenomena related to solar
radiation in the atmosphere.  The measurements are needed to improve
present general circulation models that researchers use to predict
future climates.  The ARM Archive will store, manage, process, and
disseminate data collected during the ARM project.<P>

During FY 1992 significant progress in the design of the archive system
was made, and a prototype program that stores and retrieves data files
on the ORNL Mass Storage Tape Tower is now operational.  High-speed
data connections to the first ARM site (instituted in Oklahoma in the
summer of 1992) and to other DOE laboratories participating in the
project are being installed.  These activities are coordinated with
ORNL's High Performance Computing initiative.<P>

The ARM Archive will eventually store multiple terabytes of information
each year and will be a worldwide resource of meteorological
information that is useful not only for refining general circulation
models but also for understanding atmospheric phenomena, such as hail
formation and downbursts.<P>

<H2>Oak Ridge Environmental Information System</H2>

The Environmental Restoration programs at the DOE Oak Ridge Field
Office and at Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc., initiated the
development of OREIS to meet requirements regarding management of and
access to environmental data as specified in the Federal Facilities
Agreement (FFA) and the Tennessee Oversight Agreement.  The FFAa
tripartite agreement among DOE, EPA, and the state of Tennesseerequires
DOE to maintain one consolidated data base for environmental data
generated at DOE facilities on the Oak Ridge Reservation.<P>

The consolidated data base is to include data generated pursuant to the
agreement, as well as data generated under federal and state
environmental permits (i.e., environmental restoration, compliance, and
surveillance monitoring data).  The Tennessee Oversight Agreement
requires that such monitoring information be shared on a near real-time
basis with the state by way of electronic processing.<P>

In addition to providing a single source for environmental data, the
OREIS project institutes standards and procedures to promote
consistency in the data and ensure their legal defensibility.  The
project also establishes a robust information system to manage,
display, and analyze the data.<P>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="94"><H1>94</H1></A>

<H2>Measurements from Flask Sampling Sites in the Former U.S.S.R. Show
Rising Levels of Atmospheric CO2 Concentrations</H2>

<DL>
<DT>T. A. Boden
</DL>

Monitoring efforts around the world have provided irrefutable evidence
that concentrations of CO2 in the troposphere have risen during the
past few decades.  Such measurements are crucial for global carbon
cycle and greenhouse-gas-induced climate change studies.  The Carbon
Dioxide Information Analysis Center (CDIAC) has recently obtained and
documented reliable records of daily atmospheric CO2 concentrations
from four sampling sites (Teriberka Station, Ocean Station Charlie,
Bering Island, and Kotelny Island) in the former U.S.S.R.

The period of record varies by station; the earliest measurements date
back to 1983, and recent estimates are from early 1991.  These CO2
concentrations were derived from air samples collected in 1.5-L
stainless steel electropolished flasks and later analyzed at the Main
Geophysical Observatory in St. Petersburg, Russia, using a
nondispersive infrared gas analyzer.  Given the recent disbanding of
the Soviet Union, the acquisition of these records was particularly
timely.  These four records support the rising trend in atmospheric CO2
concentrations measured at other monitoring sites around the world and
exhibit pronounced seasonal oscillations (i.e., amplitudes of 1030
ppmv) due to photosynthetic depletion during northern growing
seasons.   The mean annual growth rate for the four sites, calculated
from individual flask measurements, was ~1 ppmv/year.  These stations
provide much-needed measurements from sparsely monitored regions in the
northern latitudes and will be extremely useful for interhemispheric
transport modeling exercises.<P>

<A NAME="95"><H1>95</H1></A>

<H2>CDIAC Collaborates with Russian Data Center to Produce Bilingual
Bibliographies on Mechanisms of Climate Change</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. M. Cushman, C. B. Ravina (1), and M. D. Burtis
</DL>

In Russia a considerable research and monitoring effort has been
devoted to climate change.  Unfortunately, much of the Russian
literature has not been translated into English, so it is largely
unavailable to Western researchers.  ESD's Carbon Dioxide Information
Analysis Center (CDIAC) has been participating, as part of DOE's Global
Change Research Program, in a bilateral scientific exchange with
Russian data centers.<P>

Researchers at the All-Russian Research Institute of
Hydrometeorological Information--World Data Center (ARRIHMI-WDC) in
Obninsk, Russia, compiled a bibliography of important Russian-language
literature, not previously available in English, on four topics of
interest to researchers studying the relationship between atmospheric
chemistry and climate--the earth's surface energy budget, aerosols,
clouds, and general circulation models.  A translator, brought to CDIAC
from ARRIHMI-WDC, produced English-language versions of the
bibliography for the topical area of surface energy budget.  Both the
Russian- and English-language versions of the bibliography were
incorporated into a document issued as a joint ORNL/CDIAC and
ARRIHMI-WDC report.  The translation was assisted by newly available
Globalink (TM) personal-computer-based translation software.  (CDIAC is
a test site for more widespread use of this software by U.S.
participants in the bilateral exchange.)<P>

This report will be available for distribution by CDIAC to its user
community around the world.  It is hoped that work will continue toward
the production of additional Russian-English bibliographies on the
three remaining topical areas: aerosols, clouds, and general
circulation models.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>All-Russian Research Institute of Hydrometeorological
Information--World Data Center, Obninsk, Russia.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="96"><H1>96</H1></A>

<H2>The Consolidation of Environmental Data from the DOE Oak Ridge
Reservation Benefits Environmental Cleanup</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. A. McCord and L. D. Voorhees
</DL>

The Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS) is being
designed to store and analyze environmental measurements from the Oak
Ridge Reservation.  The consolidation of these data is a regulatory
requirement of a Federal Facilities Agreement among DOE, EPA, and the
state of Tennessee.  Because OREIS will receive input from many
programs within the Oak Ridge facilities, standards and procedures for
data management and documentation are being developed to ensure
consistency within the data base.  OREIS also includes the
implementation of an information system that can support the analysis
of environmental data through the integration of statistics, graphics,
and geographic information systems.  OREIS has already accomplished an
initial version of each of these features.<P>

The development of OREIS is important to DOE and Energy Systems because
it will enable these organizations to present a consistent and unified
view of environmental data to the regulators across all of its
facilities.  In the absence of a consolidated data base, a consistent
representation of environmental data has become more difficult because
the environmental programs have expanded in recent years.  OREIS will
also enable several projects to share data.  The ability to share this
information will contribute to both the cost effectiveness and
technical enhancement of environmental studies, which need a
significant quantity and diversity of expensive measurements.<P>

<A NAME="97"><H1>97</H1></A>

<H2>Data and Metadata Are Essential for Environmental Planning
and Restoration</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. J. Olson and R. A. McCord
</DL>

The Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS) provides
consolidated, consistent, and well-documented environmental data and
data products to support environmental restoration activities, which
are a major focus at the DOE facilities managed by the Oak Ridge Field
Office.  OREIS collects data from a variety of sites and projects,
furnishes the data in electronic formats to regulators, and provides
long-term archival data storage and retrieval as specified in the
Federal Facilities Agreement among DOE, EPA, and the state of
Tennessee.<P>

A comprehensive data management plan was written to define the data
processing, data base structure, systems operations, and interactions
among users.  The plan specifically addresses the responsibilities of
individual projects to collect, document, validate, and transmit data
to OREIS.  Under the plan, OREIS staff maintain and provide access to
data through a user interface with data analysis capabilities.  The
OREIS data base is unique in incorporating metadata (documenting
information about data) in the data base and user applications.
Metadata aid users in understanding how to analyze and interpret the
data on the basis of the original context of the data.  Metadata define
the sampling objectives, design, collection, and attributes of
analysis, as well as the results of quality control and quality
assurance.  Metadata also indicate how data from several projects can
be combined for analysis.<P>

As more data and associated metadata are entered into OREIS, the data
base will provide an increasingly valuable tool to monitor the success
of environmental restoration.  In addition, the tools and procedures
for managing, analyzing, and displaying data can be applied within
other environmental projects.<P>

<A NAME="98"><H1>98</H1></A>

<H2>Researchers Compile and Analyze a Long-Term Data Base of Monthly
Temperature, Precipitation, and Station-Level and Sea Level
Pressure</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. Vose (1) and T. Boden
</DL>

Greenhouse gas concentrations in the atmosphere have increased markedly
during the past several decades.  Most simulations of climate change
suggest that significant modifications of global temperature,
precipitation, and pressure patterns may accompany these rising
concentrations.  If the global historical climate record were studied,
the presence or absence of an enhanced greenhouse effect might possibly
be verified.  Unfortunately, detection of climate change from present
global data bases has seldom produced more than tenuous results.   This
is a direct consequence of the quantity and quality of the data that
are available to study the problem.<P>

In June 1990 the Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center began a
long-term initiative to construct an improved historical climatological
data base of monthly temperature, precipitation, and station-level and
sea level pressure.  The primary goal for the first year of the project
was to consolidate several national, regional, and global-scale data
sets in order to maximize the quantity of information available for the
study of global climate change.  As a secondary goal, an attempt was
made to assess the overall quality of the data.<P>

Results indicate that an impressive improvement in spatial and temporal
resolution was achieved.  The number of long-term temperature stations,
for example, increased to 6200, which represents a 50% gain over those
of other global data bases (e.g., World Weather Records; World Monthly
Surface Station Climatology).  Critical data gaps were filled in the
eastern former Soviet Union and northern China.  An even more important
gain was made in the number of sources for precipitation data, which
doubled from 4000 to 8000 stations.  Major improvements were visible
over Africa and South America.  For station-level and sea level
pressure, the improvements were more modest (~20%), though a
substantial amount of previously unavailable data for the Southern
Hemisphere was located.<P>

A preliminary analysis of data quality suggests that in a manner
consistent with other global data sets, 25-30% of the time series
contain some sort of quality problem.  In addition to occasional
keypunch and data transcription errors, substantial ``rounding''
inconsistencies were identified.  Roughly 10% of the time series also
contain a nontrivial homogeneity problem, which could have been caused
by any number of factors, such as instrumentation changes, station
relocations, or urbanization effects.  In the future we will attempt to
correct these gross data errors and develop techniques to resolve
inhomogeneity problems.<P>

The implications of these findings on global change research are
considerable.  Previous estimates of global temperature, for example,
may include substantial biases introduced by the lack of data in
critical areas like the Sahara Desert or Amazon rain forest.  Moreover,
in light of the questionable quality of the data, estimates of climate
change on the order of tenths of degrees (for temperature) or tenths of
millimeters (for precipitation) may be well within the range of
statistical insignificance.  For these reasons, we believe that future
research should focus on the acquisition of even more climatological
data from areas that despite recent improvements still contain only
marginal quantities of data.  Greater emphasis should also be placed
upon the elimination of gross data inadequacies.  Only then can we
produce reliable estimates of global change.<P>

<DL>
<DT>_________________________
<DT>(1) <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

