<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT13-B35-186</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA001-000008-B016-66</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.esd.ornl.gov:80/annual-reports/FY94/earth.html 128.219.24.7 19970101060530 text/html 105026
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 01 Jan 1997 06:05:35 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.2
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<TITLE>Earth and Atmospheric Sciences</TITLE>

<H1>Earth and Atmospheric Sciences</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

Staff in the Earth and Atmospheric Sciences Section of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) conduct basic and applied research on interdisciplinary problems related to the broad field of earth sciences.  Most of the section's research focuses on managing energy-related waste materials.  Field, laboratory, and computer-based investigations support these efforts.  Research is directed toward understanding the factors that control the movement of materials through the solid earth, the hydrosphere, and the atmosphere.  Major sponsors include the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) (the <a href="http://www.er.doe.gov/production/oher/oher_intro.html/">Office of Health and Environmental Research</a>; the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/research-org/1995.html#td/">Office of Technology Development</a>; <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/orcmt/bmp/envirres.html/">Environmental Restoration</a>; <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/orcmt/bmp/envirres.html/cgi-bin/waisgate-2-0/">Defense Waste and Environmental Restoration</a>; the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>; the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html>Paducah, Kentucky, and Portsmouth, Ohio, gaseous diffusion plants</a>; and other national laboratories), the <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">Tennessee Valley Authority</a>, the <a href="http://www.usgs.gov/">U.S. Geological Survey</a>, the <a href="http://www.epri.com/">Electric Power Research Institute</a>, and the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA).<P>

<H2>Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes</H2>

The Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes Group performs basic research designed to quantify and to understand the processes that influence the transport, transformation, deposition, and fate of materials released into the environment.  This research encompasses the fields of atmospheric, marine, freshwater, and soil sciences.  Primary areas include the atmospheric chemistry and deposition of trace metals, air-surface exchange and its role in biogeochemical cycling, and processes controlling the transformation and mobility of radionuclides and other contaminants in aquatic and soil systems.<P>

During FY 1994, staff of the Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes Group completed several significant objectives.  Researchers characterized the speciation of mercury in contaminated soils near Oak Ridge, finding that the projected costs of remediation could be significantly reduced.  Staff developed a pioneering method for micrometeorological measurements of mercury vapor fluxes over soils, surface waters, and vegetation at background sites; open-literature publication of these results has established the significance of natural remission of mercury to the atmosphere.  Researchers also demonstrated that annual rings in red cedar trees faithfully record historical atmospheric mercury releases from known point sources, thus allowing for assessment of historical air exposures.  For a joint U.S. and Russian study, scientists in the Atmospheric and Geochemical Processes Group analyzed arctic sediments for radionuclides resulting from waste disposal activities of the former Soviet Union to assess the impact of the radionuclides on arctic food chains.<P>

<H2>Earth Systems Modeling</H2>

The Earth Systems Modeling Group develops, applies, and evaluates mathematical models used in addressing local-, regional-, and global-scale environmental issues.  Current research emphasizes the development of new models and the examination and integration of disparately scaled existing models to comprehensively address global carbon dynamics.  This work is designed to increase understanding of the global carbon cycle and to forecast the effects that changes in atmospheric carbon emissions will have on global climate and ecological resources during the next century.  Group interests also include quantification of the implications of model uncertainties for model performance.  Sensitivity and uncertainty analyses are conducted to evaluate performance and to place model forecasts in the context of global risks.  Earth systems modelers use an innovative synthesis of techniques to address problems in mesoscale, regional, and global modeling.<P>

The Earth Systems Modeling Group seeks to improve our understanding of the Earth's major dynamic systems, climate, and the global biogeochemical cycles through the development and analysis of comprehensive earth systems models.  The group's research objectives address major issues within the <a href="http://www.gcdis.usgcrp.gov/">U.S. Global Change Research Program</a>.  These objectives include clarifying the relationship between fossil fuel emissions and changes in atmospheric greenhouse gas concentrations, analyzing means of decreasing greenhouse gas emissions or compensating for emissions by increased elimination from the atmosphere, and assessing ways in which climatic change resulting from greenhouse gas increases can affect the carbon cycle and its control of atmospheric CO<SUB>2</SUB> concentration.  The group also addresses interactions between the global biogeochemical cycles and the potential impacts of global environmental change on terrestrial ecosystems.  <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> and <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a> fund group projects.  Group members participate in activities of the <a href="http://www.igbp.kva.se/">International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme</a> and assessments of the Intergovernmental Panel on <a href="http://www.envirolink.org/orgs/climatechg/">Climate Change</a>.<P>

During FY 1994, the Earth Systems Modeling Group completed a number of major tasks. Researchers analyzed how plant growth response to increases in atmospheric CO<SUB>2</SUB> influence estimates of atmospheric releases of carbon that result from changes in land use. Group members developed (1) a spatially explicit global terrestrial model of carbon cycling and (2) an oceanic radiocarbon inventory for model testing.  In addition, a book entitled <I>Greenhouse Puzzles</I> was completed.<P>

<H2>Energy Systems Groundwater Program</H2>

The Groundwater Program Office provides coordination for all groundwater activities at the three <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities managed by Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc., in Oak Ridge, Tennessee, and the DOE gaseous diffusion plants in Paducah, Kentucky, and Portsmouth, Ohio.  The Energy Systems Groundwater Program's primary objective is to develop a consistent approach to ensure that applicable state or federal environmental laws and relevant DOE orders are satisfied and that the environment and the health of the public are protected.  The Groundwater Program Office, working through groundwater coordinators at each of the three Oak Ridge sites as well as at the Paducah and Portsmouth sites, provides management support to achieve these goals.<P>

The Oak Ridge Hydrology Support Program offers technical expertise in the broad areas of hydrology and geology to the three <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">Energy Systems</a> plants in Oak Ridge and the Paducah and Portsmouth gaseous diffusion plants.  Two principal groups make up this program.  The first consists of hydrologists who advise the groundwater programs on groundwater and surface water issues related to environmental restoration and regulatory compliance.  The second group is directed toward understanding fundamental hydrogeologic principles related to groundwater flow and remediation in fractured rock systems such as those that dominate the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR).<P>

<H2>Environmental Engineering</H2>

The Environmental Engineering Group performs basic and applied research related to environmental restoration and waste management.  This research involves process modeling, bench-scale and pilot-scale field experimentation, and full-scale field experimentation and demonstration activities.  Current emphasis includes research on processes controlling the measurement, behavior, and treatment of contaminants in waste deposits and in contaminated soil and groundwater systems.  Staff conduct research on environmental monitoring technologies and assessment strategies, spatial modeling of contaminant distributions, process modeling of physicochemical treatment systems, and in situ treatment by physicochemical and biological processes.  Research is also directed toward the development of critical enabling technologies, including in situ recirculation systems, fracture emplacement methods, and mixed-region subsurface reactors.  Increasing efforts are placed on field-scale research and on the demonstration of emerging environmental restoration technologies at sites across the United States and abroad.<P>

<H2>Geology and Geophysics</H2>

The Geology and Geophysics Group addresses field-based geologic and geophysical aspects of waste management.  Principal emphasis is on the elucidation of geologic principles that are important in quantifying groundwater flow and the characterization and evaluation of waste disposal sites.  New and continuing research projects are directed toward two broad-based goals:  (1) the development of noninvasive geophysical techniques for investigating waste management areas and (2) the evaluation of geologic properties of fractured sedimentary rocks that control groundwater flow and contaminant transport.  In addition, staff continue to expand the geologic and geophysical database by providing support for ongoing site-specific investigations.<P>

Airborne geophysical studies consist of a helicopter-based aerial survey of <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">ORR</a> and development of model airplane capabilities for reconnaissance studies.  FY 1994 aerial survey activities concentrated on ground truthing, developing applications for characterizing karst features, and acquiring high-resolution data in a smaller portion of ORR.  Model airplane photographic capabilities were demonstrated during this fiscal year, and staff are continuing to develop the capability acquiring magnetic data.  Surface geophysical investigations are targeted toward evaluating optimal methods and instrumentation.  FY 1994 activities included a test to determine the most appropriate source for seismic investigations in shale units on ORR, an evaluation of different geophysical techniques to characterize karst features, and the application of low-frequency ground-penetrating radar in different hydrologic settings.  Subsurface borehole investigations included the successful application of borehole geophysics to determine the integrity of well casing and continued characterization work to identify groundwater flow paths and hydrogeologic properties.<P>

The purpose of geologic investigations conducted by staff is to understand rock matrix properties that control contaminant storage, to define hydrologically important fracture parameters, and to define spatial changes in fracture networks.  These studies are both laboratory and field based and take advantage of a growing ORR database of core information and borehole geophysical and hydrologic data.  Matrix porosities are being evaluated and calibrated through a combination of laboratory, geophysical, and petrographic measurements.  In FY 1994, we started concentrating on the factors that control development and measurement of shale porosity.<P>

Fracture studies identify lateral and vertical changes in the fracture characteristics, evaluate the origin of the networks in terms of rock properties and geologic history, and examine hydrologic fracture behavior.  In FY 1994, staff conducted a surface fracture mapping study that showed a change in fracture characteristics from other parts of ORR.  Fracture connectivity and spacing in sedimentary rocks was examined in a study that integrates core, borehole geophysical, and hydrologic data from multiport instrumented wells.  Laboratory studies are directed toward determining fracture toughness measurements of competent rock units on ORR.  This work will be used to determine physical properties, primarily elastic moduli, of the aquifers on ORR.<P>

In FY 1994, we completed an effort to translate our regional geologic mapping data into digital form.  The data are now available for investigations as a geographic information system layer.  In addition, portions of our subsurface borehole data have been incorporated into three-dimensional visualization software.<P>

Results of our studies are being integrated into conceptual and numerical groundwater flow models.  In addition, the results provide the framework for developing conceptual and analytical models for transport of dense nonaqueous-phase liquids in sedimentary rocks.<P>

<H2>Groundwater Hydrology</H2>

The Groundwater Hydrology Group addresses technical problems related to the preservation and restoration of groundwater quality.  Staff activities include application of complex numerical models to simulate multiphase flow of fluids in porous and fractured systems, design and operation of groundwater-monitoring systems, characterization of large-area hydrologic properties, use of artificial tracers and natural groundwater chemistry to study transport processes, and studies of interactions with surface water and groundwater.  The primary strength of the group lies at the interface between modeling and field activities.  Field work is directed at understanding flow mechanisms in complex subsurface systems.  Research topics include the effects of fracture flow systems on the dynamic storage and release of pollutants, development of innovative drilling and sampling methods, and direct measurement of rates of recharge by means of groundwater dating with &#179;H and &#179;He.  Modelers within the groups are adapting the extensive ensemble of <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> groundwater models to massively parallel computers and exploring new modeling techniques on these computers.<P>

<H2>Soil Science</H2>

The Soil Science Group conducts applied and basic research in the characterization and management of soils and sediments.  Much of the research centers on understanding how contaminants interact with soils and wastes in a subsurface environment.  Because the soils and sediments contain many of the pollutants released when <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> waste management practices of the past were used, the Soil Science Group expends considerable effort in developing methods to characterize, decontaminate, and control the fate of these contaminants.  Soil scientists interact with environmental engineers, hydrologists, and aquatic and terrestrial ecologists in defining the magnitude of the problems with respect to the transport and fate of a large spectrum of inorganic and organic pollutants in the environment.<P>

Recent projects include the development of a large database characterizing the concentrations of anthropogenic constituents potentially in the natural soils surrounding the Oak Ridge DOE facility.  The purpose of the study is to determine background levels of these constituents in soils so that contaminating events can be properly identified.  Other projects involve the development of methods to remove uranium from contaminated soils through the use of selective leaching processes and the containment of contaminants in soils through the use of in situ vitrification processes.  Also during FY 1994, a report on background soil characterization for ORR was completed; soil characterization of uranium in soils at the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/K25/">Oak Ridge K-25 Site</a>, the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html/">Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant</a>, and the Fernald, Ohio, facilities was completed; and bench- and pilot-scale studies revealed that 80 to 95&#176; of the uranium in Fernald soils can be removed with carbonate-based extractions.<P>

<H2>Subsurface and Surficial Geochemistry</H2>

Research in geochemistry emphasizes the understanding of processes that control the transport, fate, and transformation of elements in subsurface and surficial geological environments.  This understanding is used in developing and applying interpretive models of element behavior to solve energy-related problems.  Complementary field, laboratory, and computational research efforts are undertaken to evaluate strategies for the effective use of energy resources, the future disposal of wastes, and environmental restoration at existing contaminated sites.<P>

This research incorporates principles from the disciplines of aqueous geochemistry, biogeochemistry, computer science, geology, hydrology, isotope geochemistry, limnology, radiogeochemistry, and soil chemistry.  Research efforts focus on biotic and abiotic transformations of contaminants in natural waters, soils, and sediments; characterization of contaminants in active and inactive waste disposal areas; colloid mobility; contaminant transport in unsaturated, heterogeneous soils; hydrogeochemical aspects of the local groundwater system; in situ vitrification for the stabilization of contaminated soils; sorption of trace metals onto natural materials; and trace element transport and cycling in river, lake, and coastal zone environments.<P>

In FY 1994, measurements of the concentrations of transuranium isotopes were made in Waste Area Grouping (WAG) 4 groundwaters.  Identification of the specific isotopes will aid in tracing contaminants to their sources in WAG 4 and in assessing risks and planning for any required remedial actions.  Also during the year, staff organized and conducted a workshop to evaluate the use of <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/ISV/">in situ vitrification</a> (ISV) technology to produce large silicate melts that would serve as analogs for natural magmas for the study of magmatic properties and processes.  In preparation for the treatability study of ISV at the formerly used Waste Seepage Pit 1, &quot;remote&quot; surveys were conducted in FY 1994 to obtain both the dimensions of the original pit and the current distribution of radioactivity.  In addition, researchers initiated investigations into the kinetics and mechanisms governing the oxidation state of organically chelated <SUP>60</SUP>Co, which has migrated from waste burial sites on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a>.<P>

<H2>Surface Water Hydrology</H2>

The Surface Water Hydrology Group addresses problems related to flow and water quality in water systems affected by industrial activities and waste disposal, and the group compares research results with measurements in unaffected watersheds.  Staff characterize and quantify contaminant transport in contaminated drainages on ORR by investigating mechanisms of flow, sediment production, sediment transport, and contaminant movement.  Group members study interactions between groundwater and surface water by analyzing the occurrence and chemical signature of seeps and springs and their roles in surface water production.  Investigations include developing water budgets and modeling watershed hydrology, with an emphasis on streamflow production in fractured-rock terrains.<P>

During FY 1994, the work performed by the Surface Water Hydrology Group mainly focused on environmental restoration issues at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  The group conducted surveys of springs and seeps on the ORNL site to determine the distribution and quality of contaminant inputs to the White Oak Creek drainage system that have leaked from closed low-level radioactive disposal facilities.  Sampling of tributaries during storms showed patterns of partial dilution of contaminants; the patterns reflected the mechanisms of runoff generation.  In turn, the results are leading to better understanding of the roles of precipitation, geology, and terrain in mobilizing and transporting contaminants.  A flood-monitoring system was fully activated and three large storms were intensively sampled for sediments and sediment-bound contaminants.  This sampling information is being used along with innovative sediment transport modeling to estimate off-site movement of contaminants and resulting risk to human health brought about by extreme storms.  The group continued to use diverse surface water and groundwater data to improve an innovative risk-based methodology to guide and evaluate monitoring to WAG 6.  The monitoring system emphasizes the measurement of major contaminant releases, identifies contaminants that exceed risk-based concentration levels, and proves to be cost-effective.<P>

Our new project includes (1) the application of a topographically based hydrologic model to simulate streamflow from the basic hydrogeological land units on ORR and (2) the merging of the results to yield improved hydrological predictions on a large scale.  This approach may provide a new method for addressing large-scale heterogeneities found in the Valley Ridge geological province.<P>

