<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="1"><H1>1</H1></A>

<H2>Comprehensive Survey Identifies Major Dry-Weather Sources of Contaminants to Upper East Fork Poplar Creek</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. A. Bogle and R. R. Turner
</DL>

Staff members of <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ORNL's Environmental Sciences Division</a> participated in a comprehensive sampling effort (four rounds of dry-weather surface-water sampling) to characterize the movement of mercury and other contaminants into <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev27-3/text/envside1.htm/">Upper East Fork Poplar Creek</a> (UEFPC), which runs through the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a> site.  This effort focused on sampling 29 active building outfalls located below the North-South Pipe, 9 outfalls or trunklines in the Exclusion Area, and 3 in-stream locations.<P>

The sampling locations spanned the length of the creek from the site furthest upstream at the west end of the Y-12 Plant to the oil skimmer at the east end.  In-stream sites were used as checkpoints for monitoring flow and contaminant mass balance.  Water samples were collected and analyzed for mercury, polychlorinated biphenyls, pesticides, metals, volatile and semivolatile organics, radiological contaminants, and anions.<P>

To identify major sources of contaminants in the creek and to assess outfall contributions to the total creek load during dry weather conditions, researchers took flow measurements and water samples concurrently.  An analysis of flow data indicated that 83&#176; of the average flow at the site furthest downstream (i.e., the oil skimmer) could be attributed to inputs from the sampled outfalls.  Inputs for two of the contaminants of most concern, mercury and uranium, were associated with outfalls serving buildings in the areas where mercury formerly was used.  Mercury entered the creek at the rate of 15 g/d; &#126;60&#176; of this came from three outfalls draining two buildings in the Exclusion Area.  An additional 25&#176; came from two outfalls serving Building 9201-2.  Mass balance calculations for mercury indicate a loss of mercury in the lower reaches of UEFPC; this loss could result from biotic uptake or volatilization.  Almost 70&#176; of the uranium load came from two outfalls associated with a single building in the Exclusion Area.  Depending on the sampling round, from 70 to 95&#176; of the uranium load at the oil skimmer could be attributed to outfall inputs.<P>

Results of this survey are helping researchers decide which locations and contaminants should be sampled in the future (in wet weather as well as dry weather); in addition, they are providing data necessary for evaluating and prioritizing possible remedial actions, especially for mercury contamination. <P>

<A NAME="2"><H1>2</H1></A>

<H2>Beryllium-7 Inventories Are Used to Estimate Particle Settling Rates in the Bering Sea</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. W. Cooper, I. L. Larsen, and J. M. Grebmeier
</DL>

Beryllium-7 (half-life 53.3 d) is produced in the upper atmosphere by cosmic ray spallation of nitrogen and oxygen.  The radionuclide is particle-reactive and, following wash-out from the atmosphere into the ocean, is associated with organic production and particulate deposition to the sea floor.  Because of its short half-life, <SUP>7</SUP>Be decays before reaching the deeper portions of the sea.<P>

An extensive survey of Bering Sea continental shelf sediments in June 1993 showed that <SUP>7</SUP>Be became undetectable when bottom depths exceeded 100 m.  Based on the average life of an individual <SUP>7</SUP>Be atom (half-life/ln 2 = 77 d), a net particle settling velocity of 1 to 2 m/d can be estimated.  This particle settling velocity is consistent with independent estimates of particle flux in the Bering Sea based on sediment trap deployment and sediment oxygen utilization.<P>

Determination of particle settling velocities is important for estimating carbon fluxes to continental shelf and slope sediments as well as for identifying regions of particle focusing and accumulation.<P>

<A NAME="3"><H1>3</H1></A>

<H2>Airborne Geophysical Survey of the Oak Ridge Reservation Is Conducted</H2>

<DL>
<DT>W. E. Doll and J. E. Nyquist
</DL>

During December 1992 and January 1993, sensors suspended from a helicopter were used to collect magnetic, electromagnetic, and radiometric data over the entire <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a>.  The data acquisition technique was an adaptation of methods used in the mineral-prospecting industry.  The goals were to detect unknown waste sites, to better characterize known waste sites, and to image geologic structures that might influence contaminant transport, such as faults, fractures, or lithologic contacts.<P>

Data were acquired at lower elevations (100 ft) and smaller flight-line spacings (150 ft) than in mining applications, and contractor processing steps were modified to enhance smaller man-made targets that are typically filtered out of exploration data.  Because the sensitivity of airborne sensors to environmental targets is unknown, data were collected at four test sites.  Test data from Waste Area Grouping 6 were acquired to determine sensor response to a variety of targets whose constitution and position were well characterized.  Airborne data were collected over Solid Waste Storage Area (SWSA) 4 for comparison with earlier surface measurements.  The sensitivity to individual 55-gal drums and to tree cover and topography was evaluated by placing groups of one to eight decoy drums at SWSA 7 and at the Preferred Advanced Neutron Source site.<P>

Some of the processed data received to date are very encouraging.  The magnetic data were particularly abundant at waste sites and near buried metals, although sensors recorded a smaller response to lithologic contacts between limestones and shales.  Most electromagnetic data were from lithologic contacts and changes in soil moisture.  To enhance targets of interest for site characterization work, further processing will be applied and techniques for improving resolution of airborne geophysical methods will be tested.<P>

<A NAME="4"><H1>4</H1></A>

<H2>Natural and Anthropogenic Radionuclides Are Used to Interpret Black Sea Sedimentation Dynamics</H2>

<DL>
<DT>I. L. Larsen, J. M. Grebmeier, L. W. Cooper, L. R. Shugart, and K. Shimkus (1)
</DL>

Analysis of a sediment core collected in March 1993 from a water depth of 300 m in the Russian portion of the Black Sea revealed <SUP>134</SUP>Cs and <SUP>137</SUP>Cs contamination in the upper 4-cm layer that was unequivocally related to the Chernobyl nuclear reactor accident that occurred in April and May 1986.  The presence of <SUP>134</SUP>Cs provided a tool to distinguish 1960-era atmospheric fallout cesium from Chernobyl-derived cesium and to determine the degree of sediment mixing due to bioturbation.  At this location &#126;25&#176; of the underlying 1960-era sediment is mixed into the upper layer of more recently (1980 era) deposited sediment.  The presence of atmospherically derived <SUP>7</SUP>Be (53.3 d half-life) in the top 1-cm layer of sediment at a 300-m water depth suggests a water column particle settling rate of &#126;4 m/d (&#126;0.005 cm/s).<P>

On the basis of this particle settling rate and sea water viscosity, an average particle settling diameter of 0.05 mm was estimated; measuring confirmed this diameter.  Analysis of <SUP>210</SUP>Pb inventories revealed a sediment accumulation rate of &#126;0.36 cm/year.  These estimates of sedimentation dynamics are being used to delineate the age of phytoplanktonic molecular markers preserved in the anoxic sediments of the Black Sea, including the potential measurement of DNA damage resulting from ultraviolet radiation over historical time frames.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Southern Branch of P. P. Shirshov Institute of Oceanology, Russian Academy of Science, Gelendzhik, Russia.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="5"><H1>5</H1></A>

<H2>The Micrometeorological Gradient Similarity Method Is Tested to Measure Air-Surface Exchange Rates for Vapor-Phase Mercury</H2>

<DL>
<DT>S. E. Lindberg, K.-H. Kim, P. J. Hanson, J. Owens, and T. P. Meyers (1)
</DL>

To determine the processes that control biogeochemical cycling of important trace gases, scientists are developing methods of estimating air-surface exchange rates.  Because micrometeorological methods yield area-averaged fluxes over undisturbed surfaces, they hold important advantages over chamber approaches.<P>

The Mercury Air-Surface Exchange (MASE) Project is testing the gradient similarity method for application to mercury vapor in the first-ever application of a tower-based micrometeorological method for mercury fluxes.  The method involves quantification of time-averaged concentration gradients (&#126;1 h) of mercury and related trace gases (i.e., CO<SUB>2</SUB> and H<SUB>2</SUB>O) over the surface of interest.  Values for these gradients are combined with direct measurements of the fluxes of CO<SUB>2</SUB>, H<SUB>2</SUB>O, and heat, measured by fast-response sensors and eddy correlation to compute fluxes of mercury.  To measure air concentrations with the high precision and accuracy necessary for quantifying small concentration gradients over forest canopies and soils, scientists designed a sampler employing 12 replicate mass flow controllers.<P>

During spring 1993, tests were made to determine whether meaningful concentration gradients over mercury-contaminated soils in Oak Ridge could be measured.  The mercury-concentration gradients and fluxes behaved as predicted from first principles:  (1) all gradients indicated a strong soil emission of mercury; (2) the concentrations decreased logarithmically with height, similar to the wind-speed profile; (3) the gradients decreased with increasing atmospheric turbulence;  and (4) mercury fluxes increased with soil temperature.  These data provide confidence in the approach, and measurements have begun over background soil and canopy sites in <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/science-to-life/wbw.html/">Walker Branch Watershed</a>, near Oak Ridge.<P>

Preliminary results indicate that mercury gradients are very small (a small percentage of the mean concentrations) and are bidirectional, which suggests that the cycling of mercury in forests may be strongly influenced by re-emission.  Gradients over soils are influenced by soil temperature, turbulence, and soil moisture, whereas those over the canopy are influenced by stomatal conductance, leaf wetness, and turbulence.  The methods developed will prove useful for other important tropospheric species for which real-time sensors are not available, such as reduced sulfur gases.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Atmospheric Turbulence and Diffusion Division, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</dl>

<A NAME="6"><H1>6</H1></A>

<H2>A Discrepancy Exists Between Observation and Carbon Cycle Model Prediction for the Global Bomb-Radiocarbon Inventory</H2><DL>
<DT>T.-H. Peng
</DL>

Measurements of stratospheric radiocarbon resulting from aboveground nuclear testing in the 1950s and the early 1960s do not match predictions of a carbon cycle model used to quantify dilution of the radiocarbon.  The ratio of atmospheric <SUP>14</SUP>C to C has steadily declined since reaching nearly twice its prenuclear value just after implementation of the ban on aboveground testing of nuclear devices.  This decline is largely the result of dilution of bomb-test radiocarbon, a dilution that occurs through isotope exchange between atmospheric CO<SUB>2</SUB> and terrestrial and oceanic carbon.<P>

A carbon cycle model has been used to quantify the dilution of bomb-test atmospheric <SUP>14</SUP>C as it mixes with oceanic and terrestrial carbon.  The model atmosphere is constrained to follow the observed history of the time that excess bomb radiocarbon takes to decline in the troposphere.<P>

Research shows that, after the implementation of the ban on atmospheric testing in 1963, the model's inventory of bomb-test <SUP>14</SUP>C atoms kept growing but at an ever-decreasing rate, finally leveling off at a near-constant value in the late 1980s.  The obvious explanation is that the growth in inventory is driven by the downward mixing of excess <SUP>14</SUP>C atoms stored in the stratosphere.  The model suggests that as of 1964, about one-third of the bomb-test <SUP>14</SUP>C remained in the stratosphere and that it was released to the troposphere with an e-folding time of about 7 years.<P>

By contrast, measurements carried out in the stratosphere suggest that, as of 1964, the excess was closer to one-quarter of the total bomb-test <SUP>14</SUP>C and that the e-folding time for its decline was 3 &#177; 1 years.  This anomaly cannot be attributed solely to an inadequacy in the model's representation of the terrestrial biosphere.  Rather, it must reflect an inadequacy either in the oceanic part of the model or in the measured stratospheric inventories.<P>

<A NAME="7"><H1>7</H1></A>

<H2>Global Maps of Carbon Dioxide Emissions from Fossil Fuel Consumption and Cement Manufacture Are Created</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. J. Andres (1) and G. Marland
</DL>

Tables of global and national estimates of CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions from fossil fuel consumption and cement manufacture are not in a convenient form for some climate-modeling studies.  To address this need, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers created 1&#176; latitude by 1&#176; longitude (1 &#215; 1) maps of CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions for 1950, 1960, 1970, 1980, and 1990.<P>

National estimates of carbon emissions were then combined with 1 &#215; 1 maps of political units and human population density to create the new 1 &#215; 1 carbon emissions maps.  The human population density map has an effective resolution of the country or state level.  The resolution translates to the CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions 1 &#215; 1 maps because population density was used to distribute within-country CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions.  Latitudinal distributions of emissions were also calculated.<P>

The maps show continual growth over most of the world; increased growth rates are particularly notable in major urban areas.  As Asian countries increase their energy consumption to support their growing economies and populations, a slow equatorial shift in the bulk of the emissions is also seen.  The maps will become part of the Global Emissions Inventory Activity, which is part of the <a href="http://www.igbp.kva.se/">International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme</a>.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="8"><H1>8</H1></A>

<H2>Recent Carbon Dioxide Emissions Estimates from Fossil Fuel Consumption Show Slowing Global Growth Rate</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G.Garland, R. J. Andres (1), and T. A. Boden
</DL>

Each year, a time-series estimate of annual CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions from fossil fuel consumption, cement production, and gas flaring is generated by <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff.  The emission estimates are critical to global carbon cycle studies and quantify the major anthropogenic source of CO<SUB>2</SUB> to the atmosphere.  The estimates are derived using methods developed by Marland and Rotty<SUP>2</SUP> energy statistics compiled by the United Nations (UN), hydraulic cement production estimates published by the U.S. Bureau of Mines, and gas-flaring data furnished by the UN and <a href="http://www.eia.doe.gov/">DOE's Energy Information Administration</a>.<P>

Global, regional, and national CO<SUB>2</SUB> emission estimates have recently been calculated for 1950-1991.  These estimates show that global emissions rose to an all-time high of &#126;6.19 gigatons of carbon in 1991.  Only 1.5&#37; higher than the 1990 level, this estimate maintains a recent declining trend in the global growth rate of CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions.  If the Kuwait oil fires had not emitted 130 million metric tons of carbon to the atmosphere as CO<SUB>2</SUB>, the global estimate for 1991 would have been less.<P>

Regionally, North America and Eastern Europe continue to be the largest emitters despite recent declines, while the developing regions are contributing greater percentages to the global share.  In 1950 North America, Western Europe, and Eastern Europe accounted for 89.2&#37; of global CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions.  In 1991 these regions contributed 59.5&#37; of global CO<SUB>2</SUB> emissions.<P>

Nationally, the United States continues to be the world's largest emitter (1.35 gigatons of carbon in 1991) despite two successive years of small decline.  Emissions from the former U.S.S.R. declined 12&#37; from 1988 to 1991.  The three largest emitters, the United States, the former U.S.S.R., and the People's Republic of China, contributed 48.8&#37; of the world's 1991 CO<SUB>2</SUB>  emissions.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
<DT>(2)  <I>G. Marland and R. M. Rotty, &quot;Carbon Dioxide Emissions from Fossil Fuels:  A Procedure for Estimation and Results for 1950-82,&quot;  Tellus 36(B), 232-61.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="9"><H1>9</H1></A>

<H2>Active Streamflow and Rainfall Gaging Sites for ORR Are Summarized</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. D. Huff, D. M. Borders (1), and B. K. Thompson (1)
</DL>

The Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation DOE Oversight Division is concerned about the adequacy of current streamflow and rainfall-gaging activities on and near the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR).  The issue is whether the current long-term data acquisition strategy is sufficient to support site remediation assessment on the ORR, including implementation of rainfall-runoff-solute transport models.<P>

Because no central point of contact was responsible for maintaining a current status summary for all streamflow and rainfall gaging on ORR, <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> directed the Energy Systems Groundwater Program Office to contact representatives from each of the site <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a> offices, the site compliance organizations, the </a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/BMAP/">Biological Monitoring and Abatement Program</a>, DOE contractors, and research and development projects to assemble a comprehensive synthesis of activities.  This is viewed as the first step toward evaluating the nature of the network of gages on ORR and determining whether significant gaps exist in the information being collected.<P>

On the basis of a comprehensive survey, 36 active streamflow-gaging sites and 16 active rainfall-gaging sites were known to be operational on ORR in early October 1993.  Using the current Geographical Information Systems map base, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers prepared two maps of ORR.  The first provides the locations of the stream-gaging sites together with main roads, streams, and topographic contours; the second, locations of active rainfall-gaging sites.  Each map has a set of identifier numbers that relate each location to a table that summarizes the type of installation, data attributes collected, period of record, and organization responsible for maintaining the data.<P>

An indication of expected longevity of the data collection project is also given.  Clearly, the number and density of streamflow and rainfall gages is determined by specific study objectives that differ depending on the scale of the focus.  One scale would support rainfall and runoff modeling; it is basin-wide for major drainages on ORR (e.g., White Oak Creek drainage).  Another scale involves individual remediation sites within the major drainages; it is also evident in the assortment of gaging sites.  The major basin scale is likely most appropriate for long-term record keeping, and the data obtained should provide a framework for site-specific characterization studies, for which the duration of the record will seldom exceed a few years.<P>

The maps and summary tables should prove useful to those engaged in rainfall-runoff investigations and related work.  In particular, identification of the current network in a published format can eliminate duplication of effort, enhance data sharing, and provide a basis for the design of a cost-effective gaging network for the entire ORR.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="10"><H1>10</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Chemical Oxidation of Contaminated Groundwater and Soil Is Investigated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>D. D. Gates, R. L. Siegrist, S. R. Cline, and D. S. Marshall
</DL>

Laboratory experiments to evaluate in situ chemical oxidation as a method of remediating contaminated groundwater and soil are under way.  Aqueous chemical oxidants such as hydrogen peroxide (H<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>2</SUB>) and potassium permanganate (KMnO<sub>4</sub>) are being studied to determine their ability to oxidatively degrade volatile organic compounds (VOCs), such as trichloroethylene, perchloroethylene, and trichloromethane, and semivolatile organic compounds (SVOCs), such as naphthalene, pryene, and phenanthrene.  Preliminary findings indicate that VOC reductions of up to 98&#37; can be achieved using chemical oxidation.<P>

In the laboratory, chemical oxidants are added to artificially contaminated soil slurries in custom-fabricated, zero-headspace extraction vessels.  Ensuring that the reaction vessels are gas-tight minimizes contaminant losses due to volatilization and facilitates independent evaluation of losses due to oxidation.<P>

Chemical oxidation treatment efficiency is evaluated at several oxidant concentrations under a variety of operating conditions.  Clean soil was obtained from four <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites for use in this study so that the operating conditions needed for treating sites with different soil properties (i.e., clayey vs sandy and low vs high organic carbon content) could be determined in the laboratory before this technology is implemented in the field.<P>

To evaluate the effect of in situ chemical oxidation on metal contaminants that are often found in areas contaminated with VOCs and SVOCs, companion studies are being conducted at <a href="http://www.utk.edu/">The University of Tennessee, Knoxville</a>.<P>

Once the optimum treatment conditions for in situ chemical oxidation are determined, methods for delivering and distributing chemical oxidants to contaminated zones will be evaluated.  In situ chemical oxidation with H<SUB>2</SUB>O<SUB>2</SUB> and KMnO<SUB>4</SUB> is applicable to many of the contaminated sites found in the DOE complex; it appears to be an effective and inexpensive treatment technique that can be used to help restore many of those sites.<P>

<A NAME="11"><H1>11</H1></A>

<H2>Elemental Iron Filings Are Effective in Reductive Dechlorination of TCE</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. Liang, J. D. Goodlaxson (1), and N. E. Korte 
</DL>

Elemental iron was found to be effective as an abiotic, reductive reagent in the dechlorination of trichloroethylene (TCE).  To determine the reaction half-time and the by-products of the reaction, batch studies were conducted.  Three sources of iron filings were used in the research:  Fisher Scientific; Columbus Chemical Industries, Inc.; and Master Builders, Inc.<P>

With a solid:solution ratio of 1:5, the half-time of the reduction was between 7 and 12 h, depending on the sources of iron.  When the Fisher Scientific filings were precleaned with HCl, the reaction half-time was reduced from 7 to 5 h.  The major by-product of the reaction is ethylene; dichloroethylene and vinyl chloride are minor by-products.<P>

To confirm the TCE mass loss through the iron column by physical transfers and chemical degradations, a flow-through experiment is ongoing.  Rate information will be obtained in these experiments as well.  The results of the research will have direct applications for environmental restoration activities at many <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Oak Ridge Research Institute, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="12"><H1>12</H1></A>

<H2>Natural Organic Sorbents Offer Effective In Situ Treatment of Contaminated Groundwater</H2>

<DL>
<DT>L. Liang, J. D. Goodlaxson (1), and R. L. Siegrist
</DL>

<a href="http"//www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers have found that peat offers a simple, inexpensive, and passive means of in situ treatment for contaminated seep water in the solid waste storage areas (SWSAs) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  Initial bench-scale studies using simulated seep water showed that peat is an excellent sorbent of heavy metals:  in the presence of 5 g of peat per liter, Cd, Ni, Cr, and Pb were reduced by 90 to 98&#37; at initial concentrations ranging from 0.5 to 5 mg/L.<P>

Among the four types of peat tested, the most decomposed peat had the highest sorption capacities for heavy metals.  At the concentration 10g/L, two types of peat also reduced <SUP>90</SUP>Sr in SWSA groundwater seeps from 18,000 Bq/L to 4200 Bq/L (a decrease of 77&#37;) and 960 Bq/L (a decrease of 95&#37;).  Kinetic experiments indicated that sorption was completed within an hour.<P>

Because peat is inexpensive, treating contaminated seep water with peat would be cost-effective.  Because the thermal combustion of spent peat will produce only a small volume of residue, storing spentpeat will pose few problems.  Using peat as a reactive barrier for in situ treatment of contaminated groundwater appears to be an effective, inexpensive technique that can be used at many contaminated <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Oak Ridge Research Institute, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="13"><H1>13</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Treatment of Mixed Contaminants in Groundwater Is Accomplished by Innovative Horizontal Flow Field and Module Methods</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Siegrist, N. E. Korte, and M. T. Muck (1)
</DL>

Groundwater contamination by mixtures of organic chemicals and radionuclides is a significant problem within the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> complex.  The coupling of simple but robust in situ treatment processes with groundwater recirculation has great potential for treating those sites.  Consequently, DOE's <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/research-org/1995.html#td/">Office of Technology Development</a> has funded <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> to develop and demonstrate such a system.<P>

Initial studies determined that current recirculation applications use vertical wells and are limited to aquifers that are relatively thick (i.e., &gt;5 m) and have horizontal-to-vertical conductivity ratios between 1 and 10.  Horizontal wells are less constrained by these restrictions, and their use extends the applicability of recirculation treatment to a broader range of hydrogeologic conditions.<P>

Advanced microtunneling methods and materials technology originally identified in Germany with the sponsorship of DOE's International Technology Exchange Program were selected for inclusion in a field test at the DOE Portsmouth, Ohio, facility in October 1994.  A continuous guidance and drilling method was used to install two 500-ft-long horizontal wells &#126;100 ft apart and at &#126;30 ft depth.  The central 200-ft section of each well was laid on a bedrock surface and was composed of a unique porous polyethylene casing.  The test is expected to show that the combination of the advanced materials and installation methods will yield a horizontal recirculation system with improved performance, flexibility, and cost-effectiveness in comparison with the features of installation with conventional materials.<P>

Development of the in situ treatment module was also initiated during 1994.  Potentially useful in situ treatment processes were identified and screened by a panel of ORNL scientists.  Specific processes considered were (1) simultaneous reduction and adsorption of radionuclides and the reduction of hydrocarbons by zero-valence metals (e.g., iron), (2) destruction of hydrocarbons through the use of chemical oxidants, and (3) countercurrent air stripping (cocurrent air stripping is currently used).  Bench-scale testing and a field pilot test will be completed in 1994; a full-scale technical demonstration will be established at a contaminated site during 1995.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Health Sciences Research Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="14"><H1>14</H1></A>

<H2>In Situ Remediation of DNAPLs in Low-Permeability Media Is Studied in a Joint DOE and American Petroleum Institute Project</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Siegrist, O. R. West, N. E. Korte, D. R. Smuin, A. D. Laase, D. D. Gates, L. Liang, A. V. Palumbo, J. Strong-Gunderson, B. Gu, and D. T. Davenport (1)
</DL>

Dense nonaqueous-phase liquid (DNAPL) compounds like trichloroethylene (TCE) and perchloroethylene are prevalent at <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites, and their presence in low-permeability media poses challenges for effective in situ remediation technologies.  <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> researchers have been coordinating a joint program sponsored by DOE and the American Petroleum Institute wherein in situ remediation technologies are being tested and evaluated for both source control and mass removal of DNAPLs in fine-grained media.<P>

The project includes technology evaluation and screening and laboratory- and field-scale testing at clean and contaminated test sites in the United States and Canada; participants include staff from numerous universities and industries (e.g., Oregon Graduate Institute, Colorado State University, University of Cincinnati, New Jersey Institute of Technology, University of California-Berkeley, University of Waterloo, BP Oil, Freeze Engineering, CH2M Hill).  Progress to date has included technical workshops, preparation of 16 state-of-the-art papers, and field-scale experimentation at three sites.<P>

At the site near Sarnia, Canada, a controlled release of 50-L nonaqueous-phase liquids (gasoline and TCE) occurred during fall 1992 within a 10- by 10-m test cell and was followed by studies of soil vacuum extraction (SVE) performance.  Because researchers observed relatively low mass removal efficiency (30-40&#37;) during two summers of SVE, they focused their current studies on the enhancement of SVE by hydraulic fracturing and dewatering and on the potential for bioremediation.<P>

At the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html/">DOE Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant</a> near Piketon, Ohio, a field test was initiated during October 1994 to explore the fracture-enhanced injection and dispersal of reactive fluids such as oxidants/reductants and surfactants/nutrients in uncontaminated clay soils.  At the site on Aber Road near Cincinnati, a field study of hydraulic fracturing and heated fluid injection was initiated in late fall 1994.  The results from the various facets of the project will provide the basis for designing and conducting a full-scale field test at a contaminated site during 1995.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Environmental Restoration Program, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="15"><H1>15</H1></A>

<H2>Options Are Evaluated for Treating and Disposing of Low-Level Mixed Waste Sludges at the Rocky Flats Site</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. L. Siegrist, K. S. Dickerson (1), M. I. Morris (2), and M. J. Wilson-Nichols (1)
</DL>

Solar evaporation ponds have been used at the DOE Rocky Flats site since the early 1950s for the disposal of process wastewater containing radioactive and hazardous materials.  In 1993, sludges were removed from the existing ponds by vacuum truck and placed into about fifty-five 10,000-gal double-wall polyethylene tanks under a tent on a concrete pad for temporary storage.<P>

During 1994, <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> staff evaluated treatment and disposal options for the containerized sludges and prepared a report for the DOE Rocky Flats site.  The sludges were characterized as low-level mixed waste containing high concentrations of dissolved salts (e.g., nitrates, sulfates) and heavy metals (e.g., nickel, cadmium) and low levels of radionuclides (e.g., <SUP>239</SUP>Pu, <SUP>241</SUP>Am, <SUP>234</SUP>U, <SUP>235</SUP>U, <SUP>238</SUP>U).  The sludges exceeded land disposal restrictions for cadmium and nickel.  A literature review and survey of federal facilities identified stabilization/solidification (S/S) as the most frequently implemented remedial action for pond sludges.<P>

A query about <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> and <a href="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html/">U.S. Department of Defense</a> sites revealed that &#126;75&#37; of the sites have disposed of or plan to dispose of the treated sludges off-site rather than on-site.  After taking a formal survey of more than 80 private industry vendors, ORNL researchers proposed six types of treatment technologies:  S/S, chemical extraction/precipitation, polyethylene immobilization, vitrification, molten metal, and pyrolytic concentration.  The project team integrated the results of the review and developed more than 20 candidate treatment and disposal systems for further evaluation.  An interdisciplinary, multi-institutional team was assembled, and a systems analysis and ranking exercise was completed.<P>

The top-ranked system was cement-based S/S.  Middle-ranked systems were simple stabilization, biochemical stabilization, biodenitrification followed by cement S/S, pressure S/S, and polymer S/S.  The lowest ranked systems were vitrification, microwave S/S, and plasma hearth S/S.  Whereas stabilization systems appeared most feasible, additional testing and treatability studies were deemed necessary and appropriate to support design and implementation.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Health Sciences and Research Division, ORNL.</I>
<DT>(2)  <I>Chemical Technology Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="16"><H1>16</H1></A>

<H2>Fracture Spacing and Connectivity Are Observed in Multiport Instrumented Wells</H2>

<DL>
<DT>R. B. Dreier and G. L. Davidson (1)
</DL>

Characteristics of hydraulically active fractures determine groundwater flow paths and strongly influence contaminant transport on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR), which is located in the Eastern Tennessee Appalachian Fold and Thrust Belt and overlies an area of folded, faulted, and moderately dipping Cambrian through Mississippian clastic and carbonate rocks.  <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers are conducting a study to understand the lateral and vertical changes in fracture behavior on ORR.  Fourteen core holes that have been geophysically logged and instrumented with multiport systems provide detailed vertical resolution of the fractured rock groundwater system.  Fracture spacing increases with depth, suggesting that fracture distribution is related to near-surface processes such as weathering and unloading.<P>

Fractures create a connected system that shows smooth, fairly continuous vertical changes in the hydraulic head that extend to depths of 700 ft.  This depth range contains the majority of borehole geophysical logging responses indicative of fractures.  Below these depths the fractures are more widely spaced and likely range from being poorly connected to unconnected, leading to unpredictable and reversible vertical hydraulic head gradients.  Locally, packages of strata (as much as 100-ft thick) exhibit no vertical gradient.  These packages are delimited by abrupt and significant changes in head (as much as 30 ft) that probably reflect a poor hydraulic connection between hydrostratigraphic packages.<P>

Where fractures are not observed in cores from the base of deep wells, hydraulic heads at these levels show a sharp drop, greater than 60 ft; this drop suggests that the zone is underpressured, possibly as a result of unloading.  Core analysis has determined that most fractures are strike parallel, but dip-parallel fractures must occur to produce continuity in the groundwater flow paths.  Continuity varies locally, and connectivity can be qualitatively determined from hydraulic head patterns.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="17"><H1>17</H1></A>

<H2>The Modified Ring Test Is Effective in Determining the Fracture Toughness of Competent Rock Cores from ORR</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. J. Lemiszki (1) and J. D. Landes (1)
</DL>

Rock mechanics tests of rock cores from the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) provide a necessary database for mechanical modeling of the bedrock in response to past deformational events, unloading and uplift, hydrofracture injections, and hydrologic testing.  Located in the southern Appalachian Valley and Ridge province, ORR is underlain by a variety of sedimentary rock types with distinct physical properties.<P>

The modified ring test (MRT), a new technique, is a fracture mechanics extension of the Brazilian tensile-strength test.  MRT provides an estimate of rock fracture toughness from core-sized samples that were once considered too small to produce reliable results.  The major limitation of MRT is that it requires rock types that maintain their integrity during sample preparation; therefore it cannot be used to test friable shales.<P>

Tests have been completed on 20 samples obtained from the JOY2 corehole in the Copper Creek thrust sheet.  Sandstone samples are from the Rome Formation; dolomite samples are from the Copper Ridge Dolomite and Maynardville Limestone.  Although more tests must be performed to evaluate the data statistically, preliminary results indicate that average fracture toughnesses of sandstone and dolomite are 4.5 MPa(m)<SUP>1/2</SUP> and 3.0 MPa(m)<SUP>1/2</SUP> respectively.<P>

In addition to testing more core samples, future work will include comparing core sample and outcrop sample test results and testing samples under confining pressure to simulate subsurface conditions.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="18"><H1>18</H1></A>

<H2>Geologic Mapping Is Used as the First Step in Planning Subsurface Studies to Unravel the Complex Geology of the Oak Ridge K-25 Site</H2>

<DL>
<DT>P. J. Lemiszki (1)
</DL>

<a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental restoration and waste management</a> plans for the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/K25/">Oak Ridge K-25 Site</a> require a complete understanding of the site geology because various aspects of the groundwater flow system are directly influenced by stratigraphic and structural characteristics of the bedrock.  This study involved mapping the bedrock geology of a 52-km<SUP>2</SUP> (20-mile<SUP>2</SUP>) area in and around the plant site at a scale of 1 to 12,000.  Field mapping focused on (1) checking the accuracy of previously mapped stratigraphic contacts and faults, (2) dividing the bedrock into distinct stratigraphic units based on field criteria, (3) determining the geometry of map-scale folds and faults, and (4) conducting a preliminary assessment of various aspects of the local fracture system.<P>

Results from this study led to two new hypotheses regarding the site geology that may have an important influence on the groundwater flow system.  First, macroscopic folding within the Chickamauga carbonates in the plant area suggests the existence of a thrust fault in the subsurface that detaches the overlying folds in the Chickamauga from the underlying Knox Group.  The possible surface location of this fault is within the Carters Limestone where a zone of deformation occurs parallel to bedrock strike.  The fault zone may be intensely fractured and may enhance local fracture permeability.  Second, thrust slices of the Rome Formation that overlie the Chickamauga carbonates may be thin and have a more limited aerial extent than previously mapped.  Therefore, the potential exists for contaminants to migrate through the clastics of the Rome Formation into the karstified Chickamauga carbonates.  Evaluating these hypotheses will require information about the subsurface that can be acquired only through drilling and surface geophysical surveys.
The geologic map produced from this study can be used to choose the location of coreholes to intersect a combination of stratigraphic, structural, and hydrologic targets.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="19"><H1>19</H1></A>

<H2>A Statistical Approach for Optimizing the Monitoring of Temporal Changes in Groundwater Quality Is Developed for WAG 6</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. R. Moline, J. J. Beauchamp, and T. Wright (1)
</DL>

Applying the Data Quality Objectives process during the development of the Environmental Monitoring Program for Waste Area Grouping (WAG) 6 led to a decision rule that bases criteria for action on changes in the summed releases of contaminants from WAG 6 in relation to releases from other WAGs that contribute to the total contaminant flux over White Oak Dam.  This approach is consistent with the overall strategy for remediation of the White Oak Creek watershed; the strategy allows for prioritization of remedial activities on the basis of a WAG's relative contribution to off-site flux.  Currently, WAG 6 contributes only 1-3&#37; of the total contaminant flux over White Oak Dam; thus, it is low on the priority list for remedial action.<P>

Studies found that contaminant releases from WAG 6 must undergo a tenfold increase to reach a magnitude comparable to the worst contributors to off-site contaminant flux.  This conclusion led to the following decision rule:  if total contaminant flux from WAG 6 increases by a factor of 10 over 5 years or by a factor of 2 annually, then actions will be taken, including increased monitoring and/or implementation of source control measures.  In applying the decision rule to groundwater monitoring, we developed two statistical methods to provide a measure of comprehensive change that could be declared statistically significant at predetermined levels of confidence.  These methods incorporate both spatial and temporal variability and utilize historical data to determine initial statistical parameters that can be updated as new data are obtained.<P>

The first method is used for evaluating the summed changes in contaminant concentration within a population of wells during an arbitrary &quot;out&quot; year in comparison with the concentration during a baseline year.  The second method is used for evaluating the statistical significance of a trend in mean contaminant concentration for a group of wells.  For either method, the magnitude of change that can be declared statistically significant can be calculated, given the pooled variance from a set of well data, the levels for Type I and Type II errors, and a sampling frequency for the set of wells.  Alternatively, given the desired magnitude of change and the other statistical parameters, a minimum sampling frequency can be determined.  Because the costs of sampling and analysis are known, a cost/benefit analysis can be performed to provide a direct measure of the incremental costs for increased levels of confidence and resolution.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Engineering Physics and Mathematics Division, ORNL.</I>
</DL>

<A NAME="20"><H1>20</H1></A>

<H2>Historical Water-Level Data Provide a Means for Examining Regional Groundwater Flow</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. R. Moline and D. E. Allred (1)
</DL>

Historical water-level data from more than 600 wells in Melton Valley are being evaluated through the use of multivariate statistical techniques to provide a framework for understanding flow dynamics on a regional scale.  This framework will provide the means for examining the spatial variability of hydrologic parameters such as hydraulic conductivity and recharge to the groundwater system, which in turn can be used to improve the calibration of the Melton Valley groundwater model and to guide decisions about well plugging and abandonment.<P>

The objectives are to categorize the wells according to their variations in water level, to determine the spatial distribution of the different categories, and to investigate the correlations between types of water-level responses and potential controlling factors.  Water levels within groundwater wells and piezometers respond to a variety of forcing events, including precipitation, evapotranspiration, earth tides, barometric pressure changes, and anthropogenic activities.  The degree of response is controlled by subsurface hydrologic characteristics as well as by the construction design of the well.  When variations in well design are accounted for and when forcing events are assumed to be uniform across all well locations, then variations in water-level response reflect variations in subsurface hydrologic properties.  Water-level measurements that range in frequency from monthly to daily were examined for suitability and edited to remove outliers and other nonrepresentative points.<P>

Using a subset of daily well hydrographs as a test set, scientists developed a method for separating the low-frequency seasonal responses from the high-frequency storm responses.  Statistical parameters that characterize the seasonal and storm responses were then used to cluster the wells into groups that respond similarly; as a result, nine classes emerged.  Future work will focus on classifying the remaining wells in the data set, analyzing the spatial distribution of dynamic classes, and linking well responses to specific hydrologic properties.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</I>
</dl>

<A NAME="21"><H1>21</H1></A>

<H2>Sampling Protocols for Fractured Media Are Being Investigated</H2>

<DL>
<DT>G. R. Moline and M. E. Schreiber (1)
</DL>

To accurately calculate contaminant flux from waste disposal sites and the subsequent risk to the environment, researchers must have groundwater samples that are representative of in situ flow conditions at the sampling location and that take into account the spatial and temporal variability in groundwater quality.  At an uncontaminated site in West Bear Creek Valley, researchers are collecting data to help determine what constitutes a representative sample in the  fractured shale that is typical of the geology underlying many of the waste disposal sites on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> and to determine how the construction of monitoring wells and the choice of sampling methods affect the representativeness of samples.<P>

The specific objectives are (1) to measure the spatial and temporal variability of geochemical and tracers constituents; (2) to identify discrete transport pathways and construct new monitoring wells that isolate those zones; (3) to determine the influence that the design of monitoring wells has on sample representativeness; and (4) to investigate the impact that various purge volumes have on the flow system, particularly with regard to the potential for increased mobilization of contaminants.<P>

Injection of helium and bromide tracer was initiated in early spring 1994 to create surrogate contaminant plumes for initial characterization of flow dynamics and for later testing of sampling methods.  Three new boreholes were drilled into the shallow bedrock adjacent to existing screened wells.  Electromagnetic borehole flowmeter tests and point dilution tests were conducted to identify and characterize the active flow zones and to determine the appropriate placement of multilevel sampling ports.<P>

Data obtained from screened wells and multilevel wells will be compared to determine the impact of well design on the representativeness of samples.  To examine the spatial variability in water quality, we are analyzing the geochemical and tracer composition of samples taken from discrete zones within the boreholes.  Results of this study will lead to recommendations for revisions in strategies for groundwater monitoring so that researchers can obtain samples that better represent undisturbed flow conditions within active transport pathways.<P>

<DL>
<DT>__________________
<DT>(1)  <I>University of Wisconsin, Madison.</I>
</dl>

<A NAME="22"><H1>22</H1></A>

<H2>Attrition Scrubbing, Ultrasonic Treatment, and Oxidant Additions Enhance Uranium Removal from Contaminated Soils</H2>

<DL>
<DT>M. E. Timpson, M. P. Elless, and C. W. Francis
</DL>

As part of DOE's Uranium in Soils Integrated Demonstration Project, bench-scale investigations of selective uranium leaching from soils at the Fernald Environmental Management Project site, in Ohio, were conducted.  Two Fernald site soils, one sampled adjacent to an old trash incinerator and another sampled adjacent to a storage pad, representing the major contaminant sources at the site, were extracted using carbonate- and citric acid-based lixiviants.<P>

To increase the rate of uranium released from the soils, physical and chemical processes were used in combination with the two extractants; attrition scrubbing and ultrasonic dispersion were the two physical processes used.  Potassium permanganate was used as an oxidizing agent to transform tetravalent uranium to the hexavalent state, because hexavalent uranium is easily complexed in solution by the carbonate radical.  Attrition scrubbing increased the rate of uranium released from both soils when compared with rotary shaking.  At equivalent extraction times and solids loadings, however, attrition scrubbing proved effective only on the soil sampled adjacent to the old trash incinerator.<P>

Additions of potassium permanganate to the carbonate extractant resulted in significant changes in the extractability of uranium from the incinerator soil but had no effect on the removal of uranium from soil sampled adjacent to a storage pad.   Ultrasonic treatments on the incinerator soil removed 71&#37; of the uranium contamination in a single extraction.  Multiple extractions of the same sample removed as much as 90&#37; of the uranium.<P>

<a name="23"><h1>23</h1></a>

<h2>Background Soil Characterization Project Provides Data for Remedial Action Evaluation</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. R. Watkins, J. T. Ammons (1), J. L. Branson (1), B. B. Burgoa (1), P. L. Goodard (2), T. L. Hatmaker (3), L. A. Hook, B. L. Jackson (4), C. W. Kimbrough (5), S. Y. Lee, D. A. Lietzke (6), C. W. McGinn (7), B. D. Nourse (8), R. L. Schmoyer (8), S. E. Stinnette (7) and J. Switek
</dl>

The Background Soil Characterization Project (BSCP) will provide the necessary data to make informed decisions based on extensive characterization of natural background soil concentrations of organics, inorganics (metals), and radionuclides found on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR).  Standards for cleanup of potentially contaminated soils on the ORR will be based on concentrations above those established as background in this project for typical soil constituents.<p>

If data from this project can be used to determine that levels of organics, metals, and radionuclides at a suspected contaminated site are no greater than those found in nature, then those constituents will not be considered contaminants of concern for that site.  However, if concentrations of contaminants are greater than those found in nature, then appropriate remedial actions will be evaluated in site-specific cleanup projects to reduce the elevated concentrations to naturally occurring levels or to technically feasible levels.  The objectives of the BSCP were to provide (1) fully validated and defensible data for assessing contaminated sites and (2) estimates of risk from background concentrations of naturally occurring (but potentially hazardous) substances in undisturbed soils.<p>

The BSCP addresses the variability of concentration levels in relation to major soil types occurring in different geologic formations, soil-sampling depths (i.e., horizons) within specific soil profiles, and natural variations in soils developed in the same geologic formation.  ESD was instrumental in completing this 2-year field project for the DOE <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a>.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Site Program Office, Oak Ridge K-25 Plant, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>Measurement Applications and Development Group, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(4)  <i>Computing Applications Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(5)  <i>Analytical Projects Office, Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.</i>
<dt>(6)  <i>Consultant, Rutledge, Tennessee.</i>
