<a name="24"><h1>24</h1></a>

<h2>Convection in a Large Artificial Magma Is Observed Indirectly Through Thermal Perturbations and Cooling Rates Recorded During Crystallization of an In Situ Vitrification Melt</h2>

<dl>
<dt>G. K. Jacobs, M. T. Naney, and N. W. Dunbar1
</dl>

A large (5-m<sup>3</sup>, 12,500-kg) hemispherical-shaped, high-calcium basaltic melt was created by in situ vitrification technology and allowed to cool from a crystal-free, superheated condition to a solidified rock body.  The interior of the solidified rock body consists of large (1 &#215; 5 mm) diopsidic pyroxene phenocrysts in a ground mass of small pyroxenes and anorthitic feldspars.  The margin of the body contains more glass as well as pyroxenes with textures indicative of rapid cooling.  The melt was well mixed by convection during its formation:  tracer elements placed as point sources in the precursor soil before the melt were found to be distributed homogeneously throughout the solidified rock body.<p>

Direct observation of the melt surface indicated convection rates of 6 m/min during active melting.  Convection of the melt during cooling was evaluated using information about the size of the melt combined with data from thermocouples placed in the melt at various distances from the melt margin.<p>

Cooling rates of -0.5&#176;C/min were measured from 1400 to 1325&#176;C by all thermocouples immediately following termination of heating.  At 1210&#176;C the cooling rates in the melt interior decreased to -0.25&#176;C/min, whereas rates near the melt margin were -0.37&#176;C/min.  Thermocouples in the melt interior recorded large, distinct thermal perturbations that started at 1325&#176;C and that had a 10- to 20-min period with a temperature variation of 10 to 20&#176;C.  Thermocouples near the melt margin measured less distinct perturbations.  The thermal perturbations in the melt interior started to dampen at 1210&#176;C, which is near the liquidus temperature derived from the MELTS model of Ghiorso.<p>

The thermal perturbations completely disappeared by 1160 to 1180&#176;C, just prior to a thermal arrest at 1140&#176;C, which indicated extensive crystallization of the melt.  The MELTS-calculated crystallization history suggests that the system is 25&#37  crystals at 1190&#176;C.  Thus, convection appeared to decrease near the liquidus and to cease as the melt approached 25&#37  crystals.<p>

On the basis of the observed thermal behavior, estimated convection rates were 0.25 m/min during cooling from 1400 to 1325&#176;C, 0.1 m/min from 1325 to 1210&#176;C, and 0.025 m/min just prior to the thermal arrest.  The lack of distinct thermal perturbations and the presence of dendritic textures and more glass in the margin of the solidified rock body are consistent with a conceptual model of minimal convection, rapid crystal growth, and significant heat transfer from the margins of the melt to the surrounding soil.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>New Mexico Bureau of Mining and Mineral Resources, Socorro, New Mexico.</i>
</dl>

<a name="25"><h1>25</h1></a>

<h2>Subsurface Column Studies Identify the Importance of Time-Dependent Diffusion During Solute Transport</h2>

<dl>
<dt>P. M. Jardine, R. O'Brien (1), and O. Reedy (2)
</dl>

The majority of groundwater and contaminant fluxes on the DOE <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) occur in subsurface materials &lt;3 m deep.  These materials are characterized by  fractures or networks of large pores, which are highly conductive zones, and the surrounding matrix materials, which are less conductive.  Mass transport from the conductive zones to the matrix material provides a sink for contaminants entering the groundwater system.  The subsequent release of this mass from the matrix back into conductive zones serves as a long-term, secondary source of contaminants to the groundwater.<p>

The objectives of this investigation were to characterize and to quantify the mass transport processes that move contaminants between these two subsurface regions.  Cylindrical columns (18 &#215; 40 cm) of undisturbed, highly weathered shale were collected from ORR and instrumented for laboratory simulations of saturated groundwater flow.  Columns were acquired parallel to the subsurface bedding planes, the primary conductors of groundwater movement.<p>

Conservative tracer tests were performed over a range of groundwater fluxes; these conditions encompassed the range of measured in situ fluxes.  Additional tracer tests involved flow interruption techniques and the use of multiple tracers with varying diffusion coefficients. Results from the tracer tests indicate that both the amount of mass and its transfer rate into the matrix vary with changes in flux.  The mass transferred into the matrix decreases with an increase in groundwater flux, whereas the transfer rate increases.<p>

Existing numerical groundwater models do not adequately predict the observed data; this suggests that not all pertinent transport processes are included in the selected models.  Flow interruption experiments confirm that the molecular diffusion of solutes is a significant transport process over the entire range of experimental fluxes.  Multiple tracer tests indicate that this diffusion occurs throughout all stages of solute transport and breakthrough.<p>

<dl>
<dt>
<dt>(1)  <i>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Advanced Sciences, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="26"><h1>26</h1></a>

<h2>Common Soil Minerals Alter the Fate and Transport of Contaminants in Subsurface Environments</h2>

<dl>
<dt>P. M. Jardine and D. L. Taylor (1)
</dl>

Low-level radioactive waste generated at <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities has traditionally involved shallow land burial as a mixed waste source.  Contaminants such as <sup>60</sup>Co and <sup>90</sup>Sr are chelated with organic ligands, such as ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA), prior to disposal.  Because of complex interactions with soil minerals, chelating agents tend to alter the geochemical behavior of contaminants in subsurface environments.<p>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers investigated the kinetics and mechanisms of Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup> oxidation to Co(III)EDTA<sup>-</sup> by the soil mineral Mn-oxide.  The environmental significance of this reaction is that the product, Co(III)EDTA<sup>-</sup>,  is much more stable and travels farther in subsurface environments relative to Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup>.<p>

Quartz sand was coated with 0.04 to 0.4&#37 beta-Mn(IV)O<sub>2</sub>, and Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup> reactivity was investigated for various Mn:Co molar ratios and different MnO<sub>2</sub> surface coverages through batch and column techniques.  The soil mineral MnO<sub>2</sub> exhibited catalytic capabilities such that each mole of Mn(IV) catalyzed the oxidation of significantly more than two moles of Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup>.  A loss in oxidative potential of the MnO<sub>2</sub> occurs, however, upon continuous reaction with Co(II)EDTA2-.<p>

Evidence suggests that the oxidation of Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup> involves the reduction of Mn(IV) to both an aqueous Mn<sup>2+</sup> species and a Mn(III)-oxide solid phase.  A catalytic cycle is observed as the Mn(III)-oxide is regenerated to a Mn(IV)-oxide and as the Mn<sup>2+</sup> is readsorbed and reoxidized on the solid phase.  The loss of oxidative potential was shown not to result from direct surface poisoning by adsorbed Mn<sup>2+</sup> but rather to apparently be caused by formation of an intermediate Mn(III)-oxide solid phase whose oxidative potential was significantly less than Mn(IV)O<sub>2</sub>.  These results suggest that the kinetics of Co(II)EDTA<sup>2-</sup> oxidation to Co(III)EDTA<sup>-</sup> in subsurface environments depend on the rate of Mn-oxide surface regeneration.<p>

<dl>
<dt>
<dt>(1)  <i>Advanced Sciences, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="27"><h1>27</h1></a>

<h2>Presence of Natural Organic Matter Decreases Sulfate Adsorption in Subsurface Environments</h2>

<dl>
<dt>Z. S. Kooner (1) and P. M. Jardine
</dl>

Predicting in situ, multispecies subsurface transport requires knowledge of specific geochemical interactions that occur in soil.  Because of hydrologic and mineralogic heterogeneities, geochemical interactions may be spatially complex at the field scale.  In this study, researchers characterized competitive surface-complexation reactions of sulfate and natural organic matter (NOM) as a function of pH on different soil types spatially distributed throughout a field facility located at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  Soil samples acquired from the field site were treated to remove indigenous NOM and sulfate, and a batch technique was used to investigate competitive surface reactions of added NOM and sulfate as a function of pH.<p>

The adsorption of sulfate onto the different soil types was a time-dependent process that reached equilibrium in 4 d.  Sulfate adsorption decreased in the presence of NOM and was found to be strongly pH dependent on several soil types.  The pH-dependent adsorption data were successfully represented by a surface-complexation model based on electrical double-layer theory using a single adsorption reaction between the sulfate anion and the soil surface.  Model-estimated surface-complexation constants were of the order log K = 10, which suggested strong sulfate adsorption.<p>

Although the presence of NOM consistently decreased sulfate adsorption over the pH range, model-estimated surface-complexation constants for sulfate were essentially the same in the presence and absence of NOM.  The surface-complexation constants also appear to be spatially consistent throughout the field site.  The stability constants obtained from this study are being used, in conjunction with other information, to parameterize a field-scale, three-dimensional, multispecies hydrogeochemical transport model.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
</dl>

<a name="28"><h1>28</h1></a>

<h2>Forager Sponge Helps Remove Technetium from Groundwater</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. D. Marsh, Jr., L. Liang, M. T. Muck (1), and D. T. Davenport (2)
</dl>

Four forms of a new proprietary material, the Forager Sponge, have been evaluated for their effectiveness in removing technetium from groundwater.  Batch experiments using <sup>95m</sup>Tc were carried out for the aluminum, acid-activated aluminum (Al-H), calcium, and hydrogen forms of the Forager Sponge.  Results of a 5-d experiment showed that the Al, Al-H, and Ca forms reached equilibrium with respect to Tc removal after about 1 d, whereas the H form required 4 d to achieve equilibrium.  The hydrogen form also had the highest capacity for sorption of technetium, being about 50&#37 greater than the other forms and sorbing about 63&#37 of the initial technetium activity after 5 d.  The order of the sorption capacity was H &gt; Al-H &gt; Ca &gt; Al.  The sorption of technetium was also found to be a linear function of the technetium concentration up to 18 nCi/g of sponge.  Saturation of the sponge was not achieved at this concentration.  From these experiments, the hydrogen form of the Forager Sponge appears to be a candidate medium for removing technetium from groundwater.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Health Sciences Research Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Environmental Restoration Program, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<a name="29"><h1>29</h1></a>

<h2>Use of In Situ Vitrification to Study Natural Magmatic Processes Is Discussed During a Workshop at ORNL</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. T. Naney and G. K. Jacobs
</dl>

Melts generated by <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/ISV/">in situ vitrification</a> (ISV) technology provide unique opportunities to advance the understanding of magmas and magmatic processes and thus justify the development of a proposal to seek funding for a new research initiative at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  This was the consensus of participants in a workshop conducted by ORNL <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers in Oak Ridge, Tennessee, March 29-30, 1994.<p>

Workshop participants evaluated the use of ISV technology to produce large silicate melts that would serve as analogs to natural magmas for studying magmatic properties and processes.  ISV melts provide a controlled and monitored environment for testing hypotheses that cannot be tested by bench-top experiments or by studying natural systems.  The scale of ISV melts is intermediate (i.e., between that of natural lava lakes and laboratory crucible experiments); melt volumes of 15 to 300 m<sup>3</sup> are easily obtained.  This approach makes possible the investigation of dynamic processes that either (1) operate on a scale too large to simulate with bench-top experiments or (2) are not amenable to direct observation or control in natural systems (e.g., degassing, convection, crystal settling).<p>

The process produces &quot;containerless&quot; silicate melts; this permits the development of important analog components of natural magma systems, including partial melt zones, stoping, contact metamorphic halos, and &quot;hydrothermal&quot; fluids.  The absence of a melt container makes it possible to use standard field-scale geophysical instrumentation to study the seismic and electrical properties of the melt and the host materials.  Volatile and particulate emissions from an ISV melt can be sampled by using methods that avoid reaction with, and contamination by, host rocks.<p>

Geoscientists from across the United States who have expertise in theoretical, experimental, and field investigations attended the workshop.  The 23 participants represented universities, research institutions, and national laboratories, including <a href="http://www.pnl.gov:2080/">Pacific Northwest Laboratory</a>, where engineering staff developed ISV techniques for applications in environmental restoration.  A workshop report is being prepared. <p>

<a name="30"><h1>30</h1></a>

<h2>Cedar (<i>Juniperus virginiana</i>) Records Historical Atmospheric Releases of Mercury</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. R. Turner and N. S. Bloom
</dl>

Recent dendrochemical studies have demonstrated anatomical, chemical, and ecological attributes of red cedar (<i>Juniperus virginiana</i>) that can aid researchers in defining long-term trends in environmental chemistry.  The assumption in these studies is that the elemental composition of the annual woody growth partially reflects the chemistry of the environment in which it was formed.  Validation of this basic assumption for a given tree and location is difficult to obtain in the absence of an exposure history.<p>

Use of more than 1.1 &#215; 10<sup>10</sup> g of elemental mercury at a federal facility in Oak Ridge, Tennessee, in the 1950s has provided a relatively well-defined exposure history for red cedar growing in the vicinity of the facility.  An estimated 2.3 &#215; 10<sup>7</sup> g of mercury was released to the atmosphere between 1950 and 1963; &#126;30&#37 of the total air release occurred in 1955.  During the same period, &#126;1.1 &#215; 10<sup>8</sup> g was released to a stream, resulting in the contamination of a 150-ha floodplain downstream of the facility.<p>

Red cedar are abundant in the vicinity of the facility, growing on both uncontaminated and contaminated soils.  Thus, these trees provide exposure routes via foliar absorption alone and by combined foliar and root uptake.<p>

In addition, ambient air-monitoring data for mercury are available for the past 8 years near two locations where red cedar trees occur.  These data provide a unique opportunity to compare average annual mercury concentrations in wood with those in ambient air.  With one exception, trees growing on low-mercury soil within 30 km of the facility revealed sharp, well-defined peaks in mercury centered in the mid-1950s.  Background concentrations of mercury in red cedar appear to range from 2 to 5 ng/g, whereas peak concentrations were 500 to 1500 ng/g.<p>

One tree, located closest to the center of mercury use at the facility, exhibited mid-1950s peaks as well as one large peak in 1966 that seemed to correspond with the decommissioning and decontamination of a large building.   Trees growing in the mercury-contaminated floodplain also exhibited large (i.e., up to 7000 ng/g) mid-1950s peaks that appear to include both root and foliar uptake.<p>

Comparison of the recent ambient air data with red cedar wood values demonstrated that wood values correlated closely with the general trends in air values.  ESD researchers have also shown that red cedar growing near other industrial sources of mercury, such as chlorine-caustic soda plants, have accurately recorded the historical atmospheric releases from nearby facilities.  Once fully verified, this method could prove highly useful in analyzing historical exposure levels to atmospheric mercury. <p>

<a name="31"><h1>31</h1></a>

<h2>Characterization of the Relationship Between Concentration and Discharge in WAG 4 Helps Resolve Discrepancy in the Conceptual Model of Contaminant Transport at Different Scales</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. M. Borders (1),  R. B. Clapp, and M. F. Tardiff (2)
</dl>

Recent developments in the conceptual model of the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> hydrologic system have largely shifted the emphasis of monitoring and sampling from groundwater to surface water so that the characteristics of contaminant movement and discharge from waste disposal sites can be identified more effectively.  However, when the conceptual model is examined at different temporal and spatial scales, a discrepancy appears in the relationship between contaminant concentration (C) and stream discharge (Q).  At the tributary scale, contaminant concentrations tend to decrease as flow increases; for example, contaminants entering tributaries are partially diluted during storms.  In contrast, monthly data collected at the major monitoring stations (weirs) on the White Oak Creek (WOC) watershed indicate that concentrations of contaminants (e.g., <sup>3</sup>H, <sup>90</sup>Sr) increase as discharge increases; partial dilution does not appear to occur at the larger scale.<p>

During two storm events, researchers collected samples from the tributary draining Waste Area Grouping (WAG) 4 into WOC.  The samples indicate that, for a given storm, concentrations decrease as discharge decreases.  However, the wet-season storm produced higher concentrations (at higher levels of discharge) than the dry-season storm; this suggests a resolution of differences in the conceptual model at the tributary scale (i.e., storm event sampling) and the site-wide scale (i.e., monthly flow proportional sampling).  Although an individual storm may exhibit the typical C-Q relationship, the average concentration for a storm in the wet season is higher than the average concentration for a storm during the dry season.  Consequently, the monthly data show higher concentrations associated with higher discharges, particularly during the wet season, when the water table is elevated.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Office of Environmental Compliance and Documentation, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<a name="32"><h1>32</h1></a>

<h2>Hydrologic Data for the White Oak Creek Watershed Are Summarized</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. M. Borders (1), D. K. Reece, J. A. Watts, B. J. Frederick (1), W. M. McCalla (2), and K. S. Ziegler (3)
</dl>

The White Oak Creek (WOC) watershed--consisting of WOC and its tributaries, White Oak Lake, and the WOC Embayment on the Clinch River--is the primary surface drainage for <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  WOC drains ORNL and receives radioactive and nonradioactive effluents (treated and untreated) from ORNL activities, as well as leachates from subsurface waste storage areas in use since the early 1940s.<p>

Streamflow has been monitored in the watershed for over 45 years; the stream network consists of small perennial and intermittent, first- to third-order streams.  In addition to natural runoff and groundwater discharge, WOC and its tributaries receive waste effluents and process water discharges from ORNL facilities.  These effluents and discharges represent a significant portion of the annual streamflow.  Sediments within the WOC flow system have sorbed chemical and radioactive contaminants from nearby waste areas.  Consequently, the WOC floodplain sediments and the White Oak Lake sediments and water contain measurable quantities of <sup>3</sup>H, <sup>90</sup>Sr, <sup>137</sup>Cs, and <sup>60</sup>Co.<p>

A hydrologic data report, published for the fourth consecutive year, summarizes the hydrologic data collected on the WOC watershed and its vicinity.  The collection of hydrologic data is an integral component  of numerous ongoing ORNL environmental studies and monitoring programs and is designed to help (1) characterize the quantity and quality of water in the flow system, (2) plan and assess remedial action activities, (3) provide long-term data and quality assurance, and (4) support long-term measures of contaminant fluxes at a spatial scale that will provide a comprehensive picture of watershed performance commensurate with future remedial actions.<p>

The report continues the characterization and provides the sources of data needed for long-term assessment of the effectiveness of remedial restoration activities.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Analysas Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>Midwest Technical, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="33"><h1>33</h1></a>

<h2>Third Annual Report of Environmental Restoration Monitoring and Assessment for ORNL Is Completed</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. B. Clapp and J. A. Watts
</dl>

The <i>Third Annual Report of Environmental Restoration Monitoring and Assessment at the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a></i> summarizes the investigation and monitoring activities within the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration (ER) Program</a> during fiscal year 1993.  The report results from the cooperative effort of more than 30 contributing authors and is the product of the Waste Area Grouping (WAG) 2 and Site Investigation (SI) Program.  Data collection and assessment activities are divided into four major areas:  surface water, groundwater, soils and sediments, and biota.  Data are presented in a watershed-wide perspective.<p>

Because risk reduction is a primary goal of the ER Program, the data are interpreted in terms of risk to humans.  The key indicator for the ER Program is the risk associated with ingesting water discharged at White Oak Dam, the outflow point for most of the ORNL site.  In 1993, the risk factor was 5.4 &#215; 10<sup>-4</sup> chance of an excess cancer, which exceeds the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> action limit of 1 &#215; 10<sup>-4</sup>.  The primary contaminant of concern is <sup>90</sup>Sr, followed by <sup>3</sup>H and <sup>137</sup>Cs.  The areas where contaminant releases contributed most to this site-wide risk factor were WAG 5, followed by WAG 1 and WAG 4 (59&#37, 18&#37, and 17&#37 contribution, respectively).<p>

To reduce off-site risk, the ER Program is initiating removal actions with significant involvement of ORNL's <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff.  The WAG 2 and SI Program exemplifies the integration of applied research and environmental information collection and assessment.  This third annual report and future reports will form a basis for prioritizing sites, initially selecting and finally evaluating remedial actions within the White Oak Creek watershed.<p>

<a name="34"><h1>34</h1></a>

<h2>Rainfall-Runoff Models Fail to Simulate Extreme Floods Accurately</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. A. Fontaine
</dl>

An important application of rainfall-runoff models is the simulation of peak discharge and runoff volume of extreme floods for risk analyses of dams, nuclear energy facilities, and other high-hazard structures.  Runoff models also are used for analyses involving the design of hydraulic structures, flood protection, sediment transport, and research on a variety of surface water hydrology issues.<p>

A major limitation of runoff models is that little information exists on the accuracy of these models for simulating extreme floods (used here to mean floods ranging from the 100-year event up to the probable maximum flood).  To evaluate runoff model accuracy for extreme events, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers compared simulated and observed peak discharge and runoff volume for a historic 100-year flood on a medium-sized catchment.  To investigate whether more sophisticated modeling results in significantly greater accuracy, the extreme flood was simulated using two approaches: a quick analysis with a relatively simple model and an extensive analysis with a complex model.<p>

The runoff models overestimated the peak discharge by 40 to 79&#37 and the runoff volume by 20 to 29&#37.  The more elaborate modeling approach used a calibrated, continuous model; it gave more accurate results but required much more effort than the simple modeling analysis.  The amount of error in the simulated flood indicates the importance of including estimates of error in all modeling analyses of extreme floods and the need to develop tools to evaluate the errors on a routine basis.  The uncertainty in simulated flood hydrographs potentially affects public safety, increases the cost of new construction, and limits researchers' abilities to solve many hydrologic and environmental problems.<p>

In spite of the potential for significant error, runoff models will continue to play a critical role in the simulation of extreme floods because of the few available alternatives.<p>

<a name="35"><h1>35</h1></a>

<h2>Dye Tracer and Point Dilution Tests Are Used to Determine Permeable Zones near the Water Table in Fractured Shales on ORR</h2>

<dl>
<dt>W. E. Sanford
</dl>

Information about the location and configuration of relatively permeable zones is critically important to understanding the movement of groundwater contaminants.  Furthermore, the occurrence or nonoccurrence of permeable zones in the open intervals of monitoring wells will affect sampling results and their interpretation.<p>

The current distribution of the groundwater dye Rhodamine-WT at the West Bear Creek Valley Tracer Test Site on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) was used, along with point dilution tests, to examine the distribution of permeable zones near the water table. These zones typically occur at the base of the weathered zone (known as the water table interval).  The dye was added as a groundwater tracer in April 1988 under natural gradient conditions.<p>

Cores of saprolite from the Nolichucky Shale (Upper Cambrian) were recently collected to the depth of auger refusal and analyzed for dye.  The analyses indicate that the greatest dye concentrations occur along the centerline of the plume in an apparently laterally continuous zone &#126;1.5 m thick.  The direction of plume migration is parallel to the local geologic strike.  The vertical distribution of dye concentrations suggests that vertical transport perpendicular to the permeable zones is diffusion dominated.<p>

In addition, the specific flux of groundwater has been measured by point dilution testing at 0.3-m intervals within saprolite and bedrock core holes at the tracer site.  In general, the highest (1 m/d) and lowest (0.01 m/d) discharges occur in the bedrock; the highest values occur at discrete locations.  In the saprolite the discharges are larger (i.e., an average of 0.16 m/d), and the permeable zones are defined by gradual changes.<p>

These results, along with the dye distribution, suggest that most of the shallow groundwater flows through two or three permeable zones within the water table interval.  The permeable intervals appear to be spaced at vertical distances of 1 to 2 m and can be traced laterally for over 30 m.  A similar spacing was also observed in gamma counts from wells located near waste trenches on ORR.<p>

The results of this study have been used to locate the sampling wells for a noble gas tracer test that was designed to demonstrate and to quantify the dynamic storage (and release) of contaminants in low-permeability zones while contaminants are transported in high-permeability zones.<p>

This information is necessary for the accurate parameterization of the next generation of groundwater models.<p>



