<TITLE>Ecosystem Studies</TITLE>

<H1>Ecosystem Studies</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

Research in the Ecosystem Studies Section of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) is directed toward quantitatively characterizing the structure and functional relationships of regional landscapes and terrestrial and aquatic ecosystems, communities, and populations.  This information is used to predict the responses of the regions and ecosystems to both natural and human-induced disturbances.  The section focuses on complementary areas of research, including theoretical ecology, biogeochemical cycling of materials, physiological ecology of terrestrial plants, resource analysis, biofuels, and hydrosystems.  Major sponsors of the section's research are the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) Environmental Sciences Division of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/research-org/1995.html#td/">Office of Health and Environmental Research</a>, the DOE Carbon Dioxide Research Program, the DOE <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a>, the DOE Hydropower Program, the <a href="http://www.fsl.orst.edu/home/usfs/usfshome.htm/">U.S. Forest Service</a> (USFS), the <a href="http://www.fedworld.gov/ferc/">Federal Energy Regulatory Commission</a> (FERC), the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA), the <a href="http://www.epri.com/">Electric Power Research Institute</a> (EPRI), the <a href="http://www.nsf.gov/">National Science Foundation</a> (NSF), the <a href="http://www.nps.gov/">National Park Service</a> (NPS), and the <a href="http://www.onr.navy.mil/">Office of Naval Research</a>.  Work is also conducted in cooperation with the <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">Tennessee Valley Authority</a> (TVA).<p>

<h2>Biogeochemical Cycling</h2>

Staff in the Biogeochemical Cycling Group study elemental cycling within environmental systems; the spatial and temporal patterns of storage and fluxes of nutrients and pollutants; the role of the biogeochemical cycling of chemicals in regulating the productivity, diversity, and sustainability of natural and human-dominated ecosystems; and the development of innovative methods to measure, analyze, model, and interpret biogeochemical cycles at site-specific, regional, and global scales.<p>

The group is currently involved in research in six areas: (1) the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/science-to-life/wbw.html/">Walker Branch Watershed</a> project, which includes long-term studies of basic biogeochemical processes in a mixed deciduous forest catchment and a major manipulation experiment evaluating forest ecosystem response to potential changes in precipitation that result from global climate change; (2) an <a href="http://www.nsf.gov/">NSF</a>-funded project investigating spatial gradients in nutrient cycling in streams; (3) a DOE study to evaluate hydrologic processes and the fate of precipitation-borne contaminants in arctic watersheds; (4) two <a href="http://www.onr.navy.mil/">Office of Naval Research</a> studies of radionuclide contamination resulting from activities in the former U.S.S.R.; (5) studies of the dynamics of nitrogen and carbon and their storage or export from high- and low-elevation watersheds in the region; and (6) projects that monitor, predict, and assess water resources and water quality at local and regional scales.<p>

<h2>Biomass Systems and International Studies</h2>

The Biomass Systems and International Studies Group develops and applies methodologies that assess the feasibility and implications of the development of biomass energy systems in a national and international framework.  Through this group's efforts, <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> is recognized as an international force in transforming concepts of integrated, sustainable biomass energy systems into reality.  Staff members from <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a>, <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">ORNL's Energy Division</a>, and <a href="http://www.hsrd.ornl.gov/index.html/">ORNL's Health Sciences Research Division</a> contribute expertise in resource analysis, economic analysis, forestry, ecology, and information management.  Staff manage and maintain biomass databases, evaluate the global role of biomass energy systems in reducing carbon emissions from the burning of fossil fuels, characterize the systems of energy crop production and analyze their economics, and conduct analyses of the total fuel cycle.  The group also evaluates and documents the environmental risks and benefits of biomass energy systems, as well as evaluates integrated biomass energy systems in developing countries.  Members of the group participate in International Energy Agency and biomass energy activities, and they develop strategies for the commercialization of biomass energy.<p>

<h2>Hydrosystems</h2>

The Hydrosystems Group conducts applied and basic research required for the management and analysis of water resources and related natural systems.  For example, researchers study how fish populations are affected by water allocation or land-use practices that influence water quality.  The group's research focuses specifically on hydroelectric energy production and its environmental effects.  The Hydrosystems Group specializes in the development and application of quantitative assessment techniques to solve environmental problems ranging in spatial scale from small stream segments or local levels to large river basins or national levels.  In addition, the group addresses such issues as instream flow needs, fish population modeling, multiple-use trade-off analyses, cumulative impact assessment, contaminant transport, surface water and groundwater monitoring, acidic deposition, and climate change.  Research capabilities include simulation and optimization modeling, sensitivity and uncertainty analysis, geostatistical applications, geographic information systems, and scientific database management.  <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, <a href="http://www.fedworld.gov/ferc/">FERC</a>, and <a href="http://www.epri.com/">EPRI</a> are the three major sponsors of the Hydrosystems Group.<p>

<h2>Physiological Ecology</h2>

Members of the Physiological Ecology Group evaluate the effects that global climate change and environmental stress have on plant growth and vigor, and they examine the role that physiological processes play in the biogeochemical cycling of pollutants within terrestrial ecosystems.  The physiological mechanisms of vegetation response to global climate change (i.e., change in CO<sub>2</sub> levels, temperature, precipitation) are evaluated at the seedling, whole-plant, and ecosystem levels.  The group examines specific atmospheric pollutants such as ozone, acid deposition, and nitrogen oxides, as well as the effects of other changes in the chemical and physical atmospheric environment (e.g., high-energy ultraviolet radiation, also known as ultraviolet-B radiation or UV-B).  Recently research has shifted toward determining the response of trees and forest ecosystems to global climate change, with emphasis on changes in precipitation, atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>, temperature, and high-energy ultraviolet radiation.  Helping to develop nonfossil energy sources, researchers are investigating the use of physiological indicators in intensive biomass production from woody and herbaceous crops grown for the production energy feedstock.<p>

These indicators provide an indirect assessment of stress tolerance.  In addition, research attention has focused on the effect that interactive stresses have on physiological indicators of whole-plant resource utilization.  <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, <a href="http://www.epri.com/">EPRI</a>, <a href="http://www.fsl.orst.edu/home/usfs/usfshome.htm/">USFS</a>, and <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a> are the primary sponsors of the work.<p>

During FY 1994, investigators in the Physiological Ecology Group successfully completed the first full year of the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/science-to-life/wbw.html/">Walker Branch Watershed</a> Throughfall Displacement Experiment, which is designed to provide mechanistic studies of ecosystem- and plant-level responses to changing precipitation patterns.  <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff and collaborators from several universities initiated further related studies at the experiment site.<p>

At the Global Change Field Research Site, researchers in the Physiological Ecology Group established and tested a system for evaluating tree responses to increased concentrations of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> and to increased temperature.  Related work focused on (1) the enhancement of photosynthesis in loblolly pine seedlings through CO<sub>2</sub> enrichment and (2) the chemical composition and decomposition rates of yellow poplar leaves in increased and ambient levels of CO<sub>2</sub>.  Studies sponsored by <a href="http://www.fsl.orst.edu/home/usfs/usfshome.htm/">USFS</a> provided the first direct measurements of the effects that ambient ozone has on the growth of mature forest trees.  Research for the Model Herbaceous Energy Species task area of the  <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a> revealed that an increase in ploidy levels among different populations of switchgrass did not consistently increase photosynthetic rates.<p>

Research in physiological ecology contributed to new initiatives in modeling the global carbon cycle.  The effort centered around incorporating a model of soil organic matter decomposition and a net primary productivity model based on a biochemical model of photosynthesis.<p>

<h2>Resource Analysis</h2>

Staff of the Resource Analysis Group characterize environmental resources and evaluate their development and sustainability, especially at large spatial scales.  They also devise and improve methodologies for making such evaluations.  Efforts of the group can be divided into those activities focused on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> and other <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities and those activities not related to specific DOE facilities.  The Resource Analysis Group characterizes and reports on environmental measurements taken at DOE facilities, develops environmental databases for DOE <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/orcmt/bmp/envirres.html/">Environmental Restoration</a>, manages the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/facilities/nerp.html/">Oak Ridge National Environmental Research Park</a>, and provides on-site and off-site environmental programs with geographic information system support.  Members of the group are also involved in broader resource issues, including the sustainability of protected areas, the environmental implications of large-scale development of biomass energy, and the analysis and development of global environmental data sets.  DOE is the primary sponsor of this group.<p>

In FY 1994, members of the Resource Analysis Group presented their work at several foreign meetings; produced an annual environmental report for all DOE facilities managed by Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc.; and moved ahead in developing a land area plan for the Oak Ridge Reservation.<p>

<h2>Theoretical Ecology</h2>

The Theoretical Ecology Group develops simulation and mathematical methods to describe and predict the behavior of ecological systems.  The tools developed within the group are applied to a spectrum of problems, including environmental assessments, theoretical questions in population and ecosystem dynamics, and analyses of phenomena that span spatial scales from a stream segment to the globe.  Research focuses on landscape ecology, development of individual-based models of animal populations, development of landscape indicators and models for environmental monitoring and assessment, integration of socioeconomic and ecological models of land-use change, and development of analytical techniques that can be used to manage ecosystems.  <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, <a href="http://www.epri.com/">EPRI</a>, <a href="http://www.nsf.gov/">NSF</a>, <a href="http://www.nps.gov/">NPS</a>, <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a>, and <a href="http://www.fsl.orst.edu/home/usfs/usfshome.htm/">USFS</a> are among the groups supporting this work.<p>

An individual-based population model for sympatric populations of brown and rainbow trout was developed as part of the Program on Compensatory Mechanisms in Fish Populations.  In collaboration with utility biologists, Theoretical Ecology Group staff are testing their model in a small stream in the Sierra Mountains of California.  Researchers will apply the model to evaluate alternative flow and temperature regimes in an effort to assess instream flow requirements.  This process-oriented model represents the growth, survival, and reproduction of individual trout and is designed to complement alternative modeling approaches that focus solely on amount of suitable habitat.<p>

During FY 1994, other research in the Theoretical Ecology Group used neutral-landscape models to focus on the simulation of species responses to general changes in landscape structure.  The models help researchers assess ecological processes in heterogenous environments without being specific to a particular landscape.<p>

<h2>TVA Cooperative Forest Studies Program</h2>

As a consequence of a common interest in the environmental impacts of energy development and utilization, <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">TVA</a> and the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/doe_oro/oro_home.html/">DOE Oak Ridge Operations Office</a> have developed an agreement to pursue joint research activities specifically involving <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff and members of the <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">TVA</a> Resources Group.  Under this arrangement, TVA personnel are assigned to <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> to develop programs investigating the effects that emissions into air and water have on terrestrial and aquatic resources.  This working relationship combines ESD's unique research-support facilities and the experience that TVA has gained from its power-producing and resource management activities.  As a result, the group can produce timely and relevant research findings.  A number of major collaborative projects have been undertaken.  Whereas initial research projects centered on water quality and nutrient-cycling issues in the context of acid rain, more recent and proposed activities focus on (1) biological effects of chemical and physical changes in the environment that are associated with global change and (2) environmental impacts of the conversion of cropland to biomass plantations.<p>

Belowground research on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/science-to-life/wbw.html/">Walker Branch Watershed</a> Throughfall Displacement Experiment indicates that although total root elongation generally increased as treatment areas received more throughfall volume, no significant differences in treatment areas were detected during the 1994 growing season:  because the rainfall was unusually high, the plants did not experience any stress from a lack of moisture.  The Environmental Impacts of Conversion of Cropland to Biomass Plantations project has virtually completed the installation of both equipment and crop and tree plots at three sites in the Tennessee Valley (including one at Alabama A. & M. University, supported through DOE's <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a>).  This study will compare conventional crops with woody biomass from plantations with regard to erosion, water quality of surface runoff, belowground contamination, physical and chemical properties of soil, carbon sequestration, nutrient cycling, and wildlife biodiversity.<p>

