<a name="tech"><h1>Technical Summaries</h1></a>
<hr>

<a name="36"><h1>36</h1></a>

<h2>Exchange of Dissolved Nutrients Between Free-Flowing Water and Storage Zones of Streams Is Modeled</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. L. DeAngelis, D. R. Hart (1), E. R. Marzolf, and P. J. Mulholland
</dl>

The purpose of the <a href="http://www.nsf.gov/">National Science Foundation</a> project &quot;Nutrient Cycling, Ecosystem Structure, and Ecosystem Stability&quot; is to characterize the recycling of nutrients along streams.  As part of this characterization, it is necessary to determine (1) the rate of transfer of dissolved nutrients from the free-flowing part of the stream to nonflowing water near the stream's bottom and to within-stream sediments (called the transient storage zones) and (2) the rate of release of nutrients back into the free-flowing water.  Researchers determined these rates for streams in the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/science-to-life/wbw.html/">Walker Branch Watershed</a>, using a combination of conservative tracer-injection experiments and mathematical modeling.<p>

Conservative tracers (salt or tritiated water) were injected upstream at known concentrations, and the concentrations were measured at downstream locations.  A partial differential equation model was used to describe the advection and dispersion of the solute along the stream as well as the exchange between the flowing water zone and the transient storage zone through turbulent diffusion.  A new solution technique was developed that is both more efficient and easier to interpret than previous methods of solution.  A new technique was also developed for determining the parameters of nutrient transfer and dispersion.<p>

These methods will make it possible to compare these important characteristics in a variety of streams.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Knoxville College, Knoxville, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="37"><h1>37</h1></a>

<h2>Seasonal Changes in Hydraulic Features Affect the Transport of Dissolved Compounds in Streams</h2>

<dl>
<dt>E. R. Marzolf, P. J. Mulholland, and D. L. DeAngelis
</dl>

An understanding of the hydraulic conditions [e.g., transient storage zone volume (S), water velocity (V), solute dispersion (D), wetted cross-sectional area (A)] of streams is necessary for understanding the behavior of dissolved solutes in streams.  Conservative tracers were injected into a 70-m, first-order reach of Walker Branch and into 20-m laboratory streams throughout the year to examine relationships between hydraulic features and other seasonal characteristics of streams (e.g., flow, accumulation of leaves, periphyton mat development).  A solution of <sup>3</sup>H<sub>2</sub>O or NaCl was injected as a tracer, and concentrations of the tracer were then measured by liquid scintillation detection or by electrical conductivity determinations.<p>

Hydraulic features such as the transient storage zone volume [i.e., the portion of water within reach residing in areas of low velocity (e.g., backwaters, sediments)] were estimated from a stream transient storage zone model through use of an automated, nonlinear optimization method.<p>

In Walker Branch, the strong linear relationship between V<sup>2</sup> and D and the analysis of Reynolds numbers suggest that during low-flow periods the flow is partially laminar.  The change from laminar to turbulent flow occurs at about 10 L/s and appears to be reflected in greater rates of water movement between the free-flowing and stationary storage zones, as indicated by increased piston velocities between the two zones.  In autumn, leaf inputs reduced V and increased A; this change increased solute exposure to microbe-colonized leaf surfaces and resulted in the highest rates of nutrient uptake within the reach during the year.  In laboratory streams, S increased as algal biomass increased; this facilitated solute retention under conditions of high nutrient demand by the periphyton mat.  Further understanding of the hydraulic features in streams will be useful in analyzing the transport of other solutes, such as contaminants, within streams.<p>

<a name="38"><h1>38</h1></a>

<h2>Laboratory Stream Studies Demonstrate Important Links Between Upstream and Downstream Nutrient-Cycling Processes</h2>

<dl>
<dt>P. J. Mulholland, E. R. Marzolf, S. P. Hendricks, and R. V. Wilkerson
</dl>

Streams are long, narrow ecosystems with strong advective transport processes resulting from water flow.  Stream organisms both alter and respond to the quantity and chemical form of materials transported in water.  As a result, biological processes occurring in upstream areas can have strong effects on organisms downstream.  However, the effects are sometimes difficult to observe in the field because of longitudinal variability in groundwater inflow and local environ-mental conditions.<p>

Using a network of longitudinally linked laboratory streams housed in <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a>, scientists sought to determine whether changes in biomass, metabolism, and nutrient cycling occurred from upstream to downstream over 88 m under constant environmental conditions.  The studies indicated that stream algae became more nutrient deficient as a result of a net depletion of nutrients in the water from upstream to downstream.  Scientists observed both increases in several measures of nutrient cycling and a shift in the dominant species from diatoms to blue-green algae from upstream to downstream.<p>

In contrast, measurements of biomass, production, and respiration indicated few consistent upstream-downstream changes.  Increases in nutrient cycling and changes in algal species composition apparently compensated for lower nutrient concentrations in stream water; this precluded large upstream-downstream changes in biomass and metabolism.<p>

The study results indicate that stream algal communities can be longitudinally linked through nutrient cycling and transport processes, particularly in nutrient-poor streams.  Nutrient cycling and algal species composition were more sensitive indicators of upstream-downstream changes than were the coarser measures of biomass and metabolism.  Because stream ecosystems are longitudinal linked, evaluations of disturbance effects in streams must include local effects as well as the effects that the disruption of processes upstream have on downstream communities.<p>

<a name="39"><h1>39</h1></a>

<h2>ESD Develops Information to Support Water Resource Strategic Planning</h2>

<dl>
<dt>A. W. Renshaw, R. S. Turner, and D. S. Shriner
</dl>

Prudent management of water resources can facilitate worldwide sustainable energy and economic development.  <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> has the scientific, technical, and socioeconomic expertise to make major contributions in the water resources conservation/development area.<p>

A dynamic strategic planning effort began in the fall of 1992, and a draft plan was developed outlining the means of using ORNL's unique capabilities to address water resource problems of national significance.  We produced several additional documents to support ORNL staff in achieving strategic goals in many areas.  The brochure Water Resources Activities and Goals provides more detailed support information for the strategic planning effort as well as information for other organizations that ORNL may be working for and with.  The brochure lists selected publications related to water resources that have been published by ORNL staff.<p>

Two other documents are primarily for internal use:  (1) a directory of organizations listing federal, state, academic, and private organizations that also have an interest in water resources and (2) a brochure that briefly describes ongoing projects that our research staff are currently undertaking and identifies the principal investigators and sources of funding.  These documents consolidate information into single sources for dissemination to <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff and other organizations.<p>

<a name="40"><h1>40</h1></a>

<h2>ORNL Provides Support for the National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program</h2>

<dl>
<dt>A. W. Renshaw, R. S. Turner, and D. S. Shriner
</dl>

<a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> is working with the <a href="http://www.lumina.com/taflist/">National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program</a> (NAPAP) Office in preparing an operating plan and an assessment plan.  NAPAP is required to prepare periodic assessments to comply with the Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAAs) of 1990.<p>

To gather information germane to segments of the operating plan, two workshops were held in November 1993:  an Acidic Deposition Workshop in Easton, Maryland, and an Assessment Workshop in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.  A Visibility Workshop has also been scheduled for 1994 in Washington, D.C.<p>

NAPAP's Interagency Committee members are evaluating alternative means to assess acidic deposition control effectiveness.  Alternatives include integrated assessment models and other less-integrated approaches in which specific aspects of monitoring, assessing, and reducing acidic deposition are left with separate federal departments and agencies.<p>

The value of an integrated assessment model is that it addresses the problem of how one element in human and natural systems qualitatively and quantitatively affects the others.  A major concern with this approach is that significant development will be needed to get a scientifically credible and policy-relevant model ready for use.  NAPAP's first report to Congress on compliance with the CAAAs of 1990 is due in 1994; the first periodic assessment, in 1996.<p>

<a name="41"><h1>41</h1></a>

<h2>Relationships Between Columbia River Flows and Juvenile Salmon Survival Are Examined</h2>

<dl>
<dt>G. F. Cada, M. D. Deacon (1), S. V. Mitz (1), and M. S. Bevelhimer (2)
</dl>

One of the most difficult issues facing the Northwest Power Planning Council (NPPC) in its attempts to restore salmon and steelhead to the Columbia River Basin is the question of the amount of stream flow needed to transport juvenile salmon safely downstream to the ocean through a series of dams and reservoirs.  Compared with preimpoundment conditions, lower river flows and decreased water velocities are believed to increase juvenile salmonid travel times to the ocean and to potentially reduce survival.<p>

Because of continuing disagreement about the quantities of flow releases needed to increase smolt survival, the NPPC called for an independent review of literature relating to the influence of water velocity on the survival of juvenile salmon and steelhead from within and outside the Columbia River Basin.  Most of the studies reviewed found a positive relationship between outmigration flows and survival, but substantial uncertainty remains about many of the estimates.  Early survival estimates made in the basin did not quantify variance, and they contain biases, errors, or evidence of interactions with factors other than water velocity.  Other influential factors that were examined in the review include predation, water quality, and the physiological state of the smolts at the time of migration.  Our review concluded that despite the limitations of existing data, it remains a reasonable assumption that increasing survival corresponds positively to increasing flow in the Columbia River Basin.<p>

The NPPC will use the report and other input to develop a working hypothesis regarding the flow/survival issue that (1) can provide a basis for inclusion of measures in the NPPC's Fish and Wildlife Program and (2) will be the subject of future research and adaptive management efforts.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Science Applications International Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="42"><h1>42</h1></a>

<h2>Benefits of Fish Passage and Protection Measures Are Examined at 16 Hydroelectric Projects</h2>

<dl>
<dt>G. F. Cada, J. E. Francfort (1), D. W. Jones, D. D. Dauble (2), R. T. Hunt (3), and R. J. Costello (4)
</dl>

As part of its mission to promote environmentally sound hydroelectric development, DOE's Hydropower Program supported a study of the benefits and costs of measures used to enhance upstream and downstream fish passage at dams; operational monitoring data from 16 case study projects across the United States were examined.  Measures used to mitigate fish passage impacts included fish ladders and elevators and a variety of intake screens.  In seven projects, the passage rates or survival of anadromous fish was successfully increased.  Only one of the installations appears to have failed to enhance fish populations, but in the case of other study projects, the benefits are unclear.  In six projects, only limited performance monitoring has been completed.  Adverse environmental conditions or changing management goals have prevented an assessment of benefits at two other projects.<p>

Costs of the mitigative measures ranged from 0.004 to 1.06 cents/kWh.  Benefits of the mitigative measures for most case study projects could be expressed only in terms of the numbers of individual fish that were transported around the dam or protected from turbines; fish population-level effects or economic values were rarely known.  The study identified the need for clearly defined mitigation goals, more extensive quantitative monitoring of the measures' effects on both target and nontarget species, and the development of techniques to express benefits as well as costs in economic terms.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Idaho National Engineering Laboratory, Idaho Falls, Idaho.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Battelle Pacific Northwest Laboratory, Richland, Washington.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>Richard Hunt Associates, Inc., Annapolis, Maryland.</i>
<dt>(4)  <i>Northwest Water Resources Advisory Services, Seattle.</i>
</dl>

<a name="43"><h1>43</h1></a>

<h2>Chinook Salmon Response to Flow Regulation Is Simulated for the Tuolumne River</h2>

<dl>
<dt>H. I. Jager, M. J. Sale, M. S. Bevelhimer (1), C. C. Coutant, and H. E. Cardwell (2)
</dl>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> scientists used a population model to predict the response of fall-run chinook salmon to alternative minimum flow requirements for the New Don Pedro Project, a large multiple-use reservoir on the Tuolumne River in California.  The flow schedules that produced the highest numbers of model outmigrants were characterized by relatively high spring flows during outmigration and relatively low winter flows.  High spring flows mitigate against high water temperatures in spring.<p>

The first round of model validation conducted included comparison of model results with seining data and sensitivity analysis.  The comparison suggested that chinook development, growth, and survival rates are predicted well but that a substantial late-fall run must exist to explain why large numbers of fry emerge in spring.  The sensitivity analysis showed the final date of upmigration to be a sensitive parameter, but later dates were associated with lower numbers of outmigrants.<p>

To address this issue and to improve model predictions, we have added a late-fall run of chinook.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="44"><h1>44</h1></a>

<h2>Mitigation Actions Are Recommended to Protect Chinook Salmon on the Lower Mokelumne River, California</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. J. Sale, C. C. Coutant, R. D. Perlack (1), W. P. Staub (1), M. S. Bevelhimer (2), B. M. Vogt (1), J. W. Webb, I. M. Smith (3) and H. E. Cardwell (3)
</dl>

A Final Environmental Impact Statement was completed by <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> staff in which modifications to the operation of the Lower Mokelumne River Project are recommended.  This existing hydroelectric project is a multipurpose, multireservoir system licensed to the East Bay Municipal Utilities District (EBMUD) and supplies municipal water to Oakland and the East Bay area of California.<p>

Chinook salmon and steelhead trout in the lower Mokelumne River have experienced recent population declines and mortality associated, in part, with discharges from Camanche Dam.  Other stresses in the river, such as irrigation diversions and acid mine drainage, have also affected these important fishery resources.  The <a href="http://darkstar.delta.dfg.ca.gov/">California Department of Fish and Game</a> and the California Sportfishing Protection Alliance have asked the <a href="http://www.fedworld.gov/ferc/">Federal Energy Regulatory Commission</a> to investigate and correct fishery impacts in the river.  Subsequently, a wide range of potential mitigation actions were identified as part of this assessment.<p>

All appropriate alternatives were evaluated in terms of (1) the benefits that would be accrued to anadromous fishery resources in the lower Mokelumne River and (2) the costs each action would impose on EBMUD's water supply system.  Final recommendations include new minimum flow and minimum pool elevation requirements at Camanche Reservoir, ramping rates on dam releases, interim attraction and out-migrant pulse flows, instream habitat improvements, and a series of studies, along with monitoring, to determine feasible means for solving off-site fish passage problems.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Energy Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Automated Sciences Group, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="45"><h1>45</h1></a>

<h2>New Soil-Remediation Technology Is Evaluated for Ecological Risk</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. A. Gunderson, E. A. Childs (1), M. H. Gibbs (2), J. M. Kostuk (3), G. E. Napolitano (2), J. E. Richmond, L. F. Wicker, and A. J. Stewart
</dl>

Technological advances in hazardous chemical removal from soils have begun to produce cost-effective methods, but the ecological effects of these treatments have seldom been addressed.  For example, on-site composting is a cost-effective method to reduce concentrations of 2, 4, 6-trinitrotoluene and other explosives that contaminate many soils at <a href="http://www.army.mil/">U.S. Army</a> and <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> munitions installations, but the effects of the residual contamination on terrestrial organisms were not known.<p>

Researchers developed a replicated greenhouse-scale test system to evaluate a suite of responses across taxonomic groups and levels of organization.  The responses of two soil invertebrates, three crops, and the existing soil microorganisms were chosen to form a chain of evidence predictive of effects at higher levels.<p>

During the 6-month study, researchers compared biological responses in two compost types:  an uncontaminated reference and the final product from a U.S. Army composting study.  The study examined long-term effects on plant growth and physiology, including photosynthesis, root nodulation, and symbiotic N<sub>2</sub>-fixation in soybeans; invertebrate growth, reproduction, and population dynamics; and microbial processes, including soil lipid classes associated with microbial and microinvertebrate physiological status.<p>

Compost prepared from the contaminated soil inhibited several aspects of plant performance, but few adverse effects on soil invertebrates were detected.  In fact, reproduction was initially much higher in the contaminated soil compost than it was in the reference compost.  This indicated that compost differences are not associated with contamination and highlighted a difficulty inherent in the assessment of hazardous waste sites: finding an appropriate reference soil to estimate ecological risk.<p>

Nevertheless, these results, including those from complementary short-term tests, suggest some nonlethal adverse effects from the contaminated-soil compost, primarily on plants.  Judicious application of this methodology can provide information on ecological effects by explicitly including measurements at several levels of ecological organization.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Roane State Community College, Harriman, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>University of Wisconsin, Stevens Point.</i>
</dl>

<a name="46"><h1>46</h1></a>

<h2>Interactive Effects of Ambient Ozone and Climate Are Measured on the Basis of Stem Growth of Mature Forest Trees</h2>

<dl>
<dt>S. B. McLaughlin and D. J. Downing (1)
</dl>

Historically, quantifying the effects of air pollution on forest productivity and function was hampered by difficulties in measuring the direct growth responses of mature forest trees to ambient levels of pollutants.  Now, however, serial measurements of seasonal variations in the stem expansion rate have been made with a sensitive dendrometer system to estimate the effects of ozone and climate variables on the growth of large trees in an undisturbed forest environment.<p>

Measurements of changes in the stem circumference of 28 mature loblolly pine (<i>Pinus taeda</i> L.) trees were made at 138 intervals during a 5-year study conducted on the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/facilities/nerp.html/">Oak Ridge National Environmental Research Park</a>.  Significant differences in stand stocking and soil fertility were also included in the study design.<p>

Large interannual and intraannual variations in physical climate and ozone were encountered over the study interval.  Regression techniques detected the effects of ozone as high-frequency departures from seasonal growth trends.  In addition, cumulative ozone exposure significantly influenced year-to-year variations in growth trends on an annual scale.  Ambient ozone significantly reduced the stem expansion of mature trees, and effects varied widely among individual trees and years.  The rapidity of stem responses to ozone indicated that ozone exposure reduced whole-tree control of water loss.  High temperatures and low levels of soil moisture amplified the effects; this amplification suggests that future climate changes that increase moisture stress will enhance the impacts of ozone on forests.  Moreover, ozone-induced changes in whole-tree-water status suggest that tropospheric ozone may modify the gas exhange between the canopy and the atmosphere.<p>

Mechanistic studies are needed to define the physiological processes and potential significance of such changes.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Engineering Physics and Mathematics Division, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<a name="47"><h1>47</h1></a>

<h2>New Chamber Design Permits Control of Temperature in Global Change Studies</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. J. Norby, N. T. Edwards, J. Riggs, and C. H. Abner
</dl>

The ability to predict how global climate changes will affect the distribution and productivity of forests is limited by the paucity of data on how the stresses associated with climate change might be alleviated or compensated for in a CO<sub>2</sub>-enriched atmosphere.<p>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> scientists developed and tested a system for temperature control in open-top CO<sub>2</sub>-exposure chambers, as part of an effort to measure the interactive effects of CO<sub>2</sub> and climate variables on the competitive relationships and critical ecosystem processes of tree species under field conditions.  The system design is based on evaporative coolers that replace the blower boxes of standard open-top chambers.  A feedback control system regulates the heating and cooling of the airstream entering the chambers to maintain the temperature within the chambers at ambient levels or at ambient levels plus 4&#176;C regardless of weather conditions.  Several performance criteria were set:  reproducibility, reliability, and consistent attainment of ambient- and increased-temperature regimes without secondary confounding effects.<p>

All of the performance criteria were met in a prototype system, and the experimental system has now been expanded to a fully replicated design in which sugar maple seedlings are being grown under ambient or increased temperatures combined with ambient or increased concentrations of CO<sub>2</sub> .  The project has been accepted as part of the Global Change in Terrestrial Ecosystems Core Project of the <a href="http://www.igbp.kva.se/">International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme</a>.<p>

<a name="48"><h1>48</h1></a>

<h2>Workshop Identifies High-Priority Research Areas Related to Belowground Responses to Increased Atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub></h2>

<dl>
<dt>E. G. O'Neill, P. S. Curtis (1), and J. A. Teeri (2)
</dl>

Many studies of the effects of increasing atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> levels point to soil systems as critical sources or sinks in global carbon cycling and as primary determinants of ecosystem response to climate change.  A workshop was organized (1) to assess the current level of understanding of belowground responses to increased atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> and to identify key areas where fundamental knowledge is lacking, (2) to evaluate existing and proposed methods for investigating belowground responses, and (3) to identify high-priority research topics to improve our understanding of belowground responses to increased CO<sub>2</sub> and the consequences for entire ecosystems.  The workshop--jointly organized by researchers from <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a>, Ohio State University, and the University of Michigan Biological Station (UMBS)--was held May 30-June 2, 1993, at UMBS in Pellston, Michigan.<p>

Workshop participants identified carbon flux dynamics as the most important research priority, beginning with a reasonable estimate of carbon input through increased root turnover and exudation and including an assessment of carbon allocation to short- vs long-lived soil carbon pools.  Other high-priority research areas are (1) CO<sub>2</sub> enrichment effects on plant symbionts and pathogens, including feedbacks to community and ecosystem processes; (2) rates of microbially mediated soil nutrient transformations and the potential for long-term changes in nutrient availability; and (3) interactions of increased atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> with other environmental variables, such as changes in amount or temporal patterns of water availability and potential temperature increases.<p>

The workshop will help provide structure and direction for the next decade's research into the effects that elevated CO<sub>2</sub>  and climate change have on belowground systems.  The critical nature of global change issues and the limited amount of research funds make the outcome of the synthesis and planning workshop important to researchers, funding agencies, and policy makers.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Ohio State University, Columbus.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>University of Michigan Biological Station, Pellston.</i>
</dl>

<a name="49"><h1>49</h1></a>

<h2>Physiological Studies Support the Development of Switchgrass as Herbaceous Energy Crop</h2>

<dl>
<dt>S. D. Wullschleger
</dl>

Widely recognized as an important perennial component of the tall-grass prairie and as a productive, warm-season forage, switchgrass (<i>Panicum virgatum</i> L.) has been selected by DOE's <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a> as a promising cellulosic energy crop from which a renewable source of transportation fuel and biomass-generated electricity could be derived.  Little information is available, however, on this crop, and quantification is needed on the extent of genetic diversity that exists within readily available germ plasm for traits associated with superior plant productivity.  Such information would be useful in future crop management and breeding activities.<p>

A series of multisite field studies (in Texas, Tennessee, and Virginia) have been conducted to assess whether rates of photosynthesis differed among switchgrass varieties.  Early in the season, photosynthetic rates were consistently 10 to 15&#37; higher for the lowland varieties (e.g., Alamo, Kanlow) than they were for the upland varieties (e.g., Blackwell, Cave-in-Rock, Shelter).  Later in the growing season, photosynthetic rates of upland varieties surpassed those of the lowland varieties.  This transition coincided with a severe midseason drought, during which photosynthesis declined equally in all varieties.<p>

Whether this reversal reflects a greater capacity of some varieties to recover from drought (possibly because of osmotic adjustment or shifts in carbon allocation during stress), favoring increased rooting and water uptake poststress, is not known.  Answers to these and other questions will come only as researchers learn more about the physiological and morphological traits that contribute to high yield and/or yield stability for this perennial forage and biofuels crop.<p>

<a name="50"><h1>50</h1></a>

<h2>Threatened and Endangered Animal Species on ORR Are Surveyed</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. A. Gabrielsen
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) provides habitats suitable for federally listed and state-listed threatened and endangered animal species.  To maintain compliance with the Federal Endangered Species Act, current information on the animals' status within ORR is necessary.<p>

A substantial amount of existing animal survey data reveals that nearly 50 listed species are permanent, potential, or transitory residents of ORR.  However, many of the field surveys locating threatened and endangered animal species on ORR were conducted before 1980.  Many changes have occurred at ORR, and habitats have been substantially altered; therefore, the lists need to be updated.<p>

Data necessary for compliance with federal and state regulations regarding the threatened and endangered animals on ORR must be collected.  In response to this need, the Environmental Restoration Remote Sensing and Special Surveys Program has initiated a Threatened and Endangered Animal Species Survey Project.  A 2-year work plan outlining a study, including field surveys, has been developed.  <a href="http://www.fws.gov/fwshomep.html/">Fish and Wildlife Services</a> has reviewed the plan, and <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> has approved it.  Land-use decisions made without current information could destroy necessary habitats and result in the inadvertent extirpation of a federally listed or state-listed animal species.  Habitat information collected during this study will facilitate the making of informed decisions regarding land use.<p>

<a name="51"><h1>51</h1></a>

<h2>ORR Resource Management Organization Is Restructured</h2>

<dl>
<dt>P. D. Parr
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) Resource Management Organization (RMO), established in 1982, was restructured and chartered to reflect changes in authority, management, and mission.  The mission is to oversee and coordinate management of ORR resources, including land, buildings, structures, and infrastructure; wetlands; floodplains; rare or endangered plants and animals and their habitats; archaeological, cultural, and historical sites; forest; fish; wildlife; air; soils; geologic features; surface and subsurface water; and research areas.  Defined roles are (1) to assist and advise <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">Energy Systems</a> and <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> Oak Ridge Operations (DOE-ORO) management in planning for the effective use and development of resources on ORR, as well as conservation, protection, and responsible stewardship; (2) to review documents and proposals pertaining to ORR resources and land to ensure their completeness, accuracy, and compliance compatibility with Energy Systems and DOE objectives; and (3) to assist DOE-ORO and Energy Systems management, as requested, in assessing and coordinating proposed actions and land use by other DOE contractors, federal agencies, state and local governments, and the private sector when such actions and land use could potentially impact ORR resources.<p>

The RMO consists of the RMO Council and the RMO Committee.  The committee is divided into three working groups--administrative, natural, and functional--and consists of experts representing various ORR resources.  Procedures describing the process that must be followed to obtain RMO approval for any changes in land or facility use or activities that impact ORR resources are now in the <i>Property Procedures Manual</i>.<p>

<a name="52"><h1>52</h1></a>

<h2>Population Model Helps in Study of Habitat Selection by Smallmouth Bass</h2>

<dl>
<dt>H. I. Jager, M. J. Sabo (1), D. J. Orth (1), and W. Van Winkle
</dl>

Three factors believed to influence habitat selection by smallmouth bass in streams are (1) profitability, in terms of foraging success; (2) energetic costs, particularly when maintaining position in fast currents; and (3) predation risk.  Scientists used a population model that assumes that fish optimize the ratio of growth to predation risk by leaving locations that have a lower-than-expected ratio.<p>

Model simulations of juvenile smallmouth bass in a reach of the North Anna River, Virginia, predicted fish preferences for depths and velocities with and without spatial heterogeneity in each of the three factors listed.  Model results were compared with observations of habitat preferences in the field and video observations of profitability (i.e., number of bites) and energetic cost (i.e., number of tail beats).  The field observations suggested that profitability was more important than energetic cost in determining habitat choice for this life stage, but they did not address the importance of predation risk.<p>

None of the model scenarios produced habitat preferences identical with those observed in the field, but three of the scenarios came closest:  (1) spatial heterogeneity in prey only, (2) spatial heterogeneity in energetic costs only, and (3) all three factors together.  Another interesting model result highlighted the importance of prey refuges.  Twice as many survivors were noted in simulations with spatial heterogeneity in predation risk, even though the average risk was the same in both cases.  At the population level, the researchers hope to clarify the role that regulated stream flow and fish density play in strategy choice.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University, Blacksburg.</i>
</dl>

<a name="53"><h1>53</h1></a>

<h2>Individual-Based Model Sheds Light on Behavioral Strategies of Trout</h2>

<dl>
<dt>H. I. Jager, W. Van Winkle, and B. D. Holcomb (1)
</dl>

Two behavioral strategies have been observed in trout studies in streams:  &quot;movers&quot; forage on benthic prey near the bottom of the stream and do not defend a foraging station; &quot;stayers&quot; tend to be larger in size, defend a foraging station, and spend more time foraging on drifting prey.  Our individual-based and spatially explicit model of a sympatric trout population will allow us to study these strategies.  The foraging submodule identifies a velocity threshold above which drift foraging is more profitable than foraging on benthic prey.  The simulated choice of foraging strategy can influence the energetic costs incurred by the model trout--ts foraging success, growth, predation risk, movement history, and patterns in habitat use.<p>

By keeping track of the simulated foraging behavior and habitat selection of individual model trout, researchers can predict whether individual fish continue to use one strategy for a significant length of time, and the consequences of strategy choice on survival and long-term reproductive success can be evaluated.  At the population level, researchers hope to clarify the role of regulated stream flow and fish density in strategy choice.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Electric Power Research Institute, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="54"><h1>54</h1></a>

<h2>Increases in Global Temperature Affect the Release of Nitrate in Southern Appalachian Spruce-Fir Ecosystems</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. D. Joslin (1),  M. H. Wolfe (1), C. T. Garten, and S. B. McLaughlin
</dl>

The possibility of accelerated decomposition of organic matter and accompanying nitrate releases in nitrogen-saturated ecosystems is a concern raised in response to predictions of global temperature increases from CO<sub>2</sub> emissions.  Possible effects of excess nitrate production on ecosystems include elevated concentrations of soil solution aluminum, increased leaching of base cations from soil, elevated levels of aluminum and nitrate in streams, and species shifts in plant communities.<p>

In a recent uncontrolled pilot study on a nitrogen-saturated spruce-fir forest in Southern Appalachia, researchers compared the soil solution on the sun side of a clearing with that on the shaded side.  Significantly greater nitrate leaching accompanied the higher soil temperature (&#43;2&#176;C).<p>

Researchers are examining the effects of temperature increases on nitrogen-saturated forests in a controlled field experiment using a previously tested passive solar &quot;mini-greenhouse&quot; to elevate soil temperature &#126;2&#176;C (simulating postulated global warming). The potential impacts of changes in tree nutrition, stand biogeochemical cycling, and streamwater chemistry will be evaluated.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Tennessee Valley Authority, Knoxville.</i>
</dl>

<a name="55"><h1>55</h1></a>

<h2>Genetic Diversity Among Aspen Populations Increases as a Result of Seedling Regeneration After the 1988 Fires in Yellowstone National Park</h2>

<dl>
<dt>G. A. Tuskan and M. G. Turner
</dl>

Aspen (<i>Populus tremuloides</i> Michx.) in the Intermountain West region of North America typically regenerates stands through root sprouting and clonal propagation.  A single mature stand of aspen can occupy several hectares through this process.  Before the fires of 1988 in <a href="http://www.forestry.umt.edu/yellowstone/">Yellowstone National Park</a> (YNP), aspen occurred in the park solely in mature, vegetatively propagated stands.  After the 1988 fires, aspen seedlings were recorded for the first time in the park's 116-year history.  This unique event provided an opportunity to study the effects of catastrophic environmental change on a species' genetic diversity.<p>

The objectives of this project were to quantify the amount of genetic diversity within and among mature aspen populations in YNP and to determine whether aspen seedlings seen growing after the fires were direct progeny of the mature stands that existed before the fires.  To accomplish these objectives, a polymerase chain reaction-based, randomly amplified polymorphic DNA (RAPD) procedure was used to derive estimates of genetic diversity.  These genetic markers indicated that seedlings within geographic areas were more similar to each other than to neighboring seedling stands; that mature stands clustered as discrete clades, separate from the seedling clusters; and that there was no relationship between the geographic origin of mature stands and the genetic diversity among these stands.  The RAPD markers also revealed that the mature stands were clonal in nature yet contained as many as ten and as few as three separate genotypes, suggesting that the mature stands had existed in YNP for a time long enough to accumulate numerous somatic mutations before the fires.<p>

In addition, genetic diversity was substantially increased as a result of seedling regeneration after the fires.  The processes that (1) eliminate genetic variability in newly regenerated seedling populations, leading to clonally propagated mature stands, and (2) allow the accumulation of genetic variants within these mature stands have not yet been described.<p>

Understanding these processes has implications for predicting a species' ability to respond to global climate changes.<p>
  

