<TITLE>Environmental Analyses</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Analyses</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Analyses Section of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) focuses on interdisciplinary analysis and assessment of environmental problems.  In this context, the section develops problem-solving tools, such as methodologies, databases, and information and policy analyses.  The section deals with environmental issues that range from those at individual sites and regional landscapes to those of national and global concern.  The staff provide a variety of sponsors technical assistance for the development of environmental management and regulatory policies.  Technical information and analyses produced by the section also serve in a broader capacity--as a resource for the scientific and technical communities.  Section sponsors include the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) Assistant Secretary for <a href="http://nattie.eh.doe.gov/">Environment, Safety, and Health</a>; the DOE Assistant Secretary for Environmental Restoration and Waste Management; the DOE <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/research-org/1995.html#td/">Office of Health and Environmental Research</a>; the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA); the <a href="http://www.af.mil/">U.S. Air Force</a>; the <a href="http://www.noaa.gov/">National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration</a>; the Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc., <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a>; and the <a href="http://www.bpa.gov/">Bonneville Power Administration</a>.<p>

<h2>Environmental Assessment</h2>

The goal of the Environmental Assessment Group is to apply state-of-the-art assessment tools to complex issues at individual facilities and at sites that are large geographically and to issues that are programmatic in scope.  The group prepares impact analyses for <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, the <a href="http://www.fedworld.gov/ferc/">Federal Energy Regulatory Commission</a>, the <a href="http://www.nrc.gov/">Nuclear Regulatory Commission</a>, and the <a href="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html">U.S. Department of Defense</a> as part of agency compliance with the <a href="http://www.eh.doe.gov/nepa/">National Environmental Policy Act</a> (NEPA).  Impacts on terrestrial and aquatic ecological resources, on land and water use, and on water quality are assessed for environmental impact statements (EISs) and related documents.  Staff members provide technical reviews and analyses of NEPA documents for the DOE Office of NEPA Oversight, as well as technical support for the EPA Office of Federal Activities.  As members of audit teams, staff in the group also help assess NEPA compliance at DOE facilities.  In addition, the group provides NEPA training for DOE managers.<p>

During FY 1994, the group participated in the preparation of nine EISs and ten environmental assessments, as well as contributed to the preparation of other materials, such as biological surveys, ecological risk assessments, and environmental reports for use in preparing NEPA documents.  Staff provided comments on a monthly average of four to five documents covering a wide range of issue areas, including floodplains and wetlands, transportation, historic and archaeological sites, socioeconomics, accident potentials, water and air quality, human health, impacts on ecological resources, and radiological impacts.  Major intensive review activities were conducted for the spent nuclear fuel-Idaho National Engineering Laboratory EIS, a series of NEPA documents for the <a href="http://www.srs.gov/">Savannah River Site</a>, a series of NEPA documents for the Formerly Utilized Sites Remedial Action Program, and the Foreign Research Reactor EIS.<p>

<h2>Environmental Compliance</h2>

The Environmental Compliance Group provides information resources and regulatory expertise to assist various sponsors in their efforts to comply with federal and state environmental laws and regulations.  The group tracks, monitors, and reports new environmental legal and regulatory initiatives; provides up-to-date reference materials on all major federal environmental laws; and uses scientific, engineering, legal, and regulatory expertise to analyze regulatory issues, develop environmental compliance methodologies, and assist the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> Office of Environmental Guidance in creating and implementing environmental policy and guidance.  Other important activities include developing and conducting courses on environmental laws and regulations for DOE, <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">Energy Systems</a>, and other sponsors.  Staff also conduct environmental compliance audits at <a href="http://www.af.mil/">U.S. Air Force</a> bases and other federal facilities.  In addition, the Environmental Compliance Group serves as a resource for regulatory technical assistance to <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> and the Energy Systems <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a>.<p>

In FY 1994, the group developed numerous guidance documents on subjects that included the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a>'s off-site rule under the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act (CERCLA); continuous releases of CERCLA hazardous substances; and DOE's responsibilities under the National Historic Preservation Act.  Staff developed and presented new training workshops, including a 2-day overview of the <a href="http://earth1.epa.gov/OSWRCRA/">Resource Conservation and Recovery Act</a> and a 1-day introductory course on defining hazardous waste.  The group also provided newsletters, reference books, and regulatory tracking services for DOE and contractor staff across the nation.  Environmental Compliance Group staff conducted numerous environmental compliance assessments for the Air Combat Command (ACC) of the U.S. Air Force, and they prepared for and presented to ACC personnel a 5-day course on hazardous waste management, the most in-depth training ever developed by the group.  In addition, group staff prepared Environmental Compliance Assessment System manuals for the <a href="http://www.army.mil/">U.S. Army</a>, Europe, to use in evaluating compliance at its European bases in Germany, The Netherlands, Italy, and other countries.<p>

<h2>Environmental Risk</h2>

The Environmental Risk Group devises methods for the quantitative assessment of environmental risks; applies these methods to local-, regional-, and national-scale environmental problems; and provides regulatory agencies with guidance on the uses of environmental risk assessment.  The group defines and measures the health of ecological resources, extrapolates test data from laboratory to field and from individuals to populations and ecosystems, quantifies ecological risks at the watershed and landscape levels, and predicts the movement of contaminants through food chains.  Sponsors include <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">EPA</a>, <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">Energy Systems</a> <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a>, the <a href="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html">U.S. Department of Defense</a>, and the <a href="http://www.bpa.gov/">Bonneville Power Administration</a>.<p>

In FY 1994, members of the Environmental Risk Group developed a monitoring and assessment program for the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) to evaluate impacts that DOE facility operations have on wide-ranging species.  In addition, the group revised and updated an approach and strategy for assessing ecological risks on ORR.  Staff also revised and updated toxicological benchmarks for wildlife, aquatic biota, sediment-associated biota, plants, and soil invertebrates and heterotrophic processes, as well as developed a database to facilitate use of the benchmarks.  The group completed baseline ecological risk assessments for two operable units on ORR; for the Portsmouth, Ohio, facility; and for the Paducah, Kentucky, facility.<p>

<h2>Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems</h2>

The Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems Group provides the information, data, and analytical capabilities essential to performing comprehensive, resource-intensive regional and global evaluations of increases in radiatively active trace gases (also called greenhouse gases) in the atmosphere and the potential effects of such changes on environmental and societal resources.  The group employs state-of-the-art information, data management, and analytical techniques to ensure proper exchange of information and data between researchers and a diverse user community of scientists, policymakers, educators, students, and corporate officials.  To achieve the careful balance of information and data support needed to meet project requirements, the group relies on information theory, computer science, geographic information systems, library science, telecommunications, scientific visualization, statistical science, and data management.<p>

The group produces journal articles, newsletters, brochures, <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> and <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> reports, and fully documented numeric data packages and computer model packages.  The largest function of the group is to operate the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC), in support of the <a href="http://www.er.doe.gov/production/oher/GC/ESD_gc.html/">DOE Global Change Research Program</a>, and the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/cdiac/">World Data CenterA for Atmospheric Trace Gases</a>, which is part of the <a href="http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/wdc/wdcmain.html/">World Data Center System</a> coordinated by the International Council of Scientific Unions.  The Global Trace Gas and Climate Information Systems Group also analyzes the potential effects that changes in climate and sea level would have on environmental and societal resources.<p>

During FY 1994, the group staff, in their role as operators of CDIAC, published four numeric data packages covering (1) long-term climate data from the former U.S.S.R., (2) oceanic carbon chemistry, (3) carbon emissions from land-use change, and (4) data for assessing the vulnerability of the U.S. Gulf Coast to sea-level rise.  Among the many reports and other documents published, the most important were <i>Trends '93:  A Compendium of Data on Global Change and Direct Effects of Atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> Enrichment on Plants and Ecosystems:  An Updated Bibliographic Data Base</i>.  CDIAC staff filled more than 7000 information requests from more than 2700 individuals in 67 countries and responded to approximately 1100 requests for numeric data packages and computer model packages.<p>

<hr>
<a name="tech"><h1>Technical Summaries</h1></a>
<hr>

<a name="56"><h1>56</h1></a>

<h2>Potential Ecological Impacts of Chlorofluorocarbon Replacement at DOE's Gaseous Diffusion Plants Are Cumulative and Global</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. A. Dickerman
</dl>

While preparing a <a href="http://www.eh.doe.gov/nepa/">National Environmental Policy Act</a> (NEPA) assessment for <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>'s two gaseous diffusion plants, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> scientists assessed the cumulative impacts of coolant usage in the uranium enrichment process.  This included (1) the current coolant, chlorofluorocarbon (CFC-114), which leaked over 272,400 kg in 1992 and which potentially contributes to stratospheric ozone depletion, and (2) an interim replacement coolant, perfluorocarbon (PFC), an extremely powerful heat absorber that contributes to global warming (with four times the warming potential of the CFC-114 coolant) but one that is not an ozone-depleting chemical.  Both ozone depletion and global warming are global issues with the potential of having a cumulative impact on ecological resources.<p>

A review of the ecological literature on ozone depletion and global warming was presented in tables that identified ecosystem types, anticipated ecosystem impacts, and listed the causes of the impacts.  Potentially, the largest impacts from stratospheric ozone depletion, to which CFCs contribute, are from UV-B-induced mutagenesis and immune function suppression in mammals.  The largest potential impacts from global warming, to which PFCs contribute, involve the rate at which climatic patterns of temperature and precipitation may change (10 to perhaps 100 times faster than in the historic past) and a possible result of substantial shifts in biome distribution.<p>

The NEPA assessment showed that a proposed action alternative that minimized both CFC and PFC releases would minimize potential environmental impacts.  That alternative was an aggressive loss minimization alternative, one in which funds proposed for the interim replacement of CFC-114 activities would be used instead to reduce leakages of CFC-114 (about 4&#37; in 1992) to about 0.7&#37; per year.  This NEPA assessment considered a range of alternatives which, in this case, showed that the environmentally motivated proposed action (i.e., a mandated interim coolant replacement) was not actually the most environmentally supportive alternative.<p>

<a name="57"><h1>57</h1></a>

<h2>Environmental Impacts of PCFB Technology Are Expected to Be Smaller than Those of Conventional Technologies</h2>

<dl>
<dt>W. E. Schramm, G. K. Eddlemon, R. Miller, M. Socolof, C. C. Trettin, and B. M. Vogt (1)
</dl>

<a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>'s Clean Coal Technology Program promotes more efficient, reliable, and environmentally responsive coal use and environmental control technologies.  The program consists of cost-shared demonstration projects.  The potential environmental impacts of demonstrating one such technology, Pressurized Circulating Fluidized Bed (PCFB) combustion, were analyzed.  Alternatives assessed included (1) no project and (2) a project of equal generating capacity using conventional generating and control technology.  The proposed project would install PCFB technology in an inactive coal-fired generating facility, the Des Moines Energy Center, Pleasant Hill, Iowa.<p>

Compared with conventional combustion and control technologies, PCFB technology would likely increase combustion efficiency as well as reduce costs, emissions, and waste disposal problems.  The greater efficiency of PCFB in comparison with conventional technology is expected to reduce coal consumption per unit of electricity generated.  Compared with conventional combustion technology without controls, PCFB is expected to reduce emissions of sulfur dioxide (SO<sub>2</sub>) by 90&#37; and oxides of nitrogen (NO<sub>x</sub>) by 70&#37;.  These rates exceed reduction rates currently achievable by conventional control technologies (e.g., SO<sub>2</sub> reductions of 70 to 90&#37; for wet lime/limestone scrubbers, depending on type of coal, and NO<sub>x</sub> reductions of 45 to 60&#37; for low NO<sub>x</sub> burners).<p>

Additionally, PCFB technology would, unlike conventional control technologies, produce a dry solid waste that is easily disposable.  Analyses indicate that operational impacts of the proposed project on air quality, surface water, groundwater, and waste management would generally be smaller than those of conventional technology.  This is the case for two reasons:  (1) the combustion process yields flue gas containing fewer pollutants, and (2) increased process efficiency reduces fuel and other resource demands as well as reducing emissions and wastes.  Some impacts--including habitat loss from site redevelopment, socioeconomic effects, and project-related, airborne particulate concentrations--are similar whether PCFB or conventional technology is used.  Particulate levels are similar because both PCFB and conventional combustion technologies use a baghouse for particulate control.<p>

Assessing the impacts of proposed clean coal technologies assists DOE in making environmentally sound decisions concerning program implementation. <p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Energy Division, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<a name="58"><h1>58</h1></a>

<h2>ESD Prepares an Environmental Assessment Sourcebook for EPA</h2>

<dl>
<dt>L. L. Sigal
</dl>

To meet an increased demand by localities, states, and foreign goverments for information on the environmental assessment (EA) process, the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a>'s (EPA's) Office of Federal Activities asked <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff to prepare an EA sourcebook.  The sourcebook is organized around the major activities required for a successful EA.  These include initiation, scoping, assessment, decision making, and postdecision analysis.  In each major section, activities are discussed, and the needs, tools, issues, linkages, and key references for those activities are described.  In addition, attachments provide information that is not often readily available, particularly to those in foreign countries or those just starting EA programs.<p>

A computer software supplement to the sourcebook is also included.  Because the generic elements of the EA process are emphasized, the sourcebook could be used by any group charged with the responsibility of providing adequate environmental information to decision makers for projects and programs that may directly or indirectly impact the environment.<p>

<a name="59"><h1>59</h1></a>

<h2>ORNL Technical Review Enhances the Quality and Credibility of the DOE Spent Nuclear Fuel and Idaho National Engineering Laboratory Environmental Impact Statement</h2>

<dl>
<dt>E. D. Smith, L. L. Sigal, and G. K. Eddlemon
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> environmental impact statement (EIS) on programmatic spent nuclear fuel (SNF) management and <a href="http://www.inel.gov/">Idaho National Engineering Laboratory</a> (INEL) environmental restoration and waste management is a complex, high-profile document, prepared under exceptional time constraints in response to a court order that mandated its schedule and certain of its contents.  The EIS has two components:  (1) a programmatic EIS oncerned with the entire program of DOE management of DOE and U.S. Navy SNF and (2) a site-specific EIS concerned with a 10-year program of waste management, SNF management, and environmental restoration projects at NEL.<p>

A major purpose of the EIS is to respond to stakeholder concerns about the impacts of transporting SNF to INEL and managing it there.  DOE also had to reexamine its entire SNF management program following the 1992 phase-out of DOE SNF reprocessing and a 1993 DOE study that identified vulnerabilities in DOE's management of SNF.<p>

<a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>, in support of the DOE Office of <a href="http://www.eh.doe.gov/nepa/">NEPA</a> Oversight, conducted a comprehensive technical and National Environmental Policy Act-compliance review of the prepublication draft EIS.  To provide expertise in all relevant technical areas, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> organized a review team of more than 20 staff members drawn from 5 ORNL divisions.  Despite exceptional time constraints (in the first review cycle, reviewers had only about 3.5 working days to evaluate thousands of pages of material), ORNL reviewers contributed hundreds of comments and recommendations on technical validity of the data and analyses, major omissions and inconsistencies, significant environmental issues, organization of the EIS, and presentation of information.  Three ESD staff members participated in comment resolution meetings in which EIS preparers, DOE managers, and reviewers worked together to solve problems identified during the review.<p>

As the only comprehensive, independent technical review before publication, the ORNL review significantly enhanced the quality and credibility of the draft EIS, which was issued for public comment June 30, 1994.  The review effort demonstrated ORNL's technical depth, breadth, and familiarity with DOE sites, facilities, and programs, as well as the staff's ability to deliver high-quality work under difficult time constraints.<p>

<a name="60"><h1>60</h1></a>

<h2>Large-Scale Hybrid Poplar Plantings Provide the Opportunity to Continue Addressing Environmental Research Questions</h2>

<dl>
<dt>V. R. Tolbert
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a>'s (BFDP's) scale-up of energy crop production systems reached a major milestone in mid-June with the completed planting of the first large-scale hybrid poplar plantations on 1000 acres in Minnesota.  The plantings, which ranged in size from 25 to 160 acres, should provide answers to questions regarding the environmental effects of the large-scale commercialization of energy crops compared with results obtained from the earlier BFDP small-scale demonstration plots (5 to 20 acres).<p>

University of Minnesota scientists will conduct the environmental research conceived and sponsored by <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>'s BFDP, comparing utilization of these larger plantings by both resident and migratory bird species with utilization of forest, grassland, and row crop areas of similar size.  The results of this large-scale study will be compared with results obtained during the past 2 years from small-scale plantings.  Those studies showed that energy crop plantations can contribute to bird biodiversity by providing more diverse habitats for forest and edge species in areas that are typically dominated by row crops and by <a href="http://ngp.ngpc.state.ne.us/wildlife/">Conservation Reserve Program</a> grasslands.  Studies of small mammals will also be expanded to include these large-scale plantings to address further habitat utilization and movement patterns between energy-crop plantations and forest or grassland areas.<p>

BFDP is also sponsoring research using these large-scale plantings to address soil carbon, groundwater depletion, and the chemical fate of pesticides, herbicides, and nutrients beneath the individual plantation sites compared with that of row crops, grasslands, and forest lands of equal size.  This research is designed to determine the potential for carbon sequestering by energy crops and the effects of energy crop production on the environment.  Large-scale plantings offer a unique opportunity for BFDP to evaluate the role of scale and environmental effects in efforts to successfully commercialize energy crops.<p>

<a name="61"><h1>61</h1></a>

<h2>Programmatic Environmental Impact Statement Helps USAP Minimize Impacts, Improve Planning, and Comply with National and International Mandates</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. W. Webb
</dl>

Environmental analysts in <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> and the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/divisions/energy/energy.html/">Energy Division</a> of <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> are helping the U.S. Antarctic Program (USAP) prepare a programmatic environmental impact statement (PEIS).  The analysts have first-hand knowledge of research and support activities through visits to Antarctica in 1992-93 and through the preparation of a variety of environmental documents about the activities (e.g., using explosives, drilling, using research balloons, preparing a new ice runway, relocating existing runway facilities, building new facilities).<p>

Key questions to be addressed in the impact statement include whether (and how much) to augment financial support and scientific staff in Antarctica, how to minimize fuel use and waste and to optimize energy efficiency, whether (and how) to construct a new South Pole Station and other new facilities on the continent, whether (and how) to treat human waste at McMurdo Station, and how to protect the continent's fragile and unique environment from the impacts of program activities.<p>

Antarctic research for the United States must comply with U.S. and international environmental review requirements, such as the <a href="http://www.eh.doe.gov/nepa/">National Environmental Policy Act</a> and the <a href="http://www.nbs.ac.uk/">Antarctic Treaty</a>.  The PEIS with its supporting analyses will provide USAP decision makers with information that will help determine the direction of future research.<p>

<a name="62"><h1>62</h1></a>

<h2>Legal and Regulatory Interpretations of &quot;Adverse Ecological Effects&quot; Are Identified</h2>

<dl>
<dt>W. S. H. Ramsey, P. M. O'Connell (1), J. S. Fackenthal, C. G. Heckman, and C. F. Baes III
</dl>

In its second generation, the <a href="http://www.lumina.com/taflist/">National Acid Precipitation Assessment Program</a> (NAPAP) must pose questions about the effectiveness of current acid precipitation controls in the context of the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/oar/caa.html/">Clean Air Act</a>, as amended, and its implementing regulations.  One legislative mandate of NAPAP is to determine the reductions in acid deposition needed to prevent adverse ecological effects.  However, the phrase &quot;adverse ecological effects&quot; is not defined.<p>

A team of environmental regulatory and legal analysts reviewed federal environmental laws and regulations and case law to determine congressional, agency, and judicial views of this and similar phrases.  The phase &quot;adverse ecological effects&quot; has been variously interpreted in environmental statutes, regulations, and case law.  Although no single definition was found, legal and regulatory interpretations identify elements that are central to assessing ecological effects.  These elements include (1) the toxicological hazard potential to select organisms, (2) loss of the use value of an ecosystem-dependent resource, and (3) endangerment of a species or natural landmark of national significance.<p>

Such interpretations (e.g., natural resource damage assessment and injury determinations) also identify methods accepted in regulatory contexts for determining that an &quot;adverse ecological effect&quot; has occurred.  Knowledge of thes components and methods may be used in determining whether &quot;adverse ecological effects&quot; caused by acid precipitation have been prevented by regulatory controls on air emissions.  This legal and regulatory review supplements technical approaches to defining ecological terms by identifying interpretations accepted by Congress and agencies implementing the environmental laws.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Oak Ridge Associated Universities, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="63"><h1>63</h1></a>

<h2>Careful Attention to Environmental Issues Will Likely Result in a Higher Level of Production and Use of Biomass as Fuels in the Future</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. S. Salk and G. Marland
</dl>

The viability of future technologies will depend not only on economic, technical, and political considerations but also on the need to maintain a sustainable environment.  Thus, as part of a situation analysis, current environmental issues were reviewed to determine those most likely to have either positive or negative affects on the future use of biomass as fuel.  Those likely to have such impacts include air pollution, global climate change, quality and quantity of surface water and groundwater, soil degradation, deforestation, preservation of unique habitats, maintenance and enhancement of biodiversity, prevention of major extinctions, solid and hazardous wastes, refuse removal from land, fuel spills, and the misuse of fertilizer and pesticide.<p>

As with any energy technology, interactions between and among these factors, or interactions between them and other environmental stresses, may result in cumulative environmental effects.  The issues that prove most significant will be closely related to site-specific characteristics (e.g., soil type, water quality).  Opportunities for greater use of biomass as fuel will result from its positive effects on air quality and other environmental issues, whereas some issues, such as the potential misuse of fertilizers and pesticides (a concern for all farming operations, not just those growing biomass for fuel), may reduce the potential use of biomass.  A higher level of environmentally compatible production and use of biofuels in the future will result from careful attention to measures that either minimize potential negative impacts or maximize positive ones.<p>

<a name="64"><h1>64</h1></a>

<h2>Environmental Compliance Group Assists in Overseas Compliance</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. F. Sigmon, A. A. Aramowicz Smith, R. L. Jolley (1), M. L. Bell, J. S. Fackenthal, W. S. H. Ramsey, and M. J. Rooks (2)</h2>
</dl>

Federal agencies that have activities overseas must comply with applicable host nation requirements in addition to U.S. government requirements that might apply overseas.  Determining the applicability of requirements and evaluating compliance with them are difficult tasks.  Determining the applicability of overseas requirements depends on sponsor interpretations of applicability, sponsor priorities, and limitations on resources of U.S. entities overseas.<p>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a>'s Environmental Compliance Group (ECG) assists the <a href="http://www.army.mil/">U.S. Army</a>, Europe (USAREUR) in tackling the difficult challenge of overseas compliance by developing compliance evaluation tools for the Army's Environmental Compliance Assessment System (ECAS).  ECAS documents are assessment tools to guide personnel conducting environmental audits of USAREUR installations.  Thus, ECG assists USAREUR in ensuring that its overseas activities protect human health and the environment and that they do not violate the laws of host nations.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Chemical Technology Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Oak Ridge Research Institute, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="65"><h1>65</h1></a>

<h2>Model of Nitrogen Outputs from Forested Watersheds in the Chesapeake Bay Drainage Basin Can Be Improved</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. T. Hunsaker, C. T. Garten, and P. J. Mulholland
</dl>

The Chesapeake Bay Agreement between several states and federal agencies requires that by the year 2000, controllable phosphorus and nitrogen that enter the tidal bay be reduced by 40&#37;.  To attain this goal, the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/r3chespk/">Chesapeake Bay Program</a> needs accurate estimates of nutrient loadings, including atmospheric deposition, from various land uses.  The current form of the Chesapeake Bay Watershed Model, which uses the <a href="http://www.hydrocomp.com/HSPFinfo.html/">Hydrologic Simulation Program</a>, overestimates nitrate concentrations and outputs but performs adequately for ammonium concentrations.<p>

We reviewed the literature on forest nitrogen pools and fluxes and identified nitrogen data from research catchments in the Chesapeake Basin for model development.  Based on this information and on expert opinions elicited during a workshop, our recommendation was that a nitrogen module for forests be added to the existing Watershed Model in an effort to improve estimates of nitrogen output to the bay.  We specified the structure of the nitrogen module, possible functional forms for fluxes, and watersheds with adequate data for model parameterization.<p>

<a name="66"><h1>66</h1></a>

<h2>Ecoregions Effectively Characterize Landscape Pattern for Regional Assessments</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. T. Hunsaker, R. V. O'Neill, B. L. Jackson (1), and S. P. Timmins (2)
</dl>

The characterization of landscape patterns is important for long-term ecological monitoring and assessment because it may be an integrative indicator of ecosystem condition at the regional scale.  The premise for regionalization, regardless of the purpose, is that the characteristics of the region are more homogenous within the region than they are outside the region.<p>

The way in which we measure landscape pattern is a function of many attributes, but three are especially important--data resolution, geographic extent, and number of land cover types.  Thus, an important decision is the selection of the assessment region; options are ecologically based or politically based (i.e., aggregations of states, or counties).<p>

This study evaluates the behavior of several landscape metrics for large geographic areas in the conterminous United States.  Behavior includes distribution of values across the potential range of metrics, independence among metrics, and the ability to discriminate between landscapes on the basis of land cover data (urban, agricultural, rangeland, forest, wetland, barren land, tundra, snow or ice, and water).<p>

The aggregated ecoregions as defined by J. Omernik of the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> in Corvallis, Oregon, and the Standard Federal Regions (aggregations of states) were evaluated using Advanced Very High Resolution Radiometer imagery at 1-km2 resolution.  Metrics include proportion of landscape in a land cover type and the number of edges between types, as well as integrative measures such as patch size distribution, shape complexity of patches, and dominance and fragmentation of the landscape.<p>

Integrative landscape metrics, which characterize patterns for all land covers in a single value, can discriminate among different landscape types; however, their discriminating power is not maximized for large regions.  Ecoregions maximize the homogeneity of land cover types within a region and have a wider range of metric values than do Standard Federal Regions; thus ecoregions are the most useful for regional monitoring and assessment.<p>

Basic investigations such as this are critical for designing programs to assess ecosystem condition and developing good management plans.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Computing Applications Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Analysas Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="67"><h1>67</h1></a>

<h2>A 1/16 Sample of the United States Cannot Serve as the Sole Basis for Monitoring Landscape Pattern</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. T. Hunsaker, R. V. O'Neill, B. L. Jackson (1), S. P. Timmins (2), and D. A. Levine (3)
</dl>

Current research suggests that metrics of landscape patterns may reflect ecological processes operating at different scales and may provide an appropriate indicator for monitoring regional ecological changes.  Landscape condition is a resource of interest to the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a>'s Environmental Monitoring and Assessment Program (EMAP).<p>

Investigators have examined the extent to which a 1/16 areal subset of the landscape, using equally spaced 40-km<sup>2</sup> hexagons, can characterize the spatial extent of land cover types and landscape pattern (number of types of edges, patch shape complexity, dominance, and contagion).  This type of equal area support base is being used for EMAP's field monitoring of forests and surface waters.<p>

For 200-m resolution data, the hexagon subset gives a reasonable estimate of overall landscape cover but may not be adequate for monitoring uncommon land cover types such as wetlands.  For agriculture and forest, the proportion of the full landscape analysis units is only outside the 95&#37; confidence interval of the hexagon estimate 4-8&#37; of the time, whereas the proportions for wetlands and barren areas are outside the confidence interval 11-34&#37; of the time.<p>

Also, the hexagon subset does not appear adequate as the sole basis for monitoring landscape pattern.  The values for contagion, dominance, and shape complexity calculated on the full landscape units are outside the 95&#37; confidence interval of the hexagon estimate 27-76&#37; of the time.<p>

Other statistical analyses include regressions between full landscape and hexagon subsets, mean differences and standard errors, along with tests on the number of positive and negative values, and percentage of relative error of hexagon estimates.  Two or more types of land cover data at different spatial resolutions will likely be required for adequate monitoring of landscape pattern change for the nation.<p>

Research continues on methods of determining the appropriate sample units (including size, shape, and distribution) for estimating landscape pattern and the selection of adequate indicators of landscape pattern for long-term monitoring of ecological condition (i.e., sensitivity to change).<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Computing Applications Division, ORNL.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Analysas Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<a name="68"><h1>68</h1></a>

<h2>Landscape Status and Trends Are Quantified at the Regional Scale</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. V. O'Neill, C. T. Hunsaker, B. L. Jackson (1), K. H. Riitters, and J. D. Wickham
</dl>

Remotely sensed data for the Southeastern United States (Standard Federal Region 4) were used to develop an approach for reporting landscape patterns in a large, heterogeneous region.  The study indicated that landscape indices are more meaningful and interpretable if Region 4 is disaggregated into three component ecoregions, each representing an area with relatively homogeneous ecological processes.  The analyses also revealed that some of the available indices are not independent (i.e., they may provide redundant information about some aspects of pattern).<p>

The indices are also sensitive to the calculation scale (i.e., the unit area or extent over which the index is computed).  To avoid bias, this &quot;sample area&quot; must be two to five times larger than landscape patches.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Computing Applications Division, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<a name="69"><h1>69</h1></a>

<h2>Data Center Continues Information-Sharing Activities in Support of U.S.-China Bilateral Agreement</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. A. Boden
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.er.doe.gov/production/oher/GC/ESD_gc.html/">DOE Global Change Research Program</a> and the People's Republic of China's Academy of Sciences (PRC-AS) signed a collaborative agreement in August 1987 to study the greenhouse effect.  The objectives of the agreement are to improve the performance of general circulation models, to quantify methane emissions from Chinese rice paddies, and to prepare climate databases suitable for long-term regional and local climate analyses.<p>

The <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a>'s (CDIAC) role in the Joint Research Project on the Greenhouse Effect is to provide data processing, archival, documentation, and distribution support to the climate data and methane emission components of the project.  In the early years of the agreement, CDIAC provided computer hardware and software support to the Institutes of Atmospheric Physics and Geography (Beijing, PRC) and developed protocols for data exchange.  During the ensuing years, as data collection and compilation efforts intensified and progressed, CDIAC's principal role became one of archiving, documenting, and distributing data sets generated under the DOEPRC-AS bilateral agreement.<p>

To date, CDIAC has archived &#126;20 databases, fully documented 8 U.S. and PRC instrumental climate databases, and distributed &#126;1000 copies of the documented databases and DOE technical reports to individuals in more than 100 countries.<p>

At a recent meeting in Beijing, it was agreed that during the coming years CDIAC will continue all of these data-related support activities but will focus primarily on documenting and analyzing (1) a 2000-year proxy precipitation record being compiled by the Chinese and (2) the methane flux measurements made in Chinese rice paddies.<p>

<a name="70"><h1>70</h1></a>

<h2>CDIAC Produces an Updated Bibliographic Database on the Effects that Elevated Levels of CO<sub>2</sub> Have on Vegetation</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. M. Cushman, B. R. Strain (1), and J. D. Cure (1)
</dl>

The effects of increased concentrations of CO<sub>2</sub> on plants and ecosystems is an important issue in assessing global change.  The <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC), in collaboration with Boyd R. Strain and Jennifer D. Cure of Duke University, has updated a 1986 bibliography on the effects of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> on plants and ecosystems.<p>

The new bibliography, <i>Direct Effects of Atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> Enrichment on Plants and Ecosystems:  An Updated Bibliographic Database</i> (ORNL/CDIAC-70), provides complete bibliographic citations, abstracts, keywords, and common and scientific plant names for 798 references that were published between 1980 and 1994; half of the cited references were published in 1990 or later.<p>

A version of the bibliography in machine-readable form is also available.  Used with appropriate bibliographic database software, the bibliography offers new possibilities of database management for the user, such as searching by author, keyword, and year.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Duke University, Durham, North Carolina.</i>
</dl>

<a name="71"><h1>71</h1></a>

<h2>Coastal Hazards Database for the U.S. Gulf Coast Is Published as a CDIAC Numeric Data Package</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. W. White
</dl>

The <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC) published a coastal hazards database that provides an overview of the relative vulnerabilities of the U.S. Gulf coastline to inundation and erosion hazards associated with increasing sea levels.  This database quantitatively describes the U.S. Gulf Coast by integrating point, line, and polygon data into 0.25&#176; latitude by 0.25&#176; longitude grid cells and 1:2,000,000 digitized line segments containing 22 data and 7 relative-risk variables on elevation, geology, geomorphology, vertical land movement, erosion and accretion, tidal range, and wave height.<p>

Several algorithms for calculating a coastal vulnerability index (CVI) are included in the documentation.  The CVI algorithm least affected by data error is that calculated by taking the square root of the mean product of the seven risk variables divided by the number of variables present.  An analysis using this CVI indicates that the Gulf coastline is particularly vulnerable to inundation because of low-lying topography composed primarily of limestones and sandstones overlaid by unconsolidated sediments and unstable landforms (i.e., high-risk values for elevation, lithology, and geomorphology are predominant on the Gulf).<p>

Nearly half of the Gulf shoreline is eroding, and measurements of local vertical movement indicate a relative sea level change of more than 1 m/year for the entire Gulf Coast.  The Gulf Coast is a low-energy coastline with microtidal mean tide ranges (&lt;2 m) and with wave heights under 5 m.  For this reason, the Gulf of Florida has lower CVI values than those calculated for the Atlantic Coast portion of the state.  Gulf Coast CVI values range from 2.12 to 40.09; the mean approaches 16 (i.e., moderate risk).  Areas at high risk include the Louisiana barrier islands, New Orleans; Freeport, Texas; and portions of the Florida Everglades.<p>

<a name="72"><h1>72</h1></a>

<h2>ESD Assists in Reevaluating the Strategy for Managing Transuranic Wastes at ORNL</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. R. Trabalka
</dl>

An <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff member chaired an interdisciplinary team charged with reevaluating the strategy for managing transuranic-contaminated (TRU) wastes at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  A proposal had suggested that the Waste Handling and Packaging Plant (WHPP) process ORNL's TRU wastes for disposal in the <a href="http://www.wipp.carlsbad.nm.us/">Waste Isolation Pilot Plant</a> (WIPP) in New Mexico.  Because much of ORNL's TRU waste is mixed hazardous and radioactive waste, processing in the WHPP was required for compliance with the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/epaoswer/hazwaste.htm#ldr/">Land Disposal Restrictions</a> imposed by the <a href="http://earth1.epa.gov/OSWRCRA/">Resource Conservation and Recovery Act</a> (RCRA).<p>

The project had not been accepted, however, because of delays in the opening of WIPP and uncertainties in its Waste Acceptance Criteria (WAC), uncertainties in <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> waste management strategies, and the negative reaction to the high costs of WHPP.  The team was asked to identify alternatives to the WHPP and to evaluate them through the use of a common set of criteria (e.g., safety, compliance, technical soundness).<p>

Uncertainties dominated the evaluation process; most were not reducible by engineering studies or through technical assessments.  Some uncertainties were associated with issues that were national in scope and that required both social and scientific solutions.  Others were more local in origin but carried equal weight (e.g., the uncertain future for low-level waste disposal on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a>).<p>

Major uncertainties regarding the quantities of solid TRU wastes from ORNL that could be disposed of in WIPP related to (1) the unique nature and limited characterization of ORNL's solid TRU wastes, (2) limitations of current assay technologies, and (3) questions about the feasibility of retrieving wastes in earthen trenches.  The evaluation of alternatives was also hampered by uncertainties in WAC for disposing of secondary wastes from processing.<p>

Under such conditions informed judgment, supported by formal decision-aiding tools (such as multiobjective utility analysis), must be relied upon to develop and to evaluate alternatives.  Although the team found nothing conceptually wrong with WHPP, it concluded that a phased, step-wise approach that copes with current uncertainties and resource constraints in planning and making decisions about TRU-waste processing should be presented to DOE and other stakeholders for consideration as an alternative.  This approach would (1) allow resolution of critical technical, regulatory, and political issues before a commitment to a processing alternative or facility is made; (2) iteratively incorporate the results of external decisions on disposal options into process design activities; (3) utilize feedback from waste characterization, risk assessment, technology development, and pilot-scale processing activities in the design of full-scale processing capabilities; (4) defer investments in capital facilities until critical issues have been resolved and DOE strategies are developed; and (5) spread capital costs over a longer period to cope with the current budget shortfall.<p>

