<TITLE>Environmental Biotechnology</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Biotechnology</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Biotechnology Section of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) carries out basic and applied research on (1) mechanisms that influence the response of biological systems to contaminants, (2) effects of receiving systems on the availability and distribution of materials to which they are exposed, and (3) modifications of biological systems to enhance degradation or immobilization of contaminants.  Experimental, observational, and simulation studies are conducted at different levels of biological organization, from the subcellular and biochemical levels to the ecosystem level.  Section activities are supported by the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) Headquarters; the <a href="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html/">U.S. Department of Defense</a>; and the environmental compliance and remedial action programs at DOE facilities in Oak Ridge (ORNL, the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>, and the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/K25/">Oak Ridge K-25 Site</a>) as well as at the Kansas City, Missouri, plant and the gaseous diffusion plants in Paducah, Kentucky, and Portsmouth, Ohio.<p>

<h2>Biological Markers</h2>

The Biological Markers Group assists in the assessment of the health of the environment by identifying and evaluating biological responses induced in biota exposed to contamination.  Biological responses are studied at the molecular, biochemical, and physiological levels both to understand the basic toxicological mechanisms that underlie responses elicited by exposure to environmental contaminants and to relate the responses to effects observed at higher levels of biological organization.<p>

In FY 1994, using the biological indicator approach, staff assessed the health of several aquatic systems, including streams receiving mixed contaminants, rivers affected by pulp and paper effluents, reservoirs containing polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs) and heavy metals, and natural lakes containing hydrocarbon compounds.  Researchers also conducted field assessments, laboratory analyses, and bioassays to determine the effects that environmental stressors had on the health of these systems, to evaluate the effectiveness of remedial actions, and to assess compliance with environmental regulations.  Currently, new indicators of aquatic ecosystem health that involve DNA diversity and antioxidant enzymes are being developed and tested in a variety of aquatic systems.<p>

<h2>Biological Monitoring and Assessment</h2>

The Biological Monitoring and Assessment Group conducts projects that evaluate the ecological health of aquatic and terrestrial ecosystems near the three <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR) and the ecosystems associated with the DOE facilities in Paducah, Kentucky, and Portsmouth, Ohio.  The biological monitoring programs provide a basis for assessing compliance with environmental regulations.  The programs also help identify causes of adverse ecological impacts and assess the effectiveness of remedial action programs by documenting ecological recovery.  Biological monitoring techniques range from manipulative field experiments and new in situ bioassays to more conventional approaches, including quantitative biotic surveys and laboratory toxicity tests.  The Biological Monitoring and Assessment Group consists of three projects that reflect different aspects of the biological monitoring programs:  Ecotoxicology, Biomonitoring, and Ecological Monitoring.<p>

<h2><i>Ecotoxicology</i></h2>

The biological monitoring programs not only use established biomonitoring protocols but also include the development of new procedures, as appropriate, for assessing toxicity.  The goals of the Ecotoxicology Project are (1) to develop alternative methods for assessing water quality through the use of lower trophic level indicators, such as the autotrophs (algae) and heterotrophs (fungi, bacteria, and protozoans) that constitute stream periphyton communities, and (2) to apply these methods in both <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> regulatory monitoring programs and work-for-others projects.  The project also conducts experimental studies of community structure and food webs in contaminated and noncontaminated streams, ponds, and wetlands to determine how contaminants modify aquatic communities or indirectly alter populations, communities, or ecological processes.<p>

In FY 1994, a major accomplishment of the Ecotoxicology Project was the development and validation of an earthworm toxicity test that can be used to estimate the acute and chronic toxicity of soils.  Results of the test were used in a site-wide baseline ecological risk assessment for the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html>Portsmouth Gaseous Diffusion Plant</a>.  In cooperation with Biomonitoring Project staff, Ecotoxicology Project staff identified lithium as a toxicant of concern in some waste treatment operations at the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Y-12 Plant</a>.  Results of this investigation were used to establish a waste acceptance criterion for lithium that was protective of the environment.  A combination of both field and laboratory studies demonstrated that fish can acclimate to chlorine, a toxicant that has been associated with fish kills in some <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">ORR</a> streams.  Other research showed that fatty acid profiles of stream periphyton communities can be used as high-resolution biomarkers of exposure to chlorine.<p>

<h2><i>Biomonitoring</i></h2>

Biomonitoring is a major component of the environmental compliance programs at the three <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities in Oak Ridge and the DOE gaseous diffusion plants in Kentucky and Ohio.  The Biomonitoring Project uses various aquatic species in laboratory tests to detect acute and chronic toxicity of water (both effluents and receiving streams) and sediments.  These tests are necessary to comply with the requirements of the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/EPA-WATER/1995/April/Day-07/">National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System</a> (NPDES) permits issued under the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/oar/caa.html/">Clean Water Act</a> and to comply with requirements of the Comprehensive Environmental Response, Compensation, and Liability Act that are related to ecological risk assessment.  The Biomonitoring and Ecotoxicology projects support the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> concept of biomonitoring as a combination of established toxicity-testing protocols and innovative ecotoxicological approaches that together can be used to assess regulatory compliance and ensure environmental protection and restoration.<p>

In FY 1994, staff completed more than 200 compliance-related aquatic toxicity tests required under the NPDES permits for the DOE Oak Ridge facilities and under the Kentucky Pollutant Discharge Elimination System permit for the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html>Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant</a>.  Staff provided significant support for various environmental restoration programs that required both water and sediment toxicity tests in order to assess ecological risks.  Special studies also were implemented (1) to identify sources of toxicity in the groundwater treatment facility and Outfall 201 at the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Y-12 Plant</a> and in the sewage treatment plant at ORNL and (2) to develop site-specific criteria for metals at the Paducah facility.<p>

<h2><i>Ecological Monitoring</i></h2>

The Ecological Monitoring Project evaluates the ecological effects and human health risks of regulated discharges from ongoing operations and fugitive emissions from waste disposal sites at <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities in Tennessee, Kentucky, Ohio, and Missouri.  Such monitoring documents compliance with <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/EPA-WATER/1995/April/Day-07/">NPDES</a> permits and provides a direct measure of the effectiveness of remedial actions at contaminated sites.  Staff also conduct research on the transport and transformations of chemicals in surface water and groundwater and in terrestrial environments, and they develop innovative methods for monitoring the transport and effects of chemicals in the environment.<p>

In FY 1994, staff of the Ecological Monitoring Project continued to provide information that guides remedial actions.  Such guidance has led to the striking, well-documented ecological recovery of fish and invertebrate communities in several streams affected by operations of DOE facilities.  Elimination and reduction of discharges of chlorinated water to streams at the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/general/OverviewPaducah.html>Paducah Gaseous Diffusion Plant</a>, the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/K25/">Oak Ridge K-25 Site</a>, the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>, and ORNL resulted in the repopulation of reaches of streams that previously contained very limited aquatic life.  Results of research on the life history of the Tennessee dace, a fish uncommon in East Tennessee but abundant in some <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">ORR</a> streams and listed for special protection by the Tennessee Wildlife Resources Agency, will be used to guide environmental restoration activities that may affect critical habitat of this species.  An evaluation of the site-specific relationship between waterborne inorganic mercury concentrations and methylmercury accumulation in fish was conducted for the Y-12 Plant to assist the Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation in setting mercury discharge limits in the NPDES permit for the facility.  PCB monitoring using fish, caged clams, and semipermeable membrane devices at the DOE Oak Ridge facilities helped researchers identify contaminated aquatic environments and sources of PCB contamination in those systems.  Furthermore, measurements of contaminant transfer from landfilled fly ash to terrestrial organisms provided key data for assessing ecological risks at a site under evaluation for possible remediation.<p>

<h2>Contaminant Transport</h2>

The mission of the Contaminant Transport Group is to assist the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a> in reducing both on-site and off-site risks to human health and the environment that result from past waste disposal practices.  The group (1) provides data to identify contaminant sources in the ORNL waste disposal areas and to prioritize areas for remediation, (2) characterizes contaminant transport mechanisms through surface water and shallow subsurface pathways in order to select and design effective remediation strategies, and (3) assesses the performance of remedial actions in reducing contaminant risks.<p>

The group's mission is accomplished principally by implementing the Waste Area Grouping (WAG) 2 Remedial Investigation and Site Investigations Project.  Staff monitor surface water tributaries and seeps to collect data to evaluate temporal discharge patterns and fluxes during both baseline and transient storm events.  Data are also collected to characterize the spatial distribution of contaminants in sediments and the distribution of contaminants between dissolved and particle-associated phases in suspended sediments.  Other group activities include database manipulation and data visualization using geographic information system techniques, safety and quality assurance/quality control oversight, and project coordination and management.<p>

Principal accomplishments in FY 1994 include (1) providing technical and assessment support of surface water sampling in ORNL waste disposal areas in order to prioritize potential actions by the ORNL Environmental Restoration Program and (2) conducting soil and sediment sampling in WAG 2 to identify major contaminant source areas for potential corrective action.  Results of these efforts were summarized in the <i>Third Annual Environmental Restoration Monitoring and Assessment Report</i>, a key Federal Facilities Agreement milestone for the ORNL Environmental Restoration Program.<p>

<h2>Environmental Chemistry</h2>

The Environmental Chemistry Group investigates the transport, transformation, and accumulation of materials in surface water environments, including sediments and biota.  Investigations conducted by the group form an important link between information on basic principles and processes and their applications to current applied research, such as environmental restoration and remedial actions.<p>

Significant accomplishments by the Environmental Chemistry Group in FY 1994 were associated with the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/CRERP/">Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program</a>, which addresses the transport, fate, and distribution of waterborne contaminants released from <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">ORR</a> and which assesses potential risks to human health and the environment that are associated with those contaminants.  The <i>Phase 2 Sampling and Analysis Plan</i> for the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/CRERP/">Clinch River remedial investigation</a> and baseline risk assessment was submitted to regulatory agencies for review, and sampling and analysis for contaminants in sediment and water were completed in FY 1994.  Information collected during this phase of the study will be used to characterize the nature and extent of contamination in the Clinch River and to assess the risks to human health and the environment from those contaminants.  The <i>Remedial Investigation/Feasibility Study and Proposed Plan</i> for the lower Watts Bar Reservoir study area was also submitted for regulatory review in FY 1994.  The report concluded that the greatest risks to human health would result from the consumption of certain species of fish containing PCBs and the transfer of sediment from deeper areas of the reservoir to upland disposal sites where farming might occur.  Existing laws and regulations would be effective in protecting human health from these contaminants.<p>

<h2>Microbial Interactions</h2>

The Microbial Interactions Group uses powerful new techniques in molecular biology to complement traditional microbiological methods to better understand the processes by which microorganisms transform hazardous chemical contaminants in soils, surface water, and groundwater.  The goals of these investigations are to optimize the microbial degradation of hazardous chemical contaminants and to demonstrate the application of innovative microbial techniques and bioremediation approaches as a means of solving contamination problems at <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites.<p>

Investigations of deep subsurface formations at DOE sites were expanded in FY 1994 to include shale reserves in Colorado and volcanic outcrops in New Mexico.  Microorganisms from the new sites appear to have application for remediation of DOE sites.  A new project was initiated to examine the relationship between bacterial heterogeneity and the physical/chemical heterogeneity in shallow subsurface environments, whereas microbial monitoring of trichloroethylene degradation at a <a href="http://www.srs.gov/">Savannah River</a> demonstration site was completed, and the technology was transferred to other DOE sites (e.g., Hanford, Washington).  An unexpected finding--that the addition of surfactants to the lux bioreporter system enhances the bioavailability of contaminants to natural organic matter--may have significance for site bioremediation activities.<p>

One cooperative research and development agreement CRADA) was completed in FY 1994, and work on another was initiated.  The <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>-Envirogen CRADA to assess the effectiveness of a bench-scale vapor-phase bioreactor in removing trichloroethylene from a complex aqueous waste stream was completed, and an ORNL-National Center for Manufacturing Science (NCMS) CRADA was prepared for review and approvals.  In collaboration with NCMS partners at Ford Motor Company, General Motors, and Texaco, researchers will develop and demonstrate approaches to improving in situ bioremediation of contaminated aquifers.  In other work, researchers developed a consortium of microorganisms that is capable of degrading glycol-based wastes, such as antifreeze and deicing fluids, thus providing an opportunity for establishing partnerships between ORNL and various industries.<p>

<h2>Reservation Data Systems</h2>

The Reservation Data Systems Group primarily provides data management support for environmental restoration projects conducted at the three <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities in Oak Ridge.  The group also supports environmental restoration activities through the development and operation of the Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS) and through leadership of the Environmental Restoration Data Quality Program, which is aimed at developing common data management practices among environmental restoration projects.  OREIS is sponsored by the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/doe_oro/oro_home.html/">DOE Oak Ridge Operations Office</a> to fulfill the requirements of state and federal oversight agreements instituted in response to environmental restoration activities across <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a>ORR</a>.  The successful implementation of OREIS and the Environmental Restoration Data Quality Program will promote consistency in the data, increase their legal defensibility, and enhance the cost-effectiveness of environmental restoration activities.  Through the initiation of a new activity this past year, the group also supports to the <a href="http://www.nasa.gov//">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</a> (NASA) <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/otherdaacs.html/">Earth Observing System Data and Information System</a> (EOSDIS) through the <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/">ORNL Distributed Active Archive Center (DAAC) for Biogeochemical Dynamics</a>.  EOSDIS is part of the NASA contribution to the effort by the <a href="http://www.ciesin.org/">U.S. Global Change Research Program</a> to develop a predictive understanding of the global environment.<p>

A key accomplishment in FY 1994 was the successful transition of OREIS from a developmental program to an operational system.  <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> staff, as well as state and federal regulators, can now access and display environmental restoration data for ORR through OREIS.<p>

The <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/ornldaac.html/">ORNL DAAC</a> became operational this year and is now electronically linked to other NASA data centers.  The ORNL DAAC has developed a local user interface to allow users to search and order data that are available locally.<p>

