<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="73"><H1>73</H1></A>

<H2>Integrative Assessment Approaches Help Evaluate the Effects of Contaminant-Related Stress on Aquatic Ecosystem Health</h2>

<dl>
<dt>S. M. Adams and M. S. Greeley, Jr.
</dl>

Many species of fish, because of their position in the food chain, are integrators of environmental conditions and, therefore, may reflect the overall health of an aquatic ecosystem.  A variety of methods or approaches are available for evaluating the effects of environmental conditions or stressors on fish populations.<p>

Each approach, however, typically has its own unique limitations and advantages, each of which will influence the evaluation and interpretation of the effects of stress on fish populations.  For fish inhabiting streams that receive a variety of industrial effluents, including polychlorinated biphenyls, polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, heavy metals, and chlorine, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> scientists compared and evaluated three approaches for investigating how contaminants affected fish health.  These approaches include (1) individual variable responses, primarily at lower levels of biological organization; (2) statistically based integrative indices, based on multivariate responses; and (3) ecologically relevant measurements, such as population and community-level responses.<p>

Individual variables best reflect stress responses at the biochemical, physiological, and histopathological levels and are used to evaluate the effects of short-term environmental stressors.  Multivariate analyses provide a more integrative assessment of stress, because this approach takes into account the interrelationships and associations among stress responses.  Ecologically relevant measurements, however, reflect the combined and cumulative effects of both indirect and direct stress pathways.<p>

The studies showed that applying all methods together provides the best strategy for evaluating fish health to make environmentally sound decisions regarding the ecological implications of stressors on aquatic ecosystem health.<p>

<A NAME="74"><H1>74</H1></A>

<H2>Preliminary Studies Suggest that Contaminant Plumes from a Military Reservation Are Not Adversely Affecting Fish Health in Cape Cod Ponds</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. S. Greeley, Jr., and S. M. Adams
</dl>

The accelerated pace of military base closings in the United States underscores the need for more innovative and sensitive approaches to the assessment of the environmental impacts of both active and deactivated <a href="http://lcweb.loc.gov/global/executive/defense.html/">U.S. Department of Defense</a> (DOD) facilities.  One such approach used in biological monitoring and assessment activities at various <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites involves the comparative evaluation of a diverse suite of molecular, biochemical, physiological, and population/community bioindicators of toxicant exposure and effects in organisms inhabiting potentially contaminated sites.<p>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers are currently in the process of applying the bioindicator approach to the assessment of the biological effects of groundwater contamination associated with a DOD site on Cape Cod, Massachusetts.  Two small recreational lakes, Ashumet and Johns Ponds, near Falmouth, Massachusetts, are in the paths of several distinct groundwater contaminant plumes migrating from the Massachusetts Military Reservation.  Preliminary results of this study suggest that the exposure of pond fish to chemical toxicants in the plumes has been minimal to date.<p>

More intensive studies are now under way to better characterize the exposure history of fish in the ponds and to explain the relatively high incidence of surface tumors and other abnormalities observed in a species of catfish during the preliminary studies.  The ongoing investigation is expected to serve as a test of the applicability of the bioindicator approach to environmental assessments associated with DOD facilities.  The results of this investigation will also aid in the interpretation of the results of similar studies being conducted on or near the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a>.<p>

<A NAME="75"><H1>75</H1></A>

<H2>The Genetic Relationship Between Two Species of Freshwater Snails Is Analyzed</h2>

<dl>
<dt>K. L. Lee, A. J. Stewart, and L. R. Shugart
</dl>

DNA fingerprinting is a powerful tool in the analysis of genetic relationships and genetic diversity.  Among current DNA fingerprinting methods, the polymerase chain reaction (PCR)-based, randomly amplified, polymorphic DNA (RAPD) technique is particularly suitable for the genetic analysis of populations.  The main advantages of the RAPD technique include (1) the requirement of only small quantities of DNA, (2) the ability to work even when base sequence in the target genome is not known, and (3) the ability to scan the entire genome.<p>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers have recently adapted the RAPD fingerprinting technique to assess the taxonomic relationships of two closely related species of freshwater pleurocerid snails, <i>Elimia clavaeformis Lea</i> and <i>Pleurocera unciale</i>.  Several DNA purification protocols were attempted; one was found to be economical, fast, and able to produce DNA with sufficient purity for PCR.  This protocol included extracting the DNA with phenol (to remove proteins) and purifying it by precipitating mucopolysaccharide contaminants in a concentrated salt solution.  DNA yield from individual snails using this protocol was 2 to 60 &#171;g per snail.  Analysis of purified DNA samples from the snails on 0.8&#37; agarose gels revealed undegraded high-molecular-weight DNA.<p>

Thirty-seven arbitrary primers were tested to analyze purified snail DNA from the two species.  Nine of these primers generated RAPD fragments that could be detected on agarose gels.  Five of the nine primers amplified RAPD fragments that were polymorphic in individual snails of the same species.  Thus, these five primers can be used for the genetic diversity analysis of snails.<p>

Additionally, four of the five primers are highly informative in the analysis of taxonomic relationships of the two snail species.  Primer OPD-5 amplified a 900-bp fragment limited to <i>Pleurocera</i>, whereas primer OPD-3 generated a 730-bp fragment only in <i>Elimia</i>.  These two DNA fragments could be diagnostic for individuals of <i>Pleurocera</i> or <i>Elimia</i> respectively.  On the other hand, primer OPD-5 and primer UBC-4 amplified 400-bp and 740-bp RAPD fragments, respectively, which were common to both <i>Pleurocera</i> and <i>Elimia</i>.  These fragments may represent DNA markers specific for a family or a higher level taxonomic group.<p>

Further analyses of other snail species and genera will be used to determine the specificity of these DNA markers to pleurocerid snail species.<p>

<A NAME="76"><H1>76</H1></A>

<H2>Laboratory-Formulated Sediments Should Provide Meaningful Controls for Toxicity Tests</h2>

<dl>
<dt>A. M. Gonzalez and L. A. Kszos
</dl>

Contaminants introduced into natural waters are often concentrated in sediments through adsorption and may adversely affect benthic organisms that feed on or inhabit the surface sediments.  In the laboratory, sediment toxicity can be evaluated by monitoring the survival, growth, or reproduction of surrogate benthic invertebrates exposed to sediment samples.  The <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> Toxicology Laboratory currently maintains healthy cultures of <i>Hyalella azteca</i> and <i>Chironomus tentans</i>, both of which are being considered by the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> as standard test organisms for sediment toxicity testing. Organisms such as these have successfully been used in toxicity evaluations of sediments for the Clinch River/Poplar Creek Phase II Sampling and Analysis Plan, a component of the Watts Bar Reservoir Remedial Investigation.<p>

One clear weakness of current sediment toxicity testing protocols is the lack of an appropriate control with which sediment toxicity test data may be compared.  The current practice is to use sediments sampled from a reference site, typically upstream of the presumably impacted sites, but which may not itself be &quot;clean.&quot;  The ESD Toxicology Laboratory is developing artificial sediments that can be made to match test sediments with respect to key geochemical and geophysical properties, such as particle size distribution, organic matter and organic carbon content, and pH.  Such substrates could be used as site-specific controls, thus minimizing the influence of major differences in sediment geochemistry on organism response. This methodology would increase the sensitivity of the sediment bioassay to the presence of toxicants.  The initial goal is to develop an artificial sediment that will support biological activity for prolonged periods and then to evaluate the interactions of the artificial sediment with such contaminants as copper or polychlorinated biphenyls.<p>

<A NAME="77"><H1>77</H1></A>

<H2>Environmental Effects of Storm Water Pollutants Are Evaluated at ORNL</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. L. Hinzman, A. J. Stewart, G. R. Southworth, and M. J. Filson
</dl>

Despite the best management practices, total suspended solids (TSS) and oil and grease (O&G) concentrations in storm water runoff frequently exceed the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/EPA-WATER/1995/April/Day-07/">National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System</a> (NPDES) permit limits at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a>.  At the request of the ORNL Office of Environmental Compliance and Documentation, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff initiated a study to clarify whether these noncompliances are only a regulatory problem or are a source of ecological impact that requires remediation.<p>

A review of the 1988-92 NPDES noncompliance data showed that ORNL operations were conducted with care.  Only 7&#37; of the TSS and O&G noncompliances were one-time occurrences indicative of a spill.<p>

Laboratory tests were conducted to examine the effects of storm water runoff on the survival and reproduction of <i>Ceriodaphnia dubia</i> and on the feeding rate of <i>Elimia clavaeformis</i>.  Storm water runoff from one outfall was acutely toxic to <i>Ceriodaphnia</i>, and water from two outfalls significantly lowered snail feeding rates.  However, the tests could not determine whether the observed effects were because of TSS, O&G, or some other constituent.  Five databases were searched for literature published since 1988 on the ecological effects of storm water runoff and alternatives for best management practices.  Current storm water treatment options were identified, and proactive approaches for addressing storm water noncompliances were recommended.<p>

An analysis of sediment samples collected from seven sites in area streams showed that total petroleum hydrocarbons (TPHs) accumulated in the sediment of at least some sites in White Oak Creek (WOC) at concentrations that could adversely affect biota.  Hydrocarbon signatures in sediments collected from WOC down-stream of ORNL outfalls and from <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev27-3/text/envside1.htm/">East Fork Poplar Creek</a> downstream of the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a> were similar to each other but different from off-site reference streams. This disparity suggests that TPH accumulation in sediment may be related to facility operations.  Sediment toxicity testing could be conducted to assess the potential ecological effects of this accumulation.<p>

<A NAME="78"><H1>78</H1></A>

<H2>Toxicity of Lithium Drives the Need for New Waste Acceptance Criteria</h2>

<dl>
<dt>A. J. Stewart and L. A. Kszos
</dl>

Routine compliance testing shows that effluent from the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>'s Groundwater Treatment Facility is acutely toxic to <i>Ceriodaphnia dubia</i> (a micro-crustacean) and to fathead minnow larvae.  Subsequent testing suggests that the toxicity is due to the presence of lithium.<p>

Lithium is a light, strong metal (only one-third as massive as sodium) used in various <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> operations, including fusion weapons, fission reactors, and gamma detectors.  Virtually no information exists about the toxicity of lithium to aquatic biota despite widespread and increasing industrial usage, and surprisingly little information exists about the concentrations of lithium that occur naturally in surface waters.  When additional toxicity tests were conducted with lithium-spiked control water, wastewaters, and stream-water samples, the results confirmed that lithium is acutely toxic at concentrations as low as 1 mg/L.  Water type appeared to influence the toxicity of lithium:  the metal was about six times more toxic in low-sodium diluted mineral water than it was in sodium-rich wastewaters.<p>

These findings are significant to Waste Treatment Operations at the Y-12 Plant because (1) some batches of wastewaters treated at the Y-12 Plant's West End Treatment Facility (WETF) contain lithium at high concentrations (&gt;5000 mg/L), (2) lithium is exceptionally difficult to remove from solution by conventional waste-treatment procedures, and (3) WETF effluent typically contains a high concentration of sodium.  The results of the toxicity tests are being used to establish waste acceptance criteria for lithium at WETF.<p>

<A NAME="79"><H1>79</H1></A>

<H2>Mercury Found in Periphyton and Grazing Fish in East Fork Poplar Creek Is an Indicator of Contaminant Movement</h2>

<dl>
<dt>W. R. Hill and A. J. Stewart
</dl>

The impressive sorptive capacity and large surface area of periphyton (substrate-attached algae and microheterotrophs) gives it the potential to be an important mediator of contaminant movement in aquatic ecosystems.<p>

Periphyton's role as an entry point of mercury into stream food webs was investigated in <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev27-3/text/envside1.htm/">East Fork Poplar Creek</a> (EFPC), a second-order stream contaminated by spills of elemental mercury from the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>.  Both methylmercury and inorganic mercury were analyzed in periphyton and whole-body samples of fish (periphyton-grazing stoneroller minnows and omnivorous striped shiners) that were collected at three sites in EFPC.<p>

Total mercury concentrations were very high at the site closest to the Y-12 Plant (exceeding 50 &#181;g/g dry mass in stonerollers), and they decreased with distance downstream from the plant.  Interestingly, inorganic mercury was the predominant form in both periphyton and fish.  The proportion of methylmercury increased with distance downstream:  methylmercury in periphyton was 0.15&#37;, 0.23&#37;, and 0.37&#37; of total mercury at the three sites (from upstream to downstream); organic mercury was 1.6&#37;, 9.5&#37;, and 21.4&#37; of total mercury for stonerollers at the sites.  Methylmercury concentrations were much lower in stonerollers than in striped shiners; these results suggest that a periphyton diet may be an important influence on mercury speciation.<p>

The predominance of inorganic mercury found in stonerollers and striped shiners contrasts with previous research, which has shown methylmercury to be the major species present in fish tissue.  Because inorganic mercury is much less toxic than methylmercury, the results of this study may have important implications for ecological risk analysis.<p>

<A NAME="80"><H1>80</H1></A>

<H2>Kingfishers on the Oak Ridge Reservation Accumulate Trace Metals and Radionuclides from Aquatic Prey</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. L. Ashwood and L. A. Baron (1)
</dl>

Belted kingfishers are highly territorial predators that consume half of their body weight per day in fish and crayfish from streams and lakes.  This high rate of consumption leads to a high potential for exposure to contaminants that have accumulated in their prey; however, no information is available in the wildlife or toxicological literature on the impacts of contaminants on kingfishers.<p>

Researchers in <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ORNL's ESD</a> are investigating contaminant levels in kingfishers that feed from streams on the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Reservation</a> (ORR).  Initial results of analyses on three dead kingfishers found at different locations on ORR suggest that each had accumulated high concentrations of some trace metals or radionuclides.  Although reference site values are not available for kingfishers, the wide variations in results for each contaminant among the three birds suggest that values at the high end of the ranges should be considered elevated.  Cadmium ranged from &lt;0.20 to 7.21 mg/kg in feathers and from &lt;0.20 to 4.04 mg/kg in kidneys.  Mercury ranged from 2.72 to 13.9 mg/kg in feathers and from 1.46 to 26.8 mg/kg in kidneys.  Cesium-137 ranged from 3 to 151 pCi/g in muscle.<p>

Lead and selenium were also measured in samples from each bird, but the ranges among birds were not as wide.  Kingfisher nest burrows are being probed with a remote video camera and grabber to obtain samples of discarded feathers and unsuccessful eggs without harming the birds. <p>

<dl>
<dt>___________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Advanced Sciences Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="81"><H1>81</H1></A>

<H2>Long-Term Monitoring of Stream Biota near DOE Oak Ridge Facilities Detects Changes in Organic Contamination Concentrations</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. J. Peterson and G. R. Southworth
</dl>

From 1985 to 1993, organic contaminant concentrations in stream biota were monitored near <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> facilities in Oak Ridge.  One of the primary objectives of the monitoring effort was to detect spatial and temporal changes in biotic contamination to evaluate the effectiveness of pollution abatement activities.<p>

Asiatic clams (<i>Corbicula fluminea</i>) were the bioindicator of choice for monitoring most organic contaminants, because clams can accumulate organic pollutants that are rapidly metabolized by fish.  On an annual basis, Asiatic clams taken from an uncontaminated reference stream were placed in cages for 4-week exposures in the receiving streams.  Clam monitoring successfully detected a localized source of chlordane contamination, and annual follow-up monitoring tracked a steady decrease in contamination.  The use of clams to resolve spatial differences in polychlorinated biphenyl (PCB) contamination was found to be limited in the presence of  sublethal concentrations of residual chlorine; therefore, the use of resident fish was preferred for monitoring PCBs under those exposure conditions.<p>

Annual monitoring of resident sunfish from White Oak Creek, a stream receiving discharges from the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> complex, showed a significant decrease in PCB concentration over a 5-year period at all five sites monitored.<p>

Overall, the long-term, concurrent monitoring of resident fish and transplanted Asiatic clams was effective in identifying and evaluating changes in organic contaminant bioaccumulation downstream of the DOE facilities.<p>

<A NAME="82"><H1>82</H1></A>

<H2>Dechlorination of Outfalls in Upper EFPC Does Not Decrease Rate of Fish Mortality</h2>

<dl>
<dt>M. G. Ryon
</dl>

<a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev27-3/text/envside1.htm/">Upper East Fork Poplar Creek</a> (EFPC), adjacent to the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a>, was surveyed daily in June 1994 to establish  baseline fish mortality.  The last regularly scheduled surveys of dead fish in EFPC had been suspended in May 1993, following the dechlorination of major outfalls in November 1992.  A decrease in the mortality rate and an increase in fish community density had been expected as a result of the reduced levels of total residual chlorine (TRC).<p>

The June 1994 surveys revealed, however, that the overall mortality rate did not decrease in relation to the size of the population.  Contrary to expectation, the June 1994 surveys found a total of 115 dead fish, a higher total than those from the daily surveys in June 1991 and June 1992, which counted 77 and 36, respectively.  Thus, the mean daily mortality rate increased from 1.80 per day in June 1992 to 5.48 per day in June 1994.  However, the increase in the daily mortality rate was matched by an increase in fish community density at the sample site closest to the survey area:  the density rose from 2.22 to 5.64 fish per square meter.  Therefore, despite the greater total number of dead fish, the relative proportion of dead fish to the total fish community was similar in 1992 and 1994 (i.e., 0.17&#37; and 0.19&#37;).<p>

Apparently, the reduction of TRC levels in upper EFPC did not lower the overall mortality rate in relation to the population.  The continued level of overall mortality may result from the increased number of fish exposed to chlorine (even in smaller quantities), another toxicant effect, or the migration of fish into contaminated reaches upstream of the dechlorinators.<p>

<A NAME="83"><H1>83</H1></A>

<H2>Total Residual Chlorine Profile of WOC and Its Associated Outfalls Is Evaluated for Possible Effects on Fish Populations</h2>

<dl>
<dt>E. M. Schilling, M. G. Ryon, B. A. Carrico (1), R. P. Hoffmeister (1),  J. W. Lotts (2), and W. K. Roy
</dl>

A fish kill that resulted in an occurrence report was investigated in White Oak Creek (WOC) in November 1993.  Sporadic fish kills in WOC have occurred since 1987, and some were thought to be associated with toxic concentrations of total residual chlorine (TRC).  Future remediation efforts include a plan to dechlorinate many of the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> outfalls to WOC.<p>

A chlorine profile of WOC was conducted in January 1994 to determine TRC concentrations in WOC and identify the outfalls discharging to WOC from the main ORNL complex upstream from Melton Valley Drive.  Water samples were taken at 25-m intervals and at all flowing outfalls.  Measurements of elevated TRC in outfalls discharging to WOC ranged from 0.18 to 0.84 mg/L.  Exposure to similar TRC concentrations have been shown to have detrimental effects on the fish populations.  Instream TRC concentrations ranged from 0.03 mg/L (at Melton Valley Drive) to a high of 0.17 mg/L (just above Fifth Creek confluence).  No measurable instream TRC concentrations were found upstream from White Oak Avenue.<p>

The <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> water quality criteria limit for a chronic concentration of TRC is 0.011 mg/L.  Continued monitoring of WOC and its associated outfalls will allow researchers to determine trends in TRC concentrations and expected changes in the fish populations resulting from future dechlorination actions.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>JAYCOR, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="84"><H1>84</H1></A>

<H2>Temporal Trends Reflect Recovery in the Benthic Macroinvertebrate Community of a Chronically Affected Watershed</h2>

<dl>
<dt>J. G. Smith
</dl>

Temporal trends in benthic macro-invertebrate community structure in five streams within a single watershed have been followed for 6 years to help assess (1) the impact of operations and (2) the effectiveness of pollution abatement activities and remedial actions taken at ORNL.<p>

An initial characterization of the macroinvertebrate community structure determined that the sampling sites closest to one or more major effluent discharges generally exhibited the greatest evidence of impact.  Invertebrate community structure at these sites also exhibited the greatest evidence of change indicative of improving conditions (e.g., significant increases in total richness) as pollution abatement projects (e.g., effluent dechlorination) were implemented or other <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> operational changes occurred (e.g., reactor shutdown).<p>

By contrast, community structure changed little at sites located much farther downstream (far-field sites) or at sites where no abatement activities were implemented.  This pattern of temporal change helps demonstrate the effect of ORNL effluents on the community structure near the point of discharge.  The absence of responses at far-field sites suggests that more substantial abatement activities and remedial actions may be needed and that more time may be necessary for the communities to respond to subtle changes in water quality.<p>

<A NAME="85"><H1>85</H1></A>

<H2>A Site-Specific Water Quality Criterion for Mercury Is Determined for EFPC at the Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</h2>

<dl>
<dt>G. R. Southworth, R. R. Turner, and B. D. Nourse (1)
</dl>

In the renewed <a href="http://www.epa.gov/docs/EPA-WATER/1995/April/Day-07/">National Pollutant Discharge Elimination System</a> permit, the Tennessee Department of Environmental Conservation (TDEC) plans to regulate mercury discharges from the <a href="http://www-internal.ornl.gov/Y12/y12.html/">Oak Ridge Y-12 Plant</a> to <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/ORNLReview/rev27-3/text/envside1.htm/">East Fork Poplar Creek</a> (EFPC) to ensure that the discharges do not result in the accumulation of hazardous concentrations of mercury in aquatic biota.  The <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA) water quality criterion for mercury, 0.012 &#181;g/L, which has been adopted as the Tennessee water quality standard, is determined based on assumptions that are inappropriate for many aquatic systems.  In promulgating that criterion, EPA recommended using site-specific data on actual mercury concentrations in fish to evaluate whether regulated discharges are acceptable.<p>

To help TDEC set mercury discharge limits that will protect the classified uses of EFPC but that will also be technically achievable with current treatment and remediation technologies, researchers used data on mercury concentrations in fish and water in EFPC to calculate a site-specific mercury criterion for the upper reaches of EFPC.  Human health risk assessment procedures were used to determine mercury concentrations in fish that would be safe for human consumption, and a predictive relationship between total aqueous mercury and mercury bioaccumulation in the predominant sport and food fish in EFPC was developed.  Site-specific toxicity data and toxicity data used by EPA to calculate the national water quality criterion were reviewed to ensure that the site-specific criterion would not have adverse ecological consequences.<p>

Because the relationship between total aqueous mercury and the accumulation of methylmercury in fish is very complex and poorly understood, researchers used two approaches to define the upper and lower bounds of the predictions.  One approach used a simple linear extrapolation of the existing data for upper EFPC, where aqueous mercury concentrations are high (1 to 2 &#181;g/L), whereas the other approach used bioaccumulation factors and methylmercury-to-total mercury ratios for lower EFPC (where aqueous mercury is much lower) to provide a more conservative prediction.<p>

The range of aqueous mercury concentrations predicted to yield a mean mercury concentration in fish equal to 0.4 &#181;g/g, the &quot;safe&quot; value determined by the risk analysis, was 0.1 to 0.6 &#181;g/L.  Conservative interpolation between these upper and lower bounds of reasonable estimates has led to the recommendation of 0.2 &#181;g of total aqueous mercury per liter as an appropriate criterion for upper EFPC.  Achievement of such a concentration in the stream would represent a great reduction (&#126;80&#37;) in mercury concentration and would be a challenging goal for the Y-12 Plant environmental restoration and compliance programs.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Health Sciences Research Division, ORNL.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="86"><H1>86</H1></A>

<H2>Quantitative Sample Collection Objectives Lead to Improved Data Usability</h2>

<dl>
<dt>C. J. Ford, J. J. Beauchamp, and R. D. Schmoyer
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/CRERP/">Clinch River Environmental Restoration Program</a> is conducting the second phase of a remedial investigation (RI) on Clinch River and Poplar Creek.  One RI goal is to provide risk assessment using data representative of the river-creek system by studying several reaches along the river and the creek.<p>

One hypothesis of risk assessment is that current contaminant concentrations in Clinch River or Poplar Creek exceed risk criteria for human health or the environment.  System variability and the number of samples needed to accept or reject the risk assessment hypothesis were estimated from existing water flow and from a suite of contaminant concentration data that represent a variety of chemical behaviors.<p>

Each sample number was calculated by using a contaminant coefficient of variation (CV), a contaminant action level (AL), and a specified confidence or power level.  Statistical power is the probability of finding that the upper 95&#37; confidence limit (c.l.) of the mean is less than the AL for a particular contaminant.  The CV estimate is used to calculate the 95&#37; c.l. to be compared with the AL.  The number of samples needed was calculated by combining power, CV, and a 1:2 ratio of contaminant concentration to AL.  For the Clinch River, the number of samples that were needed to address the hypothesis ranged between 7 and 190 per study reach per quarter, depending on the contaminant.  For Poplar Creek, between 3 and 15 samples per study reach per quarter were necessary to address the hypothesis.<p>

These techniques will be used in future studies to optimize sample design and improve data usability.  The combination of quantitative analysis of existing data and randomized sample collection yields a sampling and analysis plan appropriate to the system being characterized and the questions being addressed.<p>

<A NAME="87"><H1>87</H1></A>

<H2>Data Review Activities Are Under Way for Phase 2 of the Clinch River Remedial Investigation</h2>

<dl>
<dt>S. K. Holladay, C. C. Brandt, C. J. Ford, D. A. Levine (1), R. B. Cook, R. L. Moody (2), K. A. Newman (2), D. D. Schmoyer, C. M. Chavannes (2), G. W. Suter, and B. G. Blaylock
</dl>

Innovative approaches to data collection and review are being used to assess and document the quality of the data produced in Phase 2 of the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/programs/CRERP/">Clinch River Remedial Investigation</a>.  Field documentation and data review are being performed to verifyall of the information produced in support of the sampling event, including information in the field logbooks, on the chain-of-custody forms, in the sample preparation record, and available field data.  All field quality-control samples--such as trip blanks, rinse blanks, fieldblanks, and field replicates--are being assessed.<p>

All data deliverables are inventoried upon arrival to ensure that the required sample results and quality control documentation are present.  As soon as they become available, analytical results are distributed to responsible personnel for evaluation and modification of the conceptual model as needed.  Five percent of the analytical data is assessed by full data validation, which includes reviews of holding times, calibration criteria, surrogates, matrix spikes, duplicates, blanks, laboratory control samples, and other instrument parameters.  Holding times, spike recoveries, and laboratory control samples will be reviewed for all analytical data that are available electronically.<p>

Software developed by the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA) is used to screen and load the electronic data.  CAVEAT, software developed by Science Applications International Corporation, is used to assist in the analytical review and validation of all EPA Superfund Contract Laboratory Program electronic deliverables.<p>

During each step of the review process, the data are qualified through the use of predefined flags.  The final data assessment involves the integration and evaluation of all the review information to assess the usability of the data in relation to the project data quality objectives.  Any problems that may affect data quality are reported as programmatic exceptions and are tracked until they are resolved.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Automated Sciences Group, Inc., Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Science Applications International Corporation, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="88"><H1>88</H1></A>

<H2>Groundwater Transport of Multiple Bacterial Strains Is Detected Through PCR Analysis</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. S. Burlage, A. V. Palumbo, and J. F. McCarthy
</dl>

A goal of <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>'s Subsurface Microbiology Program is to describe factors that control bacterial transport through soil subsurface.  Tracing individual species of bacteria under field conditions is often difficult because (1) genetically modified microorganisms cannot be used and (2) a large population of indigenous microorganisms is present.<p>

Because molecular methods can overcome these problems, they were employed to distinguish injected bacteria from indigenous bacteria.  A field experiment was performed with five different bacterial strains used by investigators in the program.  Strains were grown in 20-L carboys and transported to the injection site, a well-characterized field site near Georgetown, South Carolina.<p>

Samples were then withdrawn from five wells and collected by filtration on filters with a 0.2-&#181;m pore size.  A reference strain was added to the samples to determine DNA extraction and polymerase chain reaction (PCR) efficiency.  Using a modified extraction technique, researchers obtained total DNA from these filtered samples.  DNA samples were then subjected to PCR analysis for each of the five strains.<p>

PCR primers (20-mer) were described for each strain, as well as a set of nested primers that were used for reamplification of weak signals.  Thus, tools were developed that could be used to examine the transport or survival of bacteria.  Other field injections are planned to identify factors that enhance or inhibit bacteria transport.<p>

<A NAME="89"><H1>89</H1></A>

<H2>Selective Agents Are Necessary to Isolate Rare Native Strains for Bacterial Transport Studies</h2>

<dl>
<dt>A. V. Palumbo, R. S. Burlage, S. P. Scarborough, and J. F. McCarthy
</dl>

Unlike in controlled laboratory studies, in field experiments researchers can have difficulty tracing the transport of injected bacteria because of high background concentrations of bacteria in a receiving aquifer (e.g., 2 &#215; 10<sup>5</sup> colony-forming units per milliliter at a proposed field site in Oyster, Virginia).  In a collaborative transport experiment funded by the DOE Subsurface Science Program, researchers are examining the application of molecular techniques (DNA hybridization and polymerase chain reaction) to field transport studies.  These techniques will be used to obtain quantitative results on breakthrough of multiple strains of bacteria with different surface properties, size, and shape.<p>

In this study, scientists are constrained to using bacteria from the site in Oyster or from its vicinity; the strategy is to use highly selective media both to isolate rare strains for use in the transport studies and to combine colony hybridization with specific DNA probes for use in transport monitoring.  Rare strains for injection can be isolated by using either unusual carbon sources (e.g., naphthalene) or selective agents (e.g., antibiotics) that inhibit growth of most of the bacteria.  No useful strains have been isolated by using unusual carbon sources because nonspecific growth on carbon in site water or on impurities in the agar interferes with strain isolation.  Several pigmented strains were isolated on media containing streptomycin, nalidixic acid, kanamycin, and rifampicin.  However, all of them are resistant to multiple antibiotics and thus cannot be used together.<p>

Other selective agents (e.g., 8&#37; NaCl, cadmium, copper, phenol) have also been used successfully to isolate very rare strains from the site.  DNA probes are being prepared from these strains before injection at the Oyster field site.<p>

<A NAME="90"><H1>90</H1></A>

<H2>Novel Thermophilic Metal-Reducing Microorganisms Are Isolated from Deep Subsurface Sediments</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. J. Phelps, S. M. Pfiffner (1), C. Zhang (2), and D. C. White (3)
</dl>

Investigating metabolism, metal reduction, and the survival of thermophilic microorganisms isolated from deep subsurface environments provides an important knowledge base from which to evaluate the potential of deep subsurface bacteria to alter or mitigate wastes.  <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> researchers and collaborators have examined subsurface environments that are &gt;2500 m beneath the land surface and have in situ temperatures of 20 to &gt;70 C.  Fermentative and metal-reducing microorganisms that appear distinct from known taxa have been isolated from these deep subsurface formations.<p>

Thermophilic metal-reducing anaerobes isolated from &gt;2-km depths in the Taylorsville Triassic Basin were compatible with the geologic setting from which they were derived.  They metabolize, grow, and survive at 70&#176;C with an alkaline pH of 7.5 to 8.5 under brackish conditions.  Furthermore, these unusual micro-organisms tolerate brines containing 0.5 to 5&#37; salt, and they reduce iron, manganese, and uranium when using carbohydrates or volatile fatty acids as an energy source.  Investigations also focus on the ability of these micro-organisms, which were hydrologically and geologically isolated for millions of years, to survive under in situ temperatures and pressures and at low nutrient levels.<p>

The metabolic and physiologic characteristics of subsurface microorganisms and the geochemical features that constrain microbial abundance and activities in subsurface environments have been documented.  Procedures developed through these studies have been implemented by <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> bioremediation demonstration projects and by environmental consulting firms.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>Oak Ridge Institute for Science and Education, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(2)  <i>Oak Ridge Associated Universities, Oak Ridge, Tennessee.</i>
<dt>(3)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="91"><H1>91</H1></A>

<H2>Population Parameters of Small Mammals Are of Little Value as Endpoints of Toxicant Exposure in Biomonitoring Programs</h2>

<dl>
<dt>B. T. Walton, S. S. Talmage, D. L. DeAngelis, and J. J. Beauchamp
</dl>

Biological monitoring is undertaken at many <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> sites to determine whether hazardous chemicals have been released to the environment or whether known releases have an adverse impact on the biota inhabiting chemically contaminated areas.<p>

Guidance from the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a> (EPA) calls for surveying terrestrial vertebrate populations to determine whether they are adversely affected at hazardous waste sites.  To assess the value of the studies undertaken at chemically contaminated field sites, researchers at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> conducted a critical review of the published scientific literature on small mammal population studies.  On the basis of a critical analysis of the published literature spanning more than 40 years, ORNL researchers concluded that population studies failed to show demographic changes in small mammal populations exposed to toxicants in the field.  Moreover, fundamental properties of the dynamics of small mammal populations, documented by ecologists since the 1940s and earlier, mitigate against detecting single-factor causes of population declines in the field.<p>

A major concern for demographic studies of small mammals under field conditions is the inability to show statistically significant differences caused by chemical treatment against a background of high variability in animal numbers.  Considering the  populations, and in the face of the experimental limitations of population complexity and unpredictability of factors that influence the size of small mammalstudies, ORNL researchers concluded that conducting field studies to detect effects of hazardous chemicals on small mammal populations in the field is of questionable value.<p>

<A NAME="92"><H1>92</H1></A>

<H2>Signature Lipid Biomarker Analysis Is Applied to Assess Biomass, Community Structure, Nutritional Status, and Specific Metabolic Attributes of the Deep Subsurface Microbiota</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. C. White (1) and D. B. Ringelberg (1)
</dl>

Analysis of deep subsurface sediments, drilling muds, and makeup fluids by signature lipid biomarker (SLB) analysis quantitatively assesses viable biomass, community structure, and nutritional or physiological status of the microbiota in situ and thus provides quality assurance that the microbes recovered from sample cores are not contaminants acquired in the recovery process.  With the legitimacy of the isolates established by the SLB analysis, the properties of subsurface microbial communities and isolates can be examined.<p>

Organisms recovered from the Taylorsville Triassic Basin &gt;9000 ft below ground surface exhibited the attributes necessary for survival:  thermophly, salinity resistance, and anaerobic metabolism (with metal reduction as the terminal electron acceptor).  In situ SLB analysis of the extant microbiota from a semiarid site showed high levels of sulfate-reducing bacteria associated with lacustrine, but similar levels were not present in paleosol or fluvial subsurface sediments within a 30-m facies recovered from a depth of 170 m.  Subsurface sediments generally show a decreasing viable biomass with increasing depth; however, sediments recovered from high-discharge sites showed high proportions of actinomycetes signature lipids in comparison with low-discharge areas in the same horizon.  When added to subsurface soils, specific microbes, such as the anaerobic dechlorinator <i>Desulfomonile tiedjei</i>, can be detected or identified by their lipopolysaccharide lipid A hydroxy fatty acids.<p>

SLB analysis of microbial communities at the <a href="http://www.srs.gov/">Savannah River Site</a> indicated that Type II methane-oxidizers increased as the subsurface in situ remediation of TCE became more effective.  SLB analysis detected that the shifts in the microbial communities correlated with effective biodegradation of petroleum hydrocarbons from the Kwajalein Atoll.  Furthermore, SLB analysis of the rhizosphere microbiota from white oak trees showed increased fine-root rhizodeposition of viable microbial biomass when the trees were exposed to elevated levels of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The Center for Environmental Biotechnology, The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="93"><H1>93</H1></A>

<H2>Data Coordination Activities for the ORNL Site Environmental Restoration Program Are Initiated</h2>

<dl>
<dt>L. J. Allison, L. A. Hook, and J. W. Autrey
</dl>

Documenting the availability and location of historical and current environmental measurement data relevant to the <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration Program</a> is a major concern of ORNL Environmental Restoration management.  For the scope of the Environmental Restoration Program, several types of environmental measurement data are required:  sampling, field measurement, analytical laboratory, geographic information system, and facility management.<p>

Many groups collect data, and group activities may overlap with one another or with earlier sampling programs.  To avoid a duplication of effort within Environmental Restoration and ORNL, a formalized Environmental Data Coordination Activity was initiated.  Issues include the need for data coordination within the ORNL Environmental Restoration Program, the types of data in the scope of the program, and the need for standardized data formats and naming conventions that are consistent with <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/doe_oro/oro_home.html/">DOE Oak Ridge Operations Office</a> Environmental Information System standards.<p>

In addition, data collected by the ORNL environmental compliance monitoring programs for use by the Environmental Restoration Program, along with the methods by which the data are obtained and managed, are concerns.  An inventory of environmental measurement data within ORNL was initiated to determine the extent of existing data.  The survey requested information about the types of data (e.g., groundwater chemistry, surface water flow, <a href="http://www.libertynet.org/~bgmap/gis.html/">geographic information system</a>), the data custodian, the data management system, and the person with final-decision authority about the data.  Interviews with data managers have been scheduled to complete the compilation of information.<p>

The ORNL Site Environmental Restoration Data Coordination Committee will review the results of the data inventory before suggesting additional action.<p>

<A NAME="94"><H1>94</H1></A>

<H2>Specific Data Transfer Format Is Defined for OREIS</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. A. McCord
</dl>

The Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS) was developed and is being managed by <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ORNL ESD</a> staff, the Computing Applications Division, the <a href="http://www.hsrd.ornl.gov/index.html/">Health Sciences Research Division</a>, and <a href="http://wwwnt.camosun.bc.ca/cts/">Computing and Telecommunications Services</a> to fulfill a regulatory requirement for a consolidated database of environmental measurements.  The first major activity of OREIS was to define and to test a relational database model that could store the wide diversity of environmental measurements.  Those measurements, which are transferred to OREIS, are generated from activities that support the monitoring of current operations and the remediation of contamination from previous operations.<p>

When OREIS first began to collect environmental data sets from restoration projects, data were transferred in the format (structure and database) used for the project activities.  The inconsistencies and incompleteness of data and documentation received from the projects resulted in significant delays associated with loading data into the OREIS database.<p>

To correct this problem, OREIS staff defined a specific format for data transfer.  This format includes the specification of required and optional fields; the definition of one data record per measurement; the use of OREIS units, codes, and definitions; and the use of a database transport file structure.  The specification of the format more clearly defines the database requirements for projects and will promote consistency and completeness of the data before they are transferred to OREIS.  This new strategy for data transfer should enable OREIS and related environmental programs to better meet the regulatory expectations for data access.<p>
     
