<TITLE>Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</TITLE>

<H1>Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a> (BFDP) is the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a>'s (DOE's) national program to develop new crop-based sources of biomass for energy.  BFDP supports the missions of DOE and DOE's <a href="http://beijing.dis.anl.gov/ee-cgi-bin/ee_office.pl/">Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy</a>, Biofuels Systems Division, and Biomass Power Program.  The <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) of <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) leads and manages BFDP.  Universities, <a href="http://www.usda.gov/">U.S. Department of Agriculture</a> (USDA) facilities, and industrial cooperators participate in BFDP research and development activities each year.<p>

The mission of BFDP is to lead the nation in research, development, and demonstration of environmentally acceptable and commercially viable biomass supply systems.  The program is designed to integrate and promote multiple objectives in agriculture, energy, and the environment by fostering the best research, development, and demonstration in the private, academic, and government sectors.  The program is committed to ensuring that information on biomass supply systems is accurate, understandable, and accessible.<p>

ESD has provided field management, research, and analysis for BFDP since 1980.  The program currently supports projects in six major areas, referred to as tasks:  Model Wood Energy Species; Model Herbaceous Energy Species; Environmental Research; Systems Integration and Analysis; Scale-up, Feasibility, and Demonstration; and Energy Crops Data and Information Management.  Researchers at universities and USDA facilities perform much of the research in the program, particularly in the first two tasks.  Throughout its history, the program has included 25 to 35 such outside cooperators at any given time.  ESD's research efforts have emphasized basic genetics, physiology, and biotechnology projects that support the development of woody and herbaceous crops, resource assessments and economic analyses, and environmental research and analysis.<p>

BFDP's primary DOE sponsor is the Biofuels Systems Division in the <a href="http://www.eren.doe.gov/office/transportation/">Office of Transportation Technologies</a>.  BFDP also works with other governmental and private organizations.  Recent activities include assessments, cooperative projects, and work-for-others efforts with the <a href="http://www.gnn.com/gnn/wic/wics/env.17.html/">National Renewable Energy Laboratory</a>, the <a href="http://www.epa.gov/">U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</a>, the <a href="http://www.epri.com/">Electric Power Research Institute</a> (EPRI), the <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">Tennessee Valley Authority</a> (TVA), and the <a href="http://www.audubon.org/audubon/">National Audubon Society</a>.<p>

The technical summaries in this section provide details about research accomplishments in the Biofuels Feedstock Development Program.  For further information about research associated with the program, see technical summaries 49, 60, and 63, located elsewhere in the report.<p>

<h2>Model Wood Energy Species</h2>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">BFDP</a> has supported research on the production of short-rotation woody crops since 1978.  Having conducted an extensive species-screening program and developed management systems for short-rotation woody crops, BFDP is currently focusing its efforts on developing the genus <i>Populus</i> as a model wood energy species.  Using hybrids developed through BFDP research, commercial production of <i>Populus</i> as a short-rotation crop has begun in the Pacific Northwest.  Improvements in productivity, site adaptability, and tolerance for biotic and abiotic stresses are required before such systems are feasible in other regions.  <i>Populus</i> crop development projects in the upper Midwest and the South are addressing these topics, whereas work in the Pacific Northwest now emphasizes performing genetic mapping and understanding the genetic control of <i>Populus</i> productivity.  Other woody crops projects are developing production systems for hybrid willow in the Northeast and for silver maple in the Midwest.<p>

<h2>Model Herbaceous Energy Species</h2>

The objective of the Model Herbaceous Energy Species task is to select and improve herbaceous crops and cropping systems in a way that is environmentally and technically sound and that attracts industry support and cost-shared research.  Part of the objective is to ensure that environmental risks and costs are minimized and that a portfolio of high-quality feedstocks is available for end users.  The task emphasizes switchgrass (<i>Panicum virgatum</i>), a native perennial, warm-season grass.  Switchgrass was chosen for development as a model species for herbaceous crops research because of its performance in screening trials.  In the trials, switchgrass was very productive on a wide range of sites with relatively low levels of fertilizers and pesticides.<p>

Seven actively funded projects are currently under way in the herbaceous crops task, including management, breeding, physiology, and tissue culture of switchgrass.  The near-term focus of these projects is to develop the management techniques, physiological understanding, and breeding technology necessary to establish, produce, and harvest switchgrass in an economically and environmentally sound manner.  The longer term objectives are to characterize and improve switchgrass as a biofuels crop.<p>

<h2>Environmental Research</h2>

The Environmental Research task is focused on developing environmental data specific to energy crop production systems.  The objectives of this task are (1) to provide reliable information to support the environmental soundness of recommended biofuel supply systems and (2) to provide innovative approaches to energy crop production that will promote environmental benefits.  In this task, environmental data and information are developed in a way that addresses the sustainability of energy crop production and provides relevant and accurate information to support the development of effective environmental assessments.<p>

The Environmental Research task is closely coordinated with other <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">BFDP</a> tasks, and it promotes interaction with other external research and environmental groups.  Research projects have been developed through extensive discussions and interactions with industrial, utility, and environmental organizations.  For example, the initial studies of biodiversity in short-rotation woody crops included support for and cooperation with the <a href="http://www.usda.gov/">USDA</a> <www.fsl.orst.edu/home/usfs/usfshome.htm/">Forest Service</a> and the <a href="http://www.audubon.org/audubon/">National Audubon Society</a>.  Research supported by this task includes studies associated with the scale-up planting of hybrid poplar in Minnesota and a cooperative research project with <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">TVA</a> and <a href="http://www.aamu.edu/>Alabama A. & M. University</a> that addresses erosion and chemical movement from biomass plantings.<p>

Studies indicate that energy crop development promises to improve soil and water quality, increase the diversity of selected avian and mammal species, and reduce greenhouse gases.  The potential for converting millions of acres from other uses must be considered in planning the expansion of biomass energy technologies to the demonstration, scale-up, and commercialization stages.  These landscape changes will raise questions that must be addressed for biomass development to be feasible.<p>

<h2>Systems Integration and Analysis</h2>

The Systems Integration and Analysis task was created in FY 1994 from portions of two former tasks--the Economic Analysis and Integration task and the Environmental Research and Analysis task.  Systems Integration and Analysis thus unites all the analytical elements associated with feedstock supply systems.  The overall objective is to provide timely and relevant information to <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">BFDP</a>, <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>'s Biofuels Systems Division, industries, and other government organizations engaged in biomass energy research and development.<p>

The task supports a range of analyses evaluating and defining the interactions between factors affecting the price, supply, and environmental effects of biomass energy crops.  Participants include <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> staff, other <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> staff, <a href="http://www.tva.gov/">TVA</a>, other federal agencies, and universities.  In FY 1994, researchers began a major 3-year integrated analysis project covering six Midwestern and five Southeastern states.<p>

<h2>Scale-up, Feasibility, and Demonstration</h2>

The Scale-up, Feasibility, and Demonstration task was created in FY 1994 to develop information about the economics of commercial-scale energy crop plantings and to provide an identifiable and consistent contact within <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">BFDP</a> for industries that need information on feedstock development.  In cooperation with <a href="http://www.epri.com/">EPRI</a>, the Minnesota Department of Natural Resources, and <a href="http://www.usda.gov/">USDA</a>, this task supported operational-scale short-rotation woody crop plantings on 1000 acres in Minnesota during FY 1994.  The task also provided technical support for a series of feasibility studies supported by <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a>, EPRI, and private groups.  In these studies, potential users of energy crops evaluated various energy crop data (such as cost and supply data) and assessed the feasibility of various end uses.<p>

<h2>Energy Crops Data and Information Management</h2>

The Energy Crops Data and Information Management task addresses the increasing demand for information about energy crops.  Information is requested by researchers, policymakers, entrepreneurs, utility companies, and landowners.  Staff now place increased emphasis on defining the audience for each information product.  <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">BFDP</a> develops and distributes a variety of products and services--newsletters, fact sheets, technical reports, white papers, document distribution, and public accessibility on the Internet.  Staff produce and distribute the newsletter <i>Energy Crops Forum</i> three times a year.  In addition, staff respond to general and specific information requests, assembling packages of reports and reprints, queries of databases, and copies of slides.<p>

<hr>
<a name="tech"><h1>Technical Summaries</h1></a>
<hr>

<a name="95"><h1>95</h1></a>

<h2>Biomass Cost Varies Across Tennessee</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. L. Graham
</dl>

An innovative analysis of the potential spatial variation in the supply and delivered price of biomass in Tennessee was recently completed.  This analysis examined the projected delivered price of wood from energy crops to 21 evenly spaced locations across Tennessee.  Such a study is the first to systematically examine the spatial variation in the marginal cost (expressed in dollars per delivered dry ton) of supplying biomass, taking into account both spatial variations in transportation costs and in farm-gate biomass prices.  (Farm-gate prices are the prices paid to the farmer.)<p>

The supply and farm-gate price information for the study was derived from a county-level biomass database created by the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/BFDP/BFDPMOSAIC/abtbfdp.html/">Biofuels Feedstock Development Program</a>.  BRAVO, a computer model based on a geographic information system and developed at <a href="http://www.utk.edu/">The University of Tennessee</a>, was used to calculate the transportation costs associated with supplying biomass to the 21 locations.  Even at low demands (e.g., 100,000 dry tons per year, an amount sufficient to support a 20-MW power plant), some spatial variation existed in the marginal cost of delivered biomass.<p>

The central and the far southwest portion of the state had the lowest marginal costs (&#126;$35 to $40 per delivered dry ton), and a $10 spread occurred between the highest and the lowest cost locations.  At high demand (e.g., 1 million dry tons per year, an amount sufficient to support a large ethanol plant), the spatial differences were amplified and delivered prices were higher.  At this demand level, all of the lowest delivered prices were in the north-central portion of the state (&#126;$43/dry ton), and the spread was $25.<p>

The study demonstrated that fewer locations will be suited for energy technologies with large demands for biomass feedstock at a single location.  Energy technologies that demand small or moderate amounts of biomass will be feasible at more locations.<p>

<a name="96"><h1>96</h1></a>

<h2>Tissue Cultures Are Not Valid Surrogates for Whole-Plant Assessments of Water Stress Tolerance in Poplar Clones</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. J. Tschaplinski and G. A. Tuskan
</dl>

The use of water stress-tolerant poplar clones would greatly expand the acreage potentially suitable for energy plantings and would increase the productivity of available sites.  In vitro assays of water stress tolerance would greatly reduce the time and effort needed to characterize the genetic potential of selected poplar (<i>Populus</i> spp.) clones.<p>

To determine whether in vitro assays can be used to assess water stress tolerance, six clones in a pedigree consisting of black cottonwood (<i>P. trichocarpa</i> female Torr. & Gray) and eastern cottonwood (<i>P. deltoides</i> male Bartr.) and four hybrid progeny were regenerated in tissue culture and subjected to 0-20&#37; polyethylene glycol MW 8000 in the nutrient medium, providing osmotic potentials that ranged from &#45;0.40 to &#45;1.29 MPa.  Water stress tolerance was assessed by measuring callus growth and solute accumulation that occurred under various stress levels.<p>

Among the light-grown cultures (16-h photoperiod), clones with the highest relative growth rate after 18 d in the nutrient medium without polyethylene glycol included hybrids 246 female, 242 male, and the <i>P. deltoides</i> male parent--the same clones that tended to be the most stress tolerant in previous whole-plant studies.  However, stress treatments yielded few differences in relative growth rate between clones, and differences were not related to solute accumulation.  Polyethylene glycol provided severe osmotic stress that suppressed growth and dehydrated the callus cultures.  Inorganic cations and free amino acids constituted the bulk of the solutes in calli, whereas concentrations of soluble sugars were low.  Therefore, results obtained from callus cultures growing under artificially induced water stress regimes did not parallel those obtained from water stress studies on whole plants.<p>

<HR>


