<TITLE>Environmental Information Analysis Program</TITLE>

<H1>Environmental Information Analysis Program</H1>

<HR>
<A NAME="intro"><H1>Introduction</H1></A>
<HR>

The Environmental Information Analysis Program was created within the <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">Environmental Sciences Division</a> (ESD) at <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">Oak Ridge National Laboratory</a> (ORNL) in FY 1992 to consolidate ongoing research data management projects under common leadership.  The program highlights the division's abilities to support large, integrated environmental database projects with extensive data analysis components.  The management of research data has become a vital component of modern observational and theoretical science.  The significant global change projects of the 1990s--such as the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">U.S. Department of Energy</a> (DOE) <a href="http://info.arm.gov/">Atmospheric Radiation Measurement</a> (ARM) project; the <a href="http://www.epm.ornl.gov/chammp/">DOE Computer Hardware, Advanced Mathematics, and Model Physics</a> project; and the <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</a>'s (NASA's) comprehensive <a href="http://gcmd.gsfc.nasa.gov/gcmdeos.html/">Earth Observing System Program</a>--have large data management components that are vital to their success.  The ability to intelligently manage and analyze large environmental data sets is one of ESD's historically unique capabilities.<p>

The Environmental Information Analysis Program consists of four components:  the ARM Archive, which supports the DOE ARM project; the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC), which supports DOE's global change-related research; the <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/">ORNL Distributed Active Archive Center</a> (DAAC), which supports NASA's Earth Observing System Program; and the Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS), which supports the data needs of local restoration efforts at DOE facilities in Oak Ridge.</a>

The technical summaries in this section provide details about research accomplishments in the Environmental Information Analysis Program.  For further information about research associated with the program, see technical summaries 7, 8, 69, 70, 71, and 94, located elsewhere in the report.<p>

<h2>Atmospheric Radiation Measurement Archive</h2>

<a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> manages the long-term archive for the <a href="http://info.arm.gov/">ARM</a> project, a <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> field project that will obtain precise measurements of atmospheric radiation-related phenomena to improve general circulation models used in predicting climate.  The ARM Archive is a worldwide resource of meteorological and atmospheric physics information.  The information will be useful not only for refining general circulation models but also for understanding other atmospheric phenomena such as tornado and precipitation formation.  The ARM Archive stores, manages, and processes data collected during the ARM project and makes that data available for use by the ARM Science Team members and the general scientific community.<p>

The archive has received data since June 1992 and currently houses approximately 60 gigabytes of data in more than 340,000 files.  The data are stored in an <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> mass storage system that was modified by the ARM Archive to increase its storage capacity of data from 1.1 terabytes to 5 terabytes.  A graphical user interface is provided so that users can directly request data based on the set of instruments that collected the data and on a date range of interest.  The requested data files are made available for pickup via File Transfer Protocol, and the requester is notified that the data are ready to be claimed.  Design and implementation of improvements to the user interface and data documentation are proceeding.<p>

The ARM Archive is closely integrated with the ORNL Center for Global Environmental Studies, and close coordination with ORNL's High Performance Computing initiative has been established.  The new Intel Paragon supercomputer and the massive ARM Mass Storage System are linked to allow complete and close interaction of the two systems.<p>

<h2>Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</h2>

The purpose of <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">CDIAC</a> is to acquire or compile, quality-assure, document, archive, and distribute data and other information concerning CO<sub>2</sub>, other greenhouse gases, and climate change in support of <a href="http://www.er.doe.gov/production/oher/GC/ESD_gc.html/">DOE's Global Change Research Program</a> (GCRP).  By serving as GCRP's information-gathering and distribution center, CDIAC provides technical support for GCRP; the general research, policy-making, education, and corporate communities; and the public.  CDIAC also operates the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/cdiac/">World Data Center-A for Atmospheric Trace Gases</a>, which is a component of the <a href="http://www.ngdc.noaa.gov/wdc/wdcmain.html/">World Data Center System</a> of the International Council of Scientific Unions.<p>

CDIAC activities include obtaining and evaluating data and technical literature, producing numeric data packages (NDPs) and computer model packages (CMPs), and distributing CO<sub>2</sub>-related reports. During FY 1994, CDIAC published four new NDPs; topics included long-term climate data from the former U.S.S.R., oceanic carbon chemistry data, carbon emissions from land-use change, and data for assessing the vulnerability of the U.S. Gulf Coast to sea-level rise.  The center also published three issues in the <i>DOE Research Summary</i> series and an issue of the newsletteri CDIAC Communications.  In addition, CDIAC published Trends '93: A Compendium of Data on Global Change</i> (the third report in the <i>Trends</i> series) and <i>Direct Effects of Atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> Enrichment on Plants and Ecosystems: An Updated Bibliographic Data Base</i>.<p>

During FY 1994, CDIAC filled 7485 information requests from 2796 individuals in 67 countries and responded to 1099 requests from 59 countries for NDPs and CMPs.  This brings CDIAC's total to 52,405 requests from users in 113 countries since 1985.<p>

<h2>Oak Ridge Environmental Information System</h2>

The <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/ERWM/envirre.html/">Environmental Restoration programs</a> of the <a href="http://www.doe.gov/">DOE</a> <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/mmes-www/history.html/">Oak Ridge Operations Office</a> and Martin Marietta Energy Systems, Inc., completed in FY 1994 the initial development of OREIS to meet requirements described in the Federal Facilities Agreement and the Tennessee Oversight Agreement.  According to these agreements, DOE will centralize and consolidate environmental data from all restoration and compliance programs on the Oak Ridge Reservation.<p>

The first goals of the OREIS development team are to make the data useful to more environmental programs, to improve the consistency of the data quality, to improve the defensibility of the data and its analytical products, and to reduce the redundancy of data collection and handling by different environmental programs.  Subsequent goals include specifying minimal data management standards and developing a robust database and information system to manage, display, and analyze the data.  The OREIS framework--the database, standards, and information system--will be used to implement the data management program for environmental restoration activities at the DOE facilities in Oak Ridge, Tennessee; Paducah, Kentucky; and Portsmouth, Ohio.<p>

A two-part evaluation process for the beta version of OREIS was successfully implemented during the third quarter of 1994.  Twenty-four volunteers representing primary user groups participated in an intensive 2-day hands-on training session, which was followed by a 6-week period during which they extensively tested and used OREIS functions.  A second survey involved a broader representation of potential OREIS user groups that did not participate in the beta testing.  The results of both surveys were reported and used as a basis for modifications to the system before its authorized release.<p>

In June, DOE Headquarters approved the implementation of OREIS.  The approval fulfilled a milestone for the DOE Oak Ridge Operations Office and authorized the release of OREIS as a production system.<p>

<h2>ORNL Distributed Active Archive Center</h2>

In July 1993, <a href="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/">ESD</a> received funding from <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/">NASA</a> to develop and operate one of nine <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/">Distributed Active Archive Centers</a> (DAACs) for NASA's <a href="http://gcmd.gsfc.nasa.gov/gcmdeos.html/">Earth Observing System Data and Information System</a> (EOSDIS).  EOSDIS is part of NASA's contribution to the <a href="http://www.usgcrp.gov/">U.S. Global Change Research Program</a>'s effort to develop a predictive understanding of the global environment.  The mission of the <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/ornldaac.html/">ORNL DAAC</a> is to provide data and information about the Earth's biogeochemical dynamics and ecology for the global-change research community, policymakers, educators, and the general public.  This information includes (1) ground-based products relating to biogeochemical dynamics and (2) links to data available through other DAACs.<p>

The <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/ornldaac.html/">ORNL DAAC</a> became operational in July 1994 and is now linked to the NASA system-wide Information Management System (IMS).  This link allows users to search for and order data from any of the EOSDIS DAACs through a single user interface.  A local user interface that offers capabilities not available through the system-wide IMS has been developed and is now operational.<p>

Current data holdings include those from NASA's First International Satellite Land Surface Climatology Project Field Experiment (FIFE) project and the Oregon Transect Ecosystem Research project.  Obtaining these data holdings is part of a larger effort to move appropriate data from NASA's Pilot Land Data System to the ORNL DAAC.  Staff in the ORNL DAAC are also working with <a href="http://boreas.gsfc.nasa.gov/">NASA's Boreal Ecosystem-Atmosphere Study</a> (widely known as BOREAS) and the FIFE Follow-on Investigation in order to receive and distribute data from these projects.  During this past year, staff formed a close working relationship with CDIAC; as a result, the user community can now access many of CDIAC's data holdings through the NASA systemiwide IMS and through the local ORNL DAAC user interface.<p>

<HR>
<A NAME="tech"><H1>Technical Summaries</H1></A>
<HR>

<A NAME="97"><H1>97</H1></A>

<H2>CDIAC Compendium Documents Recent Trends in Global-Change Data</h2>

<dl>
<dt>T. A. Boden, D. P. Kaiser, R. J. Sepanski (1), and F. W. Stoss (1)
</dl>

Recently published by the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC), <i>Trends '93:  A Compendium of Data on Global Change</i> provides synopses of frequently used global-change data. This third edition of <i>Trends</i> presents historical and modern records of atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide (CO<sub>2</sub>), methane (CH<sub>4</sub>), nitrous oxide (N<sub>2</sub>O), two chlorofluorocarbons (CFC-11 and CFC-12), a hydrochlorofluorocarbon (HCFC-22), and two halons (H-1301 and H-1211) from an expanded number of globally distributed sites.  Additional trace-gas data include historical atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub>, CH<sub>4</sub>, and N<sub>2</sub>O records derived from ice cores.<p>

<i>Trends '93</i> provides revised and updated estimates through 1991 for global, regional, and national CO<sub>2</sub> emissions produced from the burning of fossil fuels, gas flaring, and the production of cement.  Updated global emissions estimates through 1992 are presented for CFC-11 and CFC-12.  <i>Trends '93</i> also updates and expands the presentation of long-term temperature records, whose spatial coverage ranges from an individual Antarctic (ice core) site to the entire globe and from the earth's surface to the lower stratosphere.<p>

New subject matter in <i>Trends '93</i> includes a chapter for long-term regional precipitation records, several time-series records for atmospheric aerosols, and isotopic <sup>14</sup>C measurements for atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> from several globally distributed sites.<p>

The compendium documents the recently observed reductions in the growth rates of atmospheric CO<sub>2</sub> concentrations and emissions, cooling trends in global and hemispheric temperatures following the Mt. Pinatubo eruption of 1991, and reductions in global emissions of atmospheric CFC-11 and CFC-12.  The report and electronic versions of the data are available from CDIAC at no cost.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt>(1)  <i>The University of Tennessee, Knoxville.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="98"><H1>98</H1></A>

<H2>CDIAC Assembles a Unique Numeric Data Package of Climate Data and Begins a Historical Analysis of Cloud Cover over the Former U.S.S.R.</h2>

<dl>
<dt>D. P. Kaiser
</dl>

In recent years many meteorological data have been exchanged between the <a href="http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/">National Climatic Data Center</a> (NCDC), in Asheville, North Carolina, and the Research Institute of Hydrometeorological Information (RIHMI) in Obninsk, Russia.  Under a Work for Others (WFO) agreement with NCDC, the <a href="http://cdiac.esd.ornl.gov/">Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center</a> (CDIAC) has quality-assured, documented, and made available to the public an important RIHMI database of meteorological observations made at 3- and 6-hour intervals at 223 U.S.S.R. stations during 1936-90.<p>

The RIHMI database offers a wealth of meteorological data for a large and climatologically important part of the earth's land area.  To determine the suitability of the RIHMI database for regional climate change research, we used the database to examine the spatial distribution of a critical atmospheric variable (i.e., total cloud amount) over the U.S.S.R.  The resulting distribution was compared with data from the unique atlas <i>Global Distribution of Total Cloud Cover and Cloud Type Amounts Over Land</i>.<sup>1</sup>  Seasonal and annual means of total cloud amount for 84 latitude/longitude grid cells over the U.S.S.R. were compared for the common data period 1971-81.<p>

For all seasons, the RIHMI means were higher for most grid cells (typically by 3-6&#37;); differences over the central reaches of Siberia were even greater.  However, for mean annual cloud amount, &#126;30&#37; of the cells showed differences of &lt;1&#37;; these cells are located mainly in the western part of the country, where the RIHMI database has its greatest station density.  For the central and eastern regions of the U.S.S.R., an area of varied topography where the RIHMI station density is much lower than that of the atlas's database, the RIHMI database may yield questionable values of total cloud amount.  However, for the western reaches of the country, this database may be suitable for studies involving analysis of total cloud amount.<p>

The possible causes of the seemingly systematic seasonal differences between the two databases are being investigated further.<p>

<dl>
<dt>__________________
<dt><sup>1</sup><i>S. G. Warren et al., Global Distribution of Total Cloud Cover and Cloud Type Amounts Over Land, National Center for Atmospheric Research, Boulder, Colo., 1986.</i>
</dl>

<A NAME="99"><H1>99</H1></A>

<H2>Procedures Are Developed for Processing and Validating Environmental Data for the OREIS Database</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. J. Olson
</dl>

The primary function of the Oak Ridge Environmental Information System (OREIS) is to consolidate and maintain consistent and qualified data associated with environmental restoration and monitoring.  The assumption is that the data in OREIS meet universal criteria; however, the data meet only the data quality objectives defined by each project, and the project data generators are responsible for validating the data.  OREIS checks the integrity of data and metadata in the database.<p>

One of the most difficult aspects of compiling data into the OREIS database from projects or from other sources has been the process of deciding when the data are of sufficient quality to meet the OREIS database objectives.  The majority of data coming to OREIS are very clean; however, portions of data often have problems (e.g., invalid codes).  Often, a 90&#37; rule applies to processing the data:  90&#37; of that data are good, but 10&#37; have problems.  Of that 10&#37;, 90&#37; have problems that can be resolved fairly quickly (possibly requiring twice as much time as did the first pass, when the initial data was read in), but 10&#37; of this set (1&#37; of the initial set) have more severe problems.<p>

Making several telephone calls and examining the data, researchers can resolve 90&#37; of the more severe problems (the resolution of these problems may take four times as much time as the resolution of the second-iteration problems, however).  The remaining problems (involving 0.1&#37; of the initial set) may never be completely resolved and could thus delay the transfer of the majority of data into the OREIS database.<p>

Guidelines were developed for determining when to stop working on resolving the problems and to begin placing the unresolved data, with appropriate metadata and flags, in a specially designated area of the database.  The decision to set aside data is based on how crucial the data are to the complete data transmittal, the availability of knowledgeable staff to resolve and authorize the changes, and the difficulty of the problem at hand (i.e., whether the original lab sheets, log books, and data files are available).  The problem data are described, the attempts to resolve them are documented, and the questionable data are removed from the data set to be placed in the active OREIS database and are stored separately as &quot;set aside&quot; data sets.<p>

<A NAME="100"><H1>100</H1></A>

<H2>ORNL Distributed Active Archive Center Provides Data on Biogeochemical Dynamics</h2>

<dl>
<dt>R. S. Turner, L. D. Voorhees, and P. F. Daugherty
</dl>

The <a href="http://www.nasa.gov/">National Aeronautics and Space Administration</a> (NASA) has designated <a href="http://www.ornl.gov/">ORNL</a> as the site for the <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/">Distributed Active Archive Center</a> (DAAC) for Biogeochemical Dynamics, one of eight DAACs established by NASA as a part of the <a href="http://gcmd.gsfc.nasa.gov/gcmdeos.html/">Earth Observing System (EOS) Data and Information System</a> (EOSDIS) project.<p>

EOS and EOSDIS are part of NASA's contribution to the <a href="http://www.ciesin.org/">U.S. Global Change Research Program</a>, an interagency effort of the U.S. government to develop a predictive understanding of the global environment.<p>

The <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/ornldaac.html/">ORNL DAAC</a> provides (1) an information management system that is integrally linked to the other DAACs; (2) a data archive and distribution system, including a user services function; (3) value-added products that summarize and synthesize biogeochemical dynamics data from around the globe; and (4) guidance and support in the areas of data management, data quality assurance, and data integration to enable field experimenters to prepare those data for archive and distribution to other global change researchers.  The ORNL DAAC is developing an <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/x-windows.html/">on-line user interface</a> and a <a href="http://www-eosdis.ornl.gov/daacpages/user_services.html/">user services office</a>.<p>

A User Working Group of global change researchers from ten outside organizations provides science oversight and guidance to DAAC developmental activities and operational functions.  The DAAC's on-line user interface was demonstrated at the center's first User Working Group meeting on March 21-22, 1994.<p>

<HR>
<address><a href="index.html">ESD Annual Report for 1994</a> / Linda J. Jennings</a> (<a href="jenningslj@ornl.gov">jenningslj@ornl.gov</a>)<br>
