<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Oak Ridge Energy Crop County Level Database</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE="+2"><STRONG>The <FONT SIZE="+3">O</FONT>ak <FONT SIZE="+3">R</FONT>idge
<FONT SIZE="+3">E</FONT>nergy <FONT SIZE="+3">C</FONT>rop <FONT SIZE="+3">C</FONT>ounty
<FONT SIZE="+3">L</FONT>evel Database<BR>December 20th, 1996 version</STRONG></FONT></P></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<P><B>Robin L. Graham, Linda J. Allison and Denny A. Becker</B><BR>Environmental
Sciences Division<BR>Biofuels Feedstock Development Program<BR>Oak Ridge
National Laboratory<BR>P.O. Box 2008<BR>Oak Ridge, TN 37831-6335 USA</P></CENTER>
<H2>Overview of Database</H2>
<P>The Biofuels Feedstock Development Program (BFDP) at Oak Ridge National
Laboratory has developed a county-level database on energy crops.  This
database, which encompasses all U.S. counties, provides easy access to energy
crop information specific to state or county.  </P>
<P>The county-level database is a compilation of current information on land
availability and rents, energy crop yields, and production costs. It includes
probable farmgate prices for energy crops as calculated from information within
the database. The database includes data on switchgrass (<I>Panicum virgatum</I>),
hybrid poplar (<I>Populus</I> sp.), and willow (<I>Salix</I> sp.), and  is
searchable by either state and county name or Federal Information Processing
Standards (FIPS) numeric codes for states and counties.</P>
<P>The database was first described in the paper &quot;<A
HREF="../papers/bioen96/graham2.htm">ORECCL - Oak Ridge Energy Crop County
Level Database</A>&quot; published in the  Proceedings of Bioenergy '96  The
seventh National Bioenergy Conference held in Nashville, TN September 1996
(Graham et al. 1996).  Some variables have been added and others dropped since
the publication of that proceedings so the user is advised to read this
documentation.  The database will be updated as data and models improve.</P>
<P>The database is available in three formats: </P>
<UL>
<LI>an <A HREF="oreclxls.zip">Excel&reg; 5.0 spreadsheet</A> (ORECCL.xls plus
this document (~290k),</LI>
<LI>a <A HREF="oreclsas.zip">SAS&reg; transportrable Binary File for use with
Proc Cimport</A> (ORECCL.csv  plus this document ~270k),</LI>
<LI>and an <A HREF="orecltxt.zip">Comma delimited ASCII text file</A>
(ORECCL.cpt plus this document  ~160k)</LI></UL>
<P>The files have been compressed using PKZip to speed up the file transfers.
To find a utility that dearchives 'zipped' files,
<A HREF="http://www.shareware.com">click here</A>. If you experience
difficulties, please send a message to the <A HREF="mailto:are@ornl.gov">Webmistress</A>.</P>
<P>The Excel file has 4 rows with header information. The first row is a credit
line. The second row has the variable names. The third and fourth rows contain
unit information. The remaining 3103 rows contain data for the 3103 counties in
the U.S. </P>
<P>The Ascii text file has one header line containing the variable names. The
remaining lines contain data.</P>
<P>Each file contains 3103 observations (counties) and 43 variables. The order
of the variables is identical in the Excel file and the ASCII file.  The
variables are ordered, named and defined in the following section.  Additional
information on the variables and the calculations used to derive the variables
is found at the end of this document. </P>
<H2>The 43 Variables in the ORECCL Database</H2>
<P><B>Variables which define location</B></P>
<DL>
<DD>1. <B>State_nm</B> = Full name of state. 
</DD>
<DD>2. <B>Cnty_nm </B>= Full name of county.
</DD>
<DD>3. <B>Fips_st</B>  = Two digit FIPS code for state
</DD>
<DD>4. <B>Fips_co</B> = Three digit FIPS code for county
</DD>
<DD>5. <B>LRR </B>= Letter representing Land Resource Region in which county
is found
</DD>
<DD>6. <B>MLRA </B>= Major Land Resource Area to which the county was assigned
</DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables which describe potential switchgrass yield</B></P>
<P>If the county falls in a region of the country not suitable for switchgrass
production, a numeric code  of -9999 indicating unsuitability was inserted in
each of the switchgrass yield cells (Variables 7-9)  for that county. (A county
was defined as unsuitable if its climate was such that switchgrass would be
difficult to establish or its yield was likely to be less than 2 dry
tons/acre/yr.)  The switchgrass yield is the yield one would expect once the
crop was established (year 3 and thereafter). No yield would be expected the
first year and yield 2/3rds that of the mature yield is expected the second
year. The crop lifetime is presumed to be 10 years from planting to final
harvest. The yields are based on a single cut per year.  In some regions
switchgrass might be cut twice but production costs would change significantly
under a two cut system. </P>
<DL>
<DD>7. <B>SWGyld</B> = Median estimated mature yield (dry tons/acre/yr) of
unirrigated switchgrass.</DD>
<DD>8. <B>SWGyldh</B> = Optimistic estimated mature yield (dry tons/acre/yr)
of unirrigated switchgrass.</DD>
<DD>9. <B>SWGyldl</B> = Pessimistic estimated mature yield (dry tons/acre/yr)
of unirrigated switchgrass.</DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables which describe potential short rotation woody crop (SRWC)
yield</B></P>
<P>If the county falls in a region of the country not suitable for either
willow or hybrid poplar production, a numeric code of -9999 indicating
unsuitability was inserted into each of the SRWC yield cells (Variables 11-13)
of that county. (A county was defined as unsuitable if its climate was such that
SRWC would be difficult to establish or its yield was likely to be less than 2
dry tons/acre/yr.)  The yield is the mean annual increment of a seven year
rotation if the crop is poplar. Poplar is assumed to be replanted after harvest.
The yield is the mean annual increment of a three year harvesting cycle if the
crop is willow. Willow is assumed to be coppiced with seven rotations over 22
years. (The willow is cut the year of planting but not harvested). </P>
<DL>
<DD>10. <B>Type</B> = Type of SRWC crop assumed - willow or hybrid poplar (W
or P or no).</DD>
<DD>11. <B>SRWCyld</B> = Median estimated yield (dry tons/acre/yr) of
unirrigated SRWC. </DD>
<DD>12. <B>SRWCyldh</B> = Optimistic estimated yield (dry tons/acre/yr) of
unirrigated SRWC. </DD>
<DD>13. <B>SRWCyldl </B>= Pessimistic estimated yield (dry tons/acre/yr) of
unirrigated SRWC. </DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables which describe potential landbase for growing energy crops</B></P>
<P>Variables 14 and 15 and 16 are reported for all counties whether or not they
are suitable for energy crop production.  A numeric code of -777 or -999 is used
to indicate data unavailability for these three variables.  Variables 17 and 18
are set to -9999 if the county is in a region not suitable for switchgrass
production.  Variables 19 and 20 are set to -9999 if the county is in a region
not suitable for SRWC production.  </P>
<DL>
<DD>14. <B>Crop92</B> = Total amount (acres) of all USDA classified cropland
in county (as of 1992).</DD>
<DD>15. <B>Pstr92</B> = Total amount (acres) of all USDA classified pasture
land in county (as of 1992).</DD>
<DD>16. <B>CRP</B>  =  Total amount (acres) of Conservation Reserve Program
land in the county as of the 12th sign-up.</DD>
<DD>17. <B>SWG_gd </B>= Amount of cropland (acres) in county suitable for
producing switchgrass.</DD>
<DD>18. <B>SWG_gdp</B> = Amount of pasture (acres) in county suitable for
producing switchgrass.</DD>
<DD>19. <B>SRWC_gd</B> = Amount of cropland (acres) in county suitable for
producing SRWC.</DD>
<DD>20. <B>SRWC_gdp</B> = Amount of pasture (acres) in county suitable for
producing SRWC.</DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables describing the cost of producing energy crops </B></P>
<P>If energy crops are not suited for that county then a place holder of -999
is put as the value. The Net Present Value (NPV) of the production costs over
the lifetime of the crop assumes a 6.5% discount rate. Note that production
costs are sensitive to yield and region of the country.  Variable costs include
custom operations and purchased materials (seed, fertilizer, fuel, chemicals).
1993 dollars are used. </P>
<DL>
<DD>21.  <B>GNPVtot</B> = NPV of total economic production costs of
switchgrass energy crops ($/acre) excluding only land costs and assuming <B>median
switchgrass yield</B>, and 10 yr crop life.</DD>
<DD>22.  <B>GNPVtoth</B> = NPV of total economic production costs of
switchgrass energy crops ($/acre) excluding only land costs and assuming <B>optimistic
switchgrass yield</B>, and 10 yr crop life.</DD>
<DD>23.  <B>GNPVtotl</B> = NPV of total economic production costs of
switchgrass energy crops ($/acre) excluding only land costs and assuming <B>pessimistic
switchgrass yield</B>, and 10 yr crop life.</DD>
<DD>24.  <B>GNPVvar</B> = NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of
switchgrass energy crops, assuming <B>median switchgrass yield</B> and a 10 yr
crop life. </DD>
<DD>25. <B>GNPVvarh</B> = NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of
switchgrass energy crops, assuming <B>optimistic switchgrass yield</B>
switchgrass yield and a 10 yr crop life.</DD>
<DD>26. <B>GNPVvarl </B>= NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of
switchgrass energy crops, assuming <B>pessimistic switchgrass yield</B>
switchgrass yield and a 10 yr crop life. </DD>
<DD>27. <B>WNPVtot</B> = NPV of total economic production cost ($/acre) of
SRWC energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>median SRWC yield</B>
and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life if willow.</DD>
<DD>28. <B>WNPVtoth</B> = NPV of total economic production cost ($/acre) of
SRWC energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>optimistic SRWC
yield</B> and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life
if willow.</DD>
<DD>29. <B>WNPVtotl </B>= NPV of total economic production cost ($/acre) of
SRWC energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>pessimistic SRWC
yield </B>and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life
if willow.</DD>
<DD>30. <B>WNPVvar </B>= NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of SRWC
energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>median SRWC yield</B>
and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life if willow.</DD>
<DD>31. <B>WNPVvarh </B>= NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of
SRWC energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>optimistic SRWC
yield</B> and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life
if willow.</DD>
<DD>32. <B>WNPVvarl </B>= NPV of all variable production costs ($/acre) of
SRWC energy crops excluding only land costs and assuming <B>pessimistic SRWC
yield</B> and a 7 yr crop life if poplar and a 22 year (7 rotations) crop life
if willow.</DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables describing value of land for current uses  (land rent)</B></P>
<P>If the county falls in a state for which state-level cash-rent data are
unavailable, then the average cash rent of the states surrounding that state was
calculated and that average value was used as the variable value for Variables
33 and 34.  (Hawaii and Alaska  values were set to -777 as there was no way to
derive these values).  If the county has no CRP acres (Variable 16 equals zero)
a numeric code indicating no CRP land (-9999) was inserted into the cell for
Variable 35.  </P>
<DL>
<DD>33. <B>ERS_crop</B> = State-level cash rents ($/acre/yr) for unirrigated
cropland.</DD>
<DD>34. <B>ERS_past</B> = State level cash rents ($/acre/yr) for pasture.</DD>
<DD>35. <B>CRPrent </B>= Average CRP rental rate ($/acre/yr) through the 12th
sign-up (June 1992).</DD>
<DD>36.<B> Renta</B> = Source of cropland land rent information used in
farmgate calculation (derive, CRP or ERS).</DD>
<DD>37. <B>Rent</B> = Rent used in farmgate price calculations - generally
derived county-level cash rents ($/acre/yr) for cropland. Derived rents are
based on farm value ($/acre) for the county and state cash rent values for
unirrigated cropland .</DD></DL>
<P><B>Variables describing farmgate price</B></P>
<P>The farmgate prices of switchgrass and SRWC  biomass were calculated as
breakeven prices (no inflation) such that the breakeven price would assure that
the net present value (NPV) of the gross revenues generated by selling the crop
(breakeven price times sold biomass per acre) minus the NPV of the total costs
of production equalled the NPV of the cash land rents the landowner could have
received if he had rented the land for the duration of the crop life instead of
growing the crop. If energy crops are not suited for that county then a place
holder of -9999 is put as the farmgate price value.</P>
<P>NPV (cash rent over the crop life) = NPV (gross revenues from the crop) -
NPV (production costs excepting land costs over the crop life)</P>
<P>A 6.5% discount rate was assumed. A storage loss of 6% of the harvested
switchgrass was also included in the calculations.  </P>
<DL>
<DD>38. <B>Gprice</B> = Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of <B>switchgrass bales</B>
at the side of the field assuming <B>median yield</B>.</DD>
<DD>39. <B>Gpriceh</B> = Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of <B>switchgrass bales</B>
at the side of the field assuming <B>optimistic yield.</B></DD>
<DD>40. <B>Gpricel</B> = Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of <B>switchgrass bales</B>
at the side of the field assuming <B>pessimistic yield.</B></DD>
<DD>41.<B> Wprice</B> = Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of  <B>SRWC chips</B> in a
trailer at the side of the field assuming <B>median yield.</B></DD>
<DD>42. <B>Wpriceh</B> = Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of  <B>SRWC chips</B> in
a trailer at the side of the field assuming <B>optimistic yield</B>.</DD>
<DD>43. <B>Wpricel </B>= Farmgate price ($/dry ton) of  <B>SRWC chips</B> in
a trailer at the side of the field assuming <B>pessimistic yield.</B></DD></DL>
<H3>ENDNOTES:</H3>
<P><B>Variables which define location</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>MLRAs were originally coded using a combination of integers followed
sometimes by a letter - such as 102A or 56B or 7. If a letter was in the code it
always was as the end digit. To convert MLRAs to numeric codes, we simply
converted the final letter to a number using the rule (A=1 , B=2 etc). If the
original code had no final letter we assigned the value 0.  Thus 57 became 570
and 56B became 562.</LI>
<LI>LRRs and MLRAs  are assigned to counties by taking the most dominant MLRA 
or LRR within the county tract.</LI>
<LI>We include cities, parishes, and census tracks as county observations if
they have a unique FIPS identification.</LI></UL>
<P><B>Variables which describe potential switchgrass or SRWC yield</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Although energy crop yield values are reported at the county-level, they
were derived at a regional (multi-county) level, since existing energy crop
yield data are generally inadequate for predicting yields with county-level
specificity.  Thus an important step in developing the database was defining the
yields, boundaries and counties of homogeneous energy-crop production regions.
The boundaries and energy crop yields of these regions were developed using
expert opinion, published yield values, available yield data from research
trials, and existing yield models.  In general these regions follow Major Land
Resource Areas boundaries. These production regions vary by energy crop type as
switchgrass and short rotation woody crops yields do not demonstrate the same
geographic pattern.  If a county falls in a region of the country not suitable
for switchgrass and/or SRWC production that is noted in the database.</LI>
<LI>A median, optimistic and pessimistic annual yield value were developed for
each switchgrass or SRWC production region. </LI>
<LI>The yield represents the harvested yield before any storage losses. It does
not include the effects that weather or management failures or major insect or
disease problems might have on regional yields. Furthermore, the yield
represents that which would be expected if
<OL>
<LI>the stand was planted on former cropland (as opposed to former pasture) 
</LI>
<LI>the stand was planted in the year 2000 </LI>
<LI>best management practices were followed</LI>
<LI>the best genetic stock was used </LI>
<LI>crop establishment was successful and </LI>
<LI> no irrigation was applied.</LI></OL></LI>
<LI>The median yield is the median yield an expert would expect if planted on &quot;typical
unirrigated cropland&quot; in that production region.  The pessimistic yield is
an estimate of the 25th percentile yield across all cropland in that region. 
The optimistic yield is an estimate of the 75th percentile yield across all
cropland in that region. That is, if all unirrigated cropland in the region were
planted to the energy crop using good practices and the best stock, experts
would expect 50% of the land to achieve at least the &quot;median&quot; yield.
They would expect 25% of the land to achieve a yield less than the &quot;pessimistic&quot;
yield and they would expect 25% of the land to achieve a yield greater than the
&quot;optimistic&quot; yield. </LI>
<LI>Median switchgrass yields along the Atlantic coast and the Gulf coast are
projected to be low although optimistic yields for these areas are predicted to
be high. Switchgrass does not do well with high water tables and heavy soils. As
this region has a lot of this type of land, median yields might be expected to
be low. Where the soil is adequately drained however, the yields should be high.
 Switchgrass yields in the northeast are projections based on hay yields. There
are no reliable switchgrass field data from this region. </LI>
<LI>Willow yields in the northern midwest are based on projections from
experiences in the northeast. There are no field willow data from this region
yet.</LI></UL>
<P><B>Variables which describe potential landbase for growing energy crops</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>CROP92 and PSTR92 are the total amount of cropland and pasture land in each
county as reported in the 1992 USDA Agricultural Census. It should be noted that
as per USDA, CROP92 includes cropland used for pasture, fallow cropland and
actively cropped cropland. USDA differentiates cropland used for pasture from
pasture/range.  CRP is the amount of land in the county in the Conservation
Reserve Program (CRP) as of the 12th sign-up (June 1992). These three variables
are reported for every county irrespective of whether or not the county falls in
a region of the country suitable for energy crop production. The CRP acreage was
taken from a USDA database provided to BFDP from USDA (T. Osbourne, personal
communication)</LI>
<LI>The amount of cropland and pasture physically suitable for switchgrass
and/or SRWC production (SWG_gd, SWG_gdp, SRWC_gd, and SRWC_gdp) was derived for
each county using USDA 1992 Agricultural Census information on land use and
expert opinion on where specific energy crops can be grown.  The acreage of
cropland suitable for energy crop production was defined as all cropland in the
county  except that cropland used for pasture, orchards or vegetables.  These
latter three types of cropland are excluded because they will be more costly to
convert to energy crop production and/or they have a different land rent value
than conventional crops (orchards and vegetables are high value crops and
unlikely to be converted to energy crop production). The acreage of pasture
suitable for energy crop production was defined as the sum of the acres of
cropland used for pasture and the acres of pasture/range (PSTR92). </LI></UL>
<P><B>Variables describing the cost of producing energy crops </B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Yield and region specific production costs were generated for switchgrass
and hybrid poplar using crop production models (BIOCOST) developed by Walsh and
Becker (1996).  Willow production costs were defined using estimates from the
State University of New York, Syracuse (D. Robison, personal communication). 
Variable production costs include fertilizer, seed, herbicides, fuel and custom
operation costs. Total economic production costs include the value of the
farmer's labor, fixed machinery costs ( i.e. depreciation and opportunity cost),
and farm overhead  in addition to variable production costs.  Labor costs, and
the machinery used to produce the crop are geographically specific. The total
economic costs do not include any of the fixed costs associated with land (e.g.
taxes, insurance, and real estate interest) as these costs are presumably
imbedded in cash rent values.</LI></UL>
<P><B>Comments on production costs:</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>In this version of the database, the rotation length of the hybrid poplar
is assumed to be a fixed seven years regardless of assumed yield and the
planting density is a fixed 6 ft by 8 ft again regardless of yield or region. If
the planting density were decreased ( ie.wider spacing), production costs go
down significantly as harvesting costs are strongly influenced by the number of
stems per acre.  It is also likely that with lower yields, it would be
economically advantageous to go to longer rotations.  Future versions of the
database will take these complexities into consideration.  </LI>
<LI>The version of BIOCOST used to estimate NPV for switchgrass has per acre
harvest costs which are fairly sensitive to yield. As yield goes up so does
harvest costs per acre and at a rate such that the harvest costs per ton are
almost constant for yields between 4 and 7 dry tons/acre. This has a major
influence on overall costs and farmgate prices. At least one recent study
suggests that harvest costs per ton go down significantly as yield goes up but
the range of yields tested was lower than what ORECCL is generally considering -
 between 2.3 and 5 (tons/acre) at one site and 1.5 and 4.5 at another (Bransby
et al., 1996).  If the experience of Bransby et al. applies for yields between 4
and 7 tons/acre then the farmgate prices of switchgrass shown in this version of
ORECCL may be slightly high. </LI></UL>
<P><B>Variables describing value of land for current uses  (land rent)</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>Four different estimates of land rent are provided for each county. These
are the 1993  state cash-rent values for cropland and pastureland as reported by
the Economic Research Service (ERS) of USDA (ERS 1993); the average annual CRP
payment ($/acre/yr) for all CRP-enrolled land in the county; and a county-level
cropland cash rent value used in the farmgate calculations.  The latter land
rent estimate (RENT) was derived by multiplying the state cash-rent value for
cropland by the ratio of the county farmland value ($/acre) to the state-average
farmland value ($/acre) as reported in the 1992 USDA Agricultural Census.  This
derived value of land rent is based on the assumption that county to county
variation in land rent ($/acre/yr) within the state mirrors county to county
variation in farmland value ($/acre) within the state.  In situations where the
county farmland value was not reported by USDA, the CRP rent (first choice) or
the state cash cropland rent (second choice) was substituted as the county-level
RENT variable. The variable RENTA denotes which rent estimate was used in the
county farmgate calculation.  The average CRP rental rate was calculated by
dividing the total annual CRP payments to the county by the total number of CRP
acres in the county as of the 12th sign-up. </LI></UL>
<P><B>Comments on the RENT values</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>It is important to recognize that farmland in counties near urban centers
has a market value which reflects its development or real estate potential
rather than its agricultural potential.  Thus the derived county-level cash
rents (RENT) (which are based on farm value) tend to quite high for these
counties (often in excess of $200/acre/yr). Cropland might actually be rented in
these counties for much less than our estimated value. On the other hand, there
generally isn't much cropland in these counties and farmers might be unlikely to
want to invest in perennial crops on these high value lands. So this distortion
is probably not of much significance from a state or national perspective with
the exception perhaps of Washington and Oregon where all the counties likely to
grow SRWC are probably urban-biased.  For example, Withrow-Robison et. al.
(1995) projected land lease rates for cropland suitable for growing poplar in
the Willamette Valley of Oregon to be $65/acre/yr. Our derived land rent values
for this area are all in excess of $100 and sometimes in excess of $200/acre/yr.
</LI></UL>
<P><B>Variables describing farmgate price</B></P>
<UL>
<LI>The farmgate price values reflect energy crop yield and county land rent.
Because urban counties were projected to have very high land rents, they have
correspondingly very high farmgate prices. This is the major explanation of the
high farmgate prices of poplar in the Pacific Northwest. The fixed rotation
length for poplar (7 years regardless of yield) affects the poplar prices too. 
In regions with low poplar yield the rotation would probably be longer and this
would reduce the farmgate price as the harvest costs (a major component of the
production costs) are more linked to the number of stems harvested per acre than
the average size of the stem.  Thus the poplar prices are probably overestimated
for lower yielding counties and all prices are probably overestimated for urban
counties.  </LI>
<LI>If the user wishes to assume a different land rent than is in the database
but keeps the yield the same then the following three equations can be used to
estimate a breakeven price based on the new  land rent.
<UL>
<LI>For Poplar: Price ($/dry ton) = ((5.841*RENT) + (WNPVtot))/(4.797*SRWCyld)</LI>
<LI>For Willow: Price($/dry ton) = ((11.414*RENT) + (WNPVtot))/(10.582*SRWCyld)</LI>
<LI>For Switchgrass: Price($/dry ton) = ((7.65*RENT)+(GNPVtot))/(5.965*SWGyld)</LI></UL></LI>
<LI>In all cases it is critical to keep the NPV value with its associated yield
value. The coefficients are specific to the assumed discount rate (6.5%) and
crop life. </LI></UL>
<H3>Acknowledgements</H3>
<P>We would like to acknowledge Dr. Shaine Tyson of the National Renewable
Energy Laboratory, Golden CO who sponsored a significant portion of the database
development and encouraged us to make the database as complete and detailed as
possible. Dr. Marie Walsh of Oak Ridge National Laboratory provided invaluable
review of the farmgate price calculations. Drs. Jerry Tuskan and Sandy
McLaughlin (also of Oak Ridge National Laboratory) provided detailed reviews of
the energy crop yield assumptions.  Questions regarding the database should be
directed to <A HREF="mailto:aeg@ornl.gov">Robin L. Graham</A>
(GrahamRL@ORNL.GOV)  The authors take full responsibility for any errors or
omissions in the database.</P>
