NAME="keywords" CONTENT="biomass, biofuels, energy crops, environmental assessment">
<TITLE>Cover Crops for Erosion Control in Bioenergy Plantations</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H1>COVER CROPS FOR EROSION CONTROL IN BIOENERGY HARDWOOD PLANTATIONS</H1></CENTER>
<CENTER>
<H3>Malik, R. K.<SUP>1</SUP> , T. H. Green <SUP>1 </SUP>, D. Mays <SUP>1
</SUP>, B. R. Bock <SUP> 2</SUP>, J. D. Joslin <SUP> 2</SUP>, F. C. Thornton
<SUP> 2</SUP>, V. R. Tolbert <SUP> 2</SUP>, G. F. Brown <SUP>1</SUP>, K.
Sistani <SUP> 1</SUP></H3>
<H3><SUP>1</SUP> Center for Forestry and Ecology, Alabama A&amp;M University,
P. O. Box 1208, Normal, AL 35762 USA</H3>
<H3><SUP>2</SUP>Tennessee Valley Authority, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, P.
O. Box 2008, Oak Ridge, TN 37831-6034 USA.</H3></CENTER>
<P><I>Proc., BIOENERGY '96 - The Seventh National Bioenergy Conference:
Partnerships to Develop and Apply Biomass Technologies</I>, September 15-20,
1996, Nashville, Tennessee.</P>
<CENTER>
<H2>ABSTRACT</H2></CENTER>
<P>The use of cover crops between tree rows has been suggested as a means of
reducing soil erosion in short-rotation woody crops (SRWC) plantations for
bioenergy production (Ranney et al. 1994). This study is designed to test
whether cover crops could reduce erosion without significantly reducing the
growth and biomass yield of sweetgum (Liquidambar styraciflua L.) planted as the
SRWC at a 1.5 X 3 m spacing. Four cover crops, winter rye grass (<I>Lolium
multigeonum </I>L., a winter annual grass); tall fescue (<I>Fescuta eliato</I>r
L., a winter perennial grass); crimson clover (<I>Trifolium incarnatum </I>L.,
a winter annual legume); and interstate sericea (<I>Lespedeza ameata </I>L., a
growing season perennial legume), are tested at two different strip widths (1.22
and 2.44 m) as well as a control with complete competition control. Small berms
were built to direct runoff to a sediment fence installed at the down slope ends
of each plot. Soil erosion is measured by sediment accumulation near the fence.
Height, ground-line diameter and crown width of trees were measured on a monthly
basis. During the first growing season all cover crops reduced growth of trees.
There were some significant differences among cover crop regimes. Slight
differences in soil erosion were detected during the first growing season. The
control plots lost more soil per hectare than cover crops, however, strip widths
and cover crops did not show any significant difference.</P>
<P><B>Keywords: </B>bioenergy, cover crop, erosion, hardwood</P>
<CENTER>
<H2>INTRODUCTION</H2></CENTER>
<P>Biomass resources have been historically important for energy supplies and
an excellent renewable alternative to fossil fuels. The biomass resources
include agricultural residues, long- rotation woody plantings, thinning, logging
residues, wood wastes and residues from production of paper and forest products,
and specialized wood and herbaceous crops developed specifically for energy
production (Hohenstein et al., 1994). As a result of increases in fossil fuel
price due to the oil embargo in 1970's, the use of biomass and other forms of
renewable energy increased. However, increases were limited mostly to the pulp,
paper and timber manufacturing industries, and to residential space heating
(Hohenstein et al., 1994). The overall energy use has increased by 167% during
1949 to 1990, wood energy use has increased by 108%, while wood energy use
represents 82% of the total biomass energy use (US Department of Energy, 1993).</P>
<P>The research on wood energy-crops is leading forestry into a new era of more
intensive silviculture because there will be a greater need for large, renewable
woody biomass plantation for conversion to gasoline and gaseous fuels. The wood
consumption of a biomass conversion facility will be in the range of 200,000 to
1 million dry megagrams per year (1 megagram = 1 metric tone = 1.1 English
Tons), similar to the demand of a pulp mill (Ranney et al., 1987). Under such a
scenario, intensive culture of hardwoods appears to fit this need very well
(Farnum et al., 1983).</P>
<P>The high-yield biomass energy crops could be produced on most of the U.S.
land currently under food crops production . The US Department of Agriculture
(USDA) reported 162 million hectare (Mha) of cropland in the United States in
1991. Out of this base, 137 Mha were either used to produce crops, were planted
but not harvested, or were summer fallowed. The remaining 25 Mha were idled
either through Annual Acreage Reduction Programs or through Conservation Reserve
Program (DOE, 1991).</P>
<P>Soil erosion is a major environmental threat and challenge to the
sustainability and productive capacity of agriculture (Pimental et. al., 1995).
About 75 billion metric tons of soil are removed every year from the land by
water and wind erosion, most of which comes from agricultural land (Pimental et
al., 1995). Similarly, erosion is a serious concern with energy crops,
especially during their establishment phase. No field data are available at this
time for comparison (Ranney et al., 1994). The short-rotation intensive culture
(SRIC) crops, after first year of establishment protect soil exceptionally well.
Under SRIC conditions, mean annual rate for productivity of 12 to 16 megagrams
per hectare (5.4 to 7.1 tons per acre ) is considered an acceptable range.
Eventually a goal of up to 20 dry megagrams per hectare (about 9 tons per acre)
may be achieved. SRIC crops would be an excellent compromise for obtaining
economic returns from the Conservation Reserve Program (Food Security Act, 1985)
land while providing needed soil protection as well (Ranney et al., 1987).</P>
<P>Hardwood SRIC is not feasible without good weed control, which is usually
accomplished through agricultural-type site preparation and herbicide use until
canopy closure (Kennedy, 1984). However, use of cover crops between tree rows
has also been suggested as a means of reducing soil erosion in short-rotation
woody crops (SRWC) plantations for bioenergy production (Ranney et al., 1994).
Sweetgum (<I>Liquidambur styraciflua </I>L.) is one of the most important
commercial hardwoods in the southeast and is put to a great many uses such as
lumber, veneer, plywood, slack cooperage, railroad ties, pulpwood and fuel,
(Agri. hand book 450, 1974).</P>
<P>The objective of this study is to examine whether cover crops could reduce
erosion without significantly reducing the growth and biomass yield of sweetgum
(<I>Liquidambur styraciflua </I>L.) planted as the short rotation woody crop at
a 1.5X3.0 m (5X10 feet) spacing.</P>
<CENTER>
<H2>MATERIALS AND METHODS</H2></CENTER>
<H3>Site Description</H3>
<P>The experiment is set up at the Winfred Thomas Agricultural Research Station
in Hazel Green, AL, 9 miles north of Alabama A &amp; M University campus. The
soil site is classified as a Decatur and cumberland silt loam, undulating
phases, with 2 to 6% slope with good natural drainage. The site has previously
been occupied by corn cultivation. Each plot measures 21.34 m X 7.62 m (65X25
feet) separated by 3.05 m (10 feet) buffer. Each plot is surrounded by a 20 to
25 cm (8-10 inch=in) high soil berm to direct runoff to a sediment fence
installed at the downslope end of each plot. There are 9 plots in a replication
and total 27 plots in three replications.</P>
<H3>Cover Crops and Sweetgum Planting</H3>
<P>The four types of cover crops planted are as: (a) winter annual - rye grass
(<I>Lolium multigeonum </I>L.) variety Kino seed @ 25 lb per acre + wheat (<I>Triticum
aestivum </I>L.) @ 40 lb per acre, (b) perennial grass - tall fescue (<I>Festuca
elatior </I>L.) variety Kentucky 31 seed @ 15 lb per acre + Wheat (<I>Triticum
aestivum </I>L.) @40 lb per acre, (c) winter annual legume - crimson clover (<I>Trifolium
incarnatum </I>L.) variety Big bee seed @ 25 lb per acre (all three planted on
November 3, 1994), and (d) perennial legume - interstate sericea (<I>Lespedeza
ameata </I>L.) variety seed @ 30 lb per acre (planted on May 17, 1995). The
cover crop strip widths between sweetgum rows was maintained at 1.22 m (4 feet)
and 2.44 m (8 feet) as well as a control with no cover crop. One-year-old
seedlings of sweetgum (<I>Liquidambar styraciflua</I> L.) were transplanted as
a short rotation woody crop on January 23 &amp; 24, 1995 at 1.5 X 3.0 m (5X10
feet) spacing with 35 sweetgum plants in each plot, 315 plants per replication
and 945 plants in three replications.</P>
<H3>Erosion</H3>
<P>Erosion was measured by sediment accumulation near the fence. The sediment
fences were fixed on July 7 &amp; 8, 1995. PVC pipes of 1.27 cm (0.5 in)
diameter, cut to 60 cm long, hand marked, from 0 to 15 cm, were driven into the
ground to a 15 cm depth so that 0 point was at the ground level. The pipes were
fixed from July 27 to July 31, 1995. The pipes were fixed at 30.48 X 30.48 cm
(1X1 foot) grid. The first row of 24 stakes at 30.48 cm (1 foot) apart was
flushed against the sediment fence followed by two more rows 24 pipes each in a
grid area of 0.61 X 7.62 m i.e. 4.65 m ( 2X25 feet 2 = 50 square feet)
(Dissmeyer, 1982).</P>
<H3>Measurements</H3>
<P>For the first year plant growth, monthly measurements of height, ground-line
diameter and crown diameter were recorded from May to September 1995 to compare
plants performance under different crop covers and their strip widths. The
growth will be assessed and related to the measures of resource availability for
nitrogen and soil moisture at different soil depths at a later date.
Sedimentation was measured in a grid system (Dissmeyer, 1982). The grid area in
this experiment is defined as 0.61 X 7.62 m (4.65 m2) (2X25 feet=50 sq ft). The
number of grid points (72) with or without sediment for each plot have been
counted and height of sediment noted. The present sedimentation data is for the
period from August, 1995 to February, 1996. The erosion volumes for different
treatments has been calculated as suggested by Dissmeyer (1982).</P>
<H3>Study Design</H3>
<P>The experiment is a Split Plot design with one level of nesting. The cover
crops per plot are the main treatments, cover crop's strip width treatments are
split with 15 trees nested. The data was analyzed by analysis of variance and
means were separated by Tukey's Studentized Range Test. The data were analyzed
using the GLM procedure of SAS.</P>
<CENTER>
<H2>RESULTS AND DISCUSSIONS</H2></CENTER>
<H3>Ground Line Diameter (D)</H3>
<P>The D was sigificantly affected by the cover crops. However, strip widths
and interactions did not significantly affect D. The effects of cover crops were
further analyzed using Tukey's studentized range test at 0.05 level (results not
shown). The crimson clover and tall fescue significantly reduced the D in
comparison to control.</P>
<H3>Height (H)</H3>
<P>The height of trees was not significantly affected by any cover crops and or
strip widths or their interactions.</P>
<H3>Volume Index (VI)</H3>
<P>The VI was not significantly affected by cover crops and or strip width or
their interactions.</P>
<H3>Diameter Growth (DGRO)</H3>
<P>The DGRO was significantly affected by both cover crops and the strip width.
While performing the Tukey's studentized range test at 0.05 level, rye grass and
tall fescue were not significantly different from each other, similarly rye
grass, tall fescue, lespedeza and crimson clover were not significantly
different from each other in DGRO responses. However, lespedeza and crimson
clover were different from control and reduced DGRO significantly.</P>
<H3>Height Growth (HGRO)</H3>
<P>The cover crops significantly affected HGRO. The strip widths and
interactions did not significantly affect HGRO. The effects of cover crops were
further analyzed using Tukey's studentized range test at 0.05 level. The crimson
clover and lespedeza were not significantly different between each other. The
crimson clover significantly reduced HGRO in comparison to control, rye grass
and tall fescue. Similarly the lespedeza and tall fescue were not significantly
different from each other, however, lespedeza significantly reduced HGRO as
compared to control and rye grass.</P>
<H3>Volume Growth (VGRO)</H3>
<P>The volume growth was not significantly affected by the cover crops, strip
widths or their interactions.</P>
<P>The possible explanations for results (Table 1) are that the cover crops had
established earlier than the planting of sweetgum seedlings. Most of the cover
crops root systems were active for nutrients and moisture utilization. During
the early period of establishment sweetgum trees may have suffered a little more
setback while competing for soil nutrients and moisture with the cover crops.
Therefore, overall reduction in growth of trees was observed during the first
year of growth in comparison to control.</P>
<CENTER>
<TABLE BORDER="BORDER" WIDTH="100%">
<TR>
