<TR>
<TD COLSPAN="10">D = Ground Line Diameter in CM, H = Height in cm, VI = Volume
Index (D<SUP>2</SUP>H)cm<SUP>3</SUP> , DGRO = Diameter Growth cm, HGRO =
Height Growth cm, VGRO = Volume Growth cm<SUP>3</SUP></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER>
<P>Although the width of strips did not significantly affect height, ground
level diameter, volume index, height growth and volume growth, there appears to
be a trend in that the wider strips reduced most growth parameter under this
study. The strip width represents relative competition to the trees, therefore,
as competition increases, the height, diameter, and volume growth is decreased.
One possible reason that the results were not significant is because of the
large amount of variation encountered in this analysis. The original seedlings
were extremely variable when planted and after one year of growth the tree to
tree variance accounts for 70 to 80% of total variation among all variables
except diameter growth, where tree to tree variance was 58% of total.</P>
<H3>Soil Erosion</H3>
<P>Cover Crops. The relationship between the vegetative cover and rainfall in
terms of the soil erosion has been a neglected area of research. From early and
later research it is clear that raindrop interception is the main way that
vegetation reduces erosion (Stocking 1994). The cover crops did not
significantly affect soil erosion during the first season of growth. This is
possibly due to the gross measurements of soil erosion and will probably become
significant later. However, it may be observed from Table 2 that rye grass and
crimson clover reduced erosion losses better than lespedeza and tall fescue.</P>
<P>Strip Width. The relationship between erosion and cover crop strip width is
curvilinear.There is little difference whether the cover is 100% or 60% (Elwell,
1980; Elwell &amp; Stocking, 1974).There were no significant reductions in soil
erosion due to the strip widths of cover crops during first season of growth.
However, it was observed that 2.44 m (10 feet) strip width reduced slightly more
erosion than the 1.22 m (4 feet) strip width. These effects were more pronounced
in crimson clover followed by rye grass. The similar effects were not seen in
case of lespedeza and tall fescue as we had a hard time to maintain germination
and width strip of 2.44 m (10 feet) during the first growing season.We
anticipate clearer results inthe future as cover crops will have a better chance
to stabilize. Again, the relatively high amount of tree to tree variance is
decreasing our ability to detect statistically significant results. However, we
hope to have clear results in the coming years of experiment.</P>
<P></P>
