<HR>
<H2>Welcome to the Virtual Brashear!</H2>

<P>
To view any isosurface, <STRONG>click the desired density</STRONG> in
the color legend in the image above.</P>

<P>
The isosurface consists of all voxels that are equal to the density
selected.  This creates a continuous shell which is the 3-D equivalent
of a 2-D contour line.  Because almost no sediment has a density less
than that of water, isosurfaces generated at densities less than 1.0
encompass the entire volume.</P>

<P>
Only the outermost isosurface shell will be visible.  For details of
the internal structure of the volume, see the <A
HREF="../SEDIMENT/BRASHEAR.HTM#volumeanimations">volume animations</A>.
For scientific details of how the Brashear volume data were obtained
and processed, see the <A HREF="../SEDIMENT/BRASHEAR.HTM">Brashear Island
Volumetric Interpolation</A> page.</P>

<P>
For an interactive interface to the Brashear volume data which allows
the construction of customized animations, see the <A
HREF="../ISOMOVIE/INDEX.HTM">Virtual Brashear - Pick a Flick</A>.</P>

