<BODY>

<H1><IMG SRC="photos/droop.gif"> </H1>

<H1>Inexpensive Aerial Photographic Mapping for Environmental
Site Characterization Using Radio-Controlled Aircraft </H1>

<H2>By <A HREF="http://www.esd.ornl.gov/~nyq">Jonathan E. Nyquist </A>
 and C. David Farmer </H2>

<H2>Oak Ridge National Laboratory </H2>

<H1>Abstract </H1>

<P>
Aerial photography can play an in important role in characterization
of hazardous waste sites. Frequently disposal records are inaccurate
or inadequate, and in such cases the comparison of current aerial
photographs with historical photographs can provide information
about burial ground construction, cut and fill activities, and
subsequent waste management practices. Subtle patterns in vegetation
associated with contaminant migration and small topographic depressions
created by the settling of the uncompacted soil used to cover
the waste trenches, can be difficult to detect from the ground,
but are often clearly visible on aerial photographs. Aerial photography
can be equally important during hazardous site clean-up. Photographs
taken before, during, and after remediation provide excellent
step-by-step documentation of the work performed. This report
describes the results work performed by researchers at Oak Ridge
National Laboratory for the Department of Energy's Office of Technology
Development (EM50). <BR>
<HR>

<H1>Table of Contents </H1>

<H3>INTRODUCTION </H3>

<UL>
<LI>A brief <A HREF="intro.htm">introduction</A> to potential
advantages of radio-controlled aircraft for aerial photography.
</UL>

