<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="Preferred Customer">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H2>Telemaster Modifications</H2>

<H4>After building and flying a standard Senior Telemaster, we
experimented with a number of design modifications.</H4>

<P>
<B>Fuselage:</B> We widened the fuselage near the wing about 2
inches to create a larger payload compartment.
<P>
<B>Flaps:</B> We added flaps in place of about one third of each
aileron to improve takeoffs and landings. Set the flaps at about
10 degrees from normal for takeoff, and about 30 degrees for landing.
<P>
<B>Spoilers:</B> For landings in tight spaces, we added spoilers
to the wings. These were constructed out of a 1.5 in. x 12 in
piece of trailing edge stock, and located inboard of each wing,
just behind the wing spar. Both spoilers are operated by a single
servo and have a maximum travel of approximately 45 degrees. With
spoilers deployed the aircraft will descend rapidly but under
good control. If both spoiler and flaps are used, the aircraft
slow very rapidly; <I>be careful not to stall the aircraft</I>.
To avoid a stall you must keep the nose down and the engine speed
up.
<P>
<B>Wing Tip Plates</B>: We enlarged the tip plates on the wings
to extend 1 in. below the bottom of the wing. This directs the
air flow that would normally slip off the end of the wing back
across the ailerons, improving maneuverability at slow speeds.
We have not seen any tendency to tip stall.
<P>
<B>Engine and Payload</B>: We use an OS91 four cycle engine with
a 13x6 propeller and a 16 oz. fuel tank. The maximum flying weight
appears to be about 17 lb., but 15 lb. is a more comfortable limit.
<P>
<IMG SRC="greenball.gif"><A HREF="tmaster.htm">Back to Telemaster</A>
<P>
<IMG SRC="redball.gif">Return to <A HREF="toc.htm" >Table of Contents</A>
